urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.1#CHAPTER I.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.2#DENISE had walked from the Saint-Lazare railway station, where a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.3#Cherbourg train had landed her and her two brothers, after a night
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.4#passed on the hard seat of a third-class carriage. She was leading Pépé
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.5#by the hand, and Jean was following her, all three fatigued after the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.6#journey, frightened and lost in this vast Paris, their eyes on every
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.7#street name, asking at every corner the way to the Rue de la Michodière,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.8#where their uncle Baudu lived. But on arriving in the Place Gaillon, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.9#young girl stopped short, astonished.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.10#“Oh! look there, Jean,” said she; and they stood still, nestling close
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.11#to one another, all dressed in black, wearing the old mourning bought
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.12#at their father's death. She, rather puny for her twenty years, was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.13#carrying a small parcel; on the other side, her little brother, five
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.14#years old, was clinging to her arm; while behind her, the big brother, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.15#strapping youth of sixteen, was standing empty-handed.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.16#“Well,” said she, after a pause, “that _is_ a shop!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.17#They were at the corner of the Rue de la Michodière and the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.18#Neuve-Saint-Augustin, in front of a draper's shop, which displayed a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.19#wealth of colour in the soft October light. Eight o'clock was striking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.20#at the church of Saint-Roch; not many people were about, only a few
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.21#clerks on their way to business, and housewives doing their morning
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.22#shopping. Before the door, two shopmen, mounted on a step-ladder,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.23#were hanging up some woollen goods, whilst in a window in the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.24#Neuve-Saint-Augustin another young man, kneeling with his back to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.25#pavement, was delicately plaiting a piece of blue silk. In the shop,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.26#where there were as yet no customers, there was a buzz as of a swarm of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.27#bees at work.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.28#“By Jove!” said Jean, “this beats Valognes. Yours wasn't such a fine
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.29#shop.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.30#Denise shook her head. She had spent two years there, at Cornaille's,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.31#the principal draper's in the town, and this shop, encountered so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.32#suddenly--this, to her, enormous place, made her heart swell, and kept
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.33#her excited, interested, and oblivious of everything else. The high
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.34#plate-glass door, facing the Place Gaillon, reached the first storey,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.35#amidst a complication of ornaments covered with gilding. Two allegorical
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.36#figures, representing two laughing, bare-breasted women, unrolled the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.37#scroll bearing the sign, “The Ladies' Paradise.” The establishment
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.38#extended along the Rue de la Michodière and the Rue Neuve-Saint
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.39#Augustin, and comprised, beside the corner house, four others--two on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.40#the right and two on the left, bought and fitted up recently. It seemed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.41#to her an endless extension, with its display on the ground floor, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.42#the plate-glass windows, through which could be seen the whole length of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.43#the counters. Upstairs a young lady, dressed all in silk, was sharpening
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.44#a pencil, while two others, beside her, were unfolding some velvet
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.45#mantles.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.46#“The Ladies' Paradise,” read Jean, with the tender laugh of a handsome
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.47#youth who had already had an adventure with a woman. “That must draw the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.48#customers--eh?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.49#But Denise was absorbed by the display at the principal entrance. There
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.50#she saw, in the open street, on the very pavement, a mountain of cheap
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.51#goods--bargains, placed there to tempt the passers-by, and attract
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.52#attention. Hanging from above were pieces of woollen and cloth goods,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.53#merinoes, cheviots, and tweeds, floating like flags; the neutral, slate,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.54#navy-blue, and olive-green tints being relieved by the large white
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.55#price-tickets. Close by, round the doorway, were hanging strips of fur,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.56#narrow bands for dress trimmings, fine Siberian squirrel-skin, spotless
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.57#snowy swansdown, rabbit-skin imitation ermine and imitation sable.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.58#Below, on shelves and on tables, amidst a pile of remnants, appeared an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.59#immense quantity of hosiery almost given away; knitted woollen gloves,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.60#neckerchiefs, women's hoods, waistcoats, a winter show in all colours,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.61#striped, dyed, and variegated, with here and there a flaming patch of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.62#red. Denise saw some tartan at nine sous, some strips of American vison
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.63#at a franc, and some mittens at five sous. There appeared to be an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.64#immense clearance sale going on; the establishment seemed bursting with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.65#goods, blocking up the pavement with the surplus.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.66#Uncle Baudu was forgotten. Pépé himself, clinging tightly to his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.67#sister's hand, opened his big eyes in wonder. A vehicle coming
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.68#up, forced them to quit the road-way, and they turned up the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.69#Neuve-Saint-Augustin mechanically, following the shop windows and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.70#stopping at each fresh display. At first they were captivated by a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.71#complicated arrangement: above, a number of umbrellas, laid obliquely,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.72#seemed to form a rustic roof; beneath these a quantity of silk
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.73#stockings, hung on rods, showed the roundness of the calves, some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.74#covered with rosebuds, others of all colours, black open-worked, red
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.75#with embroidered corners, and flesh colour, the silky grain of which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.76#made them look as soft as a fair woman's skin; and at the bottom of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.77#all, a symmetrical array of gloves, with their taper fingers and narrow
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.78#palms, and that rigid virgin grace which characterises such feminine
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.79#articles before they are worn. But the last window especially attracted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.80#their attention. It was an exhibition of silks, satins, and velvets,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.81#arranged so as to produce, by a skilful artistic arrangement of colours,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.82#the most delicious shades imaginable. At the top were the velvets,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.83#from a deep black to a milky white: lower down, the satins--pink, blue,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.84#fading away into shades of a wondrous delicacy; still lower down were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.85#the silks, of all the colours of the rainbow, pieces set up in the form
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.86#of shells, others folded as if round a pretty figure, arranged in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.87#life-like natural manner by the clever fingers of the window dressers.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.88#Between each motive, between each coloured phrase of the display, ran a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.89#discreet accompaniment, a slight puffy ring of cream-coloured silk. At
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.90#each end were piled up enormous bales of the silk of which the house
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.91#had made a specialty, the “Paris Paradise” and the “Golden Grain,” two
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.92#exceptional articles destined to work a revolution in that branch of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.93#commerce.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.94#“Oh, that silk at five francs twelve sous!” murmured Denise, astonished
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.95#at the “Paris Paradise.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.96#Jean began to get tired. He stopped a passer-by. “Which is the Rue de la
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.97#Michodiere, please, sir?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.98#On hearing that it was the first on the right they all turned back,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.99#making the tour of the establishment. But just as she was entering the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.100#street, Denise was attracted by a window in which ladies' dresses were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.101#displayed. At Cornaille's that was her department, but she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.102#never seen anything like this, and remained rooted to the spot with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.103#admiration. At the back a large sash of Bruges lace, of considerable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.104#value, was spread out like an altar-veil, with its two white wings
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.105#extended; there were flounces of Alençon point, grouped in garlands;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.106#then from the top to the bottom fluttered, like a fall of snow, a cloud
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.107#of lace of every description--Malines, Honiton, Valenciennes, Brussels,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.108#and Venetian-point. On each side the heavy columns were draped with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.109#cloth, making the background appear still more distant And the dresses
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.110#were in this sort of chapel raised to the worship of woman's beauty and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.111#grace. Occupying the centre was a magnificent article, a velvet mantle,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.112#trimmed with silver fox; on one side a silk cape lined with miniver, on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.113#the other a cloth cloak edged with cocks' plumes; and last of all,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.114#opera cloaks in white cashmere and white silk trimmed with swansdown or
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.115#chenille. There was something for all tastes, from the opera cloaks at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.116#twenty-nine francs to the velvet mantle marked up at eighteen hundred.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.117#The well-rounded neck and graceful figures of the dummies exaggerated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.118#the slimness of the waist, the absent head being replaced by a large
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.119#price-ticket pinned on the neck; whilst the mirrors, cleverly arranged
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.120#on each side of the window, reflected and multiplied the forms without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.121#end, peopling the street with these beautiful women for sale, each
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.122#bearing a price in big figures in the place of a head.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.123#“How stunning they are!” murmured Jean, finding no other words to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.124#express his emotion.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.125#This time he himself had become motionless, his mouth open. All this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.126#female luxury turned him rosy with pleasure. He had a girl's beauty--a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.127#beauty he seemed to have stolen from his sister--a lovely skin, curly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.128#hair, lips and eyes overflowing with tenderness. By his side Denise, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.129#her astonishment, appeared thinner still, with her rather long face and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.130#large mouth, fading complexion, and light hair. Pépé, also fair, in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.131#way of most children, clung closer to her, as if wanting to be caressed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.132#troubled and delighted at the sight of the beautiful ladies in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.133#window. They looked so strange, so charming, on the pavement, those
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.134#three fair ones, poorly dressed in black--the sad-looking young girl
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.135#between the pretty child and the handsome youth--that the passers-by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.136#looked back smilingly.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.137#For several minutes a stout man with grey hair and a large yellow
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.138#face, standing at a shop-door on the other side of the street, had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.139#been looking at them. He was standing there with bloodshot eyes and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.140#contracted mouth, beside himself with rage at the display made by The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.141#Ladies' Paradise, when the sight of the young girl and her brothers
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.142#completed his exasperation. What were those three simpletons doing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.143#there, gaping in front of the cheap-jack's parade?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.144#“What about uncle?” asked Denise, suddenly, as if just waking up.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.145#“We are in the Rue de la Michodière,” said Jean. “He must live somewhere
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.146#about here.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.147#They raised their heads and looked round. Just in front of them, above
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.148#the stout man, they perceived a green sign-board bearing in yellow
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.149#letters, discoloured by the rain: “The Old Elbeuf. Cloths, Flannels.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.150#Baudu, late Hauchecorne.” The house, coated with an ancient rusty
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.151#white-wash, quite flat and unadorned, amidst the mansions in the Louis
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.152#XIV. style which surrounded it, had only three front windows, and these
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.153#windows, square, without shutters, were simply ornamented by a handrail
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.154#and two iron bars in the form of a cross. But amidst all this nudity,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.155#what struck Denise the most, her eyes full of the light airy windows at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.156#The Ladies' Paradise, was the ground-floor shop, crushed by the ceiling,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.157#surmounted by a very low storey with half-moon windows, of a prison-like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.158#appearance. The wainscoting, of a bottle-green hue, which time had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.159#tinted with ochre and bitumen, encircled, right and left, two deep
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.160#windows, black and dusty, in which the heaped-up goods could hardly be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.161#seen. The open door seemed to lead into the darkness and dampness of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.162#cellar.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.163#[Illustration: 0021]
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.164#“That's the house,” said Jean.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.165#“Well, we must go in,” declared Denise. “Come on, Pepé.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.166#They appeared, however, somewhat troubled, as if seized with fear. When
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.167#their father died, carried off by the same fever which had, a month
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.168#previous, killed their mother, their uncle Baudu, in the emotion which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.169#followed this double mourning, had written to Denise, assuring her there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.170#would always be a place for her in his house whenever she would like to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.171#come to Paris. But this was nearly a year ago, and the young girl was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.172#now sorry to have left Valognes in a moment of temper without informing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.173#her uncle. The latter did not know them, never having set foot in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.174#Valognes since the day he left, as a boy, to enter as junior in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.175#drapery establishment kept by Hauchecorne, whose daughter he afterwards
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.176#married.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.177#“Monsieur Baudu?” asked Denise, deciding at last to speak to the stout
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.178#man who was still eyeing them, surprised at their appearance.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.179#“That's me,” replied he.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.180#Denise blushed and stammered out: “Oh, I'm so pleased! I am Denise. This
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.181#is Jean, and this is Pépé. You see we have come, uncle.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.182#Baudu seemed amazed. His big eyes rolled in his yellow face; he spoke
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.183#slowly and with difficulty. He was evidently far from thinking of this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.184#family which suddenly dropped down on him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.185#“What--what, you here?” repeated he several times. “But you were at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.186#Valognes. Why aren't you at Valognes?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.187#With her sweet but rather faltering voice she then explained that since
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.188#the death of her father, who had spent everything in his dye-works, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.189#had acted as a mother to the two children, but the little she earned at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.190#Cornaille's did not suffice to keep the three of them. Jeàn worked at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.191#a cabinetmaker's, a repairer of old furniture, but didn't earn a sou.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.192#However, he had got to like the business, and had learned to carve
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.193#in wood very well. One day, having found a piece of ivory, he amused
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.194#himself by carving a head, which a gentleman staying in the town had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.195#seen and admired, and it was this gentleman who had persuaded them to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.196#leave Valognes, promising to find a place in Paris for Jean with an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.197#ivory-carver.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.198#“So you see, uncle,” continued Denise, “Jean will commence his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.199#apprenticeship at his new master's to-morrow. They ask no premium, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.200#will board and lodge him. I felt sure Pépé and I could manage very well.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.201#We can't be worse off than we were at Valognes.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.202#She said nothing about Jean's love affair, of certain letters written to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.203#the daughter of a nobleman living in the town, of kisses exchanged over
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.204#a wall--in fact, quite a scandal which had determined her leaving. And
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.205#she was especially anxious to be in Paris, to be able to look after
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.206#her brother, feeling quite a mother's tender anxiety for this gay and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.207#handsome youth, whom all the women adored. Uncle Baudu couldn't get over
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.208#it, and continued his questions. However, when he heard her speaking of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.209#her brothers in this way he became much kinder.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.210#“So your father has left you nothing,” said he. “I certainly thought
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.211#there was still something left. Ah! how many times did I write advising
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.212#him not to take that dye-work! A good-hearted fellow, but no head for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.213#business! And you've been obliged to keep and look after these two
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.214#youngsters since?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.215#His bilious face had become clearer, his eyes were not so bloodshot as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.216#when he was glaring at The Ladies' Paradise. Suddenly he noticed that he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.217#was blocking up the doorway.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.218#“Well,” said he, “come in, now you're here. Come in, no use hanging
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.219#about gaping at a parcel of rubbish.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.220#And after having darted a last look of anger at The Ladies' Paradise, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.221#made way for the children by entering the shop and calling his wife and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.222#daughter. .
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.223#“Elizabeth, Geneviève, come down; here's company for you!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.224#But Denise and the two boys hesitated before the darkness of the shop.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.225#Blinded by the clear light of the street, they could hardly see. Feeling
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.226#their way with their feet with an instinctive fear of encountering some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.227#treacherous step, and clinging still closer together from this vague
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.228#fear, the child continuing to hold the young girl's skirts, and the big
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.229#boy behind, they made their entry with a smiling, anxious grace.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.230#The clear morning light described the dark profile of their mourning
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.231#clothes; an oblique ray of sunshine gilded their fair hair.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.232#“Come in, come in,” repeated Baudu.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.233#In a few brief sentences he explained the matter to his wife and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.234#daughter. The first was a little woman, eaten up with anaemia, quite
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.235#white--white hair, white eyes, white lips. Geneviève, in whom her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.236#mother's degenerateness appeared stronger still, had the debilitated,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.237#colourless appearance of a plant reared in the shade. However, her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.238#magnificent black hair, thick and heavy, marvellously vigorous for such
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.239#a weak, poor soil, gave her a sad charm.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.240#“Come in,” said both the women in their turn; “you are welcome.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.241#And they made Denise sit down behind a counter. Pépé immediately jumped
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.242#up on his sister's lap, whilst Jean leant against some wood-work beside
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.243#her. Looking round the shop the new-comers began to take courage, their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.244#eyes getting used to the obscurity. Now they could see it, with its low
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.245#and smoky ceiling, oaken counters bright with use, and old-fashioned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.246#drawers with strong iron fittings. Bales of goods reached to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.247#beams above; the smell of linen and dyed stuffs--a sharp chemical
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.248#smell--seemed intensified by the humidity of the floor. At the further
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.249#end two young men and a young woman were putting away pieces of white
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.250#flannel.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.251#“Perhaps this young gentleman would like to take something?” said Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.252#Baudu, smiling at Pépé.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.253#“No, thanks,” replied Denise, “we had a cup of milk in a café opposite
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.254#the station.” And as Geneviève looked at the small parcel she had laid
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.255#down, she added: “I left our box there too.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.256#She blushed, feeling that she ought not to have dropped down on her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.257#friends in this way. Even as she was leaving Valognes, she had been full
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.258#of regrets and fears; that was why she had left the box, and given the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.259#children their breakfast.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.260#“Come, come,” said Baudu suddenly, “let's come to an understanding.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.261#'Tis true I wrote to you, but that's a year ago, and since then
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.262#business hasn't been flourishing, I can assure you, my girl.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.263#He stopped, choked with an emotion he did not wish to show. Madame Baudu
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.264#and Geneviève, with a resigned look, had cast their eyes down.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.265#“Oh,” continued he, “it's a crisis which will pass, no doubt, but I have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.266#reduced my staff; there are only three here now, and this is not the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.267#moment to engage a fourth. In short, my dear girl, I cannot take you as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.268#I promised.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.269#Denise listened, and turned very pale. He dwelt upon the subject,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.270#adding: “It would do no good, either to you or to me.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.271#“All right, uncle,” replied she with a painful effort, “I'll try and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.272#manage all the same.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.273#The Baudus were not bad sort of people. But they complained of never
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.274#having had any luck. When their business was flourishing, they had had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.275#to bring up five sons, of whom three had died before attaining the age
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.276#of twenty; the fourth had gone wrong, and the fifth had just left for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.277#Mexico, as a captain. Genevieve was the only one left at home. But this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.278#large family had cost a great deal of money, and Baudu had made things
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.279#worse by buying a great lumbering country house, at Rambouillet, near
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.280#his wife's father's place. Thus, a sharp, sour feeling was springing up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.281#in the honest old tradesman's breast.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.282#“You might have warned us,” resumed he, gradually getting angry at his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.283#own harshness. “You could have written; I should have told you to stay
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.284#at Valognes. When I heard of your father's death I said what is right on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.285#such occasions, but you drop down on us without a word of warning. It's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.286#very awkward.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.287#He raised his voice, and that relieved him. His wife and daughter still
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.288#kept their eyes on the ground, like submissive persons who would never
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.289#think of interfering. However, whilst Jean had turned pale, Denise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.290#had hugged the terrified Pépé to her bosom. She dropped hot tears of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.291#disappointment.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.292#“All right, uncle,” she said, “we'll go away.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.293#At that he stopped, an awkward silence ensued. Then he resumed in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.294#harsh tone: “I don't mean to turn you out. As you are here you must stay
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.295#the night; to-morrow we will see.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.296#Then Madame Baudu and Genevieve understood they were free to arrange
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.297#matters. There was no need to trouble about Jean, as he was to commence
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.298#his apprenticeship the next day. As for Pépé, he would be well looked
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.299#after by Madame Gras, an old lady living in the Rue des Orties, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.300#boarded and lodged young children for forty francs a month. Denise said
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.301#she had sufficient to pay for the first month, and as for herself they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.302#could soon find her a situation in the neighbourhood, no doubt.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.303#“Wasn't Vinçard wanting a saleswoman?” asked Genevieve.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.304#“Of course!” cried Baudu; “we'll go and see him after lunch. Nothing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.305#like striking the iron while it's hot.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.306#Not a customer had been in to interrupt this family discussion; the shop
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.307#remained dark and empty. At the other end, the two young men and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.308#young women were still working, talking in a low hissing tone amongst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.309#themselves. However, three ladies arrived, and Denise was left alone for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.310#a moment. She kissed Pépé with a swelling heart, at the thought of their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.311#approaching separation. The child, affectionate as a kitten, hid his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.312#head without saying a word. When Madame Baudu and Geneviève returned,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.313#they remarked how quiet he was. Denise assured them he never made any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.314#more noise than that, remaining for days together without speaking,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.315#living on kisses and caresses. Until lunch-time the three women sat
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.316#and talked about children, housekeeping, life in Paris and life in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.317#the country, in short, vague sentences, like relations feeling rather
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.318#awkward through not knowing one another very well. Jean had gone to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.319#shop-door, and stood there watching the passing crowd and smiling at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.320#pretty girls. At ten o'clock a servant appeared. As a rule the cloth was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.321#laid for Baudu, Genevieve, and the first-hand. A second lunch was served
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.322#at eleven o'clock for Madame Baudu, the other young man, and the young
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.323#woman.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.324#“Come to lunch!” called out the draper, turning towards his niece. .
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.325#And as all sat ready in the narrow dining-room behind the shop, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.326#called the first-hand who had not come.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.327#“Colomban!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.328#The young man apologised, having wished to finish arranging the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.329#flannels. He was a big, stout fellow of twenty-five, heavy and freckled,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.330#with an honest face, large weak mouth, and cunning eyes.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.331#“There's a time for everything,” said Baudu, solidly seated before
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.332#a piece of cold veal, which he was carving with a master's skill and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.333#prudence, weighing each piece at a glance to within an ounce.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.334#He served everybody, and even cut up the bread. Denise had placed Pépé
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.335#near her to see that he ate properly. But the dark close room made
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.336#her feel uncomfortable. She thought it so small, after the large
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.337#well-lighted rooms she had been accustomed to in the country. A single
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.338#window opened on a small back-yard, which communicated with the street
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.339#by a dark alley along the side of the house. And this yard, sodden and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.340#filthy, was like the bottom of a well into which a glimmer of light had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.341#fallen. In the winter they were obliged to keep the gas burning all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.342#day long. When the weather enabled them to do without gas it was duller
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.343#still. Denise was several seconds before her eyes got sufficiently used
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.344#to the light to distinguish the food on her plate.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.345#“That young chap has a good appetite,” remarked Baudu, observing that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.346#Jean had finished his veal. “If he works as well as he eats, he'll make
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.347#a fine fellow. But you, my girl, you don't eat. And, I say, now we can
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.348#talk a bit, tell us why you didn't get married at Valognes?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.349#Denise almost dropped the glass she had in her hand. “Oh! uncle--get
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.350#married! How can you think of it? And the little ones!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.351#She was forced to laugh, it seemed to her such a strange idea. Besides,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.352#what man would care to have her--a girl without a sou, no fatter than
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.353#a lath, and not at all pretty? No, no, she would never marry, she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.354#quite enough children with her two brothers.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.355#“You are wrong,” said her uncle; “a woman always needs a man. If you had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.356#found an honest young fellow, you wouldn't have dropped on to the Paris
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.357#pavement, you and your brothers, like a family of gipsies.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.358#He stopped, to divide with a parsimony full of justice, a dish of bacon
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.359#and potatoes which the servant brought in. Then, pointing to Geneviève
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.360#and Colomban with his spoon, he added: “Those two will be married next
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.361#spring, if we have a good winter season.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.362#Such was the patriarchal custom of the house. The founder, Aristide
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.363#Finet, had given his daughter, Désirée to his firsthand, Hauchecorne;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.364#he, Baudu, who had arrived in the Rue de la Michodière with seven francs
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.365#in his pocket, had married old Hauchecorne's daughter, Elizabeth; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.366#he intended, in his turn, to hand over Geneviève and the business to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.367#Colomban as soon as trade should improve. If he thus delayed a marriage,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.368#decided on for three years past, it was by a scruple, an obstinate
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.369#probity. He had received the business in a prosperous state, and did
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.370#not wish to pass it on to his son-in-law less patronised or in a worse
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.371#position than when he took it. Baudu continued, introducing Colomban,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.372#who came from Rambouillet, the same place as Madame Baudu's father; in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.373#fact they were distant cousins. A hard-working fellow, who for ten years
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.374#had slaved in the shop, fairly earning his promotions! Besides, he was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.375#far from being a nobody; he had for father that noted toper, Colomban,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.376#a veterinary surgeon, known all over the department of Seine-et-Oise, an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.377#artist in his line, but so fond of the flowing bowl that he was ruining
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.378#himself.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.379#“Thank heaven!” said the draper in conclusion, “if the father drinks and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.380#runs after the women, the son has learnt the value of money here.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.381#Whilst he was speaking Denise was examining Genevieve and Colomban. They
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.382#sat close together at table, but remained very quiet, without a blush
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.383#or a smile. From the day of his entry the young man had counted on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.384#this marriage. He had passed through the various stages: junior,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.385#counter-hand, etc., and had at last gained admittance into the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.386#confidence and pleasures of the family circle, all this patiently, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.387#leading a clock-work style of life, looking upon this marriage with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.388#Geneviève as an excellent, convenient arrangement. The certainty of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.389#having her prevented him feeling any desire for her. And the young girl
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.390#had also got to love him, but with the gravity of her reserved nature,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.391#and a real deep passion of which she herself was not aware, in her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.392#regular, monotonous daily life.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.393#“Quite right, if they like each other, and can do it,” said Denise,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.394#smiling, considering it her duty to make herself agreeable.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.395#“Yes, it always finishes like that,” declared Colomban, who had not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.396#spoken a word before, masticating slowly.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.397#Geneviève, after giving him a long look, said in her turn: “When people
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.398#understand each other, the rest comes naturally.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.399#Their tenderness had sprung up in this gloomy house of old Paris like a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.400#flower in a cellar. For ten years she had known no one but him, living
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.401#by his side, behind the same bales of cloth, amidst the darkness of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.402#shop; morning and evening they found themselves elbow to elbow in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.403#narrow dining-room, so damp and dull. They could not have been more
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.404#concealed, more utterly lost had they been in the country, in the woods.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.405#But a doubt, a jealous fear, began to suggest itself to the young girl,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.406#that she had given her hand, for ever, amidst this abetting solitude
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.407#through sheer emptiness of heart and mental weariness.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.408#However, Denise, having remarked a growing anxiety in the look Geneviève
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.409#cast at Colomban, good-naturedly replied: “Oh! when people are in love
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.410#they always understand each other.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.411#But Baudu kept a sharp eye on the table. He had distributed slices of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.412#Brie cheese, and, as a treat for the visitors, he called for a second
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.413#dessert, a pot of red-currant jam, a liberality which seemed to surprise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.414#Colomban. Pépé, who up to then had been very good, behaved rather
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.415#badly at the sight of the jam; whilst Jean, all attention during the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.416#conversation about Genevieve's marriage, was taking stock of the latter,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.417#whom he thought too weak, too pale, comparing her in his own mind to a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.418#little white rabbit with black ears and pink eyes.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.419#“We've chatted enough, and must now make room for the others,” said the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.420#draper, giving the signal to rise from table. “Just because we've had a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.421#treat is no reason why we should want too much of it.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.422#Madame Baudu, the other shopman, and the young lady then came and took
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.423#their places at the table. Denise, left alone again, sat near the door
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.424#waiting for her uncle to take her to Vinçard's.. Pépé was playing at her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.425#feet, whilst Jean had resumed his post of observation at the door. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.426#sat there for nearly an hour, taking an interest in what was going on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.427#around her. Now and again a few customers came in; a lady, then two
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.428#others appeared, the shop retaining its musty odour, its half light, by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.429#which the old-fashioned business, good-natured and simple, seemed to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.430#be weeping at its desertion. But what most interested Denise was The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.431#Ladies' Paradise opposite, the windows of which she could see through
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.432#the open door. The sky remained clouded, a sort of humid softness warmed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.433#the air, notwithstanding the season; and in this clear light, in which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.434#there was, as it were, a hazy diffusion of sunshine, the great shop
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.435#seemed alive and in full activity.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.436#Denise began to feel as if she were watching a machine working at full
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.437#pressure, communicating its movement even as far as the windows. They
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.438#were no longer the cold windows she had seen in the early morning; they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.439#seemed to be warm and vibrating from the activity within. There was a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.440#crowd before them, groups of women pushing and squeezing, devouring the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.441#finery with longing, covetous eyes. And the stuffs became animated in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.442#this passionate atmosphere: the laces fluttered, drooped, and concealed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.443#the depths of the shop with a troubling air of mystery; even the lengths
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.444#of cloth, thick and heavy, exhaled a tempting odour, while the cloaks
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.445#threw out their folds over the dummies, which assumed a soul, and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.446#great velvet mantle particularly, expanded, supple and warm, as if on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.447#real fleshly shoulders, with a heaving of the bosom and a trembling of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.448#the hips. But the furnace-like glow which the house exhaled came above
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.449#all from the sale, the crush at the counters, that could be felt behind
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.450#the walls. There was the continual roaring of the machine at work, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.451#marshalling of the customers, bewildered amidst the piles of goods, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.452#finally pushed along to the pay-desk. And all that went on in an orderly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.453#manner, with mechanical regularity, quite a nation of women passing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.454#through the force and logic of this wonderful commercial machine.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.455#Denise had felt herself being tempted all day. She was bewildered and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.456#attracted by this shop, to her so vast, in which she saw more people in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.457#an hour than she had seen at Cornaille's in six months; and there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.458#was mingled with her desire to enter it a vague sense of danger which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.459#rendered the seduction complete. At the same time her uncle's shop made
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.460#her feel ill at ease; she felt an unreasonable disdain, an instinctive
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.461#repugnance for this cold, icy place, the home of old-fashioned trading.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.462#All her sensations--her anxious entry, her friends' cold reception, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.463#dull lunch eaten in a prison-like atmosphere, her waiting amidst the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.464#sleepy solitude of this old house doomed to a speedy decay--all these
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.465#sensations reproduced themselves in her mind under the form of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.466#dumb protestation, a passionate longing for life and light. And
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.467#notwithstanding her really tender heart, her eyes turned to The Ladies'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.468#Paradise, as if the saleswoman within her felt the need to go and warm
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.469#herself at the glow of this immense business.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.470#“Plenty of customers over there!” was the remark that escaped her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.471#But she regretted her words on seeing the Baudus near her. Madame Baudu,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.472#who had finished her lunch, was standing up, quite white, with her pale
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.473#eyes fixed on the monster; every time she caught sight of this place, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.474#mute, blank despair swelled her heart, and filled her eyes with scalding
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.475#tears. As for Geneviève, she was anxiously watching Colomban, who,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.476#not supposing he was being observed, stood in ecstasy, looking at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.477#handsome young saleswomen in the dress department opposite, the counter
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.478#being visible through the first floor window. Baudu, his anger rising,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.479#merely said:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.480#“All is not gold that glitters. Patience!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.481#The thought of his family evidently kept back the flood of rancour which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.482#was rising in his throat A feeling of pride prevented him displaying
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.483#his temper before these children, only that morning arrived. At last the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.484#draper made an effort, and tore himself away from the spectacle of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.485#sale opposite.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.486#“Well!” resumed he, “we'll go and see Vinçard. These situations are soon
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.487#snatched up; it might be too late tomorrow.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.488#But before going out he ordered the junior to go to the station and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.489#fetch Denise's box. Madame. Baudu, to whom the young girl had confided
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.490#Pépé, decided to run over and see Madame Gras, to arrange about the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.491#child. Jean promised his sister not to stir from the shop.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.492#“It's two minutes' walk,” explained Baudu as they went down the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.493#Gaillon; “Vinçard has a silk business, and still does a fair trade. Of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.494#course he suffers, like every one else, but he's an artful fellow, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.495#makes both ends meet by his miserly ways. I fancy, though, he wants to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.496#retire, on account of his rheumatics.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.497#The shop was in the Rue Neuve-des-Petits-Champs, near, the Passage
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.498#Choiseul. It was clean and light, well fitted up in the modern style,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.499#but rather small, and contained but a poor stock. They found Vinçard in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.500#consultation with two gentlemen.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.501#“Never mind us,” called out the draper; “we are in no hurry; we can
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.502#wait.” And returning to the door he whispered to Denise: “The thin
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.503#fellow is at The Paradise, second in the silk department, and the stout
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.504#man is a silk manufacturer from Lyons.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.505#Denise gathered that Vinçard was trying to sell his business to Robineau
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.506#of The Paradise. He was giving his word of honour in a frank open way,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.507#with the facility of a man who could take any number of oaths without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.508#the slightest trouble. According to his account, the business was a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.509#golden one; and in the splendour of his rude health he interrupted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.510#himself to whine and complain of those infernal pains which prevented
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.511#him stopping and making his fortune. But Robineau, nervous and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.512#tormented, interrupted him impatiently. He knew what a crisis the trade
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.513#was passing through, and named a silk warehouse already ruined by The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.514#Paradise. Vinçard, inflamed, raised his voice.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.515#“No wonder! The fall of that great booby of a Vabre was certain. His
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.516#wife spent everything he earned. Besides, we are more than five hundred
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.517#yards away, whilst Vabre was almost next door to The Paradise.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.518#Gaujean, the silk manufacturer, then chimed in, and their voices fell
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.519#again. He accused the big establishments of ruining French manufacture;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.520#three or four laid down the law, reigning like masters over the market;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.521#and he gave it as his opinion that the only way of fighting them was to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.522#favour the small traders; above all, those who dealt in special classes
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.523#of goods, to whom the future belonged. Therefore he offered Robineau
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.524#plenty of credit.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.525#“See how you have been treated at The Paradise,” said he. “No notice
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.526#taken of your long service. You had the promise of the first-hand's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.527#place long ago, when Bouthemont, an outsider without any claim, came in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.528#and got it at once.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.529#Robineau was still smarting under this injustice. However, he hesitated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.530#to start on his own account, explaining that the money came from his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.531#wife, a legacy of sixty thousand francs she had just inherited, and he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.532#was full of scruples regarding this sum, saying that he would rather cut
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.533#off his right hand than compromise her money in a doubtful affair.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.534#“No,” said he, “I haven't made up my mind; give me time to think over
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.535#it. We'll have another talk about it.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.536#“As you like,” replied Vinçard, concealing his disappointment under a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.537#smiling countenance. “It's to my interest not to sell; and were it not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.538#for my rheumatics----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.539#And returning to the middle of the shop, he asked: “What can I do for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.540#you, Monsieur Baudu?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.541#The draper, who had been listening with one ear, introduced Denise, told
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.542#him as much as he thought necessary of her story, adding that she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.543#two years' country experience.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.544#“And as I have heard you are wanting a good saleswoman----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.545#Vinçard affected to be awfully sorry. “What an unfortunate thing!” said
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.546#he. “I have, indeed, been looking for a saleswoman all the week; but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.547#I've just engaged one--not two hours ago.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.548#A silence ensued. Denise seemed disheartened. Robineau, who was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.549#looking at her with interest, probably inspired with pity by her poor
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.550#appearance, ventured to say:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.551#“I know they're wanting a young person at our place, in the ready-made
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.552#dress department.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.553#Baudu could not help crying out fervently: “At your place? Never!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.554#Then he stopped, embarrassed. Denise had turned very red; she would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.555#never dare enter that great place, and yet the idea of being there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.556#filled her with pride.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.557#“Why not?” asked Robineau, surprised. “It would be a good opening
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.558#for the young lady. I advise her to go and see Madame. Aurélie, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.559#first-hand, to-morrow. The worst that can happen to her is not to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.560#accepted.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.561#The draper, to conceal his inward revolt, began to talk vaguely. He knew
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.562#Madame Aurélie, or, at least, her husband, Lhomme, the cashier, a stout
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.563#man, who had had his right arm severed by an omnibus. Then turning
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.564#suddenly to Denise, he added: “However, that's her business. She can do
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.565#as she likes.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.566#And he went out, after having said “good-day” to Gaujean and Robineau.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.567#Vinçard went with him as far as the door, reiterating his regrets. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.568#young girl had remained in the middle of the shop, intimidated, desirous
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.569#of asking Robineau for further particulars. But not daring to, she in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.570#her turn bowed, and simply said: “Thank you, sir.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.571#On the way back Baudu said nothing to his niece, but walked very fast,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.572#forcing her to run to keep up with him, as if carried away by his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.573#reflections. Arrived in the Rue de la Michodière, he was going into his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.574#shop, when a neighbouring shopkeeper, standing at his door, called him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.575#Denise stopped and waited.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.576#“What is it, old Bourras?” asked the draper.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.577#Bourras was a tall old man, with a prophet's head, bearded and hairy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.578#and piercing eyes under thick and bushy eyebrows. He kept an umbrella
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.579#and walking-stick shop, did repairs, and even carved handles, which had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.580#won for him an artistic celebrity in the neighbourhood. Denise glanced
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.581#at the shop-window, where the umbrellas and sticks were arranged in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.582#straight lines. But on raising her eyes she was astonished at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.583#appearance of the house, a hovel squeezed between The Ladies' Paradise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.584#and a large building of the Louis XIV. style, sprung up one hardly knew
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.585#how, in this narrow space, crushed by its two low storeys. Had it not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.586#been for the support on each side it must have fallen; the slates were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.587#old and rotten, and the two-windowed front was cracked and covered
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.588#with stains, which ran down in long rusty lines over the worm-eaten
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.589#sign-board.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.590#“You know he's written to my landlord, offering to buy the house?” said
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.591#Bourras, looking steadily at the draper with his fiery eyes.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.592#Baudu became paler still, and bent his shoulders. There was a silence,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.593#during which the two men remained face to face, looking very serious.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.594#“Must be prepared for anything now,” murmured Baudu at last.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.595#Bourras then got angry, shaking his hair and flowing board. “Let him buy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.596#the house, he'll have to pay four times the value for it! But I swear
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.597#that as long as I live he shall not touch a stone of it. My lease has
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.598#twelve years to run yet. We shall see! we shall see!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.599#It was a declaration of war. Bourras looked towards The Ladies'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.600#Paradise, which neither had directly named. Baudu shook his head in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.601#silence, and then crossed the street to his shop, his legs almost
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.602#failing under him. “Ah! good Lord! ah! good Lord!” he kept repeating.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.603#Denise, who had heard all, followed her uncle. Madame Baudu had just
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.604#come back with Pépé, whom Madame Gras had agreed to receive at anytime.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.605#But Jean had disappeared, and this made his sister anxious. When
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.606#he returned with a flushed face, talking in an animated way of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.607#boulevards, she looked at him with such a sad expression that he blushed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.608#with shame. The box had arrived, and it was arranged that they should
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.609#sleep in the attic.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.610#“How did you get on at Vinçard's?” asked Madame Baudu, suddenly.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.611#The draper related his useless errand, adding that Denise had heard of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.612#a situation; and, pointing to The Ladies' Paradise with a scornful
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.613#gesture, he cried out: “There--in there!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.614#The whole family felt wounded at the idea. The first dinner was at five
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.615#o'clock. Denise and the two children took their places, with Baudu,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.616#Geneviève, and Colomban. A single jet of gas lighted and warmed the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.617#little dining-room, reeking with the smell of hot food. The meal
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.618#passed off in silence, but at dessert Madame Baudu, who could not rest
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.619#anywhere, left the shop, and came and sat down near Denise. And then the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.620#storm, kept back all day, broke out, every one feeling a certain relief
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.621#in abusing the monster.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.622#“It's your business, you can do as you like,” repeated Baudu. “We
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.623#don't want to influence you. But if you only knew what sort of place it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.624#is----” And he commenced to relate, in broken sentences, the history of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.625#this Octave Mouret. Wonderful luck! A fellow who had come up from the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.626#South of France with the amiable audacity of an adventurer; no sooner
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.627#arrived than he commenced to distinguish himself by all sorts of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.628#disgraceful pranks with the ladies; had figured in an affair, which was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.629#still the talk of the neighbourhood; and to crown all, had suddenly and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.630#mysteriously made the conquest of Madame Hédouin, who brought him The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.631#Ladies' Paradise as a marriage portion.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.632#“Poor Caroline!” interrupted Madame Baudu. “We were distantly related.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.633#If she had lived things would be different. She wouldn't have let them
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.634#ruin us like this. And he's the man who killed her. Yes, that very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.635#building! One morning, when visiting the works, she fell down a hole,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.636#and three days after she died. A fine, strong, healthy woman, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.637#had never known what illness was! There's some of her blood in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.638#foundation of that house.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.639#She pointed to the establishment opposite with her pale and trembling
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.640#hand. Denise, listening as to a fairy tale, slightly shuddered; the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.641#sense of fear which had mingled with the temptation she had felt since
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.642#the morning, was caused perhaps by the presence of this woman's blood,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.643#which she fancied she could see in the red mortar of the basement.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.644#“It seems as if it brought him good luck,” added Madame Baudu, without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.645#mentioning Mouret by name.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.646#But the draper shrugged his shoulders, disdaining these old women's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.647#tales, and resumed his story, explaining the situation commercially. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.648#Ladies' Paradise was founded in 1822 by two brothers, named Deleuze.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.649#On the death of the elder, his daughter, Caroline, married the son of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.650#a linen manufacturer, Charles Hédouin; and, later on, becoming a widow,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.651#she married Mouret. She thus brought him a half share of the business.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.652#Three months after the marriage, the second brother Deleuze died
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.653#childless; so that when Caroline met her death, Mouret became sole heir,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.654#sole proprietor of The Ladies' Paradise. Wonderful luck!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.655#“A sharp fellow, a dangerous busybody, who will overthrow the whole
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.656#neighborhood if allowed to!” continued Baudu. “I fancy that Caroline,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.657#a rather romantic woman, must have been carried away by the gentleman's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.658#extravagant ideas. In short, he persuaded her to buy the house on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.659#left, then the one on the right; and he himself, on becoming his own
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.660#master, bought two others; so that the establishment has continued to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.661#grow--extending in such a way that it now threatens to swallow us all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.662#up!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.663#He was addressing Denise, but was really speaking more to himself,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.664#feeling a feverish longing to go over this history which haunted him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.665#continually. At home he was always angry, always violent, clenching
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.666#his fists as if longing to go for somebody. Madame Baudu ceased to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.667#interfere, sitting motionless on her chair; Genevieve and Colomban,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.668#their eyes cast down, were picking up and eating the crumbs off the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.669#table, just for the sake of something to do. It was so warm, so stuffy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.670#in the small room, that Pépé was sleeping with his head on the table,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.671#and even Jean's eyes were closing.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.672#“Wait a bit!” resumed Baudu, seized with a sudden fit of anger, “such
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.673#jokers always go to smash! Mouret is hard-pushed just now; I know that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.674#for a fact. He's been forced to spend all his savings on his mania for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.675#extensions and advertisements. Moreover, in order to raise money, he has
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.676#induced most of his shop-people to invest all they possess with him. So
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.677#that he hasn't a sou to help himself with now; and, unless a miracle be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.678#worked, and he treble his sales, as he hopes to do, you'll see what a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.679#crash there'll be! Ah! I'm not ill-natured, but that day I'll illuminate
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.680#my shop-front, on my word of honour!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.681#And he went on in a revengeful voice; one would have thought that the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.682#fall of The Ladies' Paradise was to restore the dignity and prestige
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.683#of compromised business. Had any one ever seen such a thing? A draper's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.684#shop selling everything! Why not call it a bazaar at once? And the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.685#employees! a nice set they were too--a lot of puppies, who did their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.686#work like porters at a railway station, treating goods and customers
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.687#like so many parcels; leaving the shop or getting the sack at a moment's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.688#notice. No affection, no manners, no taste! And all at once he quoted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.689#Colomban as an example of a good tradesman, brought up in the old
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.690#school, knowing how long it took to learn all the cunning and tricks of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.691#the trade. The art was not to sell a large quantity, but to sell dear.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.692#Colomban could say how he had been treated, carefully looked after, his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.693#washing and mending done, nursed in illness, considered as one of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.694#family--loved, in fact!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.695#“Of course,” repeated Colomban, after every statement the governor made.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.696#“Ah, you're the last of the old stock,” Baudu ended by declaring. “After
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.697#you're gone there'll be none left. You are my sole consolation, for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.698#if they call all this sort of thing business I give up, I would rather
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.699#clear out.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.700#Geneviève, her head on one side, as if her thick hair were too heavy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.701#for her pale forehead, was watching the smiling shopman; and in her look
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.702#there was a suspicion, a wish to see whether Colomban, stricken with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.703#remorse, would not blush at all this praise. But, like a fellow up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.704#to every trick of the old trade, he preserved his quiet manner, his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.705#good-natured and cunning look. However, Baudu still went on, louder than
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.706#ever, condemning the people opposite, calling them a pack of savages,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.707#murdering each other in their struggle for existence, destroying
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.708#all family ties. And he mentioned some country neighbours, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.709#Lhommes--mother, father, and son--all employed in the infernal shop,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.710#people without any home life, always out, leading a comfortless, savage
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.711#existence, never dining at home except on Sunday, feeding all the week
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.712#at restaurants, hotels, anywhere. Certainly his dining-room wasn't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.713#too large nor too well-lighted; but it was part of their home, and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.714#family had grown up affectionately about the domestic hearth. Whilst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.715#speaking his eyes wandered about the room; and he shuddered at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.716#unavowed idea that the savages might one day, if they, succeeded
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.717#in ruining his trade, turn him out of this house where he was so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.718#comfortable with his wife and child. Notwithstanding the assurance
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.719#with which he predicted the utter downfall of his rivals, he was really
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.720#terrified, feeling that the neighbourhood was being gradually invaded
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.721#and devoured.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.722#“I don't want to disgust you,” resumed he, trying to calm himself; “if
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.723#you think it to your interest to go there, I shall be the first to say,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.724#'go.'”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.725#“I am sure of that, uncle,” murmured Denise, bewildered, all this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.726#excitement rendering her more and more desirous of entering The Ladies'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.727#Paradise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.728#He had put his elbows on the table, and was staring at her so hard
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.729#that she felt uneasy. “But look here,” resumed he; “you who know the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.730#business, do you think it right that a simple draper's shop should sell
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.731#everything? Formerly, when trade was trade, drapers sold nothing but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.732#drapery. Now they are doing their best to snap up every branch and ruin
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.733#their neighbours. The whole neighbourhood complains of it, for every
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.734#small tradesman is beginning to suffer terribly. This Mouret is ruining
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.735#them. Bédoré and his sister, who keep the hosiery shop in the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.736#Gaillon, have already lost half their customers; Mademoiselle Tatin, at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.737#the under-linen warehouse in the Passage Choiseul, has been obliged to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.738#lower her prices, to be able to sell at all. And the effects of this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.739#scourge, this pest, are felt as far as the Rue Neuve-des-Petits-Champs,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.740#where I hear that Vanpouille Brothers, the furriers, cannot hold
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.741#out much longer. Drapers selling fur goods--what a farce! another of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.742#Mouret's ideas!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.743#“And gloves,” added Madame Baudu; “isn't it monstrous? He has even
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.744#dared to add a glove department! Yesterday, as I was going along the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.745#Neuve-Saint-Augustin, I saw Quinette, the glover, at his door, looking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.746#so downcast that I hadn't the heart to ask him how business was going.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.747#“And umbrellas,” resumed Baudu; “that's the climax! Bourras feels sure
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.748#that Mouret simply wants to ruin him; for, in short, where's the rhyme
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.749#between umbrellas and drapery? But Bourras is firm on his legs, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.750#won't allow himself to be beggared. We shall see some fun one of these
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.751#days.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.752#He spoke of other tradesmen, passing the whole neigbour-hood in review.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.753#Now and again he let slip a confession. If Vinçard wanted to sell it was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.754#time for the rest to pack up, for Vinçard was like the rats who leave
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.755#a house when it threatens to fall in. Then, immediately after, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.756#contradicted himself, alluded to an alliance, an understanding between
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.757#the small tradesmen in order to fight the colossus. He hesitated an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.758#instant before speaking of himself, his hands shaking, and his mouth
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.759#twitching in a nervous manner. At last he made up his mind.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.760#“As for myself, I can't complain as yet. Of course he has done me harm,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.761#the scoundrel! But up to the present he only keeps ladies' cloths, light
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.762#stuffs for dresses and heavier goods for mantles. People still come to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.763#me for men's goods, velvets for shooting suits, cloths for liveries,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.764#without speaking of flannels and serges, of which I defy him to show
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.765#as good an assortment. But he thinks to annoy me by planting his cloth
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.766#department right in front of my door. You've seen his display, haven't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.767#you? He always places his finest made-up goods there, surrounded by a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.768#framework of various cloths--a cheap-jack parade to tempt the women.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.769#Upon my word, I should be ashamed to use such means! The Old Elbeuf has
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.770#been known for nearly a hundred years, and has no need for such at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.771#its door. As long as I live, it shall remain as I took it, with a few
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.772#samples on each side, and nothing more!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.773#The whole family was affected. Geneviève ventured to make a remark after
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.774#a silence:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.775#“You know, papa, our customers know and like us. We mustn't lose
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.776#heart Madame Desforges and Madame de Boves have been to-day, and I am
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.777#expecting Madame Marty for some flannel.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.778#“I,” declared Colomban, “I took an order from Madame Bourdelais
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.779#yesterday. 'Tis true she spoke of an English cheviot marked up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.780#opposite ten sous cheaper than ours, and the same stuff, it appears.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.781#“Fancy,” murmured Madame Baudu in her weak voice, “we knew that house
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.782#when it was scarcely larger than a handkerchief! Yes, my dear Denise,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.783#when the Deleuzes started it, it had only one window in the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.784#Neuve-Saint-Augustin; and such a tiny one, in which there was barely
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.785#room for a couple of pieces of print and two or three pieces of calico.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.786#There was no room to turn round in the shop, it was so small. At that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.787#time The Old Elbeuf, after sixty years' trading, was as you see it now.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.788#Ah! all that has greatly changed!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.789#She shook her head; the drama of her whole life was expressed in these
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.790#few words. Born in the old house, she loved every part of it, living
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.791#only for it and by it; and, formerly proud of this house, the finest,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.792#the best patronised in the neighbourhood, she had had the daily grief of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.793#seeing the rival establishment gradually growing in importance, at first
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.794#disdained, then equal to theirs, and finally towering above it, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.795#threatening all the rest. This was for her a continual, open sore; she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.796#was slowly dying from sheer grief at seeing The Old Elbeuf humiliated,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.797#though still living, as if by the force of impulse, like a machine wound
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.798#up. But she felt that the death of the shop would be hers as well, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.799#that she would never survive the closing of it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.800#There was a painful silence. Baudu was softly beating a tattoo with his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.801#fingers on the American cloth on the table. He experienced a sort of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:i.802#lassitude, almost a regret at having relieved his feelings once more in
