urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.108#occupied in his life; he contented himself with encouraging the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.109#extravagance of his lady customers, feeling the greatest disdain for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.110#their frivolity, which led them to ruin themselves in stupid gewgaws.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.111#Mouret, on the contrary, affected to worship them, remained before them
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.112#delighted and cajoling, continually carried away by fresh love-affairs;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.113#and this served as an advertisement for his business. One would have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.114#said that he enveloped all the women in the same caress, the better to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.115#bewilder them and keep them at his mercy.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.116#“I saw Madame Desforges last night,” said he; “she was looking delicious
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.117#at the ball.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.118#“But it wasn't with her that you went to supper, was it?” asked the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.119#other.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.120#Mouret protested. “Oh! no, she's very virtuous, my dear fellow. I went
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.121#to supper with little Héloïse, of the Folly. Stupid as a donkey, but so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.122#comical!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.123#He took another bundle of drafts and went on signing. Bourdoncle
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.124#continued to walk about. He went and took a look through the lofty
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.125#plate-glass windows, into the Rue Neuve-Saint-Augustin, then returned,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.126#saying: “You know they'll have their revenge.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.127#“Who?” asked Mouret, who had lost the thread of the conversation.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.128#“Why, the women.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.129#At this, Mouret became merrier still, displaying, beneath his sensual,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.130#adorative manner, his really brutal character. With a shrug of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.131#shoulders he seemed to declare he would throw them all over, like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.132#so many empty sacks, when they had finished helping him to make his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.133#fortune. Bourdoncle obstinately repeated, in his cold way: “They will
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.134#have their revenge; there will be one who will avenge all the others.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.135#It's bound to be.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.136#“No fear,” cried Mouret, exaggerating his Southern accent. “That one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.137#isn't born yet, my boy. And if she comes, you know----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.138#He had raised his penholder, brandishing it and pointing it in the air,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.139#as if he would have liked to stab some invisible heart with a knife.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.140#Bourdoncle resumed walking, bowing as usual before the superiority of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.141#the governor, whose genius, though faulty, had always got the better of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.142#him. He, so clear-headed, logical and passionless, incapable of falling,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.143#had yet to learn the feminine character of success, Paris yielding
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.144#herself with a kiss to the boldest.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.145#A silence reigned, broken only by Mouret's pen. Then, in reply to his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.146#brief questions, Bourdoncle gave him the particulars of the great sale
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.147#of winter novelties, which was to commence the following Monday. This
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.148#was an important affair, and the house was risking its fortune in it;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.149#for the rumour had some foundation, Mouret was throwing himself into
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.150#speculation like a poet, with such ostentation, such a determination to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.151#attain the colossal, that everything seemed bound to give way under
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.152#him. It was quite a new style of doing business, an apparent commercial
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.153#recklessness which had formerly made Madame Hédouin anxious, and which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.154#even now, notwithstanding the first successes, quite dismayed those
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.155#who had capital in the business. They blamed the governor in secret for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.156#going too quick; accused him of having enlarged the establishment to a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.157#dangerous extent, before making sure of a sufficient increase of custom;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.158#above all, they trembled on seeing him put all the capital into one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.159#venture, filling the place with a pile of goods without leaving a sou in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.160#the reserve fund. Thus, for this sale, after the heavy sums paid to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.161#builders, the whole capital was out, and it was once more a question of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.162#victory or death. And he, in the midst of all this excitement, preserved
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.163#a triumphant gaiety, a certainty of gaining millions, like a man
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.164#worshipped by the women, and who cannot be betrayed. When Bourdoncle
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.165#ventured to express certain fears with reference to the too great
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.166#development given to several not very productive departments, he broke
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.167#out into a laugh full of confidence, and exclaimed:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.168#“No fear! my dear fellow, the place is too small!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.169#The other appeared dumbfounded, seized with a fear he no longer
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.170#attempted to conceal. The house too small! a draper's shop having
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.171#nineteen departments, and four hundred and three employees!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.172#“Of course,” resumed Mouret, “we shall be obliged to enlarge our
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.173#premises before another eighteen months. I'm seriously thinking about
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.174#the matter. Last night Madame Desforges promised to introduce me to some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.175#one. In short, we'll talk it over when the idea is ripe.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.176#And having finished signing his drafts, he got up, and tapped his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.177#lieutenant on the shoulder in a friendly manner, but the latter could
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.178#not get over his astonishment. The fright felt by the prudent people
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.179#around him amused Mouret. In one of his fits of brusque frankness with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.180#which he sometimes overwhelmed his familiars, he declared he was at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.181#heart a bigger Jew than all the Jews in the world; he took after his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.182#father, whom he resembled physically and morally, a fellow who knew
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.183#the value of money; and, if his mother had given him that particle of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.184#nervous fantasy, why it was, perhaps, the principal element of his luck,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.185#for he felt the invincible force of his daring reckless grace.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.186#“You know very well that we'll stand by you to the last,” Bourdoncle
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.187#finished by saying.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.188#Before going down into the various departments to give their usual look
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.189#round, they settled certain other details. They examined the specimen of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.190#a little book of account forms, which Mouret had just invented for use
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.191#at the counters. Having remarked that the old-fashioned goods, the dead
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.192#stock, went off all the more rapidly when the commission given to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.193#employees was high, he had based on this observation a new system. In
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.194#future he intended to interest his people in the sale of all goods,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.195#giving them a commission on the smallest piece of stuff, the slightest
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.196#article sold: a system which had caused a revolution in the drapery
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.197#trade, creating between the salespeople a struggle for existence of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.198#which the proprietor reaped the benefit. This struggle formed his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.199#favourite method, the principle of organisation he constantly applied.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.200#He excited his employees' passions, pitted one against the other,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.201#allowed the strongest to swallow up the weakest, fattening on this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.202#interested struggle. The specimen book was approved of; at the top
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.203#of the two forms--the one retained, and the one torn off--were the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.204#particulars of the department and the salesman's number; then there were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.205#columns on both for the measurement, description of the articles sold,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.206#and the price; the salesman simply signed the bill before handing it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.207#to the cashier. In this way an easy account was kept, it sufficed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.208#to compare the bills delivered by the cashier's department to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.209#clearing-house with the salesmen's counterfoils. Every week the latter
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.210#would receive their commission, and that without the least possibility
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.211#of any error.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.212#“We sha'n't be robbed so much,” remarked Bourdoncle, with satisfaction.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.213#“A very good idea of yours.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.214#“And I thought of something else last night,” explained Mouret. “Yes,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.215#my dear fellow, at the supper. I should like to give the clearing-house
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.216#clerks a trifle for every error found in checking. You can understand
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.217#that we shall then be certain they won't pass any, for they would rather
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.218#invent some.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.219#He began to laugh, whilst the other looked at him in admiration. This
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.220#new application of the struggle for existence delighted Mouret; he had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.221#a real genius for administrative business, and dreamed of organising the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.222#house, so as to play upon the selfish instincts of his employees, for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.223#the complete and quiet satisfaction of his own appetites. He often said
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.224#that to make people do their best, and even to keep them fairly honest,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.225#it was necessary to excite their selfish desires first.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.226#“Well, let's go downstairs,” resumed Mouret. “We must look after this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.227#sale. The silk arrived yesterday, I believe, and Bouthemont must be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.228#getting it in now.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.229#Bourdoncle followed him. The receiving office was on the basement floor,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.230#in the Rue Neuve-Saint-Augustin. There, on a level with the pavement,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.231#was a kind of glazed cage, where the vans discharged the goods. They
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.232#were weighed, and then slipped down a rapid slide, its oak and iron
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.233#work shining, brightened by the chafing of goods and cases. Everything
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.234#entered by this yawning trap; it was a continual swallowing up, a fall
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.235#of goods, causing a roaring like that of a cataract. At the approach of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.236#big sale times especially, the slide carried down a perpetual stream of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.237#Lyons silks, English woollens, Flemish linens, Alsatian calicoes, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.238#Rouen printed goods; and the vans were sometimes obliged to wait their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.239#turn along the street; the bales running down produced the peculiar
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.240#noise made by a stone thrown into deep water.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.241#Mouret stopped a moment before the slide, which was in full activity.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.242#Rows of cases were going down of themselves, falling like rain from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.243#some upper stream. Then some huge bales appeared, toppling over in their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.244#descent like so many pebbles. Mouret looked on, without saying a word.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.245#But this wealth of goods rushing in at the rate of thousands of francs
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.246#a minute, made his eyes glisten. He had never before had such a clear,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.247#definite idea of the struggle he was engaged in. Here was this mountain
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.248#of goods that he had to launch to the four corners of Paris. He did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.249#open his mouth, continuing his inspection.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.250#By the grey light penetrating the air-holes, a squad of men were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.251#receiving the goods, whilst others were undoing and opening the cases
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.252#and bales in presence of the managers of different departments. A
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.253#dockyard agitation filled this cellar, this basement, where wrought-iron
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.254#pillars supported the arches, and the bare walls of which were cemented.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.255#“Have you got all there, Bouthemont?” asked Mouret, going up to a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.256#broad-shouldered young fellow who was check» ing the contents of a case.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.257#“Yes, everything seems all right,” replied he; “but the counting will
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.258#take me all the morning.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.259#The manager was glancing at the invoice every now and then, standing up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.260#before a large counter on which one of his salesmen was laying, one by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.261#one, the pieces of silk he was taking from the case. Behind them ran
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.262#other counters, also encumbered with goods that a small army of shopmen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.263#were examining. It was a general unpacking, an apparent confusion of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.264#stuffs, examined, turned over, and marked, amidst a buzz of voices.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.265#Bouthemont, a celebrity in the trade, had a round, jolly face, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.266#coal-black beard, and fine hazel eyes. Born at Montpellier, noisy, too
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.267#fond of company, he was not much good for the sales, but for buying he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.268#had not his equal. Sent to Paris by his father, who kept a draper's shop
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.269#in his native town, he had absolutely refused to return when the old
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.270#fellow thought he ought to know enough to succeed him in his business;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.271#and from that moment a rivalry sprung up between father and son, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.272#former, all for his little country business, shocked to see a simple
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.273#shopman earning three times as much as he did himself, the latter joking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.274#at the old man's routine, chinking his money, and throwing the whole
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.275#house into confusion at every flying visit he paid. Like the other
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.276#managers, Bouthemont drew, besides his three thousand francs regular
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.277#pay, a commission on the sales. Montpèllier, surprised and respectful,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.278#whispered that young Bouthemont had made fifteen thousand francs the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.279#year before, and that that was only a beginning--people prophesied to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.280#the exasperated father that this figure would certainly increase.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.281#Bourdoncle had taken up one of the pieces of silk, and was examining
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.282#the grain with the eye of a connoisseur. It was a faille with a blue and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.283#silver selvage, the famous Paris Paradise, with which Mouret hoped to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.284#strike a decisive blow.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.285#“It is really very good,” observed Bourdoncle.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.286#“And the effect it produces is better than its real quality,” said
