urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.311#to increase the sales. Moreover, his former anxiety reappeared in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.312#presence of these advertising combinations which he did not understand.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.313#He ventured to show his repugnance by saying:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.314#“If we sell it at five francs twelve sous, it will be like selling it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.315#at a loss, as we must allow for our expenses, which are considerable. It
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.316#would fetch seven francs anywhere.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.317#At this Mouret got angry. He struck the silk with his open hand,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.318#crying out excitedly: “I know that, that's why I want to give it to our
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.319#customers. Really, my dear fellow, you'll never understand women's ways.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.320#Don't you see they'll be crazy after this silk?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.321#“No doubt,” interrupted the other, obstinately, “and the more they buy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.322#the more we shall lose.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.323#“We shall lose a few sous on the stuff, very likely. What matters, if
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.324#in return we attract all the women here, and keep them at our mercy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.325#excited by the sight of our goods, emptying their purses without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.326#thinking? The principal thing, my dear fellow, is to inflame them, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.327#for that you must have one article which flatters them--which causes
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.328#a sensation. Afterwards, you can sell the other articles as dear as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.329#anywhere else, they'll still think yours the cheapest. For instance, our
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.330#Golden Grain, that taffeta at seven francs and a half, sold everywhere
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.331#at that price, will go down as an extraordinary bargain, and suffice to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.332#make up for the loss on the Paris Paradise. You'll see, you'll see!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.333#He became quite eloquent.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.334#“Don't you understand? In a week's time from to-day I want the Paris
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.335#Paradise to make a revolution in the market. It's our master-stroke,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.336#which will save us, and get our name up. Nothing else will be talked of;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.337#the blue and silver selvage will be known from one end of France to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.338#other. And you'll hear the furious complaints of our competitors. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.339#small traders will lose another wing by it; they'll be done for, all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.340#those rheumatic old brokers shivering in their cellars!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.341#The shopmen checking the goods round about were listening and smiling.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.342#He liked to talk in this way without contradiction. Bourdoncle yielded
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.343#once more. However, the case was empty, two men were opening another.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.344#“It's the manufacturers who are not exactly pleased,” said Bouthemont.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.345#“At Lyons they are all furious with you, they pretend that your cheap
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.346#trading is ruining them. You are aware that Gaujean has positively
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.347#declared war against me. Yes, he has sworn to give the little houses
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.348#longer credit, rather than accept my prices.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.349#Mouret shrugged his shoulders. “If Gaujean doesn't look sharp,” replied
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.350#he, “Gaujean will be floored. What do they complain of? We pay ready
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.351#money and we take all they can make; it's strange if they can't work
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.352#cheaper at that rate. Besides, the public gets the benefit, and that's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.353#everything.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.354#The shopman was emptying the second case, whilst Bouthemont was checking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.355#the pieces by the invoice. Another shopman, at the end of the counter,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.356#was marking them in plain figures, and the checking finished, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.357#invoice, signed by the manager, had to be sent to the chief cashier's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.358#office. Mouret continued looking at this work for a moment, at all this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.359#activity round this unpacking of goods which threatened to drown
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.360#the basement; then, without adding a word, with the air of a captain
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.361#satisfied with his troops, he went away, followed by Bourdoncle.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.362#They slowly crossed the basement floor. The air-holes placed at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.363#intervals admitted a pale light; while in the dark corners, and along
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.364#the narrow corridors, gas was constantly burning. In these corridors
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.365#were situated the reserves, large vaults closed with iron railings,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.366#containing the surplus goods of each department. Mouret glanced in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.367#passing at the heating apparatus, to be lighted on the Monday for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.368#the first time, and at the post of firemen guarding a giant gas-meter
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.369#enclosed in an iron cage. The kitchen and dining-rooms, old cellars
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.370#turned into habitable apartments, were on the left at the corner of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.371#Place Gaillon. At last he arrived at the delivery department, right at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.372#the other end of the basement floor. The parcels not taken away by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.373#customers were sent down there, sorted on tables, placed in compartments
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.374#each representing a district of Paris; then sent up by a large staircase
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.375#opening just opposite The Old Elbeuf, to the vans standing alongside
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.376#the pavement. In the mechanical working of The Ladies' Paradise, this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.377#staircase in the Rue de la Michodière disgorged without ceasing the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.378#goods swallowed up by the slide in the Rue Neuve-Saint-Augustin, after
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.379#they had passed through the mechanism of the counters up above.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.380#“Campion,” said Mouret to the delivery manager, a retired sergeant
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.381#with a thin face, “why weren't six pairs of sheets, bought by a lady
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.382#yesterday about two o'clock, delivered in the evening?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.383#“Where does the lady live?” asked the employee..
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.384#“In the Rue de Rivoli, at the corner of the Rue d'Alger--Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.385#Desforges.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.386#At this early hour the sorting tables were bare, the compartment only
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.387#contained a few parcels left over night Whilst Campion was searching
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.388#amongst these packets, after having consulted a list, Bourdoncle was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.389#looking at Mouret, thinking that this wonderful fellow knew everything,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.390#thought of everything, even when at the supper-tables of restaurants or
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.391#in the alcoves of his mistresses. At last Campion discovered the error;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.392#the cashier's department had given a wrong number, and the parcel had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.393#come back.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.394#“What is the number of the pay-desk that debited that?” asked Mouret:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.395#“No. 10, you say?” And turning towards his lieutenant, he added: “No.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.396#10; that's Albert, isn't it? We'll just say two words to him.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.397#But before starting on their tour round the shops, he wanted to go up to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.398#the postal order department, which occupied several rooms on the second
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.399#floor. It was there that all the provincial and foreign orders arrived;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.400#and he went up every morning to see the correspondence. For two years
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.401#this correspondence had been increasing daily. At first occupying only
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.402#about ten clerks, it now required more than thirty. Some opened the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.403#letters, others read them, seated at both sides of the same table;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.404#others again classed them, giving each one a running number, which was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.405#repeated on a pigeon-hole. Then when the letters had been distributed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.406#to the different departments and the latter had delivered the articles,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.407#these articles were put in the pigeon-holes as they arrived, according
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.408#to the running numbers. There was then nothing to do but to check and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.409#tie them up, which was done in a neighbouring room by a squad of workmen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.410#who were nailing and tying up from morning to night.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.411#Mouret put his usual question: “How many letters this morning,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.412#Levasseur?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.413#“Five hundred and thirty-four, sir,” replied the chief clerk. “After the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.414#commencement of Monday's sale, I'm afraid we sha'n't have enough hands.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.415#Yesterday we were driven very hard.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.416#Bourdoncle expressed his satisfaction by a nod of the head. He had not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.417#reckoned on five hundred and thirty-four letters on a Tuesday. Round
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.418#the table, the clerks continued opening and reading the letters amidst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.419#a noise of rustling paper, whilst the going and coming of the various
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.420#articles commenced before the pigeon-holes. It was one of the most
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.421#complicated and important departments of the establishment, one in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.422#which there was a continual rush, for, strictly speaking, all the orders
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.423#received in the morning ought to be sent off the same evening.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.424#“You shall have more hands if you want them,” replied Mouret, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.425#had seen at a glance that the work was well done. “You know that when
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.426#there's work to be done we never refuse the men.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.427#Up above, under the roof, were the small bedrooms for the saleswomen.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.428#But he went downstairs again and entered the chief cashier's office,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.429#which was near his own. It was a room with a glazed wicket, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.430#contained an enormous safe, fixed in the wall. Two cashiers there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.431#centralised the receipts which Lhomme, the chief cashier at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.432#counters, brought in every evening; they also settled the current
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.433#expenses, paid the manufacturers, the staff, all the crowd of people who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.434#lived by the house. The cashiers' office communicated with another, full
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.435#of green cardboard boxes, where ten clerks checked the invoices. Then
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.436#came another office, the clearing-house: six young men bending over
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.437#black desks, having behind them quite a collection of registers, were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.438#getting up the discount accounts of the salesmen, by checking the debit
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.439#notes. This work, which was new to them, did not get on very well.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.440#Mouret and Bourdoncle had crossed the cashiers' office and the invoice
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.441#room. When they passed through the other office the young men, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.442#were laughing and joking, started up in surprise. Mouret, without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.443#reprimanding them, explained the system of the little bonus he thought
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.444#of giving them for each error discovered in the debit notes; and when he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.445#went out the clerks left off laughing, as if they had been whipped, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.446#commenced working in earnest, looking up the errors.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.447#On the ground-floor, occupied by the shops, Mouret went straight to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.448#pay-desk No. 10, where Albert Lhomme was cleaning his nails, waiting for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.449#customers. People regularly spoke of “the Lhomme dynasty,” since Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.450#Aurélie, firsthand at the dress department, after having helped her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.451#husband on to the post of chief cashier, had managed to get a pay
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.452#desk for her son, a tall fellow, pale and vicious, who couldn't stop
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.453#anywhere, and who caused her an immense deal of anxiety. But on reaching
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.454#the young man, Mouret kept in the background, not wishing to render
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.455#himself unpopular by performing a policeman's duty, and retaining from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.456#policy and taste his part of amiable god. He nudged Bourdoncle
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.457#gently with his elbow--Bourdoncle, the infallible man, that model of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.458#exactitude, whom he generally charged with the work of reprimanding.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.459#“Monsieur Albert,” said the latter, severely, “you have taken another
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.460#address wrong; the parcel has come back. It's unbearable!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.461#The cashier, thinking it his duty to defend himself, called as a witness
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.462#the messenger who had tied up the packet. This messenger, named Joseph,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.463#also belonged to the Lhomme dynasty, for he was Albert's foster brother,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.464#and owed his place to Madame Aurelie's influence, As the young man
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.465#wanted to make him say it was the customer's mistake, Joseph stuttered,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.466#twisted the shaggy beard that ornamented his scarred face, struggling
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.467#between his old soldier's conscience and gratitude towards his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.468#protectors.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.469#“Let Joseph alone,” Bourdoncle exclaimed at last, “and don't say
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.470#any more. Ah! it's a lucky thing for you that we are mindful of your
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.471#mother's good services!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.472#But at this moment Lhomme came running up. From his office near the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.473#door he could see his son's pay-desk, which was in the glove department.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.474#Quite white-haired already, deadened by his sedentary life, he had a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.475#flabby, colourless face, as if worn out by the reflection of the money
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.476#he was continually handling. His amputated arm did not at all incommode
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.477#him in this work, and it was quite a curiosity to see him verify the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.478#receipts, so rapidly did the notes and coins slip through his left one,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.479#the only one he had. Son of a tax-collector at Chablis, he had come to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.480#Paris as a clerk in the office of a merchant of the Port-aux-Vins.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.481#Then, whilst lodging in the Rue Cuvier, he married the daughter of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.482#doorkeeper, a small tailor, an Alsatian; and from that day he had bowed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.483#submissively before his wife, whose commercial ability filled him with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.484#respect. She earned more than twelve thousand francs a year in the dress
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.485#department, whilst he only drew a fixed salary of five thousand francs.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.486#And the deference he felt for a woman bringing such sums into the home
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.487#was extended to the son, who also belonged to her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.488#“What's the matter?” murmured he; “is Albert in fault?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.489#Then, according to his custom, Mouret appeared on the scene, to play the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.490#part of good-natured prince. When Bour-doncle had made himself feared,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.491#he looked after his own popularity.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.492#“Nothing of consequence!” murmured he. “My dear Lhomme, your son Albert
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.493#is a careless fellow, who should take an example from you.” Then,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.494#changing the subject, showing himself more amiable than ever, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.495#continued; “And that concert the other day--did you get a good seat?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.496#A blush overspread the white cheeks of the old cashier. Music was his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.497#only vice, a vice which he indulged in solitarily, frequenting the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.498#theatres, the concerts, the rehearsals. Notwithstanding the loss of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.499#his arm, he played on the French horn, thanks to an ingenious system of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.500#keys; and as Madame Lhomme detested noise, he wrapped up his instrument
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.501#in cloth in the evening, delighted all the same, in the highest
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.502#degree, with the strangely dull sounds he drew from it. In the forced
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.503#irregularity of their domestic life he had made himself an oasis of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.504#this music--that and the cash-box, he knew of nothing else, beyond the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.505#admiration he felt for his wife.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.506#“A very good seat,” replied he, with sparkling eyes. “You are really too
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.507#kind, sir.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.508#Mouret, who enjoyed a personal pleasure in satisfying other people's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.509#passions, sometimes gave Lhomme the tickets forced on him by the lady
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.510#patronesses of such entertainments, and he completed the old man's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.511#delight by saying:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.512#“Ah, Beethoven! ah, Mozart! What music!” And without waiting for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.513#a reply, he went off, rejoining Bourdoncle, already on his tour of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.514#inspection through the departments.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.515#In the central hall, an inner courtyard with a glass roof formed the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.516#silk department. Both went along the Rue Neuve-Saint-Augustin, occupied
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.517#by the linen department, from one end to the other. Nothing unusual
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.518#striking them, they passed on through the crowd of respectful
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.519#assistants. They then turned into the cotton and hosiery departments,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.520#where the same order reigned. But in the department devoted to woollens,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.521#occupying the gallery which ran through to the Rue de la Michodière,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.522#Bourdoncle resumed the character of executioner, on observing a young
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.523#man, seated on the counter, looking knocked up after a night passed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.524#without sleep. And this young man, named Liénard, son of a rich Angers
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.525#draper, bowed his head beneath the reprimand, fearing nothing in his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.526#idle, careless life of pleasure except to be recalled by his father. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.527#reprimands now began to shower down, and the gallery of the Rue de
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.528#la Michodière received the full force of the storm. In the drapery
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.529#department a salesman, a fresh hand, who slept in the house, had come
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.530#in after eleven o'clock; in the haberdashery department, the second
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.531#counterman had just allowed himself to be caught downstairs smoking a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.532#cigarette. But the tempest burst with especial violence in the glove
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.533#department, on the head of one of the rare Parisians in the house,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.534#handsome Mignot, as they called him, the illegitimate son of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.535#music-mistress: his crime was having caused a scandal in the dining-room
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.536#by complaining of the food. As there were three tables, one at half-past
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.537#nine, one at half-past ten, and another at half-past eleven, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.538#wished to explain that belonging to the third table, he always had the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.539#leavings, the worst of everything.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.540#“What! the food not good?” asked Mouret, naïvely, opening his mouth at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.541#last.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.542#He only gave the head cook, a terrible Auvergnat, a franc and a half a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.543#head per day, out of which this man still managed to make a good
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.544#profit; and the food was really execrable. But Bourdoncle shrugged
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.545#his shoulders: a cook who had four hundred luncheons and four hundred
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.546#dinners to serve, even in three series, had no time to waste on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.547#refinements of his art.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.548#“Never mind,” said the governor, good-naturedly, “I wish all our
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.549#employees to have good, abundant food. I'll speak to the cook.” And
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.550#Mignot's complaint was shelved.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.551#Then returning to their point of departure, standing up near the door,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.552#amidst the umbrellas and neckties, Mouret and Bourdoncle received the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.553#report of one of the four inspectors, charged with the superintendence
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.554#of the establishment. Old Jouve, a retired captain, decorated at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.555#Constantine, a fine-looking man still, with his big sensual nose and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.556#majestic baldness, having drawn their attention to a salesman, who,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.557#in reply to a simple remonstrance on his part, had called him “an old
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.558#humbug,” the salesman was immediately discharged.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.559#However, the shop was still without customers, except a few housewives
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.560#of the neighbourhood who were going through the almost deserted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.561#galleries. At the door the time-keeper had just closed his book, and was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.562#making out a separate list of the late comers. The salesmen were taking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.563#possession of their departments, which had been swept and brushed by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.564#the messengers before their arrival. Each young man hung up his hat
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.565#and great-coat as he arrived, stifling a yawn, still half asleep. Some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.566#exchanged a few words, gazed about the shop and seemed to be pulling
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.567#themselves together ready for another day's work; others were leisurely
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.568#removing the green baize with which they had covered the goods over
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.569#night, after having folded them up; and the piles of stuffs appeared
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.570#symmetrically arranged, the whole shop was in a clean and orderly state,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.571#brilliant in the morning gaiety, waiting for the rush of business to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.572#come and obstruct it, and, as it were, narrow it by the unpacking and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.573#display of linen, cloth, silk, and lace.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.574#In the bright light of the central hall, two young men were talking in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.575#a low voice at the silk counter. One, short and charming, well set, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.576#with a pink skin, was endeavouring to blend the colours of some silks
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.577#for indoor show. His name was Hutin, his father kept a café at Yvetot,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.578#and he had managed after eighteen months' service to become one of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.579#principal salesmen, thanks to a natural flexibility of character,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.580#a continual flow of caressing flattery, under which was concealed a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.581#furious rage for business, grasping everything, devouring everybody,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.582#even without hunger, just for the pleasure of the thing.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.583#“Look here, Favier, I should have struck him if I had been in your
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.584#place, honour bright!” said he to the other, a tall bilious fellow with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.585#a dry and yellow skin, who was born at Besançon of a family of weavers,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.586#and who, without the least grace, concealed under a cold exterior a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.587#disquieting will.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.588#“It does no good to strike people,” murmured he, phlegmatically; “better
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.589#wait.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.590#They were both speaking of Robineau, who was looking after the shopmen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.591#during the manager's absence downstairs. Hutin was secretly undermining
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.592#Robineau, whose place he coveted. He had already, to wound him and make
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.593#him leave, introduced Bouthemont to fill the vacancy of manager which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.594#had been promised to Robineau. However, the latter stood firm, and it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.595#was now an hourly battle. Hutin dreamed of setting the whole department
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.596#against him, to hound him out by means of ill-will and vexations. At
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.597#the same time he went to work craftily, exciting Favier especially, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.598#stood next to him as salesman, and who appeared to allow himself to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.599#led on, but with certain brusque reserves, in which could be felt quite
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.600#a private campaign carried on in silence.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.601#“Hush! seventeen!” said he, quickly, to his colleague, to warn him by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.602#this peculiar cry of the approach of Mouret and Bourdoncle.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.603#These latter were continuing their inspection by traversing the hall.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.604#They stopped to ask Robineau for an explanation with regard to a stock
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.605#of velvets of which the boxes were encumbering a table. And as the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.606#latter replied that there wasn't enough room:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.607#“I told you so, Bourdoncle,” cried out Mouret, smiling; “the place is
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.608#already too small. We shall soon have to knock down the walls as far as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.609#the Rue de Choiseul. You'll see what a crush there'll be next Monday.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.610#And respecting the coming sale, for which they were preparing at every
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.611#counter, he asked Robineau further questions and gave him various
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.612#orders. But for several minutes, and without having stopped talking, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.613#had been watching Hutin, who was contrasting the silks--blue, grey, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.614#yellow--drawing back to judge of the harmony of the tones. Suddenly he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.615#interfered:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.616#“But why are you endeavouring to please the eyes? Don't be afraid; blind
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.617#them. Look! red, green, yellow.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.618#He had taken the pieces, throwing them together, crushing them,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.619#producing an excessively fast effect. Every one allowed the governor to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.620#be the best displayer in Paris, of a regular revolutionary stamp, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.621#had founded the brutal and colossal school in the science of displaying.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.622#He delighted in a tumbling of stuffs, as if they had fallen from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.623#the crowded shelves by chance, making them glow with the most ardent
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.624#colours, lighting each other up by the contrast, declaring that the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.625#customers ought to have sore eyes on going out of the shop. Hutin, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.626#belonged, on the contrary, to the classic school, in which symmetry and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.627#harmony of colour were cherished, looked at him lighting up this fire of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.628#stuff on a table, not venturing on the least criticism, but biting his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.629#lip with the pout of an artist whose convictions are wounded by such a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.630#debauch.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.631#“There!” exclaimed Mouret when he had finished. “Leave it; you'll see if
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.632#it doesn't fetch the women on Monday.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.633#Just as he rejoined Bourdoncle and Robineau, there arrived a woman, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.634#remained stock-still, suffocated before this show. It was Denise, who,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.635#having waited for nearly an hour in the street, the prey to a violent
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.636#attack of timidity, had at last decided to go in. But she was so beside
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.637#herself with bashfulness that she mistook the clearest directions; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.638#the shopmen, of whom she had stutteringly asked for Madame Aurélie,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.639#directed her in vain to the lower staircase; she thanked them, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.640#turned to the left if they told her to turn to the right; so that for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.641#the last ten minutes she had been wandering about the ground-floor,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.642#going from department to department, amidst the ill-natured curiosity
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.643#and ill-tempered indifference of the salesmen. She longed to run away,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.644#and was at the same time retained by a wish to stop and admire. She felt
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.645#herself lost, she, so little, in this monster place, in this machine at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.646#rest, trembling for fear she should be caught in the movement with which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.647#the walls already began to shake. And the thought of The Old Elbeuf,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.648#black and narrow, increased the immensity of this vast establishment,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.649#presenting it to her as bathed in light, like a city with its monuments,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.650#squares, and streets, in which it seemed impossible that she should ever
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.651#find her way.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.652#However, she had not dared to risk herself in the silk hall, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.653#high glass roof, luxurious counters, and cathedral-like air of which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.654#frightened her. Then when she did venture in, to escape the shopmen in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.655#the linen department, who were grinning, she had stumbled right on to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.656#Mouret's display; and, notwithstanding her fright, the woman was aroused
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.657#within her, her cheeks suddenly became red, and she forgot everything in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.658#looking at the glow of these silks.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.659#“Hullo!” said Hutin in Favier's ear; “there's the girl we saw in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.660#Place Gaillon.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.661#Mouret, whilst affecting to listen to Bourdoncle and Robineau, was at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.662#heart flattered by the startled look of this poor girl, as a marchioness
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.663#might be by the brutal desire of a passing drayman. But Denise had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.664#raised her eyes, and her confusion increased at the sight of this young
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.665#man, whom she took for a manager. She thought he was looking at her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.666#severely. Then not knowing how to get away, quite lost, she applied to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.667#the nearest shopman, who happened to be Favier.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.668#“Madame Aurélie, please?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.669#But Favier, who was disagreeable, contented himself with replying
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.670#sharply: “First floor.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.671#And Denise, longing to escape the looks of all these men, thanked him,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.672#and had again turned her back to the stairs she ought to have mounted,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.673#when Hutin, yielding naturally to his instinct of gallantry, stopped her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.674#with his most amiable salesman's smile, “No--this way, mademoiselle; if
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.675#you don't mind.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.676#And he even went with her a little way to the foot of the staircase
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.677#on the left-hand side of the hall under the gallery. There he bowed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.678#smiling tenderly, as he smiled at all women.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.679#“When you get upstairs turn to the left. The dress department is
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.680#straight in front.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.681#This caressing politeness affected Denise deeply. It was like a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.682#brotherly hand extended to her; she raised her eyes and looked at Hutin,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.683#and everything in him touched her--his handsome face, his looks which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.684#dissolved her fears, and his voice which seemed to her of a consoling
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.685#softness. Her heart swelled with gratitude, and she bestowed her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.686#friendship in the few disjointed words her emotion allowed her to utter.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.687#“Really, sir, you are too kind. Pray don't trouble to come any further.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.688#Thank you very much.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.689#Hutin had already rejoined Favier, to whom he coarsely whispered: “What
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.690#a bag of bones--eh?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.691#Upstairs the young girl suddenly found herself in the midst of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.692#dress department. It was a vast room, with high carved oak cupboards all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.693#round, and clear glass windows looking on to the Rue de la Michodière.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.694#Five or six women in silk dresses, looking very coquettish with their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.695#frizzed chignons and crinolines drawn back, were moving about, talking.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.696#One, tall and thin, with a long head, having a runaway-horse appearance,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.697#was leaning against a cupboard, as if already knocked up with fatigue.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.698#“Madame Aurélie?” inquired Denise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.699#The saleswoman looked at her without replying, with an air of disdain
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.700#for her shabby dress, then turning to one of her friends, a short girl
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.701#with a sickly white skin and an innocent and disgusted appearance, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.702#asked: “Mademoiselle Vadon, do you know where Madame Aurélie is?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.703#The young girl, who was arranging some mantles according to their sizes,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.704#did not even take the trouble to raise her head. “No, Mademoiselle
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.705#Prunaire, I don't know at all,” replied she in a mincing tone.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.706#A silence ensued. Denise stood still, and no one took any further notice
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.707#of her. However, after waiting a moment, she ventured to put another
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.708#question: “Do you think Madame Aurélie will be back soon?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.709#The second-hand, a thin, ugly woman, whom she had not noticed before,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.710#a widow with a projecting jaw-bone and coarse hair, cried out from a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.711#cupboard, where she was checking some tickets: “You'd better wait if
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.712#you want to speak to Madame Aurélie herself.” And, addressing another
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.713#saleswoman, she added: “Isn't she downstairs?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.714#“No, Madame Frédéric, I don't think so,” replied the young lady. “She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.715#said nothing before going, so she can't be far off.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.716#Denise, thus instructed, remained standing. There were several chairs
