urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.921#the fear, inspired in her by Mouret, and Hutin's amiability, the only
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.922#pleasure she had enjoyed the whole morning, a souvenir of charming
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.923#sweetness which filled her with gratitude. When she crossed the shop to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.924#go out she looked for the young man, happy at the idea of thanking him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.925#again with her eyes; and she was very sorry not to see him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.926#“Well, mademoiselle, have you succeeded?” asked a timid voice, as she at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.927#last stood on the pavement outside. She turned round and recognised the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.928#tall, awkward young fellow who had spoken to her in the morning. He also
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.929#had just come out of The Ladies' Paradise, appearing more frightened
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.930#than she did, still bewildered with the examination he had just passed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.931#through.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.932#“I really don't know yet, sir,” replied she.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.933#“You're like me, then. What a way of looking at and talking to you they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.934#have in there--eh? I'm applying for a place in the lace department I was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.935#at Crèvecour's in the Rue du Mail.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.936#They were once more standing facing each other; and, not knowing how
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.937#to take leave, they commenced to blush. Then the young man, just for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.938#something to say in the excess of his timidity, ventured to ask in his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.939#good-natured, awkward way: “What is your name, mademoiselle?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.940#“Denise Baudu.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.941#“My name is Henri Deloche.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.942#Now they smiled, and, yielding to the fraternity of their positions,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.943#shook each other by the hand.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.944#“Good luck!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ii.945#“Yes, good luck!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.1#CHAPTER III.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.2#Every Saturday, between four and six, Madame Desforges offered a cup of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.3#tea and a few cakes to those friends who were kind enough to visit her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.4#She occupied the third floor of a house at the corner of the Rue de
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.5#Rivoli and the Rue d'Alger; and the windows of both drawing-rooms
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.6#overlooked the Tuileries Gardens. This Saturday, just as a footman was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.7#about to introduce him into the principal drawing-room, Mouret perceived
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.8#from the anteroom, through an open door, Madame Desforges, who was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.9#crossing the little drawing-room. She stopped on seeing him, and he went
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.10#in that way, bowing to her with a ceremonious air. But when the footman
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.11#had closed the door, he quickly seized the young woman's hand, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.12#tenderly kissed it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.13#“Take care, I have company!” she said, in a low voice, glancing towards
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.14#the door of the larger room. “I've just been to fetch this fan to show
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.15#them,” and she playfully tapped him on the face with the tip of the fan.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.16#She was dark, rather stout, with big jealous eyes.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.17#But he still held her hand and asked: “Will he come?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.18#“Certainly,” replied she. “I have his promise.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.19#Both of them referred to Baron Hartmann, director of the Credit
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.20#Immobilier. Madame Desforges, daughter of a Councillor of State, was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.21#the widow of a stock-broker, who had left her a fortune, denied by some,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.22#exaggerated by others. Even during her husband's lifetime people said
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.23#she had shown herself grateful towards Baron Hartmann, whose financial
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.24#tips had proved very useful to them; and later on, after her husband's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.25#death, the acquaintance had probably continued, but always discreetly,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.26#without imprudence or display; for she never courted notoriety in any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.27#way, and was received everywhere in the upper-middle classes amongst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.28#whom she was born. Even at this time, when the passion of the banker, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.29#sceptical, crafty man, had subsided into a simple paternal affection, if
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.30#she permitted herself certain lovers whom he tolerated, she displayed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.31#in these treasons of the heart such a delicate reserve and tact, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.32#knowledge of the world so adroitly applied, that appearances were saved,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.33#and no one would have ventured to openly express any doubt as to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.34#her conduct Having met Mouret at a mutual friend's, she had at first
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.35#detested him; but she had yielded to him later on, as if carried away by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.36#the violent love with which he attacked her, and since he had commenced
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.37#to approach Baron Hartmann through her, she had gradually got to love
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.38#him with a real profound tenderness, adoring him with the violence of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.39#woman already thirty-five, although only acknowledging twenty-nine,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.40#and in despair at feeling him younger than herself, trembling lest she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.41#should lose him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.42#“Does he know about it?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.43#“No, you'll explain the affair to him yourself,” she replied.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.44#She looked at him, thinking that he couldn't know anything or he would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.45#not employ her in this way with the baron, affecting to consider him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.46#simply as an old friend of hers. But he still held her hand, he called
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.47#her his good Henriette, and she felt her heart melting. Silently she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.48#presented her lips, pressed them to his, then whispered: “Oh, they're
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.49#waiting for me. Come in behind me.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.50#They could hear voices issuing from the principal drawingroom, deadened
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.51#by the heavy curtains. She pushed the door, leaving its two folds open,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.52#and handed the fan to one of the four ladies who were seated in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.53#middle of the room.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.54#“There it is,” said she; “I didn't know exactly where it was. My maid
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.55#would never have found it.” And she added in her cheerful way: “Come in,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.56#Monsieur Mouret, come through the little drawing-room; it will be less
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.57#solemn.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.58#Mouret bowed to the ladies whom he knew. The drawingroom, with its
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.59#flowered brocatel Louis XVI. furniture, gilded bronzes and large green
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.60#plants, had a tender feminine air, notwithstanding the height of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.61#ceiling; and through the two windows could be seen the chestnut trees in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.62#the Tuileries Gardens, their leaves blowing about in the October wind.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.63#“But it isn't at all bad, this Chantilly!” exclaimed Madame Bourdelais,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.64#who had taken the fan.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.65#She was a short fair woman of thirty, with a delicate nose and sparkling
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.66#eyes, an old school-fellow of Henriette's, and who had married a chief
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.67#clerk in the Treasury. Of an old middle-class family, she managed her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.68#household and three children with a rare activity and good grace, and an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.69#exquisite knowledge of practical life.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.70#“And you paid twenty-five francs for it?” resumed she, examining each
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.71#mesh of the lace. “At Luc, I think you said, to a country woman? No, it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.72#isn't dear; but you had to get it mounted, hadn't you?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.73#“Of course,” replied Madame Desforges. “The mounting cost me two hundred
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.74#francs.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.75#Madame Bourdelais began to laugh. And that was what Henriette called a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.76#bargain! Two hundred francs for a plain ivory mount, with a monogram!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.77#And that for a simple piece of Chantilly, over which she had saved five
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.78#francs, perhaps. Similar fans could be had ready, mounted for a hundred
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.79#and twenty francs, and she named a shop in the Rue Poissonnière.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.80#However, the fan was handed round to all the ladies. Madame Guibal
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.81#barely glanced at it. She was a tall, thin woman, with red hair, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.82#a face full of indifference, in which her grey eyes, occasionally
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.83#penetrating her unconcerned air, cast the terrible gleams of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.84#selfishness. She was never seen out with her husband, a barrister
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.85#well-known at the Palais de Justice, who led, it was said, a pretty free
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.86#life, dividing himself between his law business and his pleasures.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.87#“Oh,” murmured she, passing the fan to Madame de Boves, “I've scarcely
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.88#bought one in my life. One always receives too many of such things.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.89#The countess replied with delicate malice: “You are fortunate, my dear,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.90#in having a gallant husband.” And bending over to her daughter, a tall
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.91#girl of twenty, she added: “Just look at the monogram, Blanche. What
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.92#pretty work! It's the monogram that must have increased the price like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.93#that.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.94#Madame de Boves had just turned forty. She was a superb woman, with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.95#neck of a goddess, a large regular face, and big sleepy eyes, whom her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.96#husband, Inspector-General of the Stud, had married for her beauty. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.97#appeared quite moved by the delicacy of the monogram, as if seized with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.98#a desire the emotion of which made her turn pale, and turning round
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.99#suddenly, she continued: “Give us your opinion, Monsieur Mouret. Is it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.100#too dear--two hundred francs for this mount?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.101#Mouret had remained standing in the midst of the five women, smiling,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.102#taking an interest in what interested them. He picked up the fan,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.103#examined it, and was about to give his opinion, when the footman opened
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.104#the door and announced:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.105#“Madame Marty.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.106#And there entered a thin, ugly woman, ravaged with the small-pox,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.107#dressed with a complicated elegance. She was of uncertain age, her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.108#thirty-five years appearing sometimes equal to thirty, and sometimes to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.109#forty, according to the intensity of the nervous fever which agitated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.110#her. A red leather bag, which she had not let go, hung from her right
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.111#hand.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.112#“Dear madame,” said she to Henriette, “excuse me bringing my bag. Just
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.113#fancy, as I was coming along I went into The Paradise, and as I have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.114#again been very extravagant, I did not like to leave it in my cab
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.115#for fear of being robbed.” But having perceived Mouret, she resumed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.116#laughingly: “Ah! sir, I didn't mean to give you an advertisement, for I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.117#didn't know you were here. But you really have some extraordinary fine
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.118#lace just now.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.119#This turned the attention from the fan, which the young man laid on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.120#table. The ladies were all anxious to see what Madame Marty had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.121#bought. She was known to be very extravagant, totally unable to resist
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.122#temptation, strict in her conduct and incapable of yielding to a lover,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.123#but weak and cowardly, easily conquered before the least bit of finery.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.124#Daughter of a city clerk, she was ruining her husband, a master at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.125#Lycée Bonaparte, who was obliged to double his salary of six thousand
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.126#francs a year by giving private lessons, in order to meet the constantly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.127#increasing household expenses. She did not open her bag, but held it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.128#tight on her lap, and commenced to talk about her daughter Valentine,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.129#fourteen years old, one of her dearest coquetries, for she dressed her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.130#like herself, with all the fashionable novelties of which she submitted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.131#to the irresistible seduction.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.132#“You know,” she said, “they are making dresses trimmed with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.133#narrow lace for young girls this winter. So when I saw%a very pretty
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.134#Valenciennes----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.135#And she at last decided to open her bag. The ladies were stretching out
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.136#their necks, when, in the midst of the silence, the door-bell was heard.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.137#“It's my husband,” stammered Madame Marty, very confused. “He promised to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.138#fetch me on leaving the Lycée Bonaparte.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.139#She quickly shut the bag again, and put it under her chair with an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.140#instinctive movement. All the ladies set up a laugh. This made her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.141#blush for her precipitation, and she put the bag on her knees again,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.142#explaining that men never understood, and that they need not know.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.143#“Monsieur de Boves, Monsieur de Vallagnosc,” announced the footman.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.144#It was quite a surprise. Madame de Boves herself did not expect her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.145#husband. The latter, a fine man, wearing a moustache and an imperial
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.146#with the military correctness so much liked at the Tuileries, kissed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.147#the hand of Madame Desforges, whom he had known as a young girl at her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.148#father's. And he made way to allow his companion, a tall, pale fellow,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.149#of an aristocratic poverty of blood, to make his bow to the lady of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.150#house. But the conversation had hardly recommenced when two exclamations
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.151#were heard:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.152#“What! Is that you, Paul?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.153#“Why, Octave!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.154#Mouret and Vallagnosc then shook hands, much to Madame Desforges's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.155#surprise. They knew each other, then? Of course, they had grown up side
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.156#by side at the college at Plassans, and it was quite by chance they had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.157#not met at her house before. However, with their hands still united,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.158#they went into the little drawing-room, just as the servant brought in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.159#the tea, a china service on a silver waiter, which he placed near Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.160#Desforges, on a small round marble table with a light copper mounting.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.161#The ladies drew up and began talking louder, all speaking at once,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.162#producing a cross-fire of short disjointed sentences; whilst Monsieur
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.163#de Boves, standing up behind them, put in an occasional word with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.164#gallantry of a handsome functionary. The vast room, so prettily and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.165#cheerfully furnished, became merrier still with these gossiping voices,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.166#and the frequent laughter.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.167#“Ah! Paul, old boy,” repeated Mouret.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.168#He was seated near Vallagnosc, on a sofa. And alone in the little
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.169#drawing-room, very coquettish with its pretty silk hangings, out of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.170#hearing of the ladies, and not even seeing them, except through the open
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.171#door, the two old friends commenced grinning, examining each other's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.172#looks, exchanging slaps on the knees. Their whole youthful career was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.173#recalled, the old college at Plassans, with its two courtyards, its
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.174#damp classrooms, and the dining-room in which they had consumed so much
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.175#cod-fish, and the dormitories where the pillows used to fly from bed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.176#to bed as soon as the monitor began to snore. Paul, belonging to an old
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.177#parliamentary family, noble, poor, and proud, was a good scholar,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.178#always at the top of his class, continually held up as an example by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.179#the master, who prophesied for him a brilliant future; whilst Octave
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.180#remained at the bottom, stuck amongst the dunces, fat and jolly,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.181#indulging in all sorts of pleasures outside. Notwithstanding the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.182#difference in their characters, a fast friendship had rendered them
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.183#inseparable, until their final examinations, which they passed, the one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.184#with honours, the other in a passable manner after two vexatious trials.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.185#Then they went out into the world, and had now met again, after ten
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.186#years, already changed and looking older.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.187#“Well,” said Mouret, “what's become of you?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.188#“Nothing at all,” replied the other.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.189#Vallagnosc, in the joy of their meeting, retained his tired and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.190#disenchanted air; and as his friend, astonished, insisted, saying: “But
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.191#you must do something. What do you do?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.192#“Nothing,” replied he.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.193#Octave commenced to laugh. Nothing! that wasn't enough. Little by little
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.194#he succeeded in drawing Paul out to tell his story. It was the usual
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.195#story of penniless younger sons, who think themselves obliged by their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.196#birth to choose a liberal profession, burying themselves in a sort
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.197#of vain mediocrity, happy to escape starvation, notwithstanding their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.198#numerous degrees. He had studied law by a sort of family tradition; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.199#had since remained a burden on his widowed mother, who even then hardly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.200#knew how to dispose of her two daughters. Having at last got quite
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.201#ashamed, he left the three women to vegetate on the remnants of their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.202#fortune, and accepted an appointment in the Ministry of the Interior,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.203#where he buried himself like a mole in its hole.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.204#“What do you get there?” resumed Mouret.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.205#“Three thousand francs.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.206#“But that's pitiful pay! Ah! old man, I'm really sorry for you. What! a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.207#clever fellow like you, who floored all of us I And they only give you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.208#three thousand francs a year, after having already ground you down for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.209#five years! No, it isn't right!” He interrupted himself, and returned to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.210#his own doings. “As for me, I made them a humble bow. You know what I'm
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.211#doing?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.212#“Yes,” said Vallagnosc, “I heard you were in business. You've got that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.213#big place in the Place Gaillon, haven't you?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.214#“That's it. Counter-jumper, my boy!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.215#Mouret raised his head, again slapped him on the knee, and repeated,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.216#with the solid gaiety of a fellow who did not blush for the trade by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.217#which he was making his fortune:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.218#“Counter-jumper, and no mistake! You remember, no doubt, I didn't bite
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.219#much at their machines, although at heart I never thought myself duller
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.220#than the others. When I took my degree, just to please the family, I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.221#could have become a barrister or a doctor quite as easily as any of my
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.222#school-fellows, but those trades frightened me. I saw so many who were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.223#starving at them that I just threw them over without the least regret,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.224#and pitched head-first into business.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.225#Vallognosc smiled with an awkward air, and ultimately said: “It's very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.226#certain your degree can't be much good to you for selling calico.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.227#“Well!” replied Mouret, joyously, “all I ask is, that it shall not stand
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.228#in my way, and you know, when one has been stupid enough to burden one's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.229#self with it, it is difficult to get rid of it. One goes at a tortoise's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.230#pace through life, whilst those who are bare-footed run like madmen.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.231# Then, noticing that his friend seemed troubled, he took his hand in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.232#his, and continued: “Come, come, I don't want to hurt your feelings, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.233#confess that your degrees have not satisfied any of your wants. Do you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.234#know that my manager in the silk department will draw more than twelve
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.235#thousand francs this year. Just so! a fellow of very clear intelligence,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.236#whose knowledge is confined to spelling, and the first four rules. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.237#ordinary salesmen in my place make from three to four thousand francs
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.238#a year, more than you can earn yourself; and their education was not so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.239#expensive as yours, nor were they launched into the world with a written
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.240#promise to conquer it. Of course, it is not everything to make money;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.241#but between the poor devils possessed of a smattering of science who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.242#now block up the liberal professions, without earning enough to keep
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.243#themselves from starving, and the practical fellows armed for life's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.244#struggle, knowing every branch of their trade, by Jove! I don't hesitate
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.245#a moment, I'm for the latter against the former, I think they thoroughly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.246#understand the age they live in!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.247#His voice had become impassioned. Henriette, who was pouring out the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.248#tea, turned her head. When he caught her smile, at the further end of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.249#the large drawing-room, and saw the other ladies were listening, he was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.250#the first to make merry over his own big phrases.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.251#“In short, old man, every counter-jumper who commences, has, at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.252#present day, a chance of becoming a millionaire.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.253#Vallagnosc threw himself back on the sofa indolently, half-closing his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.254#eyes in a fatigued and disdainful attitude, in which a suspicion of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.255#affectation was added to his real hereditary exhaustion.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.256#“Bah!” murmured he, “life isn't worth all that trouble. There is nothing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.257#worth living for.” And as Mouret, shocked, looked at him with an air of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.258#surprise, he added: “Everything happens and nothing happens; one may as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.259#well stay with one's arms folded.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.260#He then explained his pessimism--the mediocrities and the abortions of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.261#existence. For a time he had thought of literature, but his intercourse
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.262#with certain poets had filled him with universal despair. He always
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.263#arrived at the conclusion that all effort was useless, every hour
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.264#equally weary and empty, and the world incurably stupid and dull. All
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.265#enjoyment was a failure, and there was no pleasure in wrong-doing even.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.266#“Just tell me, do you enjoy life yourself?” asked he at last.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.267#Mouret was now in a state of astonished indignation, and exclaimed:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.268#“What? Do I enjoy myself? What are you talking about? Why, of course
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.269#I do, my boy, and even when things give way, for then I am furious at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.270#hearing them cracking. I am a passionate fellow myself, and don't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.271#take life quietly; that's what interests me in it perhaps.” He glanced
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.272#towards the drawing-room, and lowered his voice. “Oh! there are some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.273#women who've bothered me awfully, I must confess. But when I've got hold
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.274#of one, I keep her. She doesn't always escape me, and then I take my
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.275#share, I assure you. But it is not so much the women, for to speak
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.276#truly, I don't care a hang for them; it's the wish to act--to create, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.277#short. You have an idea; you fight for it, you hammer it into people's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.278#heads, and you see it grow and triumph. Ah! yes, my boy, I enjoy life!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.279#All the joy of action, all the gaiety of existence, resounded in these
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.280#words. He repeated that he went with the times. Really, a man must be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.281#badly constituted, have his brain and limbs out of order, to refuse to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.282#work in an age of such vast undertakings, when the entire century was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.283#pressing forward with giant strides. And he laughed at the despairing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.284#ones, the disgusted ones, the pessimists, all those weak, sickly members
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.285#of our budding sciences, who assumed the weeping airs of poets, or the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.286#mincing ways of sceptics, amidst the immense activity of the present
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.287#day. A fine part to play, proper and intelligent, that of yawning before
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.288#other people's labour!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.289#“That's my only pleasure, yawning in other's faces,” said Vallagnosc,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.290#smiling with his cold look.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.291#At this Mouret's passion subsided, and he became affectionate again.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.292#“Ah, Paul, you're not changed. Just as paradoxical as ever! However,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.293#we've not met to quarrel. Each one has his own ideas, fortunately. But
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.294#you must come and see my machine at work; you'll see it isn't a bad
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.295#idea. Come, what news? Your mother and sisters are quite well, I hope?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.296#And weren't you supposed to get married at Plassans, about six months
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.297#ago?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.298#A sudden movement made by Vallagnosc stopped him; and as the former was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.299#looking round the drawing-room with an anxious expression, Mouret
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.300#also turned round, and noticed that Mademoiselle de Boves was closely
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.301#watching them. Blanche, tall and stout, resembled her mother; but her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.302#face was already puffed out, her large, coarse features swollen with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.303#unhealthy fat. Paul, in reply to a discreet question, intimated that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.304#nothing was yet settled; perhaps nothing would be settled. He had made
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.305#the young person's acquaintance at Madame Desforges's, where he had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.306#visited a good deal last winter, but where he very rarely came now,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.307#which explained why he had not met Octave there sooner. In their turn,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.308#the De Boves invited him, and he was especially fond of the father, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.309#very amiable man, formerly well known about town, who had retired into
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.310#his present position. On the other hand, no money. Madame de Boves
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.311#having brought her husband nothing but her Juno-like beauty as a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.312#marriage portion, the family were living poorly on the last mortgaged
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.313#farm, to which modest revenue was added, fortunately, the nine thousand
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.314#francs a year drawn by the count as Inspector-General of the Stud.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.315#And the ladies, mother and daughter, kept very short of money by him,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.316#impoverished by tender escapades outside, were sometimes reduced to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.317#turning their dresses themselves.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.318#“In that case, why marry?” was Mouret's simple question.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.319#“Well! I can't go on like this for ever,” said Vallagnosc, with a weary
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.320#movement of the eyelids. “Besides, there are certain expectations; we
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.321#are waiting the death of an aunt.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.322#However, Mouret still kept his eye on Monsieur de Boves, who, seated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.323#next to Madame Guibal, was most attentive, and laughing tenderly like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.324#a man on an amorous campaign; he turned to his friend with such a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.325#significant twinkle of the eye that the latter added:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.326#“Not that one. At least not yet. The misfortune is, that his duty calls
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.327#him to the four corners of France, to the breeding dépôts, so that he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.328#has continual pretexts for absenting himself. Last month, whilst his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.329#wife supposed him to be at Perpignan, he was living at an hotel, in an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.330#out-of-the-way neighbourhood, with a music-mistress.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.331#There ensued a pause. Then the young man, who was also watching the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.332#count's gallantries towards Madame Guibal, resumed in a low tone:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.333#“Really, I think you are right. The more so as the dear lady is not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.334#exactly a saint, if all they say is true. There's a very amusing story
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.335#about her and an officer. But just look at him! Isn't he comical,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.336#magnetising her with his eyes? The old-fashioned gallantry, my dear
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.337#fellow! I adore that man, and if I marry his daughter, he can safely say
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.338#it's for his sake!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.339#Mouret laughed, greatly amused. He questioned Vallagnosc again, and when
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.340#he found that the first idea of a marriage between him and Blanche came
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.341#from Madame Desforges, he thought the story better still. That good
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.342#Henriette took a widow's delight in marrying people, so much so, that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.343#when she had provided for the girls, she sometimes allowed their fathers
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.344#to choose friends from her company; but all so naturally, with such a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.345#good grace, that no one ever found any food for scandal. And Mouret, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.346#loved her with the love of an active, busy man, accustomed to reducing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.347#his tenderness to figures, forgot all his calculations of captivation,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.348#and felt for her a comrade's friendship.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.349#At that moment she appeared at the door of the little drawing-room,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.350#followed by a gentleman, about sixty years old, whose entry had not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.351#been observed by the two friends. Occasionally the ladies' voices became
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.352#sharper, accompanied by the tinkling of the small spoons in the china
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.353#cups; and there was heard, from time to time, in the interval of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.354#short silence, the noise of a saucer laid down too roughly on the marble
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.355#table. A sudden gleam of the setting sun, which had just emerged from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.356#behind a thick cloud, gilded the top of the chestnut-trees in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.357#gardens, and streamed through the windows in a red, golden flame, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.358#fire of which lighted up the brocatel and brass-work of the furniture.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.359#“This way, my dear baron,” said Madame Desforges. “Allow me to introduce
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.360#Monsieur Octave Mouret, who is longing to express the admiration he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.361#feels for you.” And turning round towards Octave, she added: “Baron
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.362#Hartmann.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.363#[Illustration: 0077]
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.364#A smile played on the old man's lips. He was a short, vigorous man, with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.365#a large Alsatian head, and a heavy face, which lighted up with a gleam
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.366#of intelligence at the slightest curl of his mouth, the slightest
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.367#movement of his eyelids. For the last fortnight he had resisted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.368#Henriette's wish that he should consent to this interview; not that he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.369#felt any immoderate jealousy, accepting, like a man of the world, his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.370#position of father; but because it was the third friend Henriette had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.371#introduced to him, and he was afraid of becoming ridiculous at last.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.372#So that on approaching Octave he put on the discreet smile of a rich
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.373#protector, who, if good enough to show himself charming, does not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.374#consent to be a dupe.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.375#“Oh! sir,” said Mouret, with his Southern enthusiasm, “the Credit
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.376#Immobiliers last operation was really astonishing! You cannot think how
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.377#happy and proud I am to know you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.378#“Too kind, sir, too kind,” repeated the baron, still smiling.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.379#Henriette looked at them with her clear eyes without any awkwardness,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.380#standing between the two, lifting her head, going from one to the other;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.381#and, in her lace dress, which revealed her delicate neck and wrists, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.382#appeared delighted to see them so friendly together.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.383#“Gentlemen,” said she at last, “I leave you to your conversation.” Then,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.384#turning towards Paul, who had got up, she resumed: “Will you accept of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.385#cup of tea, Monsieur de Vallagnosc?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.386#“With pleasure, madame,” and they both returned to the drawing-room.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.387#Mouret resumed his place on the sofa, when Baron Hartmann had sat
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.388#down; the young man then broke out in praise of the Credit Immobiliers
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.389#operations. From that he went on to the subject so near his heart,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.390#speaking of the new thoroughfare, of the lengthening of the Rue Reaumur,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.391#of which they were going to open a section under the name of the Rue du
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.392#Dix-Décembre, between the Place de la Bourse and the Place de
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.393#l'Opera. It had been declared a work of public utility eighteen months
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.394#previously; the expropriation jury had just been appointed. The whole
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.395#neighbourhood was excited about this new opening, anxiously awaiting the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.396#commencement of the work, taking an interest in the condemned houses.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.397#Mouret had been waiting three years for this work--first, in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.398#expectation of an increase of business; secondly, with certain schemes
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.399#of enlargement which he dared not openly avow, so extensive were his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.400#ideas. As the Rue du Dix-Décembre was to cut through the Rue de Choiseul
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.401#and the Rue de la Michodière, he saw The Ladies' Paradise invading
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.402#the whole block, surrounded by these streets and the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.403#Neuve-Saint-Augustin; he already imagined it with a princely frontage in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.404#the new thoroughfare, lord and master of the conquered city. Hence his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.405#strong desire to make Baron Hartmann's acquaintance, when he learnt that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.406#the Crédit Immobilier had made a contract with the authorities to open
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.407#and build the Rue du Dix-Décembre, on condition that they received the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.408#frontage ground on each side of the street.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.409#“Really,” repeated he, trying to assume a naïve look, “you'll hand over
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.410#the street ready made, with sewers, pavements, and gas lamps. And the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.411#frontage ground will suffice to compensate you. Oh! it's curious, very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.412#curious!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.413#At last he came to the delicate point. He was aware that the Crédit
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.414#Immobilier was buying up the houses which surrounded The Ladies'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.415#Paradise, not only those which were to fall under the demolisher's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.416#hands, but the others as well, those which were to remain standing; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.417#he suspected the projectment of some future establishment He was very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.418#anxious about the enlargements of which he continued to extend the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.419#dream, seized with fear at the idea of one day clashing with a powerful
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.420#company, owning property which they certainly would not part with. It
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.421#was precisely this fear which had decided him to establish a connection
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.422#immediately between himself and the baron--the amiable connection of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.423#woman, so powerful between men of a gallant nature. No doubt he could
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.424#have seen the financier in his office, and talked over the affair in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.425#question at his ease; but he felt himself stronger in Henriette's house;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.426#he knew how much the mutual possession of a mistress serves to render
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.427#men pliable and tender. To be both near her, within the beloved perfume
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.428#of her presence, to have her ready to convince them with a smile, seemed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.429#to him a certainty of success.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.430#“Haven't you bought the old Hôtel Duvillard, that old building next to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.431#mine?” he asked suddenly.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.432#The baron hesitated a moment, and then denied it. But Mouret looked in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.433#his face and smiled, playing, from that moment, the part of a good young
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.434#man, open-hearted, simple, and straightforward in business.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.435#“Look here, baron,” said he, “as I have the unexpected honour of meeting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.436#you, I must make a confession. Oh, I don't ask you any of your secrets,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.437#but I am going to entrust you with mine, certain that I couldn't place
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.438#them in wiser hands. Besides, I want your advice. I have long wished to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.439#call and see you, but dared not do so.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.440#He did make his confession, he related his start, not even concealing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.441#the financial crisis through which he was passing in the midst of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.442#triumph. Everything was brought up, the successive enlargements, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.443#profits continually put back into the business, the sums brought by his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.444#employees, the house risking its existence at every fresh sale, in which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.445#the entire capital was staked, as it were, on a single throw of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.446#dice. However, it was not money he wanted, for he had a fanatic's faith
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.447#in his customers; his ambition ran higher; he proposed to the baron a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.448#partnership, into which the Credit Immobilier should bring the colossal
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.449#palace he saw in his dreams, whilst he, for his part, would give his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.450#genius and the business already created. The estate could be valued,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.451#nothing appeared to him easier to realise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.452#“What are you going to do with your land and buildings?” asked he,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.453#persistently. “You have a plan, no doubt. But I'm quite certain your
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.454#idea is not so good as mine. Think of that. We build a gallery on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.455#ground, we pull down or re-arrange the houses, and we open the most
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.456#extensive establishment in Paris--a bazaar which will bring in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.457#millions.” And he let slip the fervent heartfelt exclamation: “Ah! if I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.458#could only do without you! But you get hold of everything now. Besides,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.459#I shall never have the necessary capital. Come, we must come to an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.460#understanding. It would be a crime not to do so.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.461#“How you go ahead, my dear sir!” Baron Hartmann contented himself with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.462#replying. “What an imagination!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.463#He shook his head, and continued to smile, determined not to return
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.464#confidence for confidence. The intention of the Crédit Immobilier was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.465#to create in the Rue du Dix-Décembre a rival to the Grand Hôtel, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.466#luxurious establishment, the central position of which would attract
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.467#foreigners. At the same time, as the hôtel was only to occupy a certain,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.468#frontage, the baron could also have entertained Mouret's idea, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.469#treated for the rest of the block of houses, occupying a vast surface.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.470#But he had already advanced funds to two of Henriette's friends, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.471#he was getting tired of his position as complacent protector. Besides,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.472#notwithstanding his passion for activity, which prompted him to open his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.473#purse to every fellow of intelligence and courage, Mouret's commercial
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.474#genius astonished more than captivated him. Was it not a fanciful,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.475#imprudent operation, this gigantic shop? Would he not risk a certain
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.476#failure in thus enlarging out of all bounds the drapery trade? In short,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.477#he didn't believe in it; he refused.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.478#“No doubt the idea is attractive, but it's a poet's idea. Where would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.479#you find the customers to fill such a cathedral?” Mouret looked at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.480#him for a moment silently, as if stupefied at his refusal. Was it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.481#possible?--a man of such foresight, who smelt money at no matter what
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.482#depth! And suddenly, with an extremely eloquent gesture, he pointed to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.483#the ladies in the drawing-room and exclaimed: “There are my customers!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.484# The sun was going down, the golden-red flame was now but a pale light,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.485#dying away in a farewell gleam on the silk of the hangings and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.486#panels of the furniture. At this approach of twilight, an intimacy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.487#bathed the large room in a sweet softness. While Monsieur de Boves and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.488#Paul de Vallagnosc were talking near one of the windows, their eyes
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.489#wandering far away into the gardens, the ladies had closed up, forming
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.490#in the middle of the room a narrow circle of petticoats, from which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.491#issued sounds of laughter, whispered words, ardent questions and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.492#replies, all the passion felt by woman for expenditure and finery. They
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.493#were talking about dress, and Madame de Boves was describing a costume
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.494#she had seen at a ball.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.495#“First of all, a mauve silk skirt, then over that flounces of old
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.496#Alençon lace, twelve inches deep.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.497#“Oh! is it possible!” exclaimed Madame Marty. “Some women are
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.498#fortunate!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.499#Baron Hartmann, who had followed Mouret's gesture, was looking at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.500#ladies through the door, which was wide open. He was listening to them
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.501#with one ear, whilst the young man, inflamed by the desire to convince
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.502#him, went deeper into the question, explaining the mechanism of the new
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.503#style of drapery business. This branch of commerce was now based on a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.504#rapid and continual turning over of the capital, which it was necessary
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.505#to turn into goods as often as possible in the same year. Thus, that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.506#year his capital, which only amounted to five hundred thousand francs,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.507#had been turned over four times, and had thus produced business to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.508#the amount of two millions. But this was a mere trifle, which could
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.509#be increased tenfold, for later on he certainly hoped to turn over the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.510#capital fifteen or twenty times in certain departments.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.511#“You will understand, baron, that the whole system lies in this. It
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.512#is very simple, but it had to be found out. We don't want a very large
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.513#working capital; our sole effort is to get rid as quickly as possible of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.514#our stock to replace it by another, which will give our capital as many
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.515#times its interest. In this way we can content ourselves with a very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.516#small profit; as our general expenses amount to the enormous figure of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.517#sixteen per cent., and as we seldom make more than twenty per cent, on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.518#our goods, it is only a net profit of four per cent at most; but this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.519#will finish by bringing in millions when we can operate on considerable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.520#quantities of goods incessantly renewed. You follow me, don't you?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.521#nothing can be clearer.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.522#The baron shook his head again. He who had entertained the boldest
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.523#combinations, of whom people still quoted the daring flights at the time
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.524#of the introduction of gas, still remained uneasy and obstinate.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.525#“I quite understand,” said he; “you sell cheap to sell a quantity, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.526#you sell a quantity to sell cheap. But you must sell, and I repeat my
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.527#former question: Whom will you sell to? How do you hope to keep up such
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.528#a colossal sale?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.529#The sudden burst of a voice, coming from the drawing-room, cut short
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.530#Mouret's explanation. It was Madame Guibal, who was saying she would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.531#have preferred the flounces of old Alençon down the front only.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.532#“But, my dear,” said Madame de Boves, “the front was covered with it as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.533#well. I never saw anything richer.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.534#“Ah, that's a good idea,” resumed Madame Desforges, “I've got several
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.535#yards of Alençon somewhere; I must look them up for a trimming.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.536#And the voices fell again, becoming nothing but a murmur. Prices were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.537#quoted, quite a traffic stirred up their desires, the ladies were buying
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.538#lace by the mile.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.539#“Why!” said Mouret, when he could speak, “we can sell what we like when
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.540#we know how to sell! There lies our triumph.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.541#And with his southern spirit, he showed the new business at work in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.542#warm, glowing phrases which evoked whole pictures. First came the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.543#wonderful power of the piling up of the goods, all accumulated at one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.544#point, sustaining and pushing each other, never any stand-still, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.545#article of the season always on hand; and from counter to counter the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.546#customer found herself seized, buying here the material, further on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.547#cotton, elsewhere the mantle, everything necessary to complete her dress
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.548#in fact, then falling into unforeseen purchases, yielding to her longing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.549#for the useless and the pretty. He then went on to sing the praises of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.550#the plain figure system. The great revolution in the business sprung
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.551#from this fortunate inspiration. If the old-fashioned small shops were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.552#dying out it was because they could not struggle against the low prices
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.553#guaranteed by the tickets. The competition was now going on under
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.554#the very eyes of the public; a look into the windows enabled them to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.555#contrast the prices; every shop was lowering its rates, contenting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.556#itself with the smallest possible profit; no cheating, no stroke of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.557#fortune prepared long beforehand on an article sold at double its value,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.558#but current operations, a regular percentage on all goods, success
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.559#depending solely on the orderly working of a sale all the larger from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.560#the fact of its being carried on in broad daylight. Was it not an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.561#astonishing creation? It was causing a revolution in the market,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.562#transforming Paris, for it was made of woman's flesh and blood.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.563#“I have the women, I don't care a hang for the rest!” said Mouret, in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.564#brutal confession which passion snatched from him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.565#At this cry Baron Hartmann appeared moved. His smile lost its touch of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.566#irony; he looked at the young man, won over gradually by his confidence,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.567#feeling a growing tenderness for him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.568#“Hush!” murmured he, paternally, “they will hear you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.569#But the ladies were now all speaking at once, so excited that they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.570#weren't even listening to each other. Madame de Boves was finishing the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.571#description of a dinner-dress; a mauve silk tunic, draped and caught up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.572#by bows of lace; the bodice cut very low, with more bows of lace on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.573#shoulders.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.574#“You'll see,” said she. “I am having a bodice made like it, with some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.575#satin----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.576#“I,” interrupted Madame Bourdelais, “I wanted some velvet. Oh! such a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.577#bargain!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.578#Madame Marty asked: “How much for the silk?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.579#And off they started again, all together. Madame Guibal, Henriette, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.580#Blanche were measuring, cutting out, and making up. It was a pillage of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.581#material, a ransacking of all the shops, an appetite for luxury which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.582#expended itself in toilettes longed for and dreamed of--such a happiness
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.583#to find themselves in an atmosphere of finery, that they lived buried in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.584#it, as in the warm air necessary to their existence.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.585#Mouret, however, had glanced towards the other drawingroom, and in a few
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.586#phrases whispered into the baron's ear, as if he were confiding to him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.587#one of those amorous secrets that men sometimes risk among themselves,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.588#he finished explaining the mechanism of modern commerce. And, above the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.589#facts already given, right at the summit, appeared the exploitation of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.590#woman. Everything depended on that, the capital incessantly renewed, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.591#system of piling up goods, the cheapness which attracts, the marking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.592#in plain figures which tranquilises. It was for woman that all the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.593#establishments were struggling in wild competition; it was woman that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.594#they were continually catching in the snare of their bargains, after
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.595#bewildering her with their displays. They had awakened new desires in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.596#her flesh; they were an immense temptation, before which she succumbed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.597#fatally, yielding at first to reasonable purchases of useful articles
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.598#for the household, then tempted by their coquetry, then devoured. In
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.599#increasing their business tenfold, in popularising luxury, they became
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.600#a terrible spending agency, ravaging the households, working up the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.601#fashionable folly of the hour, always dearer. And if woman reigned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.602#in their shops like a queen, cajoled, flattered, overwhelmed with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.603#attentions, she was an amorous one, on whom her subjects traffic, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.604#who pays with a drop of her blood each fresh caprice. Through the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.605#very gracefulness of his gallantry, Mouret thus allowed to appear the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.606#brutality of a Jew, selling woman by the pound. He raised a temple to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.607#her, had her covered with incense by a legion of shopmen, created the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.608#rite of a new religion, thinking of nothing but her, continually seeking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.609#to imagine more powerful seductions; and, behind her back, when he had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.610#emptied her purse and shattered her nerves, he was full of the secret
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.611#scorn of a man to whom a woman had just been stupid enough to yield
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.612#herself.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.613#“Once have the women on your side,” whispered he to the baron, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.614#laughing boldly, “you could sell the very world.” Now the baron
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.615#understood. A few sentences had sufficed, he guessed the rest, and such
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.616#a gallant exploitation inflamed him, stirring up in him the memory of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.617#his past life of pleasure. His eyes twinkled in a knowing way, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.618#he ended by looking with an air of admiration at the inventor of this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.619#machine for devouring the women. It was really clever. He made the same
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.620#remark as Bourdoncle, suggested to him by his long experience: “You know
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.621#they'll make you suffer for it.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.622#But Mouret shrugged his shoulders in a movement of overwhelming disdain.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.623#They all belonged to him, were his property, and he belonged to none
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.624#of them. After having drawn from them his fortune and his pleasure, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.625#intended to throw them all over for those who might still find their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.626#account in them. It was the rational, cold disdain of a Southerner and a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.627#speculator.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.628#“Well! my dear baron,” asked he in conclusion, “will you join me? Does
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.629#this affair appear possible to you?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.630#The baron, half conquered, did not wish, however, to engage himself yet
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.631#A doubt remained beneath the charm which was gradually operating on him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.632#He was going to reply in an evasive manner, when a pressing call from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.633#the ladies spared him the trouble. Voices were repeating, amidst silvery
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.634#laughter: “Monsieur Mouret! Monsieur Mouret!” And as the latter, annoyed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.635#at being interrupted, pretended not to hear, Madame de Boves, who had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.636#just got up, came as far as the door of the little drawing-room.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.637#“You are wanted, Monsieur Mouret. It isn't very gallant of you to bury
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.638#yourself in a corner to talk over business.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.639#He then decided to go, with an apparent good grace, an air of rapture
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.640#which astonished the baron. Both rose up and passed into the other
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.641#drawing-room.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.642#“But I am quite at your service, ladies,” said he on entering, a smile
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.643#on his lips.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.644#He was greeted with a burst of triumph. He was obliged to go further
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.645#forward; the ladies made room for him in their midst The sun had just
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.646#gone down behind the trees in the gardens, the day was departing, a fine
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.647#shadow was gradually invading the vast apartment. It was the tender hour
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.648#of twilight, that minute of discreet voluptuousness in the Parisian
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.649#houses, between the dying brightness of the street and the lighting of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.650#the lamps downstairs. Monsieur de Boves and Vallagnosc, still standing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.651#up before a window, threw a shadow on the carpet: whilst, motionless
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.652#in the last gleam of light which came in by the other window, Monsieur
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.653#Marty, who had quietly entered, and whom the conversation of these
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.654#ladies about dress had completely confused, placed his poor profile, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.655#frock-coat, scanty but clean, his face pale and wan from teaching.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.656#“Is your sale still fixed for next Monday?” Madame Marty was just
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.657#asking.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.658#“Certainly, madame,” replied Mouret, in a soft, sweet voice, an actor's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.659#voice, which he assumed when speaking to women.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.660#Henriette then intervened. “We are all going, you know. They say you are
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.661#preparing wonders.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.662#“Oh! wonders!” murmured he, with an air of modest fatuity. “I simply try
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.663#to deserve your patronage.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.664#But they pressed him with questions: Madame Bourdelais, Madame Guibal,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.665#Blanche even wanted to know.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.666#“Come, give us some details,” repeated Madame de Boves, persistently.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.667#“You are making us die of curiosity.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.668#And they were surrounding him, when Henriette observed that he had not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.669#even taken a cup of tea. It was distressing. Four of them set about
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.670#serving him, but on condition that he would answer them afterwards.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.671#Henriette poured it out, Madame Marty held the cup, whilst Madame de
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.672#Boves and Madame Bourdelais contended for the honour of sweetening it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.673#Then, when he had declined to sit down, and commenced to drink his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.674#tea slowly, standing up in the midst of them, they all approached,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.675#imprisoning him in the narrow circle of their skirts; and with their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.676#heads raised, their eyes sparkling, they sat there smiling at him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.677#“Your silk, your Paris Paradise, that all the papers are taking about?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.678# resumed Madame Marty, impatiently.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.679#“Oh!” replied he, “an extraordinary article, coarse-grained, supple and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.680#strong. You'll see it, ladies, and you'll see it nowhere else, for we
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.681#have bought the exclusive right of it.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.682#“Really! a fine silk at five francs twelve sous!” said Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.683#Bourdelais, enthusiastic. “One cannot credit it.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.684#Ever since the advertisement had appeared, this silk had occupied a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.685#considerable place in their daily life. They talked of it, promising
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.686#themselves some of it, worked up with desire and doubt. And, beneath
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.687#the gossiping curiosity with which they overwhelmed the young man, there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.688#appeared their various temperaments as buyers.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.689#Madame Marty, carried away by her rage for spending, took everything at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.690#The Ladies' Paradise, without choosing, just as the articles appeared;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.691#Madame Guibal walked about the shop for hours without ever buying
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.692#anything, happy and satisfied to simply feast her eyes; Madame de Boves,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.693#short of money, always tortured by some immoderate wish, nourished a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.694#feeling of rancour against the goods she could not carry away; Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.695#Bourdelais, with the sharp eye of a careful practical housewife, made
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.696#straight for the bargains, using the big establishments with such a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.697#clever housewife's skill that she saved a heap of money; and lastly,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.698#Henriette, who, very elegant, only procured certain articles there, such
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.699#as gloves, hosiery, and her coarser linen.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.700#“We have other stuffs of astonishing cheapness and richness,” continued
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.701#Mouret, with his musical voice. “For instance, I recommend you our
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.702#Golden Grain, a taffeta of incomparable brilliancy. In the fancy silks
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.703#there are some charming lines, designs chosen from among thousands by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.704#our buyer: and in velvets you will find an exceedingly rich collection
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.705#of shades. I warn you that cloth will be greatly worn this year; you'll
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.706#see our checks and our cheviots.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.707#They had ceased to interrupt him, and narrowed the circle, their mouths
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.708#half open with a vague smile, their eager faces close to his, as in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.709#sudden rush of their whole being towards the tempter. Their eyes grew
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.710#dim, a slight shudder ran through them. All this time he retained his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.711#calm, conquering air, amidst the intoxicating perfumes which their hair
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.712#exhaled; and between each sentence he continued to sip a little of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.713#tea, the aroma of which cooled those sharper odours, in which there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.714#was a particle of the savage. Before a captivating grace so thoroughly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.715#master of itself, strong enough to play with woman in this way without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.716#being overcome by the intoxication which she exhales, Baron Hartmann,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.717#who had not ceased to look at him, felt his admiration increasing.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.718#“So cloth will be worn?” resumed Madame Marty, whose ravished face
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.719#sparkled with coquettish passion.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.720#Madame Bourdelais, who kept a cool look-out, said, in her turn: “Your
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.721#sale of remnants takes place on Thursday, doesn't it? I shall wait. I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.722#have all my little ones to clothe.” And turning her delicate blonde head
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.723#towards the mistress of the house: “Sauveur is still your dressmaker, I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.724#suppose?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.725#“Yes,” replied Henriette, “Sauveur is very dear, but she is the only one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.726#in Paris who knows how to make a bodice. Besides, Monsieur Mouret may
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.727#say what he likes, she has the prettiest designs, designs that are not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.728#seen anywhere else. I can't bear to see my dresses on every woman's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.729#back.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.730#Mouret smiled discreetly at first. Then he intimated that Madame Sauveur
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.731#bought her material at his shop; no doubt she went to the manufacturers
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.732#direct for certain designs of which she acquired the sole right of sale;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.733#but for all black silks, for instance, she watched for The Paradise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.734#bargains, laying in a considerable stock, which she disposed of at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.735#double and treble the price she gave.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.736#“Thus I am quite sure her buyers will snap up all our Paris Paradise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.737#Why should she go to the manufacturers and pay dearer for this silk
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.738#than she would at my place? On my word of honour, we shall sell it at a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.739#loss.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.740#This was a decisive blow for the ladies. The idea of getting goods below
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.741#cost price awoke in them all the greed felt by women, whose enjoyment
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.742#as buyers is doubled when they think they are robbing the tradesman. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.743#knew them to be incapable of resisting anything cheap.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.744#“But we sell everything for nothing!” exclaimed he gaily, taking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.745#up Madame Desforges's fan, which was behind him on the table. “For
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.746#instance, here's this fan. I don't know what it cost.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.747#“The Chantilly lace was twenty-five francs, and the mounting cost two
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.748#hundred,” said Henriette.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.749#“Well, the Chantilly isn't dear. However, we have the same at eighteen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.750#francs; as for the mount, my dear madame, it's a shameful robbery. I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.751#should not dare to sell one like it for more than ninety francs.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.752#“Just what I said!” exclaimed Madame Bourdelais.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.753#“Ninety francs!” murmured Madame de Boves; “one must be very poor indeed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.754#to go without one at that price.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.755#She had taken up the fan, and was again examining it with her daughter
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.756#Blanche; and, on her large regular face, in her big sleepy eyes, there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.757#arose an expression of the suppressed and despairing longing of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.758#caprice in which she could not indulge. The fan once more went the round
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.759#of the ladies, amidst various remarks and exclamations. Monsieur de
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.760#Boves and Vallagnosc, however, had left the window. Whilst the former
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.761#had returned to his place behind Madame Guibal, the charms of whose bust
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.762#he was admiring, with his correct and superior air, the young man was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.763#leaning over Blanche, endeavouring to find something agreeable to say.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.764#“Don't you think it rather gloomy, mademoiselle, this white mount and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.765#black lace?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.766#“Oh,” replied she, gravely, not a blush colouring her inflated cheeks,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.767#“I once saw one made of mother-of-pearl and white lace. Something truly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.768#virginal!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.769#Monsieur de Boves, who had doubtless observed the heartbroken, longing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.770#looks with which his wife was following the fan, at last added his word
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.771#to the conversation. “These flimsy things don't last long, they soon
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.772#break,” said he.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.773#“Of course they do!” declared Madame Guibal, with an air of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.774#indifference. “I'm tired of having mine mended.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.775#For several minutes, Madame Marty, excited by the conversation, was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.776#feverishly turning her red leather bag about on her lap, for she had not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.777#yet been able to show her purchases. She was burning to display them,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.778#with a sort of sensual desire; and, suddenly forgetting her husband's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.779#presence, she took out a few yards of narrow lace wound on a piece of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.780#cardboard.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.781#“It's the Valenciennes for my daughter,” said she. “It's an inch and a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.782#half wide. Isn't it delicious? One franc eighteen sous.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.783#The lace was passed from hand to hand. The ladies were astonished.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.784#Mouret assured them he sold these little trimmings at cost price.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.785#However, Madame Marty had closed the bag, as if to conceal certain
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.786#things she could not show. But after the success obtained by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.787#Valenciennes she was unable to resist the temptation of taking out a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.788#handkerchief.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.789#“There was this handkerchief as well. Real Brussels, my dear. Oh! a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.790#bargain! Twenty francs!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.791#And after that the bag became inexhaustible, she blushed with pleasure,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.792#a modesty like that of a woman undressing herself made her appear more
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.793#charming and embarrassed at each fresh article she took out. There was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.794#a Spanish blonde-lace cravat, thirty francs: she didn't want it, but the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.795#shopman had sworn it was the last, and that in future the price would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.796#be raised. Next came a Chantilly veil: rather dear, fifty francs; if she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.797#didn't wear it she could make it do for her daughter.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.798#“Really, lace is so pretty!” repeated she with her nervous laugh. “Once
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.799#I'm inside I could buy everything.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.800#“And this?” asked Madame de Boves, taking up and examining a remnant of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.801#Maltese lace.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.802#“That,” replied she, “is for an insertion. There are twenty-six yards--a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.803#franc the yard. Just fancy!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.804#“But,” said Madame Bourdelais, surprised, “what are you going to do with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.805#it?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.806#“I'm sure I don't know. But it was such a funny pattern!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.807#At this moment she raised her eyes and perceived her terrified husband
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.808#in front of her. He had turned paler than usual, his whole person
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.809#expressed the patient, resigned anguish of a man assisting, powerless,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.810#at the reckless expenditure of his salary, so dearly earned. Every fresh
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.811#bit of lace was for him a disaster; bitter days of teaching swallowed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.812#up, long journeys to pupils through the mud devoured, the continued
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.813#effort of his life resulting in a secret misery, the hell of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.814#necessitous household. Before the increasing wildness of his look, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.815#wanted to catch up the veil, the cravat, and the handkerchief, moving
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.816#her feverish hands about, repeating with forced laughter: “You'll get
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.817#me a scolding from my husband. I assure you, my dear, I've been very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.818#reasonable; for there was a fine piece of point at five hundred francs,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.819#oh! a marvel!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.820#“Why didn't you buy it?” asked Madame Guibal, calmly. “Monsieur Marty is
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.821#the most gallant of men.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.822#The poor professor was obliged to bow and say his wife was perfectly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.823#welcome. But the idea of this point at five hundred francs was like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.824#a lump of ice dripping down his back; and as Mouret was just at that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.825#moment affirming that the new shops increased the comfort of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.826#middle-class households, he glared at him with a terrible expression,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.827#the flash of hatred of a timid man who would have throttled him had he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.828#dared.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.829#But the ladies had still kept hold of the bits of lace, fascinated,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.830#intoxicated. The pieces were unrolled, passed from one to the other,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.831#drawing the admirers closer still, holding them in the delicate
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.832#meshes. On their laps there was a continual caress of this tissue,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.833#so miraculously fine, and amidst which their culpable fingers fondly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.834#lingered. They still kept Mouret a close prisoner, overwhelming him with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.835#fresh questions. As the day continued to decline, he was now and again
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.836#obliged to bend his head, grazing their hair with his beard, to examine
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.837#a stitch, or indicate a design. But in this soft voluptuousness of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.838#twilight, in the midst of this warm feminine atmosphere, Mouret still
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.839#remained their master beneath the rapture he affected. He seemed, to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.840#a woman himself, they felt themselves penetrated and overcome by this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.841#delicate sense of their secret that he possessed, and they abandoned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.842#themselves, captivated; whilst he, certain from that moment to have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.843#them at his mercy, appeared, brutally triumphing over them, the despotic
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.844#monarch of dress.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.845#“Oh, Monsieur Mouret!” stammered they, in low, hysterical voices, in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.846#gloom of the drawing-room.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.847#The last rays of the setting sun were dying away on the brass-work
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.848#of the furniture. The laces alone retained a snowy reflex on the dark
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.849#dresses of the ladies, of which the confused group seemed to surround
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.850#the young man with a vague appearance of kneeling, worshipping women. A
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.851#light still shone on the side of the silver teapot, a short flame like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.852#that of a night-light, burning in an alcove warmed by the perfume of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.853#tea. But suddenly the servant entered with two lamps, and the charm was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.854#destroyed. The drawing-room became light and cheerful. Madame Marty was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.855#putting her lace in her little bag, Madame de Boves was eating a sponge
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.856#cake, whilst Henriette who had got up, was talking in a half-whisper to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.857#the baron, near one of the windows.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.858#“He's a charming fellow,” said the baron.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.859#“Isn't he?” exclaimed she, with the involuntary cry of a woman in love.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.860#He smiled, and looked at her with a paternal indulgence. This was the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.861#first time he had seen her so completely conquered; and, too proud to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.862#suffer from it, he experienced nothing but a feeling of compassion on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.863#seeing her in the hands of this handsome fellow, so tender and yet so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.864#cold-hearted. He thought he ought to warn her, and murmured in a joking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.865#tone: “Take care, my dear, or he'll eat you all up.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.866#A flash of jealousy lighted up Henriette's eyes. Perhaps she understood
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.867#Mouret had simply made use of her to get at the baron; and she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.868#determined to render him mad with passion, he whose hurried style of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.869#making love had the easy charm of a song thrown to the four winds of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.870#heaven. “Oh,” said she, affecting to joke in her turn, “the lamb always
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.871#finishes up by eating the wolf.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.872#The baron, greatly amused, encouraged, her with a nod. Could she be the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.873#woman who was to avenge all the others?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.874#When Mouret, after having reminded Vallagnosc that he wanted to show him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.875#his machine at work, came up to take his leave, the baron retained him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.876#near the window opposite the gardens, now buried in darkness. He yielded
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.877#at last to the seduction; his confidence had come on seeing him in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.878#midst of these ladies. Both conversed for a moment in a low tone, then
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.879#the banker said: “Well, I'll look into the affair. It's settled if your
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.880#Monday's sale proves as important as you expect.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.881#They shook hands, and Mouret, delighted, took his leave, for he did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.882#enjoy his dinner unless he went and gave a look at the day's receipts at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iii.883#The Ladies' Paradise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1#CHAPTER IV.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.2#The following Monday, the 10th of October, a clear, victorious sun
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.3#pierced the grey clouds which had darkened Paris during the previous
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.4#week. It had drizzled all the previous night, a sort of watery mist, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.5#humidity of which dirtied the streets; but in the early morning, thanks
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.6#to the sharp wind which was driving the clouds away, the pavement had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.7#become drier, and the blue sky had a limpid, spring-like gaiety.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.8#Thus The Ladies' Paradise, after eight o'clock, blazed forth beneath
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.9#the clear rays of the sun, in all the glory of its great sale of winter
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.10#novelties. Flags were flying at the door, and pieces of woollens were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.11#flapping about in the fresh morning air, animating the Place Gaillon
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.12#with the bustle of a country fair; whilst in both streets the windows
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.13#developed symphonies of displays, the clearness of the glass showing up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.14#still further the brilliant tones. It was like a debauch of colour,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.15#a street pleasure which burst forth there, a wealth of goods publicly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.16#displayed, where everybody could go and feast their eyes.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.17#But at this hour very few people entered, only a few rare customers,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.18#housewives of the neighbourhood, women desirous of avoiding the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.19#afternoon crush. Behind the stuffs which decorated it, one could feel
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.20#the shop to be empty, under arms and waiting for customers, with its
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.21#waxed floors and counters overflowing with goods.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.22#The busy morning crowd barely glanced at the windows, without lingering
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.23#a moment. In the Rue Neuve-Saint-Augustin and in the Place Gaillon,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.24#where the carriages were to take their stand, there were only two cabs
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.25#at nine o'clock. The inhabitants of the district, especially the small
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.26#traders, stirred up by such a show of streamers and decorations, formed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.27#little groups in the doorways, at the corners of the streets, gazing at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.28#the shop, making bitter remarks. What most filled them with indignation
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.29#was the sight of one of the four delivery vans just introduced by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.30#Mouret, which was standing in the Rue de la Michodière, in front of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.31#delivery office. They were green, picked out with yellow and red, their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.32#brilliantly varnished panels sparkling in the sun with the brightness
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.33#of purple and gold. This van, with its brand-new medley of colours,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.34#the name of the house painted on each side, and surmounted with an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.35#advertisement of the day's sale, finished by going off at a trot, drawn
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.36#by a splendid horse, after being filled up with the previous night's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.37#parcels; and Baudu, who was standing on the threshold of The Old Elbeuf,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.38#watched it as far as the boulevard, where it disappeared, to spread all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.39#over Paris in a starry radiance the hated name of The Ladies' Paradise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.40#However, a few cabs were arriving and forming a line.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.41#Every time a customer entered, there was a movement amongst the shop
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.42#messengers, who were drawn up under the lofty doorway, dressed in livery
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.43#consisting of a light green coat and trousers, and striped red and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.44#yellow waistcoat. Jouve, the inspector and retired captain, was also
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.45#there, in a frock-coat and white tie, wearing his decoration like a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.46#sign of respectability and probity, receiving the ladies with a gravely
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.47#polite air, bending over them to point out the departments. Then they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.48#disappeared in the vestibule, which was transformed into an oriental
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.49#saloon.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.50#From the very threshold it was a marvel, a surprise, which enchanted all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.51#of them. It was Mouret who had been struck with this idea. He was the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.52#first to buy, in the Levant, at very advantageous rates, a collection of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.53#old and new carpets, articles which up to the present had only been sold
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.54#at curiosity shops, at high prices; and he intended to flood the market
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.55#with these goods, selling them at a little over cost price, simply
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.56#drawing from them a splendid decoration destined to attract the best
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.57#class of art customers to his establishment From the centre of the Place
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.58#Gaillon could be seen this oriental saloon, composed solely of carpets
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.59#and door curtains which had been hung under his orders. The ceiling was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.60#covered with a quantity of Smyrna carpets, the complicated designs of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.61#which stood out boldly on a red ground. Then from each side there hung
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.62#Syrian and Karamanian door-curtains, speckled with green, yellow, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.63#vermilion; Diarbekir door-curtains of a commoner type, rough to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.64#touch, like shepherds' cloaks; besides these there were carpets which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.65#could be used as door-curtains and hangings--long Ispahan, Teheran,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.66#and Kermancha rugs, the larger Schoumaka and Madras carpets, a strange
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.67#florescence of peonies and palms, the fancy let loose in a garden of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.68#dreams. On the floor were more carpets, a heap of greasy fleeces: in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.69#centre was an Agra carpet, an extraordinary article with a white ground
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.70#and a broad delicate blue border, through which ran violet-coloured
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.71#ornaments of exquisite design. Everywhere there was an immense display
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.72#of marvellous fabrics; Mecca carpets with a velvety reflection, prayer
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.73#carpets from Daghestan with a symbolic point, Kurdistan carpets covered
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.74#with blossoming flowers; and finally, piled up in a corner, a heap of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.75#Gherdes, Koula, and Kirchur rugs from fifteen francs a piece.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.76#This sumptuous pacha's tent was furnished with divans and arm-chairs,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.77#made with camel sacks, some ornamented with many-coloured lozenges,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.78#others with primitive roses. Turkey, Arabia, and the Indies were all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.79#there. They had emptied the palaces, plundered the mosques and bazaars.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.80#A barbarous gold tone prevailed in the weft of the old carpets,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.81#the faded tints of which still preserved a sombre warmth, as of an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.82#extinguished furnace, a beautiful burnt hue suggestive of the old
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.83#masters. Visions of the East floated beneath the luxury of this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.84#barbarous art, amid the strong odour which the old wools had retained of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.85#the country of vermin and of the rising sun.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.86#In the morning at eight o'clock, when Denise, who was to commence on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.87#that very Monday, had crossed the oriental saloon, she stood there,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.88#lost in astonishment, unable to recognise the shop entrance, entirely
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.89#overcome by this harem-like decoration planted at the door. A messenger
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.90#having shown her to the top of the house, and handed her over to Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.91#Cabin, who cleaned and looked after the rooms, this person installed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.92#her in No. 7, where her box had already been put. It was a narrow
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.93#cell, opening on the roof by a skylight, furnished with a small bed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.94#a walnut-wood wardrobe, a toilet-table, and two chairs. Twenty similar
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.95#rooms ran along the convent-like corridor, painted yellow; and, out of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.96#the thirty-five young ladies in the house, the twenty who had no friends
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.97#in Paris slept there, whilst the remaining fifteen lodged outside, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.98#few with borrowed aunts and cousins. Denise at once took off her shabby
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.99#woollen dress, worn thin by brushing and mended at the sleeves, the only
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.100#one she had brought from Valognes; she then put on the uniform of her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.101#department, a black silk dress which had been altered for her and which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.102#she found ready on the bed. This dress was still too large, too wide
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.103#across the shoulders; but she was so hurried in her emotion that she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.104#paid no heed to these details of coquetry. She had never worn silk
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.105#before. When she went downstairs again, dressed up, uncomfortable, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.106#looked at the shining skirt, feeling ashamed of the noisy rustling of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.107#the silk.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.108#Down below, as she was entering her department, a quarrel burst out. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.109#heard Clara say, in a shrill voice:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.110#“Madame, I came in before her.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.111#“It isn't true,” replied Marguerite. “She pushed past me at the door,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.112#but I had already one foot in the room.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.113#It was for the inscription on the list of turns, which regulated the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.114#sales. The saleswomen wrote their names on a slate in the order of their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.115#arrival, and whenever one of them had served a customer, she re-wrote
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.116#her name beneath the others. Madame Aurélie finished by deciding in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.117#Marguerite's favour.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.118#“Always some injustice here!” muttered Clara, furiously. But Denise's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.119#entry reconciled these young ladies. They looked at her, then smiled to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.120#each other. How could a person truss herself up in that way! The young
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.121#girl went and awkwardly wrote her name on the list, where she found
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.122#herself last. Meanwhile, Madame Aurélie was examining her with an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.123#anxious face. She could not help saying:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.124#“My dear, two like you could get into your dress; you must have it taken
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.125#in. Besides, you don't know how to dress yourself. Come here and let me
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.126#arrange you a bit.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.127#And she placed herself before one of the tall glasses alternating with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.128#the doors of the cupboards containing the dresses. The vast apartment,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.129#surrounded by these glasses and the wood-work in carved oak, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.130#floor covered with red Wilton carpet of a large pattern, resembled the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.131#commonplace drawing-room of an hotel, traversed by a continual stream of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.132#travellers. The young ladies completed the resemblance, dressed in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.133#regulation silk, promenading their commercial charms about, without ever
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.134#sitting down on the dozen chairs reserved for the customers. All wore
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.135#between two buttonholes of the body of their dresses, as if stuck in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.136#their bosoms, a long pencil, with its point in the air; and half out of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.137#their pockets, could be seen the white cover of the book of debit-notes.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.138#Several risked wearing jewellery--rings, brooches, chains; but their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.139#great coquetry, the luxury they all struggled for in the forced
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.140#uniformity of their dress, was their bare hair, quantities of it,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.141#augmented by plaits and chignons when their own did not suffice, combed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.142#curled, and decked out in every way.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.143#“Pull the waist down in front,” said Madame Aurélie. “There, you have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.144#now no hump on your back. And your hair, how can you massacre it like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.145#that? It would be superb, if you only took a little trouble.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.146#This was, in fact, Denise's only beauty. Of a beautiful flaxen hue, it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.147#fell down to her ankles; and when she did it up, it was so troublesome
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.148#that she simply rolled it in a knot, keeping it together under the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.149#strong teeth of a bone comb. Clara, greatly annoyed by this head of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.150#hair, affected to laugh at it, so strange did it look, twisted up anyhow
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.151#in its savage grace. She made a sign to a saleswoman in the under-linen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.152#department, a girl with a large face and agreeable manner. The two
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.153#departments, which were close together, were in continual hostility; but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.154#the young ladies sometimes joined together in laughing at other people.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.155#“Mademoiselle Cugnot, just look at that mane,” said Clara, whom
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.156#Marguerite was nudging, feigning also to be on the point of bursting out
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.157#laughing.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.158#But Mademoiselle Cugnot was not in the humour for joking. She had been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.159#looking at Denise for a moment, and she remembered what she had suffered
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.160#herself during the first few months of her arrival in the establishment.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.161#“Well, what?” said she. “Everybody hasn't got a mane like that!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.162#And she returned to her place, leaving the two others very crestfallen.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.163#Denise, who had heard all, followed her with a look of thanks, while
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.164#Madame Aurélie gave our heroine a book of debit-notes with her name on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.165#it, saying: “To-morrow you'll get yourself up better; and, now, try and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.166#pick up the ways of the house, wait your turn for selling. To-day's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.167#work will be very hard; we shall be able to judge of your capabilities.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.168# However, the department still remained deserted; very few customers came
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.169#up at this early hour. The young ladies reserved themselves, prudently
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.170#preparing for the fatigues of the afternoon. Denise, intimidated by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.171#thought that they were watching her, sharpened her pencil, for the sake
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.172#of something to do; then, imitating the others, she stuck it into
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.173#her bosom, between two buttonholes, and summoned up all her courage,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.174#determined to conquer a position. The previous evening they had told her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.175#she entered as a probationer, that is to say without any fixed salary;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.176#she would simply have the commission and a certain allowance on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.177#everything she sold. But she fully hoped to earn twelve hundred francs a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.178#year in this way, knowing that the good saleswomen earned as much as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.179#two thousand, when they liked to take the trouble. Her expenses were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.180#regulated; a hundred francs a month would enable her to pay Pépé's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.181#board and lodging, assist Jean, who did not earn a sou, and procure some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.182#clothes and linen for herself. But, in order to attain this large sum,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.183#she would have to show herself industrious and pushing, taking no notice
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.184#of the ill-will displayed by those around her, fighting for her share,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.185#even snatching it from her comrades if necessary. As she was thus
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.186#working herself up for the struggle, a tall young man, passing the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.187#department, smiled at her; and when she saw it was Deloche, who had been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.188#engaged in the lace department the previous day, she returned his smile,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.189#happy at the friendship which thus presented itself, accepting this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.190#smile as a good omen.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.191#At half-past nine a bell rang for the first luncheon. Then a fresh peal
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.192#announced the second; and still no customers appeared. The second-hand,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.193#Madame Frédéric, who, in her disagreeable widow's harshness, delighted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.194#in prophesying disasters, declared in short sentences that the day
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.195#was lost, that they would not see a soul, that they might close the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.196#cupboards and go away; predictions which darkened Marguerite's flat
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.197#face, she being a girl who looked sharp after her profits, whilst Clara,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.198#with her runaway-horse appearance, was already dreaming of an excursion
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.199#to the Verrières woods, if the house failed. As for Madame Aurélie, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.200#was there, silent and serious, promenading her Cæsar-like mask about
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.201#the empty department, like a general who has a certain responsibility
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.202#in victory and in defeat. About eleven o'clock a few ladies appeared.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.203#Denise's turn for serving had arrived. Just at that moment a customer
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.204#came up.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.205#“The fat old girl from the country,” murmured Marguerite.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.206#It was a woman of forty-five, who occasionally journeyed to Paris from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.207#the depths of some out-of-the-way place. There she saved up for months;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.208#then, hardly out of the train, she made straight for The Ladies'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.209#Paradise, and spent all her savings. She very rarely ordered anything
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.210#by letter, she liked to see and handle the goods, and laid in a stock of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.211#everything, even down to needles, which she said were excessively dear
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.212#in her small town. The whole staff knew her, that her name was Boutarel,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.213#and that she lived at Albi, but troubled no further about her, neither
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.214#about her position nor her mode of life.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.215#“How do you do, madame?” graciously asked Madame Aurélie, who had come
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.216#forward. “And what can we show you? You shall be attended to at once.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.217# Then, turning round: “Now, young ladies!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.218#Denise approached; but Clara had sprung forward. As a rule, she was very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.219#careless and idle, not caring about the money she earned in the shop, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.220#she could get plenty outside, without trouble. But the idea of doing the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.221#new-comer out of a good customer spurred her on.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.222#“I beg your pardon, it's my turn,” said Denise, indignantly. Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.223#Aurélie set her aside with a severe look, saying: “There are no turns.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.224#I alone am mistress here. Wait till you know, before serving our regular
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.225#customers.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.226#The young girl retired, and as the tears were coming in her eyes, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.227#she wished to conceal this excess of sensibility, she turned her back,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.228#standing up before the window, pretending to be looking into the street.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.229#Were they going to prevent her selling? Would they all arrange together
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.230#to deprive her of the important sales, like that? A fear for the future
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.231#seized her, she felt herself crushed between so many interests let
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.232#loose. Yielding to the bitterness of her abandonment, her forehead
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.233#against the cold glass, she gazed at The Old Elbeuf opposite, thinking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.234#she ought to have implored her uncle to keep her. Perhaps he himself
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.235#regretted his decision, for he seemed to her greatly affected the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.236#previous evening. Now she was quite alone in this vast house, where no
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.237#one liked her, where she found herself hurt, lost. Pépé and Jean, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.238#had never left her side, were living with strangers; it was a cruel
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.239#separation, and the big tears which she kept back made the street dance
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.240#in a sort of fog. All this time, the hum of voices continued behind her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.241#“This one makes me look a fright,” Madame Boutarel was saying.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.242#“You really make a mistake, madame,” said Clara; “the shoulders fit
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.243#perfectly--but perhaps you would prefer a pelisse to a mantle?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.244#But Denise started. A hand was laid on her arm. Madame Aurélie addressed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.245#her severely:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.246#“Well, you're doing nothing now--eh? only looking at the people passing.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.247#Things can't go on this way, you know!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.248#“But they prevent me selling, madame.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.249#“Oh, there's other work for you, mademoiselle! Begin at the beginning.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.250#Do the folding-up.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.251#In order to please the few customers who had called, they had been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.252#obliged to ransack all the cupboards, and on the two long oaken tables,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.253#to the right and the left, were heaps of mantles, pelisses, and capes,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.254#garments of all sizes and all materials. Without replying, Denise set
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.255#about sorting them, folding them carefully and arranging them again
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.256#in the cupboards. This was the lowest work, generally performed by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.257#beginners. She ceased to protest, knowing that they required the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.258#strictest obedience, waiting till the first hand should be good enough
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.259#to let her sell, as she seemed at first to have the intention of doing.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.260#She was still folding, when Mouret appeared on the scene. This was a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.261#violent shock for her; she blushed without knowing why, she felt herself
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.262#invaded by a strange fear, thinking he was going to speak to her. But he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.263#did not even see her; he no longer remembered this little girl whom the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.264#charming impression of an instant had induced him to support.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.265#“Madame Aurélie,” called he in a brief voice.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.266#He was rather pale, but his eyes were clear and resolute. In making the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.267#tour of the departments he had found them empty, and the possibility
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.268#of a defeat had suddenly presented itself in the midst of his obstinate
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.269#faith in fortune. True, it was only eleven o'clock; he knew by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.270#experience that the crowd never arrived much before the afternoon. But
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.271#certain symptoms troubled him. At the previous sales, a general movement
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.272#had taken place from the morning even; besides he did not see any of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.273#those bareheaded women, customers living in the neighbourhood, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.274#usually dropped into his shop as into a neighbour's. Like all great
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.275#captains, he felt at the moment of giving battle a superstitious
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.276#weakness, notwithstanding his habitually resolute attitude. Things would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.277#not go on well, he was lost, and he could not have explained why; he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.278#thought he could read his defeat on the faces of the passing ladies
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.279#even.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.280#Just at that moment, Madame Boutarel, she who always bought something,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.281#was going away, saying: “No, you have nothing that pleases me. I'll see,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.282#I'll decide later on.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.283#Mouret watched her depart. Then, as Madame Aurélie ran up at his call,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.284#he took her aside, and they exchanged a few rapid words. She wore a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.285#despairing air, and was evidently admitting that things were looking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.286#bad. For a moment they remained face to face, seized with one of those
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.287#doubts which generals conceal from their soldiers. Ultimately he said
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.288#out loud in his brave way: “If you want assistance, understand, take a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.289#girl from the workroom. She'll be a little help to you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.290#He continued his inspection in despair. He had avoided Bourdoncle
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.291#all the morning, for his anxious doubts irritated him. On leaving the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.292#under-linen department, where business was still worse, he dropped right
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.293#on to him, and was obliged to submit to the expression of his fears. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.294#did not hesitate to send him to the devil, with a brutality that even
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.295#his principal employees came in for when things were looking bad.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.296#“Get out of my way!” said he. “Everything is going on all right. I shall
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.297#end by pitching out the tremblers.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.298#Mouret planted himself alone on the landing of the hall-staircase. From
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.299#there he commanded the whole shop; around him the departments on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.300#first-floor; beneath, those of the ground-floor. Above, the emptiness
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.301#seemed heart-breaking; in the lace department, an old woman was having
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.302#everything turned over and buying nothing; whilst three good-for-nothing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.303#minxes in the under-linen department were slowly choosing some collars
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.304#at eighteen sous. Down below, under the covered galleries, in the ray of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.305#light which came in from the street, he noticed that the customers were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.306#commencing to get more numerous. It was a slow, broken procession,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.307#a promenade before the counters; in the mercery and the haberdashery
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.308#departments some women of the commoner class were pushing about, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.309#there was hardly a customer in the linen or in the woollen departments.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.310#The shop messengers, in their green coats, the buttons of which shone
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.311#brilliantly, were waiting for customers, their hands dangling about. Now
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.312#and again there passed an inspector with a ceremonious air, very stiff
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.313#in his white neck-tie. Mouret was especially grieved by the mortal
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.314#silence which reigned in the hall, where the light fell from above from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.315#a ground glass window, showing a white dust, diffuse and suspended, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.316#it were, under which the silk department seemed to be sleeping, amid
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.317#a shivering religious silence. A shopman's footstep, a few whispered
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.318#words, the rustling of a passing skirt, were the only noises heard,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.319#and they were almost stifled by the hot air of the heating apparatus.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.320#However, carriages began to arrive, the sudden piffling up of the horses
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.321#was heard, and immediately after the banging of the carriage doors.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.322#Outside, a distant tumult was commencing to make itself heard, groups of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.323#idlers were pushing in front of the windows, cabs were taking up their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.324#positions in the Place Gaillon, there were all the appearances of an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.325#approaching crowd. But on seeing the idle cashiers leaning back on their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.326#chairs behind their wickets, and observing that the parcel-tables
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.327#with their boxes of string and reams of blue packing-paper remained
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.328#unoccupied, Mouret, though indignant with himself for being afraid,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.329#thought he felt his immense machine stop and turn cold beneath him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.330#“I say, Favier,” murmured Hutin, “look at the governor up there. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.331#doesn't seem to be enjoying himself.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.332#“This is a rotten shop!” replied Favier. “Just fancy, I've not sold a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.333#thing yet.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.334#Both of them, waiting for customers, whispered such short remarks from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.335#time to time without looking at each other. The other salesmen of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.336#department were occupied in arranging large bales of the Paris Paradise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.337#under Robineau's orders; whilst Bouthemont, in full consultation with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.338#thin young woman, seemed to be taking an important order. Around them,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.339#on frail and elegant shelves, the silks, folded in long pieces of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.340#creamy paper, were heaped up like pamphlets of an unusual size; and,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.341#encumbering the counters, were fancy silks, moires, satins, velvets,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.342#presenting the appearance of mown flowers, quite a harvest of delicate
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.343#precious tissues. This was the most elegant of all the departments, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.344#veritable drawingroom, where the goods, so light and airy, were nothing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.345#but a luxurious furnishing.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.346#“I must have a hundred francs by Sunday,” said Hutin. “If I don't make
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.347#an average of twelve francs a day, I'm lost. I'd reckoned on this sale.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.348#“By Jovel a hundred francs; that's rather stiff,” said Favier. “I only
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.349#want fifty or sixty. You must go in for swell women, then?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.350#“Oh, no, my dear fellow. It's a stupid affair; I made a bet and lost. So
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.351#I have to stand a dinner for five persons, two fellows and three girls.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.352#Hang me! the first one that passes I'll let her in for twenty yards of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.353#Paris Paradise!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.354#They continued talking for several minutes, relating what they had done
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.355#the previous day, and what they intended to do the next week. Favier
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.356#did a little betting, Hutin did a little boating, and kept music-hall
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.357#singers. But they were both possessed by the same desire for money,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.358#struggling for it all the week, and spending it all on Sunday. It was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.359#their sole preoccupation in the shop, an hourly and pitiless struggle.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.360#And that cunning Bouthemont had just managed to get hold of Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.361#Sauveur's messenger, the skinny woman with whom he was talking! good
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.362#business, three or four dozen pieces, at least, for the celebrated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.363#dressmaker always gave good orders. At that moment Robineau took it into
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.364#his head to do Favier out of a customer.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.365#“Oh! as for that fellow, we must settle up with him,” said Hutin, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.366#took advantage of the slightest thing in order to stir up the salesmen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.367#against the man whose place he coveted.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.368#“Ought the first and second hands to sell? My word of honour! my dear
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.369#fellow, if ever I become second you'll see how well I shall act with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.370#others.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.371#And all his little Norman person, so fat and jolly, played the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.372#good-natured man energetically. Favier could not help casting a side
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.373#glance towards him, but he preserved his phlegmatical air, contenting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.374#himself with replying: “Yes, I know. I should be only too pleased.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.375# Then, as a lady came up, he added in a lower tone: “Look out! Here's one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.376#for you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.377#It was a lady with a blotchy face, a yellow bonnet, and a red dress.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.378#Hutin immediately recognised in her a woman who would buy nothing.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.379#He quickly stooped behind the counter, pretending to be doing up his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.380#boot-lace; and, thus concealed, he murmured: “No fear, let some one else
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.381#take her. I don't want to lose my turn!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.382#However, Robineau called out: “Whose turn, gentlemen? Monsieur Hutin's?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.383#Where's Monsieur Hutin?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.384#And as this gentleman still gave no reply, it was the next salesman who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.385#served the lady with the blotches. Hutin was right, she simply wanted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.386#some samples with the prices; and she kept the salesman more than ten
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.387#minutes, overwhelming him with questions. However, Robineau had seen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.388#Hutin get up from behind the counter; so that when another customer
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.389#arrived, he interfered with a stern air, stopping the young man, who was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.390#rushing forward.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.391#“Your turn is passed. I called you, and as you were there behind----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.392#“But I didn't hear you, sir.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.393#“That'll do! Write your name at the bottom. Now, Monsieur Favier, it's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.394#your turn.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.395#Favier, greatly amused at heart at this adventure, threw a glance at his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.396#friend, as if to excuse himself. Hutin, with pale lips, had turned his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.397#head away. What enraged him was that he knew the customer very well,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.398#an adorable blonde who often came to their department, and whom the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.399#salesmen called amongst themselves “the pretty lady,” knowing nothing of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.400#her, not even her name. She bought a great deal, had her purchases taken
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.401#to her carriage, and immediately disappeared. Tall, elegant, dressed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.402#with exquisite taste, she appeared to be very rich, and to belong to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.403#best society.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.404#“Well! and your courtesan?” asked Hutin of Favier, when the latter
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.405#returned from the pay-desk, where he had accompanied the lady.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.406#“Oh! a courtesan!” replied the other. “I fancy she looks too lady-like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.407#for that. She must be the wife of a stockbroker or a doctor, or
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.408#something of that sort.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.409#“Don't tell me! it's a courtesan. With their grand lady airs it's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.410#impossible to tell now-a-days!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.411#Favier looked at his book of debit-notes. “I don't care!” said he, “I've
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.412#stuck her for two hundred and ninety-three francs. That makes nearly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.413#three francs for me.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.414#Hutin bit his lips, and vented his spleen on the debit notebooks.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.415#Another invention for cramming their pockets. There was a secret rivalry
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.416#between these two. Favier, as a rule, pretended to sing small, to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.417#recognise Hutin's superiority, but in reality devouring him all the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.418#while behind his back. Thus Hutin was wild at the thought of the three
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.419#francs pocketed so easily by a salesman whom he considered to be his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.420#inferior in business. A fine day's work! If it went on like this, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.421#would not earn enough to pay for the seltzer water for his guests. And
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.422#in the midst of the battle, which was now becoming fiercer, he walked
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.423#along the counters with hungry eyes, eager for his share, jealous even
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.424#of his superior, who was just showing the thin young woman out, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.425#saying to her:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.426#“Very well! it's understood. Tell her I'll do my best to obtain this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.427#favour from Monsieur Mouret.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.428#Mouret had quitted his post on the stairs some time before. Suddenly he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.429#reappeared on the landing of the principal staircase which communicated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.430#with the ground floor; and from there he commanded a view of the whole
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.431#establishment. His face had regained its colour, his faith was restored
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.432#and increasing before the crowd which was gradually filling the place.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.433#It was the expected rush at last, the afternoon crush, which he had for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.434#a moment despaired of. All the shopmen were at their posts, a last ring
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.435#of the bell had announced the end of the third lunch; the disastrous
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.436#morning, due no doubt to a shower which fell about nine o'clock, could
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.437#still be repaired, for the blue sky of early morn had resumed its
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.438#victorious gaiety. Now that the first-floor departments were becoming
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.439#animated, he was obliged to stand back to make way for the women who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.440#were going up to the under-clothing and dress departments; whilst,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.441#behind him, in the lace and the shawl departments, he heard large
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.442#sums bandied about. But the sight of the galleries on the ground-floor
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.443#especially reassured him. There was a crowd at the haberdashery
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.444#department, and even the linen and woollen departments were invaded. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.445#procession of buyers closed up, nearly all of a higher class at present,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.446#with a few lingering housewives. Under the pale light of the silk hall,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.447#ladies had taken off their gloves to feel the Paris Paradise, talking in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.448#half-whispers. And there was no longer any mistaking the noises arriving
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.449#from outside, rolling of cabs, banging of carriage-doors, an increasing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.450#tumult in the crowd. He felt the machine commencing to work under him,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.451#getting up steam and reviving, from the pay-desks where the money was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.452#jingling, and the tables where the messengers were hurriedly packing up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.453#the goods, down to the basement, in the delivery-room, which was quickly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.454#filling up with the parcels sent down, and the underground rumbling of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.455#which seemed to shake the whole house. In the midst of the crowd was the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.456#inspector, Jouve, walking about gravely, watching for thieves.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.457#“Hullo! is that you?” said Mouret, all at once, recognising Paul de
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.458#Vallagnosc whom a messenger had conducted to him. “No, no, you are
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.459#not in my way. Besides, you've only to follow me if you want to see
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.460#everything, for to-day I stay at the breach.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.461#He still felt anxious. No doubt there were plenty of people, but would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.462#the sale prove to be the triumph he hoped for? However, he laughed with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.463#Paul, carrying him off gaily.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.464#“It seems to be picking up a bit,” said Hutin to Favier. “But somehow
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.465#I've no luck; there are some days that are precious bad, my word! I've
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.466#just made another miss, that old frump hasn't bought anything.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.467#And he glanced towards a lady who was walking off, casting looks of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.468#disgust at all the goods. He was not likely to get fat on his thousand
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.469#francs a year, unless he sold something; as a rule he made seven or
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.470#eight francs a day commission, which gave him with his regular pay an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.471#average of ten francs a day. Favier never made much more than eight, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.472#there was this animal taking the bread out of his mouth, for he had just
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.473#sold another dress--a cold-natured fellow who had never known how to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.474#amuse a customer! It was exasperating.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.475#“Those chaps over there seem to be doing very well,” remarked Favier,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.476#speaking of the salesmen in the hosiery and haberdashery departments.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.477#But Hutin, who was looking all round the place, suddenly asked: “Do you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.478#know Madame Desforges, the governor's sweetheart? Look! that dark woman
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.479#in the glove department, who is having some gloves tried on by Mignot.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.480# He stopped, then resumed in a low tone, as if speaking to Mignot, on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.481#whom he continued to keep his eyes: “Oh, go on, old man, you may pull
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.482#her fingers about as much as you like, that won't do you any good! We
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.483#know your conquests!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.484#There was a rivalry between himself and the glove-man, the rivalry
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.485#of two handsome fellows, who both affected to flirt with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.486#lady-customers. As a matter of fact they had neither had any real
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.487#conquests to boast about. Mignot lived on the legend of a police
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.488#superintendent's wife who had fallen in love with him, whilst Hutin had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.489#really conquered a lace-maker who had got tired of wandering about in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.490#the doubtful hotels in the neighbourhood; but they invented a lot
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.491#of mysterious adventures, leading people to believe in all sorts of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.492#appointments made by titled ladies, between two purchases.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.493#“You should get hold of her,” said Favier, in his sly, artful way.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.494#“That's a good idea!” exclaimed Hutin. “If she comes here I'll let her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.495#in for something extensive; I want a five-franc piece!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.496#In the glove department quite a row of ladies were seated before the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.497#narrow counter covered with green velvet and edged with nickel silver;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.498#and the smiling shopmen were heaping up before them the flat boxes of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.499#bright red, taken out of the counter itself, and resembling the ticketed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.500#drawers of a secrétaire. Mignot especially was bending his pretty
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.501#doll-like face over his customer, his thick Parisian voice full of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.502#tender inflections. He had already sold Madame Desforges a dozen pairs
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.503#of kid gloves, the Paradise gloves, one of the specialities of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.504#house. She then took three pairs of Swedish, and was now trying on some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.505#Saxon gloves, for fear the size should not be exact.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.506#“Oh! quite perfect, madame!” repeated Mignot. “Six and a quarter would
