urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.706#“What sort of silk, madame?” asked he in his most gallant manner. Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.707#Desforges had no sooner opened her mouth than he added: “I know, I've
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.708#got just what you want.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.709#When the piece of Paris Paradise was unfolded on a narrow corner of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.710#counter, between heaps of other silks, Madame Marty and her daughter
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.711#approached. Hutin, rather anxious, understood that it was at first a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.712#question of serving these two. Whispered words were exchanged, Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.713#Desforges was advising her friend.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.714#“Oh! certainly,” murmured she. “A silk at five francs twelve sous will
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.715#never be equal to one at fifteen, or even ten.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.716#“It is very light,” repeated Madame Marty. “I'm afraid that it has not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.717#sufficient body for a mantle.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.718#This remarked induced the salesman to intervene. He smiled with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.719#exaggerated politeness of a man who cannot make a mistake.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.720#“But, madame, flexibility is the chief quality of this silk. It will not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.721#crumple. It's exactly what you want.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.722#Impressed by such an assurance, the ladies said no more. They had taken
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.723#the silk up, and were examining it again, when they felt a touch on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.724#their shoulders. It was Madame Guibal, who had been slowly walking about
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.725#the shop for an hour past, feasting her eyes on the heaped-up riches,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.726#without buying even a yard of calico. And there was another explosion of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.727#gossip.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.728#“What! Is that you?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.729#“Yes, it's me, rather knocked about though.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.730#“What a crowd--eh? One can't get about. And the oriental saloon?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.731#“Ravishing!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.732#“Good heavens! what a success! Stay a moment, we will go upstairs
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.733#together.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.734#“No, thanks, I've just come down.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.735#Hutin was waiting, concealing his impatience with a smile that did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.736#quit his lips. Were they going to keep him there long? Really the women
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.737#took things very coolly, it was like taking his money out of his pocket.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.738#At last Madame Guibal went away and continued her stroll, turning round
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.739#the splendid display of silks with an enraptured air.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.740#“If I were you I should buy the mantle ready-made,” said Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.741#Desforges, suddenly returning to the Paris Paradise. “It won't cost you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.742#so much.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.743#“It's true that the trimmings and making-up----” murmured Madame Marty.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.744#“Besides, one has more choice.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.745#All three had risen. Madame Desforges turned to Hutin, saying: “Have the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.746#goodness to show us to the ready-made department.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.747#He remained dumbfoundered, not being used to such defeats. What! the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.748#dark lady bought nothing! Had he then made a mistake? He abandoned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.749#Madame Marty and attacked Madame Desforges, trying his powerful
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.750#abilities as salesman on her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.751#“And you, madame, would you not like to see our satins, our velvets? We
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.752#have some extraordinary bargains.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.753#“Thanks, another time,” replied she coolly, not looking at him any more
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.754#than she had at Mignot.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.755#Hutin had to take up Madame Marty's purchases and walk before the ladies
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.756#to show them to the ready-made department But he had also the grief
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.757#of seeing that Robineau was selling Madame Boutarel a good quantity of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.758#silk. Decidedly his scent was playing him false, he wouldn't make four
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.759#sous. Beneath the amiable correctness of his manners there was the rage
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.760#of a man being robbed and swallowed up by the others.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.761#“On the first floor, ladies,” said he, without ceasing to smile.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.762#It was no easy matter to get to the staircase. A compact crowd of heads
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.763#was surging under the galleries, expanding like an overflowing river
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.764#into the middle of the hall. Quite a battle of business was going on,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.765#the salesmen had this population of women at their mercy, passing them
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.766#from one to the other with feverish haste. The moment of the formidable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.767#afternoon rush had arrived, when the over-heated machine led the dance
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.768#of customers, drawing the money from their very flesh. In the silk
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.769#department especially a breath of folly seemed to pervade all, the Paris
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.770#Paradise collected such a crowd that for several minutes Hutin could not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.771#advance a step; and Henriette, half-suffocated, having raised her eyes,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.772#beheld Mouret at the top of the stairs, his favourite position, from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.773#which he could see the victory. She smiled, hoping that he would come
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.774#down and extricate her. But he did not even recognise her in the crowd;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.775#he was still with Vallagnosc, showing him the house, his face beaming
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.776#with triumph.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.777#The trepidation within was now stifling all outside noise; one no
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.778#longer heard the rumbling of the vehicles, nor the banging of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.779#carriage-doors; nothing remained above the vast murmur of business but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.780#the sentiment of this enormous Paris, of such immensity that it would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.781#always furnish buyers. In the heavy still air, in which the fumes of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.782#heating apparatus warmed the odour of the stuffs, the hubbub increased,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.783#made up of all sorts of noises, of the continual walking about, of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.784#same phrases, a hundred times repeated around the counters, of the gold
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.785#jingling on the brass of the pay-desks, besieged by a legion of purses,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.786#and of the baskets on wheels loaded with parcels which were constantly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.787#disappearing into the gaping cellars. And, amidst the fine dust,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.788#everything finished by getting mixed up, it became impossible to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.789#recognise the divisions of the different departments; the haberdashery
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.790#department over there seemed drowned; further on, in the linen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.791#department, a ray of sunshine, entering by the window in the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.792#Neuve-Saint-Augustin, was like a golden dart in a heap of snow; close
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.793#by, in the glove and woollen departments, a dense mass of bonnets and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.794#chignons hid the background of the shop from view. The toilettes were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.795#no longer visible, the head-dresses alone appeared, decked with feathers
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.796#and ribbons.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.797#A few men's hats introduced here and there a black spot, whilst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.798#the women's pale complexions assumed in the fatigue and heat the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.799#transparencies of the camellia. At last, Hutin--thanks to his vigorous
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.800#elbows--was able to open a way for the ladies, by keeping in front of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.801#them. But on ascending the stairs, Henriette could not find Mouret,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.802#who had just plunged Vallagnosc right into the crowd to complete his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.803#bewilderment, himself feeling the physical want of a dip into this bath
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.804#of success. He lost his breath deliciously, he felt against his limbs a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.805#sort of caress from all his customers.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.806#“To the left, ladies,” said Hutin, still attentive, notwithstanding his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.807#increasing exasperation.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.808#Up above there was the same block. It invaded even the furnishing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.809#department, usually the quietest. The shawl, the fur, and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.810#under-clothing departments swarmed with people. As the ladies were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.811#crossing the lace department another meeting took place. Madame de Boves
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.812#was there with her daughter Blanche, both buried in the articles Deloche
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.813#was showing them. And Hutin had to make another halt, bundle in hand.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.814#“Good afternoon! I was just thinking of you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.815#“I've been looking for you myself. But how can you expect to find any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.816#one in this crowd?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.817#“It's magnificent, isn't it?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.818#“Dazzling, my dear. We can hardly stand.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.819#“And you're buying?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.820#“Oh! no, we're only looking round. It rests us a little to be seated.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.821#As a fact, Madame de Boves, scarcely possessing more than her cab-fare
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.822#in her purse, was having all sorts of laces handed down, simply for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.823#pleasure of seeing and handling them. She had guessed Deloche to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.824#a new salesman, slow and awkward, who dared not resist the customers'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.825#whims; and she took advantage of his bewildered good-nature, and kept
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.826#him there half an hour, still asking for fresh articles. The counter
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.827#was covered, she dived her hands into this increasing mountain of lace,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.828#Malines, Valenciennes, and Chantilly, her fingers trembling with desire,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.829#her face gradually warming with a sensual joy; whilst Blanche, close to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.830#her, agitated by the same passion, was very pale, her flesh inflated and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.831#soft. The conversation continued; Hutin, standing there waiting their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.832#good pleasure, could have slapped their faces.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.833#“Ah!” said Madame Marty, “you're looking at some cravats and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.834#handkerchiefs like those I showed you the other day.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.835#It was true, Madame de Boves, tormented by Madame Marty's lace since
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.836#the previous Saturday, had been unable to resist the desire to at least
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.837#handle some like it, as the allowance her husband made her did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.838#permit her to carry any away. She blushed slightly, explaining that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.839#Blanche wanted to see the Spanish-blonde cravats. Then she added:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.840#“You're going to the ready-made department--Well! we'll see you again.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.841#Shall we say in the oriental saloon?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.842#“That's it, in the oriental saloon--Superb, isn't it?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.843#And they separated enraptured, amidst the obstruction produced by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.844#sale of the insertions and small trimmings at low prices. Deloche, glad
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.845#to be occupied, recommenced emptying the boxes before the mother and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.846#daughter. And amidst the groups pressed along the counters, Jouve, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.847#inspector, was slowly walking about with his military air, displaying
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.848#his decoration, watching over these fine and precious goods, so easy to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.849#conceal up a sleeve. When he passed behind Madame de Boves, surprised
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.850#to see her with her arms plunged in such a heap of lace he cast a quick
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.851#glance at her feverish hands.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.852#“To the right, ladies,” said Hutin, resuming his march.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.853#He was beside himself with rage. Was it not enough that he had missed a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.854#sale down below? Now they kept him waiting at each turning of the shop!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.855#And in his annoyance there was a strong feeling of the rancour existing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.856#between the textile departments and the ready-made departments, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.857#were in continual hostility, fighting over the customers, stealing each
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.858#other's percentage and commission. Those of the silk department were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.859#more enraged than those of the woollen, whenever they were obliged to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.860#show a lady to where the ready-made articles were kept, when she decided
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.861#to take a mantle after looking at various sorts of silk.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.862#“Mademoiselle Vadon!” said Hutin, in an angry voice, when he at last
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.863#arrived in the department.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.864#But she passed by without listening, absorbed in a sale which she was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.865#conducting. The room was full, a stream of people were crossing it,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.866#coming in by the door of the lace department and going out by the door
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.867#of the under-clothing department, whilst to the right customers were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.868#trying on garments, and posing before the glasses. The red carpet
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.869#stifled the noise of the footsteps, the distant roar from the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.870#ground-floor died away, giving place to a discreet murmur, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.871#drawing-room warmth deadened by the crowd of women.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.872#“Mademoiselle Prunaire!” cried out Hutin. And as she took no notice
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.873#either, he added between his teeth, so as not to be heard: “A set of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.874#frights!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.875#He certainly was not fond of them, tired to death as he was by climbing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.876#the stairs to bring them customers, furious at the profits which he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.877#accused them of taking out of his pocket It was a secret war, in which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.878#the young ladies themselves entered with equal fierceness; and in their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.879#mutual fatigue, always on foot, worked to death, all difference of sex
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.880#disappeared, nothing remained but these contrary interests, irritated by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.881#the fever of business.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.882#“So there's no one here to serve?” asked Hutin.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.883#But he suddenly caught sight of Denise. They had kept her folding all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.884#the morning, only giving her a few doubtful customers to whom she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.885#not sold anything. When he recognised her, occupied in clearing off the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.886#counter an enormous heap of garments, he ran up to her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.887#“Look here, mademoiselle! serve these ladies who are waiting.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.888#And he quickly slipped Madame Marty's purchases into her arms, tired
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.889#of carrying them about the place. His smile returned, and in this smile
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.890#there was the ill-natured expression of the experienced salesman, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.891#shrewdly guessed into what an awkward position he had just thrown both
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.892#the ladies and the young girl. The latter, however, remained quite
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.893#troubled before this unhoped-for sale which suddenly presented itself.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.894#For the second time Hutin appeared to her like an unknown friend,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.895#fraternal and tender, always ready to spring out of darkness and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.896#save her. Her eyes glistened with gratitude; she followed him with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.897#lingering look, whilst he was elbowing his way towards his department.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.898#“I want a mantle,” said Madame Marty.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.899#Then Denise questioned her. What style of mantle? But the lady had no
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.900#idea, she wished to see what the house had got. And the young girl,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.901#already very tired, bewildered by the crowd, lost her head; she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.902#never served any but the rare customers who came to Cornaille's, at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.903#Valognes; she didn't even know the number of the models, nor their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.904#places in the cupboards. She hardly knew how to reply to the ladies, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.905#were beginning to lose patience, when Madame Aurélie perceived Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.906#Desforges, of whose connection with Mouret she was no doubt aware, for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.907#she hastened over and asked with a smile:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.908#“Are these ladies being served?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.909#“Yes, that young person over there is attending to us,” replied
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.910#Henriette. “But she does not appear to be very well up to her work; she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.911#can't find anything.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.912#At this, the first-hand completely paralysed Denise by saying to her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.913#in a whisper: “You see very well you know nothing. Don't interfere any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.914#more, please.” And turning round she called out: “Mademoiselle Vadon,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.915#these ladies require a mantle!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.916#She remained there whilst Marguerite showed the models. The girl assumed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.917#with the customers a dry polite voice, the disagreeable attitude of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.918#young person dressed up in silk, with a sort of varnish of elegance, of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.919#which she retained, unknown to herself, the jealousy and rancour.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.920#When she heard Madame Marty say she did not wish to exceed two hundred
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.921#francs, she made a grimace of pity. Oh! madame would give more, it would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.922#be impossible to find anything respectable for two hundred francs. And
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.923#she threw some of the common mantles on a counter with a gesture which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.924#signified: “Just see, aren't they pitiful?” Madame Marty dared not think
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.925#of them after that; she bent over to murmur in Madame Desforges's ear:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.926#“Don't you prefer to be served by men? One feels more comfortable?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.927#At last Marguerite brought a silk mantle trimmed with jet, which she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.928#treated with more respect And Madame Aurélie abruptly called Denise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.929#“Come, do something for your living. Just put that on your shoulders.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.930#Denise, wounded to the heart, despairing of ever succeeding in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.931#house, had remained motionless, her hands hanging by her side. No doubt
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.932#she would be sent away, and the children would be without food. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.933#tumult of the crowd buzzed in her head, she felt herself tottering, her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.934#arms bruised by the handling of so many armfuls of garments, hard work
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.935#which she had never done before. However, she was obliged to obey and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.936#allow Marguerite to put the mantle on her, as on a dummy.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.937#“Stand upright,” said Madame Aurélie.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.938#But a moment after they forgot Denise. Mouret had just come in with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.939#Vallagnosc and Bourdoncle; and he bowed to the ladies, who complimented
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.940#him on his magnificent exhibition of winter novelties. Of course
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.941#they went into raptures over the oriental saloon. Vallagnosc, who was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.942#finishing his walk round the counters, displayed more surprise than
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.943#admiration; for, after all, thought he, in his pessimist supineness,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.944#it was nothing more than an immense collection of calico. Bourdoncle,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.945#forgetting that he belonged to the establishment, also congratulated the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.946#governor, to make him forget his anxious doubts and persecutions of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.947#early part of the day.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.948#“Yes, yes; things are going on very well, I'm quite satisfied,” repeated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.949#Mouret, radiant, replying with a smile to Madame Desforges's tender
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.950#looks. “But I must not interrupt you, ladies.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.951#Then all eyes were again fixed on Denise. She placed herself entirely in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.952#the hands of Marguerite, who was making her turn round slowly.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.953#“What do you think of it--eh?” asked Madame Marty of Madame Desforges.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.954#The latter gave her advice, like a supreme umpire of fashion. “It isn't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.955#bad, the cut is original, but it doesn't seem to me very graceful about
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.956#the figure.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.957#“Oh!” interrupted Madame Aurélie, “it must be seen on the lady herself.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.958#You can understand it does not look much on this young person, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.959#is not very stout. Hold up your head, mademoiselle, give it all its
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.960#importance.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.961#They smiled. Denise had turned very pale. She felt ashamed at being thus
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.962#turned into a machine, which they were examining and joking about so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.963#freely.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.964#Madame Desforges, yielding to the antipathy of a contrary nature, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.965#annoyed by the young girl's sweet face, maliciously added: “No doubt it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.966#would set better if the young person's dress were not so loose-fitting.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.967#And she cast at Mouret the mocking look of a Parisian beauty, greatly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.968#amused by the absurd ridiculous dress of a country girl. He felt the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.969#amorous caress of this glance, the triumph of a woman proud of her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.970#beauty and of her art. Therefore, out of pure gratitude, the gratitude
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.971#of a man who felt himself adored, he thought himself obliged to joke
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.972#in his turn, notwithstanding his good-will towards Denise, whose secret
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.973#charm had conquered his gallant nature.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.974#“Besides, her hair should be combed,” murmured he.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.975#This was the last straw. The director deigned to laugh, all the young
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.976#ladies were bursting. Marguerite risked a slight chuckle, like a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.977#well-behaved girl who restrains herself; Clara had left a customer to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.978#enjoy the fun at her ease; even the saleswomen from another department
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.979#had come, attracted by the talking. As for the ladies they took it more
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.980#quietly, with an air of well-bred enjoyment. Madame Aurélie was the only
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.981#one who did not laugh, as if Denise's splendid wild-looking head of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.982#hair and elegant virginal shoulders had dishonoured her, in the orderly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.983#well-kept department. The young girl had turned paler still, in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.984#midst of all these people who were laughing at her. She felt herself
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.985#violated, exposed to all their looks, without defence. What had she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.986#done that they should thus attack her thin figure, and her too luxuriant
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.987#hair? But she was especially wounded by Madame Desforges's and Mouret's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.988#laughter, instinctively divining their connection, her heart sinking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.989#with an unknown grief. This lady was very ill-natured to attack a poor
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.990#girl who had said nothing; and as for Mouret, he most decidedly froze
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.991#her up with a sort of fear, before which all her other sentiments
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.992#disappeared, without her being able to analyse them. And, totally
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.993#abandoned, attacked in her most cherished womanly feelings of modesty,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.994#and shocked at their injustice, she was obliged to stifle the sobs which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.995#were rising in her throat.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.996#“I should think so; let her comb her hair to-morrow,” said the terrible
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.997#Bourdoncle to Madame Aurélie. He had condemned Denise the first day she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.998#came, full of scorn for her small limbs.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.999#At last the first-hand came and took the mantle off Denise's shoulders,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1000#saying to her in a low tone: “Well! mademoiselle, here's a fine start.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1001#Really, if this is the way you show off your capabilities----Impossible
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1002#to be more stupid!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1003#Denise, fearing the tears might gush from her, hastened back to the heap
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1004#of garments, which she began to sort out on the counter. There at least
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1005#she was lost in the crowd. Fatigue prevented her thinking. But she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1006#suddenly felt Pauline near her, a saleswoman in the under-clothing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1007#department, who had already defended her that morning. The latter had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1008#followed the scene, and murmured in Denise's ear:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1009#“My poor child, don't be so sensitive. Keep that to yourself, or they'll
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1010#go on worse and worse. I come from Chartres. Yes, exactly, Pauline
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1011#Cugnot is my name; and my parents are millers. Well! they would have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1012#devoured me the first few days if I had not stood up firm. Come, be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1013#brave! give me your hand, we'll have a talk together whenever you like.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1014#This hand held out redoubled Denise's confusion; she shook it furtively,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1015#hastening to take up a load of cloaks, fearing to be doing wrong and to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1016#get a scolding if they knew she had a friend.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1017#However, Madame Aurélie herself, had just put the mantle on Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1018#Marty, and they all exclaimed: “Oh! how nice! delightful!” It at once
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1019#looked quite different. Madame Desforges decided it would be impossible
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1020#to improve on it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1021#There was a good deal of bowing. Mouret took his leave, whilst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1022#Vallognosc, who had perceived Madame de Boves and her daughter in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1023#lace department, hastened to offer his arm to the mother. Marguerite,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1024#standing before one of the pay-desks, was already calling out the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1025#different purchases made by Madame Marty, who settled for them and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1026#ordered the parcel to be taken to her cab. Madame Desforges had found
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1027#her articles at pay-desk No. 10. Then the ladies met once more in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1028#oriental saloon. They were leaving, but it was amidst a loquacious
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1029#feeling of admiration. Even Madame Guibal became enthusiastic.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1030#“Oh! delicious! makes you think you are in the East; doesn't it?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1031#“A real harem, and not at all dear!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1032#“And the Smyrnas! oh, the Smyrnas! what tones, what delicacy!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1033#“And this Kurdestan! Just look, a Delacroix!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1034#The crowd was slowly diminishing. The bell, at an hour's interval,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1035#had already announced the two first dinners; the third was about to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1036#be served, and in the departments there were now only a few lingering
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1037#customers, whose fever for spending had made them forget the time.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1038#Outside nothing was heard but the rolling of the last carriages amidst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1039#the husky voice of Paris, the snort of a satiated ogre digesting the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1040#linens and cloths, silks and lace, with which he had been gorged since
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1041#the morning. Inside, beneath the flaming gas-jets, which, burning in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1042#the twilight, had lighted up the supreme efforts of the sale, everything
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1043#appeared like a field of battle still warm with the massacre of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1044#various goods. The salesmen, harassed and fatigued, camped amidst the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1045#contents of their shelves and counters, which appeared to have been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1046#thrown into the greatest confusion by the furious blast of a hurricane.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1047#It was with difficulty that one traversed the galleries on the ground
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1048#floor, blocked up with a crowd of chairs, and in the glove department it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1049#was necessary to step over a pile of cases heaped up around Mignot; in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1050#the woollen department there was no means of passing at all, Liénard was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1051#dozing on a sea of bales, in which certain piles, still standing,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1052#though half destroyed, seemed to be houses that an overflowing river was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1053#carrying away; and, further on, the linen department was like a heavy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1054#fall of snow, one ran up against icebergs of napkins, and walked on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1055#light flakes of handkerchiefs.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1056#The same disorder prevailed upstairs in the departments; the furs were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1057#scattered over the flooring, the readymade clothes were heaped up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1058#like the great-coats of wounded soldiers, the lace and the underlinen,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1059#unfolded, crumpled, thrown about everywhere, made one think of an army
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1060#of women who had disrobed there in the disorder of some sudden
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1061#desire; whilst downstairs, at the other end of the house, the delivery
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1062#department in full activity was still disgorging the parcels with which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1063#it was bursting, and which were carried off by the vans--last vibration
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1064#of the overheated machine. But it was in the silk department especially
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1065#that the customers had flung themselves with the greatest ardour. There
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1066#they had cleared off everything, there was plenty of room to pass, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1067#hall was bare; the whole of the colossal stock of Paris Paradise had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1068#been cut up and carried away, as if by a swarm of devouring locusts. And
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1069#in the midst of this emptiness, Hutin and Favier were running through
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1070#the counterfoils of their debit-notes, calculating their commission,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1071#still out of breath after the struggle. Favier had made fifteen francs,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1072#Hutin had only managed to make thirteen, thoroughly beaten that day,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1073#enraged at his bad luck. Their eyes sparkled with the passion for money.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1074#The whole shop around them was also adding up figures, glowing with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1075#same fever, in the brutal gaiety of the evening of the battle.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1076#“Well, Bourdoncle!” cried out Mouret, “are you trembling still?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1077#He had returned to his favourite position at the top of the stairs of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1078#the first floor, against the balustrade; and, in the presence of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1079#massacre of stuffs which was spread out under him, he indulged in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1080#victorious laugh. His fears of the morning, that moment of unpardonable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1081#weakness which nobody would ever know of, inspired him with a greater
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1082#desire to triumph. The battle was definitely won, the small tradespeople
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1083#of the neighbourhood were done for, and Baron Hartmann was conquered,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1084#with his millions and his land. Whilst he was looking at the cashiers
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1085#bending over their ledgers, adding up long columns of figures, whilst he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1086#was listening to the sound of the gold, falling from their fingers into
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1087#the metal bowls, he already saw The Ladies' Paradise growing beyond all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1088#bounds, enlarging its hall and prolonging its galleries as far as the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1089#Rue du Dix-Décembre.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1090#“And now are you convinced, Bourdoncle,” he resumed, “that the house is
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1091#really too small? We could have sold twice as much.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1092#Bourdoncle humbled himself, enraptured, moreover, to find himself in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1093#wrong. But a new spectacle rendered them grave. As was the custom every
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1094#evening, Lhomme, the chief cashier, had just collected the receipts
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1095#from each pay-desk; after having added them up, he usually posted up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1096#the total amount after placing the paper on which it was written on his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1097#file. He then took the receipts up to the chief cashier's office, in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1098#leather case and in bags, according to the nature of the cash. On this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1099#occasion the gold and silver predominated, and he was slowly walking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1100#upstairs, carrying three enormous bags. Deprived of his right arm, cut
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1101#off at the elbow, he clasped them in his left arm against his breast,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1102#holding one up with his chin to prevent it slipping. His heavy breathing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1103#could be heard at a distance, he passed along, staggering and superb,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1104#amidst the respectful shopmen.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1105#“How much, Lhomme?” asked Mouret.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1106#“Eighty thousand seven hundred and forty-two francs two sous,” replied
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1107#the cashier.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1108#A joyous laugh stirred up The Ladies' Paradise. The amount ran through
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1109#the establishment. It was the highest figure ever attained in one day by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1110#a draper's shop.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1111#That evening, when Denise went up to bed, she was obliged to lean
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1112#against the partition in the corridor under the zinc roof. When in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1113#her room, and with the door closed, she fell down on the bed; her feet
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1114#pained her so much. For a long time she continued to look with a stupid
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1115#air at the dressing-table, the wardrobe, all the hotel-like nudity.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1116#This, then, was where she was going to live; and her first day tormented
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1117#her--an abominable, endless day. She would never have the courage to go
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1118#through another. Then she perceived she was dressed in silk; and this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1119#uniform depressed her. She was childish enough, before unpacking her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1120#box, to put on her old woollen dress, which hung on the back of a chair.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1121#But when she was once more dressed in this poor garment of hers, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1122#painful emotion choked her; the sobs which she had kept back all day
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1123#burst forth suddenly in a flood of hot tears. She fell back on the bed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1124#weeping at the thought of the two children, and she wept on, without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1125#feeling to have the strength to take off her boots, completely overcome
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:iv.1126#with fatigue and grief.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1#CHAPTER V.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.2#The next day Denise had scarcely been downstairs half an hour, when
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.3#Madame Aurélie said to her in her sharp voice: “You are wanted at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.4#directorate, mademoiselle.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.5#The young girl found Mouret alone, in the large office hung with green
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.6#repp. He had suddenly remembered the “unkempt girl,” as Bourdoncle
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.7#called her; and he, who usually detested the part of fault-finder, had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.8#had the idea of sending for her and waking her up a bit, if she were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.9#still dressed in the style of a country wench. The previous day,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.10#notwithstanding his pleasantry, he had experienced, in Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.11#Desforges's presence, a feeling of wounded vanity, on seeing the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.12#elegance of one of his saleswomen discussed. He felt a confused
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.13#sentiment, a mixture of sympathy and anger.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.14#“We have engaged you, mademoiselle,” commenced he, “out of regard for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.15#your uncle, and you must not put us under the sad necessity----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.16#But he stopped. Opposite him, on the other side of the desk, stood
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.17#Denise, upright, serious, and pale. Her silk dress was no longer too big
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.18#for her, but fitted tight round her pretty figure, displaying the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.19#pure lines of her virgin shoulders; and if her hair, knotted in thick
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.20#tresses, still appeared untidy, she tried at least to keep it in order.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.21#After having gone to sleep with her clothes on, her eyes red with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.22#weeping, the young girl had felt ashamed of this attack of nervous
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.23#sensibility on waking up about four o'clock, and she had immediately
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.24#set about taking in her dress. She had spent an hour before the small
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.25#looking-glass, combing her hair, without being able to reduce it as she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.26#would have liked to.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.27#“Ah! thank heavens!” said Mouret, “you look better this morning. But
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.28#there's still that dreadful hair!” He rose from his seat and went up to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.29#her to try and smooth it down in the same familiar way Madame Aurélie
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.30#had attempted to do it the previous day. “There! just tuck that in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.31#behind your ear. The chignon is too high.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.32#She did not speak, but let him continue to arrange her hair;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.33#notwithstanding her vow to be strong, she had arrived at the office full
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.34#of misgivings, certain that she had been sent for to be informed of her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.35#dismissal. And Mouret's evident kindliness did not reassure her; she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.36#still felt afraid of him, feeling when near him that uneasiness which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.37#she attributed to a natural anxiety in the presence of a powerful man
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.38#on whom her fate depended. When he saw her so trembling under his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.39#hands, which were grazing her neck, he was sorry for his movement of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.40#good-nature, for he feared above all to lose his authority.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.41#“In short, mademoiselle,” resumed he, once more placing the desk between
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.42#himself and her, “try and look to your appearance. You are no longer
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.43#at Valognes; study our Parisian young ladies. If your uncle's name has
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.44#sufficed to gain your admittance to our house, I feel sure you will
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.45#carry out what your person seemed to promise to me. Unfortunately,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.46#everybody here is not of my opinion. Let this be a warning to you. Don't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.47#make me tell a falsehood.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.48#He treated her like a child, with more pity than kindness, his curiosity
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.49#in matters feminine simply awakened by the troubling, womanly charm
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.50#which he felt springing up in this poor and awkward child. And she,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.51#whilst he was lecturing her, having suddenly perceived Madame Hedouin's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.52#portrait--the handsome regular face smiling gravely in the gold
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.53#frame--felt herself shivering again, notwithstanding the encouraging
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.54#words he addressed to her. This was the dead lady, she whom people
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.55#accused him of having killed, in order to found the house with the blood
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.56#of her body.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.57#Mouret was still speaking. “Now you may go,” said he at last, sitting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.58#down and taking up his pen. She went away, heaving a deep sigh of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.59#relief.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.60#From that day forward, Denise displayed her great courage. Beneath these
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.61#rare attacks of sensitiveness, a strong sense of reason was constantly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.62#working, quite a feeling of bravery at finding herself weak and alone, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.63#cheerful determination to carry out her self-imposed task. She made very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.64#little noise, but went straight ahead to her goal, with an invincible
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.65#sweetness, overcoming all obstacles, and that simply and naturally, for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.66#such was her real character.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.67#At first she had to surmount the terrible fatigues of the department The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.68#parcels of garments tired her arms, so much so that during the first
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.69#six weeks she cried with pain when she turned over at night, bent almost
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.70#double, her shoulders bruised. But she suffered still more from her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.71#shoes, thick shoes brought from Valognes, want of money preventing her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.72#replacing them with light boots. Always on her feet, trotting about
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.73#from morning to night, scolded if seen leaning for a moment against any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.74#support, her feet became swollen, little feet, like those of a child,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.75#which seemed ground up in these torturing bluchers; her heels throbbed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.76#with fever, the soles were covered with blisters, the skin of which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.77#chafed off and stuck to the stocking. She felt her entire frame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.78#shattered, her limbs and organs contracted by the lassitude of her legs,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.79#the certain sudden weaknesses incident to her sex betraying themselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.80#by the paleness of her flesh. And she, so thin, so frail, resisted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.81#courageously, whilst a great many saleswomen around her were obliged
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.82#to quit the business, attacked with special maladies. Her good grace in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.83#suffering, her valiant obstinacy maintained her, smiling and upright,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.84#when she felt ready to give way, thoroughly worn out and exhausted by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.85#work to which men would have succumbed.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.86#Another torment was to have the whole department against her. To
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.87#the physical martyrdom there was added the secret persecution of her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.88#comrades. Two months of patience and gentleness had not disarmed them.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.89#She was constantly exposed to wounding remarks, cruel inventions,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.90#a series of slights which cut her to the heart, in her longing for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.91#affection. They had joked for a long time over her unfortunate first
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.92#appearance; the words “clogs” and “numbskull” circulated. Those who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.93#missed a sale were sent to Valognes; she passed, in short, for the fool
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.94#of the place. Then, when she revealed herself later on as a remarkable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.95#saleswoman, well up in the mechanism of the house, the young ladies
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.96#arranged together so as never to leave her a good customer. Marguerite
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.97#and Clara pursued her with an instinctive hatred, closing up the ranks
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.98#in order not to be swallowed up by this new comer, whom they really
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.99#feared in spite of their affectation of disdain. As for Madame Aurélie,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.100#she was hurt by the proud reserve displayed by the young girl, who did
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.101#not hover round her skirts with an air of caressing admiration; she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.102#therefore abandoned Denise to the rancour of her favourites, to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.103#favoured ones of her court, who were always on their knees, engaged in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.104#feeding her with a continual flattery, which her large authoritative
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.105#person needed to make it blossom forth. For a while, the second-hand,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.106#Madame Frédéric, appeared not to enter into the conspiracy, but this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.107#must have been by inadvertence, for she showed herself equally harsh the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.108#moment she saw to what annoyances her good-nature was likely to expose
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.109#her. Then the abandonment became complete, they all made a butt of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.110#“unkempt girl,” who lived in an hourly struggle, only managing by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.111#greatest courage to hold her own in the department.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.112#Such was her life now. She had to smile, look brave and gracious in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.113#silk dress which did not belong to her, although dying with fatigue,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.114#badly fed, badly treated, under the continual menace of a brutal
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.115#dismissal. Her room was her only refuge, the only place where she could
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.116#abandon herself to the luxury of a cry, when she had suffered too much
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.117#during the day. But a terrible coldness fell from the zinc roof, covered
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.118#with the December snow; she was obliged to nestle in her iron bedstead,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.119#throw all her clothes over her, and weep under the counterpane to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.120#prevent the frost chapping her face. Mouret never spoke to her now. When
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.121#she caught Bourdoncle's severe looks during business hours she trembled,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.122#for she felt in him a born enemy who would not forgive her the slightest
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.123#fault. And amidst this general hostility, Jouve the inspector's strange
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.124#friendliness astonished her. If he met her in any out-of-the-way corner
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.125#he smiled at her, made some amiable remark; twice he had saved her from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.126#being reprimanded without any show of gratitude on her part, for she was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.127#more troubled than touched by his protection.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.128#One evening, after dinner, as the young ladies were setting the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.129#cupboards in order, Joseph came and informed Denise that a young man
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.130#wanted her below. She went down, feeling very anxious.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.131#“Hullo!” said Clara, “the 'unkempt girl' has got a young man.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.132#“He must be hard up for a sweetheart,” declared Marguerite.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.133#Downstairs, at the door, Denise found her brother Jean. She had formally
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.134#prohibited him from coming to the shop in this way, as it looked very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.135#bad. But she did not dare to scold him, so excited did he appear,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.136#bareheaded, out of breath through running from the Faubourg du Temple.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.137#“Have you got ten francs?” stammered he. “Give me ten francs, or I'm a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.138#lost man.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.139#The young rascal looked so comical, with his flowing locks and handsome
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.140#girlish face, launching out with this melodramatic phrase, that she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.141#could have smiled had it not been for the anguish which this demand for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.142#money caused her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.143#“What! ten francs?” she murmured. “Whatever's the matter?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.144#He blushed, and explained that he had met a friend's sister. Denise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.145#stopped him, feeling embarrassed, not wishing to know any more about it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.146#Twice already had he rushed in to obtain similar loans, but the first
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.147#time it was only twenty-five sous, and the next thirty. He was always
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.148#getting mixed up with women.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.149#“I can't give you ten francs,” resumed she. “Pépé's board isn't paid
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.150#yet, and I've only just the money. I shall have hardly enough to buy a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.151#pair of boots, which I want badly. You really are not reasonable, Jean.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.152#It's too bad of you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.153#“Well, I'm lost,” repeated he, with a tragical gesture. “Just listen,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.154#little sister; she's a tall, dark girl; we went to the café with her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.155#brother. I never thought the drinks----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.156#She had to interrupt him again, and as tears were coming into his eyes,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.157#she took out her purse and slipped a ten-franc piece into his hand. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.158#at once set up a laugh.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.159#“I was sure--But my word of honour! never again! A fellow would have to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.160#be a regular scamp.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.161#And he ran off, after having kissed his sister, like a madman. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.162#fellows in the shop seemed astonished.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.163#That night Denise did not sleep much. Since her entry in The Ladies'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.164#Paradise, money had been her cruel anxiety. She was still a probationer,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.165#without salary; the young ladies in the department frequently prevented
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.166#her from selling, and she just managed to pay Pépé's board and lodging,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.167#thanks to the unimportant customers they were good enough to leave her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.168#It was a time of black misery--misery in a silk dress. She was often
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.169#obliged to spend the night repairing her small stack of clothes, darning
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.170#her linen, mending her chemises as if they had been lace; without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.171#mentioning the patches she put on her boots, as cleverly as any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.172#bootmaker could have done. She even risked washing things in her hand
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.173#basin. But her old woollen dress was an especial cause of anxiety to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.174#her; she had no other, and was forced to put it on every evening when
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.175#she quitted the uniform silk, and this wore it terribly; a spot on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.176#it gave her the fever, the least tear was a catastrophe. And she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.177#nothing, not a sou, not even enough to buy the trifling articles which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.178#a woman always wants; she had been obliged to wait a fortnight to renew
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.179#her stock of needles and cotton. Thus it was a real disaster when Jean,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.180#with his love affairs, dropped down all at once and pillaged her purse.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.181#A franc-piece taken away caused a gulf which she did not know how
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.182#to fill up. As for finding ten francs on the morrow it was not to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.183#thought of for a moment. The whole night she slept an uncomfortable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.184#sleep, haunted by the nightmare, in which she saw Pépé thrown into the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.185#street, whilst she was turning over the flagstones with her bruised
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.186#fingers to see if there were not some money underneath.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.187#It happened that the next day she had to play the part of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.188#well-dressed girl. Some well-known customers came in, and Madame Aurélie
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.189#called her several times in order that she should show off the new
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.190#styles. And whilst she was posing there, with the stiff graces of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.191#fashion-plate, she was thinking of Pépé's board and lodging, which she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.192#had promised to pay that evening. She could very well do without boots
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.193#for another month; but even on adding the thirty francs she had left to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.194#the four francs which she had saved sou by sou, that would never make
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.195#more than thirty-four francs, and where was she to find six francs to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.196#complete the sum? It was an anguish in which her heart failed her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.197#“You will notice the shoulders are free,” Madame Aurélie was saying.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.198#“It's very fashionable and very convenient. The young person can fold
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.199#her arms.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.200#“Oh! easily,” replied Denise, who continued to smile amiably. “One can't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.201#feel it. I am sure you will like it, madame.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.202#She now blamed herself for having gone to fetch Pépé from Madame Gras's,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.203#the previous Sunday, to take him for a walk in the Champs-Elysées. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.204#poor child so seldom went out with her! But she had had to buy some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.205#gingerbread and a little spade, and then take him to see Punch and Judy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.206#and that had mounted at once to twenty-nine sous. Really Jean could
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.207#not think much about the little one, or he would not be so foolish.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.208#Afterwards, everything fell upon her shoulders.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.209#“Of course, if it does not suit you, madame--” resumed the first-hand.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.210#“Just put this cloak on, mademoiselle, so that the lady may judge.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.211#And Denise walked slowly round, with the cloak on, saying: “This is
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.212#warmer. It's this year's fashion.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.213#And she continued to torture herself, behind her professional good
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.214#graces, until the evening, to know where she was to find this money. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.215#young ladies, who were very busy, had left her an important sale; but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.216#it was only Tuesday, and she had four days to wait before drawing any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.217#money. After dinner she decided to postpone her visit to Madame Gras
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.218#till the next day. She would excuse herself, say she had been detained,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.219#and before then she would have the six francs, perhaps.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.220#As Denise avoided the slightest expense, she went to bed early. What
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.221#could she do in the streets, with her unsociableness, still frightened
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.222#by the big city in which she only knew the streets near the shop? After
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.223#having ventured as far as the Palais-Royal, to get a little fresh air,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.224#she would quickly return, lock herself in her room and set about sewing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.225#or washing.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.226#It was, along the corridor of the bed-rooms, a barrack-like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.227#promiscuity--girls, who were often not very tidy, a gossiping over dirty
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.228#water and dirty linen, quite a disagreeable feeling, which manifested
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.229#itself in frequent quarrels and continual reconciliations. They were,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.230#moreover, prohibited from going up to their rooms in the day-time; they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.231#did not live there, but merely slept there at night, not going up till
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.232#the last minute, leaving again in the morning still half asleep, hardly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.233#awakened by a rapid wash; and this gust of wind which was continually
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.234#sweeping through the corridor, the fatigue of the thirteen hours' work
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.235#which threw them on their beds thoroughly worn out, changed this upper
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.236#part of the house into an inn traversed by the tired ill-temper of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.237#host of travellers. Denise had no friend. Of all the young ladies,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.238#one alone, Pauline Cugnot, showed her a certain tenderness; and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.239#ready-made and under-clothing departments being close to one another,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.240#and in open war, the sympathy between the two saleswomen had hitherto
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.241#been confined to a few rare words hastily exchanged. Pauline occupied
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.242#a neighbouring room, to the right of Denise's; but as she disappeared
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.243#immediately after dinner and only returned at eleven o'clock, the latter
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.244#only heard her get into bed, without ever meeting her after business
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.245#hours.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.246#This evening, Denise had made up her mind to play the part of bootmaker
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.247#once more. She was holding her shoes, turning them about, wondering how
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.248#she could make them last another month. At last she decided to take a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.249#strong needle and sew on the soles, which were threatening to leave the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.250#uppers. During this time a collar and a pair of cuffs were soaking in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.251#the basin full of soapsuds.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.252#Every evening she heard the same noises, the young ladies coming in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.253#one by one, short whispered conversations, laughing, and sometimes a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.254#dispute, which they stifled as much as possible. Then the beds creaked,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.255#the tired occupants yawned, and fell into a heavy slumber. Denise's left
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.256#hand neighbour often talked in her sleep, which frightened her very much
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.257#at first Perhaps others, like herself, stopped up to mend their things,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.258#in spite of the rules; but if so they probably took the same precautions
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.259#as she did herself, keeping very quiet, avoiding the least shock, for a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.260#shivering silence reigned in all the rooms.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.261#It had struck eleven about ten minutes before when a sound of footsteps
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.262#made her raise her head. Another young lady late! And she recognised it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.263#to be Pauline, by hearing the latter open the door next to her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.264#But she was astonished when Pauline returned quietly and knocked at her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.265#door.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.266#“Make haste, it's me!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.267#The saleswomen not being allowed to visit each other in their rooms,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.268#Denise quickly unlocked the door, so that her neighbour should not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.269#be caught by Madame Cabin, who was supposed to see this rule strictly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.270#carried out.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.271#“Was she there?” asked Denise, closing the door.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.272#“Who? Madame Cabin?” replied Pauline. “Oh, I'm not afraid of her, she's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.273#easily settled with a five-franc-piece!” Then she added: “I've wanted to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.274#have a talk with you for a long time past. But it's impossible to do so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.275#downstairs. Besides, you looked so down-hearted to-night at table.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.276#Denise thanked her, and invited her to sit down, touched by her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.277#good-natured air. But in the trouble caused by the sudden visit she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.278#not laid down the shoe she was mending, and Pauline's eyes fell on it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.279#at once. She shook her head, looked round and perceived the collar and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.280#cuffs in the basin.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.281#“My poor child, I thought as much,” resumed she. “Ah, I know what it is!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.282#When I first came up from Chartres, and old Cugnot didn't send me a sou,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.283#I many a time washed my own chemises! Yes, yes, even my chemises! I had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.284#two, and there was always one in soak.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.285#She sat down, still out of breath from running. Her large face,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.286#with small bright eyes, and big tender mouth, had a certain grace,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.287#notwithstanding the rather coarse features. And, without transition,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.288#all of a sudden, she related her history; her childhood at the mill; old
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.289#Cugnot ruined by a lawsuit; her being sent to Paris to make her fortune
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.290#with twenty francs in her pocket; then her start as a shop-girl in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.291#shop at Batignolles, then at The Ladies' Paradise--a terrible start, all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.292#the sufferings and all the privations imaginable; she then spoke of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.293#her present life, of the two hundred francs she earned a month, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.294#pleasures she indulged in, the carelessness in which she allowed her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.295#days to glide away. Some jewellery, a brooch, a watch-chain, glistened
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.296#on her dark-blue cloth dress, coquettishly made to the figure; and she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.297#wore a velvet hat, ornamented with a large grey feather.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.298#Denise had turned very red, with her shoe. She began to stammer out an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.299#explanation.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.300#“But the same thing happened to me,” repeated Pauline.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.301#“Come, come, I'm older than you, I'm over twenty-six, though I don't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.302#look it. Just tell me your little troubles.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.303#Denise yielded, conquered by this friendship so frankly offered. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.304#sat down in her petticoat, with an old shawl over her shoulders, near
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.305#Pauline in full dress; and an interesting gossip ensued.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.306#It was freezing in the room, the cold seemed to run down the bare
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.307#prison-like walls; but they did not notice that their fingers were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.308#almost frost-bitten, they were so fully taken up by their conversation.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.309#Little by little, Denise opened her heart entirely, spoke of Jean and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.310#Pépé, and how much the money question tortured her; which led them both
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.311#to abuse the young ladies in the dress department. Pauline relieved her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.312#mind.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.313#“Oh, the hussies! If they treated you properly and in a friendly manner,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.314#you could make more than a hundred francs a month.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.315#“Everybody is down on me, and I'm sure I don't know why,” said Denise,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.316#beginning to cry. “Look at Monsieur Bourdoncle, he's always watching me
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.317#for a chance of finding me in fault, as if I were in his way. Old Jouve
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.318#is about the only one----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.319#The other interrupted her. “What, that old monkey of an inspector! Ah!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.320#my dear, don't you trust him. You know, men with big noses like his! He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.321#may display his decoration as much as he likes, there's a story about
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.322#something that happened to him in our department. But what a child you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.323#are to grieve like this! What a misfortune it is to be so sensitive! Of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.324#course, what is happening to you happens to every one; they are making
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.325#you pay your footing.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.326#She seized her hands and kissed her, carried away by her good heart The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.327#money-question was a graver one. Certainly a poor girl could not support
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.328#her two brothers, pay the little one's board and lodging, and regale the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.329#big one's mistresses with the few paltry sous picked up from the others'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.330#cast-off customers; for it was to be feared that she would not get any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.331#salary until business improved in March.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.332#“Listen to me, it's impossible for you to live in this way any longer.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.333#If I were you----” said Pauline.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.334#But a noise in the corridor stopped her. It was probably Marguerite, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.335#was accused of prowling about at night to watch the others. Pauline,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.336#who was still pressing her friend's hand, looked at her for a moment in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.337#silence, listening. Then she resumed in a very low tone, with an air of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.338#tender conviction: “If I were you I should take some one.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.339#“How some one?” murmured Denise, not understanding at first.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.340#When she understood, she withdrew her hands, looking very confused. This
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.341#advice made her feel awkward, like an idea which had never occurred to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.342#her, and of which she could not see the advantage.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.343#“Oh! no,” replied she simply.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.344#“Then,” continued Pauline, “you'll never manage, I tell you so, plainly.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.345#Here are the figures: forty francs for the little one, a five franc
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.346#piece now and again for the big one; and then there's yourself, you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.347#can't always go about dressed like a pauper, with boots that make the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.348#other girls laugh at you; yes, really, your boots do you a deal of harm.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.349#Take some one, it would be much better.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.350#“No,” repeated Denise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.351#“Well! you are very foolish. It's inevitable, my dear, and so natural.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.352#We all do it sooner or later. Look at me, I was a probationer, like you,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.353#without a sou. We are boarded and lodged, it's true; but there's our
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.354#dress; besides, it's impossible to go without a copper in one's pocket,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.355#shut up in one's room, watching the flies. So you see girls forcibly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.356#drift into it.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.357#She then spoke of her first lover, a lawyer's clerk whom she had met at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.358#a party at Meudon. After him, came a post-office clerk. And, finally,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.359#ever since the autumn, she had been keeping company with a salesman at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.360#the Bon Marche, a very nice tall fellow, with whom she spent all her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.361#leisure time. Never more than one sweetheart at a time, however. She was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.362#very respectable in her way, and became indignant when she heard talk of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.363#those girls who yielded to the first-comer.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.364#“I don't tell you to misconduct yourself, you know!” said she quickly.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.365#“For instance, I should not like to be seen with your Clara, for fear
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.366#people should say I was as bad as she. But when a girl stays quietly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.367#with one lover, and has nothing to blame herself for--do you think that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.368#wrong?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.369#“No,” replied Denise. “But I don't care for it, that's all.” There was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.370#a fresh silence. In the small icy-cold room they were smiling to each
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.371#other, greatly affected by this whispered conversation. “Besides, one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.372#must have some affection for some one before doing so,” resumed she, her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.373#cheeks scarlet.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.374#Pauline was astonished. She set up a laugh, and embraced her a second
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.375#time, saying: “But, my darling, when you meet and like each other! You
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.376#are funny! People won't force you. Look here, would you like Bauge
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.377#to take us somewhere in the country on Sunday? He'll bring one of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.378#friends.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.379#“No,” said Denise, in her gently obstinate way.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.380#Pauline insisted no longer. Each one was free to act as she liked. What
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.381#she had said was out of pure kindness of heart, for she felt really
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.382#grieved to see a comrade so miserable. And as it was nearly midnight,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.383#she got up to leave. But before doing so she forced Denise to accept the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.384#six francs she wanted, begging her not to trouble about the matter, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.385#to repay the amount when she earned more.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.386#“Now,” added she, “blow your candle out, so that they can't see which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.387#door opens; you can light it again immediately.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.388#The candle blown out, they shook hands; and Pauline ran off to her room,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.389#without leaving any trace in the darkness but the vague rustling of her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.390#petticoats amidst the deep slumber of the occupants of the other little
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.391#rooms.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.392#Before going to bed Denise wanted to finish her boot and do her washing.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.393#The cold became sharper still as the night advanced; but she did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.394#feel it, this conversation had stirred up her heart's blood. She was not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.395#shocked, it seemed to her that every one had a right to arrange her life
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.396#as she liked, when alone and free in the world. She had never given way
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.397#to such ideas; her sense of right and her healthy nature maintained her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.398#naturally in the respectability in which she had always lived. About one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.399#o'clock she at last went to bed. No, she did not love any one. So what
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.400#was the use of disarranging her life, of spoiling the maternal devotion
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.401#she had vowed for her two brothers? However, she did not sleep; a crowd
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.402#of indistinct forms passed before her closed eyes, vanishing in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.403#darkness.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.404#From this moment Denise took an interest in the love-stories of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.405#department. During the slack moments they were constantly occupied
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.406#by their affairs with the men. Gossiping tales flew about, stories of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.407#adventures amused the girls for a week. Clara was a scandal; she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.408#three lovers, without counting a string of chance admirers whom she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.409#in tow; and, if she did not leave the shop, where she did the least work
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.410#possible, disdaining the money which she could easily and more agreeably
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.411#earn elsewhere, it was to shield herself from her family; for she was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.412#mortally afraid of old Prunaire, who threatened to come to Paris and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.413#break her arms and legs with his clogs. Marguerite, on the contrary,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.414#behaved very well, and was not known to have any lover; this caused
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.415#some surprise, for all knew of her adventure--her coming to Paris to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.416#confined in secret; how had she come to have the child, if she were so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.417#virtuous? And there were some who hinted at an accident, adding that she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.418#was now reserving herself for her cousin at Grenoble. The young ladies
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.419#also joked about Madame Frédéric, declaring that she was discreetly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.420#connected with certain great personages; the truth was that they knew
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.421#nothing of her love-affairs; for she disappeared every evening, stiff
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.422#as starch in her widow's ill-temper, evidently in a great hurry, though
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.423#nobody knew where she was running off to so eagerly. As to Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.424#Aurélie's passions, her pretended larks with obedient young men, they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.425#were certainly false; mere inventions, spread abroad by discontented
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.426#saleswomen just for fun. Perhaps she had formerly displayed rather too
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.427#much motherly feeling for one of her son's friends, but she now occupied
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.428#too high a place in the drapery business to allow her to amuse herself
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.429#with such childish matters. Then there was the crowd leaving in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.430#evening, nine girls out of every ten having young men waiting for them
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.431#at the door; in the Place Gaillon, along the Rue de la Michodière, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.432#the Rue Neuve-Saint-Augustin, there was always quite a troop of men
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.433#standing motionless, watching for the girls coming out; and, when they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.434#came, each one gave his arm to his lady and disappeared, talking with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.435#marital tranquillity.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.436#But what troubled Denise most was to have discovered Colomban's secret.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.437#He was continually to be seen on the other side of the street, at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.438#door of The Old Elbeuf, his eyes raised, and never quitting the young
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.439#ladies in the readymade department. When he felt Denise was watching him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.440#he blushed and turned away his head, as if afraid she might betray him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.441#to Geneviève, although there had been no further connection between the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.442#Baudus and their niece since her engagement at The Ladies' Paradise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.443#At first she had thought he was in love with Marguerite, on seeing his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.444#despairing looks, for Marguerite, being very quiet, and sleeping in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.445#building, was not very easy to get at. But what was her astonishment to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.446#find that Colomban's ardent glances were intended for Clara. He had been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.447#like that for months, devoured by passion on the opposite side of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.448#way, without finding the courage to declare himself; and that for a girl
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.449#who was perfectly free, who lived in the Rue Louis-le-Grand, and whom he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.450#could have spoken to any evening before she walked off on the arm of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.451#fresh fellow! Clara herself appeared to have no idea of her conquest.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.452#Denise's discovery filled her with a painful emotion. Was love, then,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.453#such a stupid thing as that? What! this fellow, who had real
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.454#happiness within his reach, was ruining his life, enraptured with this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.455#good-for-nothing girl as if she were a saint! From that day she was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.456#seized with a feeling of grief every time she saw Geneviève's pale and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.457#suffering face behind the green panes of The Old Elbeuf.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.458#In the evening, Denise could not help thinking a great deal, on seeing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.459#the young ladies march off with their sweethearts Those who did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.460#sleep at The Ladies' Paradise, disappeared until the next day, bringing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.461#back into their departments an outside odour, a sort of troubling,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.462#unknown impression. The young girl was sometimes obliged to reply with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.463#a smile to a friendly nod from Pauline, whom Bauge waited for every
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.464#evening regularly at half-past eight, at the corner of the fountain
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.465#in the Place Gaillon. Then, after having gone out the last and taken
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.466#a furtive walk, always alone, she was invariably the first in, going
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.467#upstairs to work, or to bed, her head filled with dreams, full of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.468#curiosity about this outdoor life, of which she knew nothing. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.469#certainly did not envy the young ladies, she was happy in her solitude,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.470#in that unsociableness to which her timidity condemned her, as to a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.471#refuge; but her imagination carried her away, she tried to guess things,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.472#evoking the pleasures constantly described before her, the cafés, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.473#restaurants, the theatres, the Sundays spent on the water and in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.474#country taverns. This filled her with a mental weakness, a desire
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.475#mingled with lassitude; and she seemed to be already tired of those
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.476#amusements which she had never tasted.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.477#However, there was but little room for these dangerous dreams in her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.478#daily working life. During the thirteen hours' hard work in the shop,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.479#there was no time for any display of tenderness between the salesmen and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.480#the saleswomen. If the continual fight for money had not abolished the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.481#sexes, the unceasing press of business which occupied their minds and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.482#fatigued their bodies would have sufficed to kill all desire. But
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.483#very few love-affairs had been known in the establishment amidst the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.484#hostilities and friendships between the men and the women, the constant
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.485#elbowings from department to department. They were all nothing but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.486#the wheels, turned round by the immense machine, abdicating their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.487#personalities, simply contributing their strength to this commonplace,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.488#powerful total. It was only outside that they resumed their individual
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.489#lives, with the abrupt flame of awakening passions.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.490#Denise, however, one day saw Albert Lhomme slipping a note into the hand
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.491#of a young lady in the underclothing department, after having several
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.492#times passed through with an air of indifference. The dead season, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.493#lasts from December to February was commencing; and she had periods of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.494#rest, hours spent on her feet, her eyes wandering all over the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.495#shop, waiting for customers. The young ladies of her department were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.496#especially friendly with the salesmen who served the lace, but their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.497#intimacy never went any further than some rather risky jokes, exchanged
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.498#in whispers. In the lace department there was a second-hand, a gay youth
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.499#who pursued Clara with all sorts of abominable stories, simply for a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.500#joke--so careless at heart that he made no effort to meet her outside;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.501#and thus it was from counter to counter, between the gentlemen and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.502#young ladies, a series of winks, nods, and remarks, which they alone
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.503#understood. At times they indulged in some sly gossip with their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.504#backs half turned and with a dreamy air, in order to put the terrible
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.505#Bourdoncle off the scent As for Deloche, for a long time he contented
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.506#him self with smiling at Denise when he met her; but, getting bolder,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.507#he occasionally murmured a friendly word. The day she had noticed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.508#Madame Aurélie's son giving a note to the young lady in the under-linen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.509#department, Deloche was asking her if she had enjoyed her lunch, feeling
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.510#to want to say something, and unable to find anything more amiable.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.511#He also saw the white paper; and looking at the young girl, they both
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.512#blushed at this intrigue carried on before them.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.513#But under these rumours which gradually awoke the woman in her, Denise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.514#still retained her infantine peace of mind. The one thing that stirred
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.515#her heart was meeting with Hutin. But even that was only gratitude
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.516#in her eyes; she simply thought herself touched by the young man's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.517#politeness. He could not bring a customer to the department without her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.518#feeling quite confused. Several times, on returning from a pay-desk, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.519#found herself making a _détour_, uselessly passing the silk counter,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.520#her bosom heaving with emotion. One afternoon she met Mouret there, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.521#seemed to follow her with a smile. He paid no more attention to her now,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.522#only addressing a few words to her from time to time, to give her a few
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.523#hints about her toilet, and to joke with her, as an impossible girl, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.524#little savage almost like a boy, of whom he would never make a coquette,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.525#notwithstanding all his knowledge of women; sometimes he even ventured
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.526#to laugh at and tease her, without wishing to acknowledge to himself
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.527#the charm which this little saleswoman inspired in him, with her comical
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.528#head of hair. Before this mute smile, Denise trembled, as if she were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.529#in fault Did he know why she was going through the silk department, when
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.530#she could not herself have explained what made her make such a _détour?_
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.531#Hutin, moreover, did not seem to be aware in any way of the young
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.532#girl's grateful looks. The shop-girls were not his style, he affected to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.533#despise them, boasting more than ever of extraordinary adventures with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.534#the lady customers; a baroness had been struck with him at his counter,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.535#and the wife of an architect had fallen into his arms one day when he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.536#went to her house about an error in measuring he had made. Beneath
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.537#this Norman boasting he simply concealed girls picked up in cafés and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.538#music-halls. Like all young gentlemen in the drapery line, he had a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.539#mania for spending, fighting in his department the whole week with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.540#miser's greediness, with the sole wish to squander his money on Sunday
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.541#on the racecourses, in the restaurants, and dancing-saloons; never
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.542#thinking of saving a penny, spending his salary as soon as he drew it,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.543#absolutely indifferent about the future. Favier did not join him in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.544#these parties. Hutin and he, so friendly in the shop, bowed to each
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.545#other at the door, where all further intercourse ceased. A great many of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.546#the shopmen, in continual contact indoors, became strangers, ignorant of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.547#each other's lives, as soon as they set foot in the streets. But Liénard
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.548#was Hutin's intimate friend. Both lived in the same lodging-house,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.549#the Hôtel de Smyrne, in the Rue Sainte-Anne, a murky building entirely
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.550#inhabited by shop assistants. In the morning they arrived together;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.551#then, in the evening, the first one free, after the folding was done,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.552#waited for the other at the Cafe Saint-Roch, in the Rue Saint-Roch, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.553#little café where the employees of The Ladies' Paradise usually met,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.554#brawling, drinking, and playing cards amidst the smoke of their pipes.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.555#They often stopped there till one in the morning, until the tired
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.556#landlord turned them out. For the last month they had been spending
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.557#three evenings a week at a free-and-easy at Montmartre; and they took
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.558#their friends with them, creating a success for Mademoiselle Laure, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.559#music-hall singer. Hutin's latest conquest, whose talent they applauded
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.560#with such violent blows and such a clamour that the police had been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.561#obliged to interfere on two occasions.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.562#The winter passed in this way, and Denise at last obtained three hundred
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.563#francs a-year fixed salary. It was quite time, for her shoes were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.564#completely worn out. For the last month she had avoided going out, for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.565#fear of bursting them entirely.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.566#“What a noise you make with your shoes, mademoiselle!” Madame Aurélie
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.567#very often remarked, with an irritated look. “It's intolerable. What's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.568#the matter with your feet?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.569#The day Denise appeared with a pair of cloth boots, for which she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.570#given five francs, Marguerite and Clara expressed their astonishment in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.571#a kind of half whisper, so as to be heard.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.572#“Hullo! the 'unkempt girl' has given up her goloshes,” said the one.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.573#“Ah,” retorted the other, “she must have cried over them. They were her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.574#mother's.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.575#In point of fact, there was a general uprising against Denise. The girls
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.576#of her department had found out her friendship with Pauline, and thought
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.577#they saw a certain bravado in this affection displayed for a saleswoman
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.578#of a rival counter. They spoke of treason, accused her of going and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.579#repeating their slightest words. The war between the two departments
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.580#became more violent than ever, it had never waxed so warm; hard words
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.581#were exchanged like cannon-balls, and there was even a slap given one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.582#evening behind some boxes of chemises. Perhaps this remote quarrel arose
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.583#from the fact that the young ladies in the under-linen department wore
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.584#woollen dresses, whilst those in the ready-made one wore silk. In any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.585#case, the former spoke of their neighbours with the shocked air of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.586#respectable girls; and facts proved that they were right, for it had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.587#been remarked that the silk dresses appeared to have a certain influence
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.588#on the dissolute habits of the young ladies who wore them. Clara was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.589#taunted with her troop of lovers, even Marguerite had, so to say, had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.590#her child thrown in her face, whilst Madame Frédéric was accused of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.591#all sorts of concealed passions. And this was solely on account of that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.592#Denise!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.593#“Now, young ladies, no ugly words; behave yourselves!” Madame Aurélie
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.594#would say with her imperial air, amidst the rising passions of her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.595#little kingdom. “Show who you are.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.596#At heart she preferred to remain neutral. As she confessed one day, when
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.597#talking to Mouret, these girls were all about the same, one was as good
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.598#as the other. But she suddenly became impassioned when she learnt from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.599#Bourdoncle that he had just caught her son downstairs kissing a young
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.600#girl belonging to the under-linen department, the saleswoman to whom he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.601#had passed several letters. It was abominable, and she roundly accused
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.602#the under-linen department of having laid a trap for Albert. Yes, it was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.603#a got-up affair against herself, they were trying to dishonour her by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.604#ruining a child without experience, after seeing that it was impossible
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.605#to attack her department. Her only object in making such a noise was to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.606#complicate the business, for she knew what her son was, fully aware
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.607#that he was capable of doing all sorts of stupid things. For a time the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.608#matter assumed a grave aspect, Mignot, the glove salesman, was mixed up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.609#in it. He was a great friend of Albert's, and the rumour got circulated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.610#that he favoured the mistresses Albert sent him, girls with big
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.611#chignons, who rummaged in the boxes for hours together; and there was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.612#also a story about some Swedish kid gloves given to the girl of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.613#under-linen department which was never properly cleared up. At last
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.614#the scandal was hushed up out of regard for Madame Aurélie, whom Mouret
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.615#himself treated with deference. Bourdoncle contented himself a week
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.616#after with dismissing, for some slight offence, the girl who allowed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.617#herself to be kissed. If they shut their eyes to the terrible doings
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.618#of their employees outdoors, the managers did not tolerate the least
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.619#nonsense in the house.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.620#And it was Denise who suffered for all this. Madame Aurélie, although
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.621#perfectly well aware of what was going on, nourished a secret rancour
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.622#against her; she saw her laughing one evening with Pauline, and took
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.623#it for bravado, concluding that they were gossiping over her son's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.624#love-affairs. And she caused the young girl to be isolated more than
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.625#ever in the department. For some time she had been thinking of inviting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.626#the young ladies to spend a Sunday near Rambouillet, at Rigolles, where
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.627#she had bought a country house with the first hundred thousand francs
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.628#she had saved; and she suddenly decided to do so; it would be a means
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.629#of punishing Denise, of putting her openly on one side. She was the only
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.630#one not invited. For a fortnight in advance, nothing was talked of but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.631#this party; the girls kept their eyes on the sky, and had already
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.632#mapped out the whole day, looking forward to all sorts of pleasures:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.633#donkey-riding, milk and brown bread. And they were to be all women,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.634#which was more amusing still! As a rule, Madame Aurélie killed her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.635#holidays in this way, going out with her lady friends; for she was so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.636#little accustomed to being at home, she always felt so uncomfortable, so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.637#strange, during the rare occasions she could dine with her husband and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.638#son, that she preferred to throw up even those occasions, and go and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.639#dine at a restaurant. Lhomme went his own way, enraptured to resume
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.640#his bachelor existence, and Albert, greatly relieved, went off with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.641#his beauties; so that, unaccustomed to being at home, feeling in each
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.642#other's way, and wearying each other when together on a Sunday, they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.643#paid nothing more than a flying visit to the house, as to some common
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.644#hôtel where people take a bed for the night. Regarding the excursion
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.645#to Rambouillet, Madame Aurélie simply declared that propriety prevented
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.646#Albert joining them, and that the father himself would display great
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.647#tact by refusing to come; a declaration which enchanted the two men.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.648#However, the happy day was drawing near, and the young girls chattered
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.649#more than ever, relating their preparations in the way of dress, as if
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.650#they were going on a six months' tour, whilst Denise had to listen to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.651#them, pale and silent in her abandonment.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.652#“Ah, they make you wild, don't they?” said Pauline to her one morning.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.653#“If I were you I would just catch them nicely! They are going to enjoy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.654#themselves. I would enjoy myself too. Come with us on Sunday, Bauge is
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.655#going to take me to Joinville.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.656#“No, thanks,” said the young girl with her quiet obstinacy.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.657#“But why not? Are you still afraid of being taken by force?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.658#And Pauline, laughed heartily. Denise also smiled. She knew how such
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.659#things came about; it was always during some similar excursions that the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.660#young ladies had made the acquaintance of their first lovers, brought by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.661#chance by a friend; and she did not want to.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.662#“Come,” resumed Pauline, “I assure you that Bauge won't bring any one.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.663#We shall be all by ourselves. As you don't want to, I won't go and marry
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.664#you off, of course.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.665#Denise hesitated, tormented by such a strong desire to go that the blood
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.666#flew to her cheeks. Since the girls had been talking about their country
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.667#pleasures she had felt stifled, overcome by a longing for fresh air,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.668#dreaming of the tall grass into which she could sink down up to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.669#neck, of the giant trees the shadows of which should flow over her like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.670#so much cooling water. Her childhood, spent in the rich verdure of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.671#Cotentin, was awakening with a regret for sun and air.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.672#“Well! yes,” said she at last.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.673#Everything was soon arranged. Bauge was to come and fetch them at eight
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.674#o'clock, in the Place Gaillon; from there they would take a cab to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.675#Vincennes Station. Denise, whose twenty-five francs a month was quickly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.676#swallowed up by the children, had only been able to do up her old black
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.677#woollen dress, by trimming it with strips of check poplin; and she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.678#also made herself a bonnet, a shape covered with silk and ornamented
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.679#with a simple blue ribbon. In this simple attire she looked very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.680#young, like an overgrown girl, exceedingly clean, rather shamefaced and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.681#embarrassed by her luxuriant hair, which appeared through the nakedness
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.682#of her bonnet.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.683#Pauline, on the contrary, displayed a pretty violet and white striped
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.684#silk dress, a hat richly trimmed and laden with feathers, jewels round
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.685#her neck and rings on her fingers, which gave her the appearance of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.686#well-to-do tradesman's wife. It was like a Sunday revenge on the woollen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.687#dress she was obliged to wear all the week in the shop; whilst Denise,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.688#who wore her uniform silk from Monday to Saturday, resumed, on Sunday,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.689#her thin woollen dress of misery.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.690#“There's Bauge,” said Pauline, pointing to a tall fellow standing near
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.691#the fountain.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.692#She introduced her lover, and Denise felt at her ease at once, he seemed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.693#such a nice fellow. Bauge, big, strong as an ox, had a long Flemish
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.694#face, in which his expressionless eyes twinkled with an infantine
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.695#puerility. Born at Dunkerque, the younger son of a grocer, he had come
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.696#to Paris, almost turned out by his father and brother, who thought him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.697#a fearful dunce. However, he made three thousand five hundred francs a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.698#year at the Bon Marche. He was rather stupid, but a very good hand in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.699#the linen department. The women thought him nice.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.700#“And the cab?” asked Pauline.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.701#They had to go as far as the Boulevard. It was already rather warm
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.702#in the sun, the glorious May morning seemed to laugh on the street
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.703#pavement. There was not a cloud in the sky; quite a gaiety floated in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.704#the blue air, transparent as crystal. An involuntary smile played on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.705#Denise's lips; she breathed freely; it seemed to her that her bosom was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.706#throwing off the stifling sensation of six months. At last she no
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.707#longer felt the stuffy air and the heavy stones of The Ladies' Paradise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.708#weighing her down! She had then the prospect of a long day in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.709#country before her! and it was like a new lease of life, an endless joy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.710#into which she entered with all the glee of a little child. However,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.711#when in the cab, she turned her eyes away, feeling very awkward as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.712#Pauline bent over to kiss her lover.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.713#“Oh, look!” said she, her head still at the window, “there's Monsieur
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.714#Lhomme. How he does walk!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.715#“He's got his French horn,” added Pauline, leaning out. “What an old
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.716#stupid! One would think he was running to meet his girl!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.717#Lhomme, with his instrument under his arm, was spinning along past
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.718#the Gymnase Theatre, his nose in the air, laughing with delight at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.719#thought of the treat in store for him. He was going to spend the day at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.720#a friend's, a flautist at a small theatre, where a few amateurs indulged
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.721#in a little chamber music on Sundays as soon as breakfast was over.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.722#“At eight o'clock! what a madman!” resumed Pauline. “And you know that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.723#Madame Aurélie and all her clique must have taken the Rambouillet train
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.724#that left at half-past six. It's very certain the husband and wife won't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.725#come across each other.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.726#Both then commenced talking of the Rambouillet excursion. They did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.727#wish it to be rainy for the others, because they themselves would be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.728#obliged to suffer as well; but if a cloud could burst over there without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.729#extending to Joinville, it would be funny all the same. Then they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.730#attacked Clara, a dirty slut, who hardly knew how to spend the money
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.731#her men gave her: hadn't she bought three pairs of boots all at the same
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.732#time, which she threw away the next day, after having cut them with her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.733#scissors, on account of her feet, which were covered with bunions. In
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.734#fact, the young ladies were just as bad as the fellows, they squandered
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.735#everything, never saving a son, wasting two or three hundred francs a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.736#month on dress and dainties.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.737#“But he's only got one arm,” said Bauge all of a sudden. “How does he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.738#manage to play the French horn?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.739#He had kept his eyes on Lhomme. Pauline, who sometimes amused herself by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.740#playing on his stupidity, told him the cashier kept the instrument up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.741#by placing it against a wall. He thoroughly believed her, and thought it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.742#very ingenious. Then, when stricken with remorse, she explained to him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.743#in what way Lhomme had adapted to his stump a system of keys which he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.744#made use of as a hand, he shook his head, full of suspicion, declaring
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.745#that they wouldn't make him swallow that.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.746#“You are ready too stupid!” she retorted, laughingly. “Never mind, I love
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.747#you all the same.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.748#They reached the Vincennes Station just in time for a train. Bauge paid;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.749#but Denise had previously declared that she washed to pay her share
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.750#of the expenses; they would settle up in the evening. They took
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.751#second-class tickets, and found the train full of a gay noisy throng.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.752#At Nogent, a wedding-party got out, amidst a storm of laughter. At last
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.753#they arrived at Joinville and went straight to the island to order
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.754#lunch; and they stopped there, lingering on the banks of the Marne,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.755#under the tall poplars. It was rather cold in the shade, a sharp breese
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.756#was blowing in the sunshine, extending far into the distance, on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.757#other side of the river, the limpid parity of a plain dotted with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.758#cultivated fields. Denise lingered behind Pauline and her lover, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.759#were walking with their arms round each others waists. She had picked
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.760#a handful of buttercups, and was watching the view of the river, happy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.761#her heart beating, her head drooping, each time Baugé leant over to kiss
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.762#his mistress. Her eyes filled with tears. And yet she was not suffering.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.763#What was the matter with her that she had this feeling of suffocation?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.764#and why did this vast landscape, where she had looked forward to having
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.765#so much enjoyment, fill her with a vague regret she could not explain?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.766#Then, at lunch, Pauline's noisy laugh bewildered her. That young lady,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.767#who loved the suburbs with the passion of an actress living in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.768#gas-light, in the thick air of a crowd, wanted to lunch in an arbour,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.769#notwithstanding the sharp wind. She was delighted with the sudden gusts
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.770#which blew up the table-cloth, she thought the arbour very funny in its
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.771#nudity, with the freshly-painted trelliswork, the lozenges of which cast
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.772#a reflection on the cloth. She ate ravenously, devouring everything with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.773#the voracity of a girl badly fed at the shop, making up for it outside
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.774#by giving herself an indigestion with the things she liked; this was her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.775#vice, she spent most of her money in cakes and indigestible dainties
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.776#of all kinds, favourite dishes stowed away in her leisure moments. As
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.777#Denise seemed to have had enough of the eggs, fried fish, and stewed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.778#chicken, she restrained herself, not daring to order any strawberries, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.779#luxury still very dear, for fear of running the bill up too high.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.780#“Now, what are we going to do?” asked Baugé when the coffee was served.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.781#As a rule Pauline and he returned to Paris to dine, and finish their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.782#day in some theatre. But at Denise's request, they decided to stay at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.783#Joinville all day; they would be able to have their fill of the country.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.784#So they stopped and wandered about the fields all the afternoon. They
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.785#spoke for a moment of going for a row, but abandoned the idea; Baugé was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.786#not a good waterman. But they found themselves walking along the banks
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.787#of the Marne, all the same, and were greatly interested by the life on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.788#the river, the squadrons of yawls and other boats, and the young men
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.789#who formed the crews. The sun was going down, they were returning to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.790#Joinville, when they saw two boats coming down stream at a racing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.791#speed, exchanging volleys of insults, in which the repeated cries of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.792#“Sawbones!” and “Counter-jumpers!” dominated.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.793#“Hallo!” said Pauline, “it's Monsieur Hutin.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.794#“Yes,” said Baugé, shading his face with his hand, “I recognise his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.795#mahogany boat. The other one is manned by students, no doubt.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.796#And he explained the deadly hatred existing between the young students
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.797#and the shopmen. Denise, on hearing Hutin's name mentioned, suddenly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.798#stopped, and followed, with fixed eyes, the frail skiff spinning along
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.799#like an arrow. She tried to distinguish the young man among the rowers,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.800#but could only manage to make out the white dresses of two women, one of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.801#whom, who was steering, wore a red hat. Their voices were drowned by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.802#rapid flow of the river.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.803#“Pitch 'em in, the sawbones!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.804#“Duck 'em, the counter-jumpers!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.805#In the evening they returned to the restaurant on the island. But it had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.806#turned too chilly, they were obliged to dine in one of the closed rooms,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.807#where the table-cloths were still damp from the humidity of the winter.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.808#After six o'clock the tables were all occupied, yet the excursionists
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.809#still hurried in, looking for a corner; and the waiters continued to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.810#bring in more chairs and forms, putting the plates closer together, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.811#crowding the people up. It was stifling, they had to open the windows.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.812#Outdoors, the day was waning, a greenish twilight fell from the poplars
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.813#so quickly that the proprietor, unprepared for these meals under cover,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.814#and having no lamps, was obliged to put a wax candle on each table. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.815#uproar became deafening with laughing, calling out, and the clacking of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.816#the table utensils; the candles flared and melted in the draught from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.817#the windows, whilst moths fluttered about in the air, warmed by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.818#odour of the food, and traversed by sudden gusts of cold wind.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.819#“What fun they're having, eh?” said Pauline, very busy with a plate
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.820#of matelote, which she declared extraordinary. She leant over to add:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.821#“Didn't you see Monsieur Albert over there?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.822#It was really young Lhomme, in the middle of three questionable women,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.823#a vulgar-looking old lady in a yellow bonnet, suspiciously like a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.824#procuress, and two young girls of thirteen or fourteen, forward and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.825#painfully impudent creatures. He, already intoxicated, was knocking his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.826#glass on the table, and talking of drubbing the waiter if he did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.827#bring some “liqueurs” immediately.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.828#“Well!” resumed Pauline, “there's a family, if you like! the mother at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.829#Rambouillet, the father in Paris; and the son at Joinville; they won't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.830#tread on one another's toes!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.831#Denise, who detested noise, smiled, however, and tasted the joy of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.832#ceasing to think, amid such uproar. But all at once they heard a noise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.833#in the other room, a burst of voices which drowned the others. They
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.834#were yelling, and must have come to blows, for one could hear a scuffle,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.835#chairs falling down, quite a struggle, amid which the river-cries again
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.836#resounded:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.837#“Duck 'em, the counter-jumpers!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.838#“Pitch 'em in, the sawbones!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.839#And when the hotel-keeper's loud voice had calmed this tempest, Hutin
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.840#suddenly made his appearance, wearing a red jersey, and a little cap
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.841#at the back of his head; he had on his arm the tall, fair girl, who had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.842#been steering, and who, in order to wear the boat's colours, had planted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.843#a bunch of poppies behind her ear. They were greeted on entering by a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.844#storm of applause; and his face beamed with pride, he swelled out his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.845#chest, assuming a nautical rolling gait, showing off a blow which had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.846#blackened his cheek, puffed up with joy at being noticed. Behind them
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.847#followed the crew. They took a table by storm, and the uproar became
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.848#something fearful.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.849#“It appears,” explained Bauge, after having listened to the conversation
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.850#behind him, “it appears that the students have recognised the woman
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.851#with Hutin as an old friend from their neighbourhood, who now sings in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.852#a music-hall at Montmartre. So they were kicking up a row for her. These
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.853#students never pay their women.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.854#“In any case,” said Pauline, stiffly, “she's jolly ugly, with her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.855#carroty hair. Really, I don't know where Monsieur Hutin picks them up,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.856#but they're an ugly, dirty lot.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.857#Denise had turned pale, and felt an icy coldness, as if her heart's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.858#blood were flowing away, drop by drop. She had already, on seeing the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.859#boats from the bank, felt a shiver; but now she no longer had any doubt,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.860#this girl was certainly with Hutin. With trembling hands, and a choking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.861#sensation in her throat, she ceased eating.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.862#“What's the matter?” asked her friend.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.863#“Nothing,” stammered she; “it's rather warm here.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.864#But Hutin's table was close to theirs, and when he perceived Bauge,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.865#whom he knew, he commenced a conversation in a shrill voice, in order to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.866#attract further attention.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.867#“I say,” cried he, “are you as virtuous as ever at the Bon Marche?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.868#“Not so much as all that,” replied Bauge, turning very red.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.869#“That won't do! You know they only take virgins there, and there's a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.870#confessional box permanently fixed for the salesmen who venture to look
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.871#at them. A house where they marry you--no, thanks!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.872#The other fellows began to laugh. Liénard, who belonged to the crew,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.873#added: “It isn't like the Louvre. There they have a midwife attached to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.874#the ready-made department. My word of honour!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.875#The gaiety increased; Pauline herself burst out, the idea of the midwife
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.876#seemed so funny. But Baugé was annoyed by the jokes about the innocence
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.877#of his house. He launched out all at once: “Oh, you're not too well off
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.878#at The Ladies' Paradise. Sacked for the slightest thing! And a governor
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.879#who seems to tout for his lady customers.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.880#Hutin no longer listened to him, but commenced to praise the house in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.881#the Place Clichÿ. He knew a young girl there so excessively aristocratic
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.882#that the customers dared not speak to her for fear of humiliating her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.883#Then, drawing up closer, he related that he had made a hundred and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.884#fifteen francs that week; oh! a capital week. Favier left behind with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.885#fifty-two francs, the whole lot floored. And it was visible he was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.886#bursting with money, he would not go to bed till he had liquidated the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.887#hundred and fifteen francs. Then, as he gradually became intoxicated,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.888#he attacked Robineau, that fool of a second-hand who affected to keep
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.889#himself apart, going so far as to refuse to walk in the street with one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.890#of his salesmen.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.891#“Shut up,” said Liénard; “you talk too much, old man.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.892#The heat had increased, the candles were guttering down on to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.893#table-cloths stained with wine; and through the open windows, when the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.894#noise within ceased for an instant, there entered a distant prolonged
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.895#voice, the voice of the river, and of the tall poplars sleeping in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.896#calm night. Baugé had just called for the bill, seeing that Denise was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.897#now quite white, her throat choked by the tears she withheld; but the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.898#waiter did not appear, and she had to submit to Hutin's loud talk. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.899#was now boasting of being more superior to Liénard, because Liénard
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.900#cared for nothing, simply squandering his father's money, whilst he,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.901#Hutin, was spending his own earnings, the fruit of his intelligence. At
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.902#last Baugé paid, and the two girls went out.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.903#“There's one from the Louvre,” murmured Pauline in the outer room,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.904#looking at a tall thin girl putting on her mantle.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.905#“You don't know her. You can't tell,” said the young man.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.906#“Oh, can't I? They've got a way of draping themselves. She belongs to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.907#the midwife's department! If she heard, she must be pleased.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.908#They got outside at last, and Denise heaved a sigh of relief. For a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.909#moment she had thought she was going to die in that suffocating heat,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.910#amidst all those cries; and she still attributed her faintness to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.911#want of air. Now she breathed freely in the freshness of the starry
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.912#night As the two young girls were leaving the garden of the restaurant,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.913#a timid voice murmured in the shade: “Good evening, ladies.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.914#It was Deloche. They had not seen him at the further end of the front
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.915#room, where he was dining alone, after having come from Paris on foot,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.916#for the pleasure of the walk. On recognising this friendly voice,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.917#Denise, suffering, yielded mechanically to the want of some support.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.918#“Monsieur Deloche, come back with us,” said she. “Give me your arm.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.919#Pauline and Baugé had already gone on in front. They were astonished,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.920#never thinking it would turn out like this, and with this fellow above
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.921#all. However, as there was still an hour before the train started,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.922#they went to the end of the island, following the bank, under the tall
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.923#poplars; and, from time to time, they turned round, murmuring: “But
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.924#where are they? Ah, there they are. It's rather funny, all the same.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.925#At first Denise and Deloche remained silent The noise from the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.926#restaurant was slowly dying away, changing into a musical sweetness in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.927#the calmness of the night; and they went further in amongst the cool of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.928#the trees, still feverish from that furnace, the lights of which were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.929#disappearing one by one behind the foliage. Opposite them there was a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.930#sort of shadowy wall, a mass of shade in which the trunks and branches
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.931#buried themselves so compact that they could not even distinguish any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.932#trace of the path. However, they went forward quietly, without fear.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.933#Then, their eyes getting more accustomed to the darkness, they saw on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.934#the right the trunks of the poplars, resembling sombre columns upholding
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.935#the domes of their branches, pierced with stars; whilst on the right the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.936#water assumed occasionally in the darkness the brightness of a mirror.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.937#The wind was subsiding, they no longer heard anything but the flowing of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.938#the river.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.939#“I am very pleased to have met you,” stammered Deloche at last, making
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.940#up his mind to speak first. “You can't think how happy you render me in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.941#consenting to walk with me.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.942#And, aided by the darkness, after many awkward attempts, he ventured to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.943#tell her he loved her. He had long wanted to write to her and tell her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.944#so; and perhaps she would never have known it had it not been for this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.945#lovely night coming to his assistance, this water that murmured so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.946#softly, and these trees which screened them with their shade. But she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.947#did not reply; she continued to walk by his side with the same suffering
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.948#air. And he was trying to look into her face, when he heard a sob.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.949#“Oh! good heavens!” he exclaimed, “you are crying, mademoiselle, you are
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.950#crying! Have I offended you?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.951#“No, no,” she murmured.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.952#She tried to keep back her tears, but she could not. Even when at table,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.953#she had thought her heart was about to burst. She abandoned herself in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.954#the darkness entirely, stifled by her sobs, thinking that if Hutin had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.955#been in Deloche's place and said such tender things to her, she would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.956#have been unable to resist. This confession made to herself filled her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.957#with confusion. A feeling of shame burnt her face, as if she had already
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.958#fallen into the arms of that Hutin, who was disporting himself with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.959#those girls.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.960#“I didn't mean to offend you,” continued Deloche, almost crying also.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.961#“No, but listen,” said she, her voice still trembling; “I am not at all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.962#angry with you. But never speak to me again as you have just done. What
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.963#you ask is impossible. Oh! you're a good fellow, and I'm quite willing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.964#to be your friend, but nothing more. You understand--your friend.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.965#He shuddered. After a few steps taken in silence, he stammered: “In
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.966#fact, you don't love me?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.967#And as she spared him the pain of a brutal “no,” he resumed in a soft,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.968#heart-broken voice: “Oh, I was prepared for it I have never had any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.969#luck, I know I can never be happy. At home, they used to beat me. In
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.970#Paris, I've always been a drudge. You see, when one does not know how
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.971#to rob other fellows of their mistresses, and when one is too awkward to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.972#earn as much as the others, why the best thing is to go into some corner
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.973#and die. Never fear, I sha'n't torment you any more. As for loving you,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.974#you can't prevent me, can you? I shall love you for nothing, like a dog.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.975#There, everything escapes me, that's my luck in life.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.976#And he, too, burst into tears. She tried to console him, and in their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.977#friendly effusion they found they belonged to the same department--she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.978#to Valognes, he to Briquebec, eight miles from each other, and this was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.979#a fresh tie. His father, a poor, needy bailiff, and sickly jealous, used
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.980#to drub him, calling him a bastard, exasperated with his long pale face
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.981#and tow-like hair, which, said he, did not belong to the family. And
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.982#they got talking about the vast pastures, surrounded with quick-set
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.983#hedges, of the shady paths winding beneath the elm trees, and of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.984#grass grown roads, like the alleys in a park.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.985#Around them night was getting darker, but they could still distinguish
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.986#the rushes on the banks, and the interlaced foliage, black beneath the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.987#twinkling stars; and a peacefulness came over them, they forgot their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.988#troubles, brought nearer by their ill-luck, in a closer feeling of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.989#friendship.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.990#“Well?” asked Pauline of Denise, taking her aside when they arrived at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.991#the station.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.992#The young girl understood by the smile and the stare of tender
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.993#curiosity; she turned very red and replied: “But--never, my dear! I told
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.994#you I did not wish to! He belongs to my part of the country. We were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.995#talking about Valognes.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.996#Pauline and Bauge were perplexed, put out in their ideas, not knowing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.997#what to think. Deloche left them in the Place de la Bastille; like all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.998#young probationers, he slept at the house, where he had to be in by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.999#eleven o'clock. Not wishing to go in with him, Denise, who had got
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1000#permission to go to the theatre, accepted Baugé's invitation to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1001#accompany Pauline to his home--he, in order to be nearer his mistress,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1002#had moved into the Rue Saint-Roch. They took a cab, and Denise was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1003#stupefied on learning on the way that her friend was going to stay all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1004#night with the young man--nothing was easier, they only had to give
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1005#Madame Cabin five francs, all the young ladies did it. Bauge did the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1006#honours of his room, which was furnished with old Empire furniture,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1007#given him by his father. He got angry when Denise spoke of settling up,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1008#but at last accepted the fifteen francs twelve sous which she had laid
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1009#on the chest of drawers; but he insisted on making her a cup of tea, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1010#he struggled with a spirit-lamp and saucepan, and then was obliged to go
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1011#and fetch some sugar. Midnight struck as he was pouring out the tea.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1012#“I must be off,” said Denise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1013#“Presently,” replied Pauline. “The theatres don't close so early.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1014#Denise felt uncomfortable in this bachelor's room. She had seen her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1015#friend take off her things, turn down the bed, open it, and pat the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1016#pillows with her naked arms; and these preparations for a night of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1017#love-making carried on before her, troubled her, and made her feel
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1018#ashamed, awakening once in her wounded heart the recollection of Hutin.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1019#Such ideas were not very salutary. At last she left them, at a quarter
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1020#past twelve. But she went away confused, when in reply to her innocent
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1021#“good night,” Pauline cried out, thoughtlessly; “Thanks, we are sure to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1022#have a good one!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1023#The private door leading to Mouret's apartments and to the employees'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1024#bedrooms was in the Rue Neuve-Saint-Augustin. Madame Cabin opened the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1025#door and gave a glance in order to mark the return. A night-light
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1026#was burning dimly in the hall, and Denise, finding herself in this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1027#uncertain light, hesitated, and was seized with fear, for on turning the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1028#corner of the street, she had seen the door close on the vague shadow of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1029#a man. It must have been the governor coming home from a party,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1030#and the idea that he was there in the dark waiting for her perhaps,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1031#caused her one of those strange fears with which he still inspired her,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1032#without any reasonable cause. Some one moved on the first-floor, a boot
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1033#creaked, and losing her head entirely, she pushed open a door which led
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1034#into the shop, and which was always left open for the night-watch. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1035#was in the printed cotton department.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1036#“Good heavens! what shall I do?” she stammered, in her emotion.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1037#The idea occurred to her that there was another door upstairs leading
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1038#to the bedrooms; but she would have to go right across the shop. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1039#preferred this, notwithstanding the darkness reigning in the galleries.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1040#Not a gas-jet was burning, there were only a few oil-lamps hung here and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1041#there on the branches of the lustres; and these scattered lights, like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1042#yellow patches, their rays lost in the gloom, resembled the lanterns
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1043#hung up in a mine. Big shadows loomed in the air; one could hardly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1044#distinguish the piles of goods, which assumed alarming profiles: fallen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1045#columns, squatting beasts, and lurking thieves. The heavy silence,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1046#broken by distant respirations, increased still more the darkness.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1047#However, she saw where she was. The linen department on her left formed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1048#a dead colour, like the blueiness of houses in the street under a summer
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1049#sky; then she wished to cross the hall immediately, but running up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1050#against some piles of printed calico, she thought it safer to follow the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1051#hosiery department, and then the woollen one. There she was frightened
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1052#by a loud noise of snoring. It was Joseph, the messenger, sleeping
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1053#behind some articles of mourning. She quickly ran into the hall, now
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1054#illuminated by the skylight, with a sort of crepuscular light which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1055#made it appear larger, full of a nocturnal church-like terror, with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1056#immobility of its shelves, and the shadows of its yard-measures which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1057#described reversed crosses. She now fairly ran away. In the mercery and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1058#glove departments she nearly walked over some more messengers, and only
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1059#felt safe when she at last found herself on the staircase. But upstairs,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1060#before the ready-made department, she was seized with fear on perceiving
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1061#a lantern moving forward, twinkling in the darkness. It was the watch,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1062#two firemen marking their passage on the faces of the indicators. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1063#stood a moment unable to understand it, watched them passing from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1064#the shawl to the furniture department, then to the under-linen,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1065#terrified by their strange manouvres, by the grinding of the key, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1066#by the closing of the iron doors which made a murderous noise. When they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1067#approached, she took refuge in the lace department, but a sound of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1068#talking made her hastily depart, and run off to the outer door. She had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1069#recognised Deloche's voice. He slept in his department, on a little iron
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1070#bedstead which he set up himself every evening; and he was not asleep
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1071#yet, recalling the pleasant hours he had just spent.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1072#“What! it's you, mademoiselle?” said Mouret, whom Denise found before
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1073#her on the staircase, a small pocket-candlestick in his hand.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1074#She stammered, and tried to explain that she had come to look for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1075#something. But he was not angry. He looked at her with his paternal, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1076#at the same time curious, air.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1077#“You had permission to go to the theatre, then?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1078#“Yes, sir.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1079#“And have you enjoyed yourself? What theatre did you go to?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1080#“I have been in the country, sir.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1081#That made him laugh. Then he asked, laying a certain stress on his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1082#question: “All alone?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1083#“No, sir; with a lady friend,” replied she, her cheeks burning, shocked
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1084#at the idea which he no doubt entertained.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1085#He said no more; but he was still looking at her in her simple black
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1086#dress and hat trimmed with a single blue ribbon. Was this little savage
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1087#going to turn out a pretty girl? She looked all the better for her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1088#day in the open air, charming with her splendid hair falling over her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1089#forehead. And he, who during the last six months had treated her like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1090#a child, some times giving her advice, yielding to a desire to gain
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1091#experience, to a wicked wish to know how a woman sprung up and lost
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1092#herself in Paris, no longer laughed, experiencing a feeling of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1093#surprise and fear mingled with tenderness. No doubt it was a lover who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1094#embellished her like this. At this thought he felt as if stung to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1095#quick by a favourite bird, with which he was playing.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1096#“Good night, sir,” murmured Denise, continuing her way without waiting.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1097#He did not answer, but stood watching her till she dis appeared. Then he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:v.1098#entered his own apartments.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.1#CHAPTER VI.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.2#When the dead summer season arrived, there was quite a panic at The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.3#Ladies' Paradise. The reign of terror commenced, a great many employees
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.4#were sent away on leave, and others were dismissed in dozens by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.5#principals, who wished to clear the shop, no customers appearing during
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.6#the July and August heat. Mouret, on making his daily inspection with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.7#Burdoncle, called aside the managers, whom he had prompted during the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.8#winter to engage more men than were necessary, so that the business
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.9#should not suffer, leaving them to weed out their staff later on. It was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.10#now a question of reducing expenses by getting rid of quite a third of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.11#the shop people, the weak ones who allowed themselves to be swallowed up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.12#by the strong ones.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.13#“Come,” he would say, “you must have some who don't suit you. We can't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.14#keep them all this time doing nothing.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.15#And if the manager hesitated, hardly knowing whom to sacrifice, he would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.16#continue; “Make your arrangements, six salesmen must suffice; you can
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.17#take on others in October, there are plenty to be had!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.18#As a rule Bourdoncle undertook the executions. He had a terrible way of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.19#saying: “Go and be paid!” which fell like a blow from an axe. Anything
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.20#served him as a pretext for clearing off the superfluous staff. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.21#invented misdeeds, speculating on the slightest negligence. “You were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.22#sitting down, sir; go and be paid!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.23#“You dare to answer me; go and be paid!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.24#“Your shoes are not clean; go and be paid!” And even the bravest
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.25#trembled in presence of the massacre which he left behind him. Then,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.26#this system not working quick enough, he invented a trap by which he got
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.27#rid in a few days, without fatigue, of the number of salesmen condemned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.28#beforehand. At eight o'clock, he took his stand at the door, watch in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.29#hand; and at three minutes past the hour, the breathless young people
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.30#were greeted with the implacable “Go and be paid!” This was a quick and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.31#cleanly method of doing the work.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.32#“You've an ugly mug,” he ended by saying one day to a poor wretch whose
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.33#nose, all on one side, annoyed him, “go and be paid!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.34#The favoured ones obtained a fortnight's holiday without pay, which was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.35#a more humane way of lessening the expenses. The salesmen accepted their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.36#precarious situation, obliged to do so by necessity and habit. Since
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.37#their arrival in Paris, they had roamed about, commencing their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.38#apprenticeship here, finishing it there, getting dismissed or themselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.39#resigning all at once, as interest dictated. When business stood still,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.40#the workmen were deprived of their daily bread; and this was well
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.41#understood in the indifferent march of the machine, the useless
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.42#workmen were quietly thrown aside, like so much old plant, there was no
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.43#gratitude shown for services rendered. So much the worse for those who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.44#did not know how to look after themselves!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.45#Nothing else was now talked of in the various departments. Fresh stories
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.46#circulated every day. The dismissed salesmen were named, as one counts
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.47#the dead in time of cholera. The shawl and the woollen departments
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.48#suffered especially; seven employees disappeared from them in one week.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.49#Then the underlinen department was thrown into confusion, a customer
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.50#had nearly fainted away, accusing the young person who had served her of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.51#eating garlic; and the latter was dismissed at once, although, badly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.52#fed and dying of hunger, she was simply finishing a collection of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.53#bread crusts at the counter. The authorities were pitiless at the least
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.54#complaint from the customers; no excuse was admitted, the employee was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.55#always wrong, and had to disappear like a defective instrument, hurtful
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.56#to the proper working of the business; and the others bowed their heads,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.57#not even attempting any defence. In the panic which was raging each one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.58#trembled for himself. Mignot, going out one day with a parcel under his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.59#coat, notwithstanding the rules, was nearly caught, and really thought
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.60#himself lost. Liénard, who was celebrated for his idleness, owed to his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.61#father's position in the drapery trade that he was not turned away one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.62#afternoon that Bourdoncle found him dozing between two piles of English
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.63#velvets. But the Lhommes were especially anxious, expecting every day
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.64#to see their son Albert sent away, the governor being very dissatisfied
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.65#with his conduct at the pay-desk. He frequently had women there who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.66#distracted his attention from his work; and twice Madame Aurélie had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.67#been obliged to plead for him with the principals.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.68#Denise was so menaced amid this general clearance, that she lived in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.69#constant expectation of a catastrophe. It was in vain that she summoned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.70#up her courage, struggling with all her gaiety and all her reason not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.71#to yield to the misgivings of her tender nature; she burst out into
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.72#blinding tears as soon as she had closed the door of her bedroom,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.73#desolated at the thought of seeing herself in the street, on bad terms
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.74#with her uncle, not knowing where to go, without a sou saved, and having
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.75#the two children to look after. The sensations she had felt the first
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.76#few weeks sprang up again, she fancied herself a grain of seed under
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.77#a powerful millstone; and, utterly discouraged, she abandoned herself
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.78#entirely to the thought of what a small atom she was in this great
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.79#machine, which would certainly crush her with its quiet indifference.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.80#There was no illusion possible; if they sent away any one from her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.81#department she knew it would be her. No doubt, during the Rambouillet
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.82#excursion, the other young ladies had incensed Madame Aurélie against
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.83#her, for since then that lady had treated her with an air of severity in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.84#which there was a certain rancour. Besides, they could not forgive her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.85#going to Joinville, regarding it as a sign of revolt, a means of setting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.86#the whole department at defiance, by parading about with a young
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.87#lady from a rival counter. Never had Denise suffered so much in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.88#department, and she now gave up all hope of conquering it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.89#“Let them alone!” repeated Pauline, “a lot of stuck-up things, as stupid
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.90#as donkeys!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.91#But it was just these fine lady airs which intimidated Denise. Nearly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.92#all the saleswomen, by their daily contact with the rich customers,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.93#assumed certain graces, and finished by forming a vague nameless class,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.94#something between a work-girl and a middle-class lady. But beneath their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.95#art in dress, and the manners and phrases learnt by heart, there was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.96#often only a false superficial education, the fruits of attending cheap
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.97#theatres and music-halls, and picking up all the current stupidities of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.98#the Paris pavement.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.99#“You know the 'unkempt girl' has got a child?” said Clara one morning,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.100#on arriving in the department. And, as they seemed astonished, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.101#continued: “I saw her yesterday myself taking the child out for a walk!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.102#She's got it stowed away in the neighbourhood, somewhere.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.103#Two days after, Margueritte came up after dinner with another piece
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.104#of news. “A nice thing, I've just seen the 'unkempt girl's' lover--a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.105#workman, just fancy! Yes, a dirty little workman, with yellow hair, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.106#was watching her through the windows.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.107#From that moment it was an accepted truth: Denise had a workman for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.108#a lover, and an infant concealed somewhere in the neighbourhood. They
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.109#overwhelmed her with spiteful allusions. The first time she understood
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.110#she turned quite pale before the monstrosity of their suppositions. It
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.111#was abominable; she tried to explain, and stammered out: “But they are
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.112#my brothers!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.113#“Oh! oh! her brothers!” said Clara in a bantering tone.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.114#Madame Aurélie was obliged to interfere. “Be quiet! young ladies. You
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.115#had better go on changing those tickets. Mademoiselle Baudu is quite
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.116#free to misbehave herself out of doors, if only she worked a bit when
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.117#here.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.118#This curt defence was a condemnation. The young girl, feeling choked as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.119#if they had accused her of a crime, vainly endeavoured to explain the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.120#facts. They laughed and shrugged their shoulders, and she felt wounded
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.121#to the heart On hearing the rumour, Deloche was so indignant that he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.122#wanted to slap the faces of the young ladies in Denise's department; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.123#was only restrained by the fear of compromising her. Since the evening
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.124#at Joinville, he entertained a submissive love, an almost religious
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.125#friendship for her, which he proved by his faithful doglike looks. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.126#was careful not to show his affection before the others, for they would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.127#have laughed at them; but that did not prevent his dreaming of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.128#avenging blow, if ever any one should attack her before him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.129#Denise finished by not answering the insults. It was too odious, nobody
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.130#would believe it. When any girl ventured a fresh allusion, she contented
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.131#herself with looking at her with a sad, calm air. Besides, she had other
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.132#troubles, material anxieties which took up her attention. Jean went on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.133#as bad as ever, always worrying her for money. Hardly a week passed that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.134#she did not receive some fresh story from him, four pages long; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.135#when the house postman brought her these letters, in a big, passionate
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.136#handwriting, she hastened to hide them in her pocket, for the saleswomen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.137#affected to laugh, and sung snatches of some doubtful ditties.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.138#Then after having invented a pretext to go to the other end of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.139#establishment and read the letters, she was seized with fear; poor Jean
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.140#seemed to be lost. All his fibs went down with her, she believed all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.141#his extraordinary love adventures, her complete ignorance of such things
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.142#making her exaggerate the danger. Sometimes it was a two-franc piece
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.143#to enable him to escape the jealousy of some woman; at other times five
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.144#francs, six francs, to get some poor girl out of a scrape, whose father
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.145#would otherwise kill her. So that as her salary and commission did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.146#suffice, she had conceived the idea of looking for a little work after
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.147#business hours. She spoke about it to Robineau, who had shown a certain
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.148#sympathy for her since their meeting at Vinçard's, and he had procured
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.149#her the making of some neckties at five sous a dozen. At night, between
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.150#nine and one o'clock, she could do six dozen, which made thirty sous,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.151#out of which she had to deduct four sous for a candle. But as this sum
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.152#kept Jean going she did not complain of the want of sleep, and would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.153#have thought herself very happy had not another catastrophe once more
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.154#overthrown her budget calculations. At the end of the second fortnight,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.155#when she went to the necktie-dealer, she found the door closed; the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.156#woman had failed, become bankrupt, thus carrying off her eighteen francs
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.157#six sous, a considerable sum on which she had been counting for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.158#last week. All the annoyances in the department disappeared before this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.159#disaster.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.160#“You look dull,” said Pauline, meeting her in the furniture gallery,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.161#looking very pale. “Are you in want of anything?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.162#But as Denise already owed her friend twelve francs, she tried to smile
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.163#and replied: “No, thanks. I've not slept well, that's all.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.164#It was the twentieth of July, when the panic caused by the dismissals
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.165#was at its worst. Out of the four hundred employees, Bourdoncle had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.166#already sacked fifty, and there were rumours of fresh executions. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.167#thought but little of the menaces which were flying about, entirely
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.168#taken up by the anguish of one of Jean's adventures, still more
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.169#terrifying than the others. This very day he wanted fifteen francs,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.170#which sum alone could save him from the vengeance of an outraged
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.171#husband. The previous evening she had received the first letter opening
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.172#the drama; then, one after the other, came two more; in the last, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.173#she was finishing when Pauline met her, Jean announced his death
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.174#for that evening, if she did not send the money. She was in agony.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.175#Impossible to take it out of Pépé's board, paid two days before. Every
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.176#sort of bad luck was pursuing her, for she had hoped to get her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.177#eighteen francs six sous through Robineau, who could perhaps find the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.178#necktie-dealer; but Robineau having got a fortnight's holiday, had not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.179#returned the previous night as he was expected to do.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.180#However, Pauline still questioned her in a friendly way; when they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.181#met, in an out-of-the-way department, they conversed for a few minutes,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.182#keeping a sharp look-out the while. Suddenly, Pauline made a move as if
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.183#to run off, having observed the white tie of an inspector who was coming
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.184#out of the shawl department.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.185#“Ah! it's only old Jouve!” murmured she in a relieved tone. “I can't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.186#think what makes the old man grin as he does when he sees us together.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.187#In your place I should beware, for he's too kind to you. He's an old
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.188#humbug, as spiteful as a cat, and thinks he's still got his troopers to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.189#talk to.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.190#It was quite true; Jouve was detested by all the salespeople for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.191#severity of his treatment More than half the dismissals were the result
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.192#of his reports; and with his big red nose of a rakish ex-captain, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.193#only exercised his leniency in the departments served by women.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.194#“Why should I be afraid?” asked Denise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.195#“Well!” replied Pauline, laughing, “perhaps he may exact some return.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.196#Several of the young ladies try to keep well with him.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.197#Jouve had gone away, pretending not to see them; and they heard him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.198#dropping on to a salesman in the lace department, guilty of watching a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.199#fallen horse in the Rue Neuve-Saint-Augustin.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.200#“By the way,” resumed Pauline, “weren't you looking for Monsieur
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.201#Robineau yesterday? He's come back.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.202#Denise thought she was saved. “Thanks, I'll go round the other way then,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.203#and pass through the silk department. So much the worse! They sent me
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.204#upstairs to the work-room to fetch a bodkin.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.205#And they separated. The young girl, with a busy look, as if she were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.206#running from pay-desk to pay-desk in search of something, arrived on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.207#stairs and went down into the hall. It was a quarter to ten, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.208#first lunch-bell had rung. A warm sun was playing on the windows, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.209#notwithstanding the grey linen blinds, the heat penetrated into the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.210#stagnant air. Now and then a refreshing breath arose from the floor,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.211#which the messengers were gently watering. It was a somnolence, a summer
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.212#siesta, in the midst of the empty space around the counters, like the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.213#interior of a church wrapt in sleeping shadow after the last mass.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.214#Some listless salesmen were standing about, a few rare customers were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.215#crossing the galleries and the hall, with the fatigued step of women
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.216#annoyed by the sun.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.217#Just as Denise went down, Favier was measuring a dress length of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.218#light silk, with pink spots, for Madame Boutarel, arrived in Paris the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.219#previous day from the South. Since the commencement of the month, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.220#provinces had been sending up their detachments; one saw nothing but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.221#queerly-dressed ladies with yellow shawls, green skirts, and flaring
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.222#bonnets. The shopmen, indifferent, were too indolent to laugh at them
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.223#even. Favier accompanied Madame Boutarel to the mercery department, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.224#on returning, said to Hutin:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.225#“Yesterday they were all Auvergnat women, to-day they're all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.226#Provençales. I'm sick of them.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.227#But Hutin rushed forward, it was his turn, and he had recognised “the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.228#pretty lady,” the lovely blonde whom the department thus designated,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.229#knowing nothing about her, not even her name. They all smiled at her,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.230#not a week passed without her coming to The Ladies' Paradise, always
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.231#alone. This time she had a little boy of four or five with her, and this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.232#gave rise to some comment.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.233#“She's married, then?” asked Favier, when Hutin returned from the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.234#pay-desk, where he had debited her with thirty yards of Duchess satin.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.235#“Possibly,” replied he, “although the youngster proves nothing. Perhaps
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.236#he belongs to a lady friend. What's certain is, that she must have been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.237#weeping. She's so melancholy, and her eyes are so red!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.238#À silence ensued. The two salesmen gazed vaguely into the depths of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.239#shop. Then Favier resumed in a low voice; “If she's married, perhaps her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.240#husband's given her a drubbing.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.241#“Possibly,” repeated Hutin, “unless it be a lover who has left her.” And
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.242#after a fresh silence, he added: “Any way, I don't care a hang!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.243#At this moment Denise crossed the silk department, slackening her pace
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.244#and looking around her, trying to find Robineau. She could not see him,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.245#so she went into the linen department, then passed through again. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.246#two salesmen had noticed her movements.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.247#“There's that bag of bones again,” murmured Hutin.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.248#“She's looking for Robineau,” said Favier. “I can't think what they're
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.249#up to together. Oh! nothing smutty; Robineau's too big a fool. They say
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.250#he has procured her a little work, some neckties. What a spec, eh?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.251#Hutin was meditating something spiteful. When Denise passed near he, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.252#stopped her, saying: “Is it me you're looking for?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.253#She turned very red. Since the Joinville excursion, she dared not read
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.254#her heart, full of confused sensations. She was constantly recalling his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.255#appearance with that red-haired girl, and if she still trembled before
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.256#him, it was doubtless from uneasiness. Had she ever loved him? Did she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.257#love him still? She hardly liked to stir up these things, which were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.258#painful to her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.259#“No, sir,” she replied, embarrassed.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.260#Hutin then began to laugh at her uneasy manner. “Would you like us to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.261#serve him to you? Favier, just serve this young lady with Robineau.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.262#She looked at him fixedly, with the sad calm look with which she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.263#received the wounding remarks the young ladies had made about her. Ah!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.264#he was spiteful, he attacked her as well as the others! And she felt a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.265#sort of supreme anguish, the breaking of a last tie. Her face expressed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.266#such real suffering, that Favier, though not of a very tender nature,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.267#came to her assistance.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.268#“Monsieur Robineau is in the stock-room,” said he. “No doubt he will
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.269#be back for lunch. You'll find him here this afternoon, if you want to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.270#speak to him.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.271#Denise thanked him, and went up to her department, where Madamé Aurélie
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.272#was waiting for her in a terrible rage. What! she had been gone half an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.273#hour! Where had she just sprung from? Not from the work-room, that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.274#was quite certain! The poor girl hung down her head, thinking of this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.275#avalanche of misfortunes. All would be over if Robineau did not come in.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.276#However, she resolved to go down again.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.277#In the silk department, Robineau's return had provoked quite a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.278#revolution. The salesmen had hoped that, disgusted with the annoyances
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.279#they were incessantly causing him, he would not return; and, in fact,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.280#there was a moment, when pressed by Vinçard to take over his business,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.281#he had almost decided to do so. Hutin's secret working, the mine he had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.282#been laying under the second-hand's feet for months past, was about to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.283#be sprung. During Robineau's holidays, Hutin, who had taken his place
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.284#as second-hand, had done his best to injure him in the minds of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.285#principals, and get possession of his situation by an excess of zeal; he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.286#discovered and reported all sorts of trifling irregularities, suggested
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.287#improvements, and invented new designs. In fact, every one in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.288#department, from the unpaid probationer, longing to become a salesman,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.289#up to the first salesman who coveted the situation of manager, they all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.290#had one fixed idea, and that was to dislodge the comrade above them, to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.291#ascend another rung of the ladder, swallowing him up if necessary; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.292#this struggle of appetites, this pushing the one against the other, even
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.293#contributed to the better working of the machine, provoking business
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.294#and increasing tenfold the success which was astonishing Paris. Behind
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.295#Hutin, there was Favier; then behind Favier came the others, in a long
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.296#line. One heard a loud noise as of jaw-bones working. Robineau was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.297#condemned, each one was grabbing after his bone. So that when the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.298#second-hand reappeared there was a general grumbling. The matter had to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.299#be settled, the salesmen's attitude appeared so menacing, that the head
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.300#of the department had sent Robineau to the stock-room, in order to give
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.301#the authorities time to come to a decision.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.302#“We would sooner all leave, if they keep him,” declared Hutin.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.303#This affair bothered Bouthemont, whose gaiety ill-accorded with such
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.304#an internal vexation. He was pained to see nothing but scowling faces
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.305#around him. However, he wished to be just “Come, leave him alone, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.306#doesn't hurt you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.307#But they protested energetically. “What! doesn't hurt us! An
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.308#insupportable object, always irritable, capable of walking over your
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.309#body, he's so proud!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.310#This was the great bitterness of the department Robineau, nervous as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.311#a woman, was intolerably stiff and susceptible. They related scores of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.312#stories, a poor little fellow who had fallen ill through it, and lady
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.313#customers even who had been humiliated by his nasty remarks.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.314#“Well, gentlemen, I won't take anything on myself,” said Bouthemont.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.315#“I've notified the directors, and am going to speak about it shortly.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.316#The second lunch-bell rang, the clang of which came up from the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.317#basement, distant and deadened in the close air of the shop. Hutin and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.318#Favier went down. From all the counters, the salesmen were arriving one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.319#by one, helter-skelter, hastening below to the narrow entrance to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.320#kitchen, a damp passage always lighted with gas. The throng pushed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.321#forward, without a laugh or a word, amidst an increasing noise of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.322#crockery and a strong odour of food. At the extremity of the passage
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.323#there was a sudden halt, before a wicket. Flanked with piles of plates,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.324#armed with forks and spoons, which he was plunging in the copper-pans, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.325#cook was distributing the portions. And when he stood aside, the flaring
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.326#kitchen could be seen behind his white-covered belly.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.327#“Of course!” muttered Hutin, consulting the bill of fare, written on a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.328#black-board above the wicket. “Beef and pungent sauce, or skate. Never
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.329#any roast meat in this rotten shop! Their boiled beef and fish don't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.330#do a bit of good to a fellow!” Moreover, the fish was universally
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.331#neglected, for the pan was quite full. Favier, however, took some skate.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.332#Behind him, Hutin stooped down, saying: “Beef and pungent sauce.” With
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.333#a mechanical movement, the cook picked up a piece of meat, and poured
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.334#a spoonful of sauce over it; and Hutin, suffocated by the ardent breath
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.335#from the kitchen, had hardly got his portion, before the words, “Beef,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.336#pungent sauce; beef, pungent sauce,” followed each other like a litany;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.337#whilst the cook continued to pick up the meat and pour over the sauce,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.338#with the rapid and rhythmical movement of a well-regulated clock.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.339#“But the skate's cold,” declared Favier, whose hand felt no warmth from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.340#the plate.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.341#They were all hurrying along now, with their plates held out straight,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.342#for fear of running up against one another. Ten steps further was the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.343#bar, another wicket with a shiny zinc counter, on which were ranged the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.344#shares of wine, small bottles, without corks, still damp from rinsing.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.345#And each took one of these bottles in his empty hand as he passed, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.346#then, completely laden, made for his table with a serious air, careful
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.347#not to spill anything.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.348#Hutin grumbled, “This is a fine dance, with all this crockery!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.349#Their table, Favier's and his, was at the end of the corridor in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.350#last dining-room. The rooms were all alike, old cellars twelve feet by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.351#fifteen, which had been cemented over and fitted up as refectories; but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.352#the damp came through the paint-work, the yellow walls were covered with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.353#greenish spots; and, from the narrow air-holes, opening on the street,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.354#on a level with the pavement, there fell a livid light, incessantly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.355#traversed by the vague shadows of the passers-by. In July as in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.356#December, one was stifled in the warm air, laden with nauseous smells,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.357#coming from the neighbourhood of the kitchen.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.358#Hutin went in first. On the table, which was fixed at one end to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.359#wall, and covered with American cloth, there were only the glasses,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.360#knives, and forks, marking oft the places. A pile of clean plates stood
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.361#at each end; whilst in the middle was a big loaf, a knife sticking in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.362#it, with the handle in the air. Hutin got rid of his bottle and laid
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.363#down his plate; then, after having taken his napkin from the bottom of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.364#set of pigeonholes, the sole ornament on the walls, he heaved a sigh and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.365#sat down.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.366#“And I'm fearfully hungry, too!” he murmured.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.367#“It's always like that,” replied Favier, who took his place on the left.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.368#“Nothing to eat when one is starving.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.369#The table was rapidly filling. It contained twenty-two places. At
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.370#first nothing was heard but a loud clattering of knives and forks, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.371#gormandising of big fellows with stomachs emptied by thirteen hours'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.372#daily work. Formerly the employees had an hour for meals, which enabled
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.373#them to go outside to a café and take their coffee; and they would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.374#despatch their dinner in twenty minutes, anxious to get into the street
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.375#But this stirred them up too much, they came back careless, indisposed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.376#for business; and the managers had decided that they should not go out,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.377#but pay an extra three halfpence for a cup of coffee, if they wanted it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.378#So that now they were in no hurry, but prolonged the meal, not at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.379#all anxious to go back to work before time. A great many read some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.380#newspaper, between mouthfuls, the journal folded and placed against
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.381#their bottle. Others, their first hunger satisfied, talked noisily,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.382#always returning to the eternal grievance of the bad food, the money
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.383#they had earned, what they had done the previous Sunday, and what they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.384#were going to do on the next one.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.385#“I say, what about your Robineau?” asked a salesman of Hutin.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.386#The struggle between the salesmen of the silk department and their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.387#second-hand occupied all the counters. The question was discussed every
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.388#evening at the Café Saint-Roch until midnight. Hutin, who was busy with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.389#his piece of beef, contented himself with replying:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.390#“Well! he's come back, Robineau has.” Then, suddenly getting angry,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.391#he resumed: “But confound it! they've given me a bit of a donkey, I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.392#believe! It's becoming disgusting, my word of honour!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.393#“You needn't grumble!” said Favier. “I was flat enough to ask for skate.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.394#It's putrid.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.395#They were all speaking at once, some complaining, some joking. At a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.396#corner of the table, against the wall, Deloche was silently eating. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.397#was afflicted with an enormous appetite, which he had never been able
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.398#to satisfy, and not earning enough to afford any extras, he cut himself
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.399#enormous chunks of bread, and swallowed up the least savoury platefuls,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.400#with an air of greediness. They all laughed at him, crying: “Favier,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.401#pass your skate to Deloche. He likes it like that. And your meat, Hutin;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.402#Deloche wants it for his dessert.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.403#The poor fellow shrugged his shoulders, and did not even reply. It
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.404#wasn't his fault if he was dying of hunger. Besides, the others might
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.405#abuse the food as much as they liked, they swallowed it up all the same.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.406#But a low whistling stopped their talk; Mouret and Bour-doncle were in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.407#the corridor. For some time the complaints had become so frequent that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.408#the principals pretended to come and judge for themselves the quality
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.409#of the food. They gave thirty sous a head per day to the chief cook,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.410#who had to pay everything, provisions, coal, gas, and staff, and they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.411#displayed a naïve astonishment when the food was not good. This very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.412#morning even, each department had deputed a spokesman. Mignot and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.413#Liénard had undertaken to speak for their comrades. And in the sudden
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.414#silence, all ears were stretched out to catch the conversation going
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.415#on in the next room, where Mouret and Bourdoncle had just entered. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.416#latter declared the beef excellent; and Mignot, astounded by this quiet
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.417#affirmation, was repeating, “But chew it, and see;” whilst Liénard,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.418#attacking the skate, was gently saying, “But it stinks, sir!” Mouret
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.419#then launched into a cordial speech: he would do everything for his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.420#employees' welfare, he was their father, and would rather eat dry bread
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.421#than see them badly fed.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.422#“I promise you to look into the matter,” said he in conclusion, raising
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.423#his voice so that they should hear it from one end of the passage to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.424#other.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.425#The inquiry being finished, the noise of the knives and forks commenced
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.426#once more. Hutin muttered “Yes, reckon on that, and drink water! Ah,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.427#they're not stingy of soft words. Want some promises, there you are! And
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.428#they continue to feed you on old boot-leather, and to chuck you out like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.429#dogs!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.430#The salesman who had already questioned him repeated: “You say that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.431#Robineau----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.432#But a noise of heavy crockery-ware drowned his voice. The men changed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.433#their plates themselves, and the piles at both ends were diminishing.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.434#When a kitchen-help brought in some large tin dishes, Hutin cried out:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.435#“Baked rice! this is a finisher!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.436#“Good for a penn'orth of gum!” said Favier, serving himself.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.437#Some liked it, others thought it too sticky. There were some who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.438#remained quite silent, plunged in the fiction of their newspaper,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.439#not even knowing what they were eating. They were all mopping their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.440#foreheads, the narrow cellar-like apartment was full of a ruddy steam,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.441#whilst the shadows of the passers-by were continually passing in black
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.442#bands over the untidy cloth.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.443#“Pass Deloche the bread,” cried out one of the wags.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.444#Each one cut a piece, and then dug the knife into the loaf up to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.445#handle; and the bread still went round.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.446#“Who'll take my rice for a dessert?” asked Hutin.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.447#When he had concluded his bargain with a short, thin young fellow, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.448#attempted to sell his wine also; but no one would take it, it was known
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.449#to be detestable.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.450#“As I was telling you, Robineau is back,” he continued, amid the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.451#cross-fire of laughter and conversation that was going on. “Oh!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.452#his affair is a grave one. Just fancy, he has been debauching the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.453#saleswomen! Yes, and he gets them cravats to make!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.454#“Silence!” exclaimed Favier. “They're just judging him.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.455#And he pointed to Bouthemont, who was walking in the passage between
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.456#Mouret and Bourdoncle, all three absorbed in an animated conversation,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.457#carried on in a low tone. The diningroom of the managers and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.458#second-hands happened to be just opposite. Therefore, when Bouthemont
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.459#saw Mouret pass he got up, having finished, and related the affair,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.460#explaining the awkward position he was in. The other two listened, still
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.461#refusing to sacrifice Robineau, a first-class salesman, who dated from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.462#Madame Hedouin's time. But when he came to the story of the neckties,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.463#Bourdoncle got angry. Was this fellow mad to interfere with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.464#saleswomen and procure them extra work? The house paid dear enough for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.465#the women's time; if they worked on their own account at night they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.466#worked less during the day in the shop, that was certain; therefore it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.467#was a robbery, they were risking their health which did not belong to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.468#them. No, the night was made for sleep; they must all sleep, or they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.469#would be sent to the right-about!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.470#“Getting rather warm!” remarked Hutin.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.471#Every time the three men passed the dining-room, the shopmen watched
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.472#them, commenting on the slightest gestures. They had forgotten the baked
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.473#rice, in which a cashier had just found a brace-button.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.474#“I heard the word 'cravat,'” said Favier. “And you saw how Bourdoncle's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.475#face turned pale at once.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.476#Mouret shared his partner's indignation. That a saleswoman should be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.477#reduced to work at night, seemed to him an attack on the organisation
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.478#of The Ladies' Paradise. Who was the stupid that couldn't earn enough
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.479#in the business? But when Bouthemont named Denise he softened down,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.480#and invented excuses. Ah I yes, that poor little girl; she wasn't very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.481#sharp, and was greatly burdened, it was said. Bourdoncle interrupted him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.482#to declare they ought to send her off immediately. They would never
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.483#do anything with such an ugly creature, he had always said so; and he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.484#seemed to be indulging a spiteful feeling. Mouret, perplexed, affected
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.485#to laugh. Dear me! what a severe man! couldn't they forgive her for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.486#once? They could call in the culprit and give her a scolding. In short,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.487#Robineau was the most to blame, for he ought to have dissuaded her, he,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.488#an old hand, knowing the ways of the house.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.489#“Well! there's the governor laughing now!” resumed Favier, astonished,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.490#as the group again passed the door.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.491#“Ah, by Jove!” exclaimed Hutin, “if they persist in shoving Robineau on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.492#our shoulders, we'll make it lively for them!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.493#Bourdoncle looked straight at Mouret. Then he simply assumed a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.494#disdainful expression, to intimate that he saw how it was, and thought
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.495#it idiotic. Bouthemont resumed his complaints; the salesmen threatened
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.496#to leave, and there were some very good men amongst them. But what
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.497#appeared to touch these gentlemen especially, was the rumour of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.498#Robineau's friendly relations with Gaujean; the latter, it was said, was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.499#urging the former to set up for himself in the neighbourhood, offering
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.500#him any amount of credit, to run in opposition to The Ladies' Paradise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.501#There was a pause. Ah! Robineau was thinking of showing fight, was he!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.502#Mouret had become serious; he affected a certain scorn, avoided coming
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.503#to a decision, treating it as a matter of no importance. They would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.504#see, they would speak to him. And he immediately commenced to joke with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.505#Bouthemont, whose father, arrived two days before from his little shop
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.506#at Montpellier, had been nearly choked with rage and indignation on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.507#seeing the immense hall in which his son reigned. They were still
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.508#laughing about the old man, who, recovering his Southern assurance,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.509#had immediately commenced to run everything down, pretending that the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.510#drapery business would soon go to the dogs.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.511#“Here's Robineau,” said Bouthemont. “I sent him to the stock-room to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.512#avoid any unpleasant occurrence. Excuse me if I insist, but things are
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.513#in such an unpleasant state that something must be done.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.514#Robineau, who had just come in, passed by the group with a bow, on his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.515#way to the table. Mouret simply repeated: “All right, we'll see about
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.516#it.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.517#And they separated. Hutin and Favier were still waiting for them, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.518#on seeing they did not return, relieved their feelings. Was the governor
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.519#coming down like this to every meal, to count the mouthfuls? A nice
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.520#thing, if they could not even eat in peace! The truth was, they had just
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.521#seen Robineau come in, and the governor's good-humour made them anxious
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.522#for the result of the struggle they were engaged in. They lowered their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.523#voices, trying to find fresh subjects for grumbling.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.524#“But I'm dying of hunger!” continued Hutin, aloud. “One is hungrier than
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.525#ever on getting up from table!” And yet he had eaten two portions of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.526#dessert, his own and the one he had exchanged for his plate of rice. All
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.527#at once he cried out: “Hang it, I'm going in for an extra! Victor, give
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.528#me another dessert!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.529#The waiter was finishing serving the dessert. He then brought in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.530#coffee, and those who took it gave him their three sous there and then.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.531#A few fellows had gone away, dawdling along the corridor, looking for a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.532#dark corner in which they could smoke a cigarette. The others remained
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.533#at table before the heaps of greasy plates and dishes, rolling up the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.534#bread-crumbs into little bullets, going over the same old stories, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.535#the odour of broken food, and the sweltering heat that was reddening
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.536#their ears. The walls reeked with moisture, a slow asphyxia fell from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.537#the mouldy ceiling. Standing against the wall was Deloche, stuffed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.538#with bread, digesting in silence, his eyes on the air-hole; his daily
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.539#recreation, after lunch, was to watch the feet of the passers-by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.540#spinning along the street, a continual procession of living feet, big
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.541#boots, elegant boots, and ladies' tiny boots, without head or body. On
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.542#rainy days it was very dirty.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.543#“What! Already?” exclaimed Hutin.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.544#A bell rang at the end of the passage, they had to make way for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.545#third lunch. The waiters came in with pails of warm water and big
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.546#sponges to clean the American cloth. Gradually the rooms became empty,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.547#the salesmen returned to their departments, lingering on the stairs. In
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.548#the kitchen, the head cook had resumed his place at the wicket, between
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.549#the pans of skate, beef, and sauce, armed with his forks and spoons,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.550#ready to fill the plates anew with the rhythmical movement of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.551#well-regulated clock. As Hutin and Favier slowly withdrew, they saw
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.552#Denise coming down.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.553#“Monsieur Robineau is back, mademoiselle,” said the former with sneering
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.554#politeness.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.555#“He is still at table,” added the other. “But if it's anything important
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.556#you can go in.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.557#Denise continued on her way without replying or turning round; but when
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.558#she passed the dining-room of the managers and second-hands, she could
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.559#not help just looking in, and saw that Robineau was really there. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.560#resolved to try and speak to him in the afternoon, and continued her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.561#journey along the corridor to her dining-room, which was at the other
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.562#end.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.563#The women took their meals apart, in two special rooms. Denise entered
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.564#the first one. It was also an old cellar, transformed into a refectory;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.565#but it had been fitted up with more comfort. On the oval table, in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.566#middle of the apartment, the fifteen places were further apart and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.567#wine was in decanters, a dish of skate and a dish of beef with pungent
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.568#sauce occupied the two ends of the table. Waiters in white aprons
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.569#attended to the young ladies, and spared them the trouble of fetching
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.570#their portions from the wicket The management had thought that more
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.571#decent.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.572#“You went round, then?” asked Pauline, already seated and cutting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.573#herself some bread.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.574#“Yes,” replied Denise, blushing, “I was accompanying a customer.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.575#But this was a falsehood. Clara nudged her neighbour. What was the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.576#matter with the “unkempt girl?” She was quite strange in her ways. One
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.577#after the other she had received letters from her lover; then, she went
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.578#running all over the shop like a madwoman, pretending to be going to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.579#work-room, where she did not even make an appearance. There was something
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.580#up, that was certain. Then Clara, eating her skate without disgust,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.581#with the indifference of a girl who had been used to nothing better than
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.582#rancid bacon, spoke of a frightful drama, the account of which filled
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.583#the newspapers.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.584#“You've heard about that man cutting his mistress's throat with a razor,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.585#haven't you?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.586#“Well!” said a little quiet delicate-looking girl belonging to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.587#under-linen department, “he found her with another fellow. Serve her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.588#right!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.589#But Pauline protested. What! just because one had ceased to love a man,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.590#he should be allowed to cut your throat? Ah! no, never! And stopping all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.591#at once, she turned round to the waiter, saying: “Pierre, I can't get
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.592#through this beef. Just tell them to do me an extra, an omelet, nice and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.593#soft, if possible.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.594#To pass away the time, she took out some chocolate which she began
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.595#eating with her bread, for she always had her pockets full of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.596#sweetmeats.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.597#“Certainly it isn't very amusing with such a fellow,” resumed Clara.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.598#“And some people are fearfully jealous, you know! Only the other day
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.599#there was a workman who pitched his wife into a well.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.600#She kept her eyes on Denise, thinking she had guessed her trouble on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.601#seeing her turn pale. Evidently this little prude was afraid of being
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.602#beaten by her lover, whom she no doubt deceived. It would be a lark if
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.603#he came right into the shop after her, as she seemed to fear he would.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.604#But the conversation took another turn, one of the girls was giving a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.605#recipe for cleaning velvet. They then went on to speak of a piece at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.606#the Gaiety, in which some darling little children danced better than
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.607#any grown-up persons. Pauline, saddened for a moment at the sight of her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.608#omelet, which was overdone, resumed her gaiety on finding it went down
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.609#fairly well.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.610#“Pass the wine,” said she to Denise. “You should go in for an omelet.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.611#“Oh! the beef is enough for me,” replied the young girl, who, to avoid
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.612#expense, confined herself to the food provided by the house, no matter
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.613#how repugnant it might be.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.614#When the waiter brought in the baked rice, the young ladies protested.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.615#They had refused it the previous week, and hoped it would not appear
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.616#again. Denise, inattentive, worrying about Jean after Clara's stories,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.617#was the only one to eat it; all the others looked at her with an air
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.618#of disgust. There was a great demand for extras, they gorged themselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.619#with jam. This was a sort of elegance, they felt obliged to feed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.620#themselves with their own money.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.621#“You know the gentlemen have complained,” said the little delicate girl
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.622#from the under-linen department, “and the management has promised----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.623#They interrupted her with a burst of laughter, and commenced to talk
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.624#about the management. All the girls took coffee but Denise, who couldn't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.625#bear it, she said. And they lingered there before their cups, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.626#young ladies from the under-linen department in woollen dresses, with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.627#middle-class simplicity, the young ladies from the dress department
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.628#in silk, their napkins tucked under their chins, in order not to stain
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.629#their dresses, like ladies who might have come down to the servants'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.630#hall to dine with their chamber-maids. They had opened the glazed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.631#sash of the airhole to change the stifling poisoned air; but they were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.632#obliged to close it at once, the cab-wheels seemed to be passing over
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.633#the table.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.634#“Hush!” exclaimed Pauline; “here's that old beast!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.635#It was Jouve, the inspector, who was rather fond of prowling about at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.636#meal times, when the young ladies were there. He was supposed, in fact,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.637#to look after their dining-rooms. With a smiling face he would come in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.638#and walk round the tables; sometimes he would even indulge in a little
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.639#gossip, and inquire if they had made a good lunch. But as he annoyed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.640#them and made them feel uncomfortable, they all hastened to get away.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.641#Although the bell had not rung, Clara was the first to disappear; the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.642#others followed her, so that soon only Denise and Pauline remained.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.643#The latter, after having drunk her coffee, was finishing her chocolate
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.644#drops. All at once she got up, saying: “I'm going to send the messenger
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.645#for some oranges. Are you coming?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.646#“Presently,” replied Denise, who was nibbling at a crust, determined to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.647#wait till the last, so as to be able to see Robineau on going upstairs.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.648#However, when she found herself alone with Jouve she felt uneasy, so she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.649#quitted the table; but as she was going towards the door he stopped her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.650#saying: “Mademoiselle Baudu----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.651#Standing before her, he smiled with a paternal air. His thick grey
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.652#moustache and short cropped hair gave him a respectable military
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.653#appearance; and he threw out his chest, on which was displayed the red
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.654#ribbon of his decoration.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.655#“What is it, Monsieur Jouve?” asked she, feeling reassured. “I caught
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.656#you again this morning talking upstairs behind the carpet department You
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.657#know it is not allowed, and if I reported you---- She must be very fond
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.658#of you, your friend Pauline.” His moustache quivered, a flame lighted up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.659#his enormous nose. “What makes you so fond of each other, eh?” Denise,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.660#without understanding, was again becoming seized with an uneasy feeling.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.661#He was getting too close, and was speaking right in her face.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.662#“It's true we were talking, Monsieur Jouve,” she stammered, “but there's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.663#no harm in talking a bit. You are very good to me, and I'm very much
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.664#obliged to you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.665#“I ought not to be good,” said he. “Justice, and nothing more, is my
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.666#motto. But when it's a pretty girl----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.667#And he came closer still, and she felt really afraid. Pauline's words
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.668#came back to her memory; she now remembered the stories going about,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.669#stories of girls terrified by old Jouve into buying his good-will. In
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.670#the shop, as a rule, he confined himself to little familiarities, such
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.671#as pinching the cheeks of the complaisant young ladies with his fat
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.672#fingers, taking their hands in his and keeping them there as if he had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.673#forgotten them. This was very paternal, and he only gave way to his real
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.674#nature outdoors, when they consented to accept a little refreshment at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.675#his place in the Rue des Moineaux.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.676#“Leave me alone,” murmured the young girl, drawing back. “Come,” said
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.677#he, “you are not going to play the savage with me, who always treats
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.678#you well. Be amiable, come and take a cup of tea and a slice of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.679#bread-and-butter with me this evening. You are very welcome.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.680#She was struggling now. “No! no!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.681#The dining room was empty, the waiter had not come back. Jouve,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.682#listening for the sound of any footsteps, cast a rapid glance around
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.683#him; and, very excited, losing control over himself, going beyond his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.684#fatherly familiarities, he tried to kiss her on the neck.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.685#“What a spiteful, stupid little girl. When one has a head of hair like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.686#yours one should not be so stupid. Come round this evening, just for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.687#fun.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.688#But she was very excited, shocked, and terrified at the approach of this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.689#burning face, of which she could feel the breath. Suddenly she pushed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.690#him, so roughly that he staggered and nearly fell on to the table.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.691#Fortunately, a chair saved him; but in the shock, some wine left in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.692#glass spurted on to his white necktie, and soaked his decoration. And
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.693#he stood there, without wiping himself, choked with anger at such
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.694#brutality. What! when he was expecting nothing, when he was not exerting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.695#his strength, and was yielding simply to his kindness of heart!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.696#[Illustration: 0297]
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.697#“Ah, you will be sorry for this, on my word of honour!” Denise ran away.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.698#Just at that moment the bell rang; but troubled, still shuddering, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.699#forgot Robineau, and went straight to her counter, not daring to go
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.700#down again. As the sun fell on the frontage of the Place Gaillon of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.701#an afternoon, they were all stifling in the first floor rooms,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.702#notwithstanding the grey linen blinds. A few customers came, put the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.703#young ladies into a very uncomfortable, warm state, and went away
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.704#without buying anything. Every one was yawning even under Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.705#Aurélie's big sleepy eyes. Towards three o'clock, Denise, seeing the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.706#first-hand falling off to sleep, quietly slipped off, and resumed her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.707#journey across the shop, with a busy air. To put the curious ones, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.708#might be watching her, off the scent, she did not go straight to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.709#silk department; pretending to want something in the lace department,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.710#she went up to Deloche, and asked him a question; then, on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.711#ground-floor, she passed through the printed cottons department, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.712#was just going into the cravat one, when she stopped short, startled and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.713#surprised. Jean was before her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.714#“What! it's you?” she murmured, quite pale.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.715#He had on his working blouse, and was bare-headed, with his hair in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.716#disorder, the curls falling over his girlish face. Standing before a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.717#show-case of narrow black neckties, he appeared to be thinking deeply.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.718#“What are you doing here?” resumed Denise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.719#“What do you think?” replied he. “I was waiting for you. You won't let
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.720#me come. So I came in, but haven't said anything to anybody. You may
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.721#feel quite safe. Pretend not to know me, if you like.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.722#Some salesmen were already looking at them with astonishment Jean
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.723#lowered his voice. “She wanted to come with me you know. Yes, she is
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.724#close by, opposite the fountain. Give me the fifteen francs quick, or we
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.725#are done for as sure as the sun is shining on us!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.726#Denise lost her head. The lookers-on were grinning, listening to this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.727#adventure. And as there was a staircase behind the cravat department
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.728#leading to the lower floor, she pushed her brother along, and quickly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.729#led him below. Downstairs he continued his story, embarrassed, inventing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.730#his facts, fearing not to be believed.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.731#“The money is not for her. She is too respectable for that. And as for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.732#her husband, he does not care a straw for fifteen francs. Not for a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.733#million would he allow his wife. A glue manufacturer, I tell you. People
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.734#very well off indeed. No, it's for a low fellow, one of her friends,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.735#who has seen us together; and if I don't give him this money this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.736#evening----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.737#“Be quiet,” murmured Denise. “Presently, do get along.” They were now
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.738#in the parcels office. The dead season had thrown the vast floor into
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.739#a sort of torpor, in the pale light from the air-holes. It was cold as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.740#well, a silence fell from the ceiling. However, a porter was collecting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.741#from one of the compartments the few packets for the neighbourhood of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.742#the Madeleine; and, on the large sorting-table, was seated Campion, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.743#chief clerk, his legs dangling, and his eyes wandering about.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.744#Jean began again: “The husband, who has a big knife----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.745#“Get along!” repeated Denise, still pushing him forward. They followed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.746#one of the narrow corridors, where the gas was kept continually burning.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.747#To the right and the left in the dark vaults the reserve goods threw out
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.748#their shadows behind the gratings. At last she stopped opposite one of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.749#these. Nobody was likely to pass that way; but it was not allowed, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.750#she shuddered.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.751#“If this rascal says anything,” resumed Jean, “the husband, who has a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.752#big knife----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.753#“Where do you expect I can find fifteen francs?” exclaimed Denise in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.754#despair. “Can't you be more careful? You're always getting into some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.755#stupid scrape!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.756#He struck his chest. Amidst all his romantic inventions, he had almost
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.757#forgotten the exact truth. He dramatised his money wants, but there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.758#was always some immediate necessity behind this display. “By all that's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.759#sacred, it's really true this time. I was holding her like this, and she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.760#was kissing me----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.761#She stopped him again, and lost her temper, feeling on thorns,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.762#completely at a loss. “I don't want to know. Keep your wicked conduct
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.763#to yourself. It's too bad, you ought to know better! You're always
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.764#tormenting me. I'm killing myself to keep you in money. Yes, I have to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.765#stay up all night at work. Not only that, you are taking the bread out
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.766#of your little brother's mouth.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.767#Jean stood there with his mouth wide open, and all the colour left his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.768#face. What! it was not right? And he could not understand, he had always
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.769#treated his sister like a comrade, he thought it quite a natural thing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.770#to open his heart to her. But what choked him above all, was to learn
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.771#she stopped up all night. The idea that he was killing her, and taking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.772#Pépé's share as well, affected him so much that he began to cry.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.773#“You're right; I'm a scamp,” exclaimed he. “But it isn't wicked, really,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.774#far from it, and that's why one always does it! This woman, Denise, is
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.775#twenty, and thought it such fun, because I'm only seventeen. Really now!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.776#I am quite furious with myself! I could slap my face!” He had taken her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.777#hands, and was kissing them and inundating them with tears. “Give me
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.778#the fifteen francs, and this shall be the last time. I swear to you.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.779#Or rather--no!--don't give me anything. I prefer to die. If the husband
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.780#murders me it will be a good riddance for you.” And as she was crying as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.781#well, he was stricken with remorse. “I say that, but of course I'm not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.782#sure. Perhaps he doesn't want to kill any one. We'll manage. I promise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.783#you that, darling. Good-bye, I'm off.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.784#But a sound of footsteps at the end of the corridor frightened them. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.785#quickly drew him close to the grating, in a dark corner. For an instant
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.786#they heard nothing but the hissing of a gas-burner near them. Then the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.787#footsteps drew nearer; and, on stretching out her neck, she recognised
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.788#Jouve, the inspector, who had just entered the corridor, with his stiff
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.789#military walk. Was he there by chance, or had some one at the door
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.790#warned him of Jean's presence? She was seized with such a fright that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.791#she knew not what to do; and she pushed Jean out of the dark spot where
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.792#they were concealed, and drove him before her, stammering out: “Be off!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.793#Be off!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.794#Both galloped along, hearing Jouve behind them, for he also had began to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.795#run. They crossed the parcels office again, and arrived at the foot of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.796#the stairs leading out into the Rue de la Michodière.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.797#“Be off!” repeated Denise, “be off! If I can, I'll send you the fifteen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.798#francs all the same.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.799#Jean, bewildered, scampered away. The inspector, who came up panting,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.800#out of breath, could only distinguish a corner of his white blouse, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.801#his locks of fair hair flying in the wind. He stood a moment to get his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.802#breath, and resume his correct appearance. He had on a brand-new white
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.803#necktie, the large bow of which shone like a snow-flake.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.804#“Well! this is nice behaviour, mademoiselle!” said he, his lips
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.805#trembling. “Yes, it's nice, very nice! If you think I'm going to stand
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.806#this sort of thing in the basement, you're mistaken.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.807#And he pursued her with this whilst she was returning to the shop,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.808#overcome with emotion, unable to find a word of defence. She was sorry
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.809#now she had run away. Why hadn't she explained the matter, and brought
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.810#her brother forward? They would now go and imagine all sorts of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.811#villanies, and say what she might, they would not believe her. Once more
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.812#she forgot Robineau, and went straight to her counter. Jouve immediately
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.813#went to the manager's office to report the matter. But the messenger
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.814#told him Monsieur Mouret was with Monsieur Bourdoncle and Monsieur
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.815#Robineau; they had been talking together for the last quarter of an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.816#hour. In fact, the door was halfopen, and he could hear Mouret gaily
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.817#asking Robineau if he had had a pleasant holiday; there was not the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.818#least question of a dismissal--on the contrary, the conversation fell on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.819#certain things to be done in the department.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.820#“Do you want anything, Monsieur Jouve?” exclaimed Mouret “Come in.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.821#But a sudden instinct warned the inspector. As Bourdoncle had come out,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.822#he preferred to relate the affair to him. They slowly passed through the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.823#shawl department, walking side by side, the one leaning over and talking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.824#in a low tone, the other listening, not a sign on his severe face
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.825#betraying his impressions. “All right,” said the latter at last.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.826#And as they had arrived close to the dress department, he went in. Just
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.827#at that moment Madame Aurélie was scolding Denise. Where had she come
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.828#from, again? This time she couldn't say she had been to the work-room.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.829#Really, these continual absences could not be tolerated any longer.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.830#“Madame Aurélie!” cried Bourdoncle.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.831#He had decided on a bold stroke, not wishing to consult Mouret, for fear
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.832#of some weakness. The first-hand came up, and the story was once more
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.833#related in a low voice. They were all waiting in the expectation of some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.834#catastrophe. At last, Madame Aurélie turned round with a solemn air.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.835#“Mademoiselle Baudu!” And her puffy emperor's mask assumed the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.836#immobility of the all-powerful: “Go and be paid!” The terrible phrase
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.837#sounded very loud in the empty department. Denise stood there pale as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.838#a ghost, without saying a word. At last she was able to ask in broken
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.839#sentences:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.840#“Me! me! What for? What have I done?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.841#Bourdoncle replied, harshly, that she knew very well, that she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.842#better not provoke any explanation; and he spoke of the cravats, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.843#said that it would be a fine thing if all the young ladies received men
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.844#down in the basement.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.845#“But it was my brother!” cried she with the grievous anger of an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.846#outraged virgin.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.847#Marguerite and Clara commenced to laugh. Madame Frédéric, usually so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.848#discreet, shook her head with an incredulous air. Always her brother!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.849#Really it was very stupid! Denise looked round at all of them:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.850#Bourdoncle, who had taken a dislike to her the first day; Jouve, who had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.851#stopped to serve as a witness, and from whom she expected no justice;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.852#then these girls whom she had not been able to soften by nine months of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.853#smiling courage, who were happy, in fact, to turn her out of doors. What
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.854#was the good of struggling? what was the use of trying to impose herself
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.855#on them when no one liked her? And she went away without a word,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.856#not even casting a last look towards this room where she had so long
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.857#struggled. But as soon as she was alone, before the hall staircase, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.858#deeper sense of suffering filled her grieved heart. No one liked her,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.859#and the sudden thought of Mouret had just deprived her of all idea of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.860#resignation. No! no! she could not accept such a dismissal. Perhaps he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.861#would believe this villanous story, this rendezvous with a man down in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.862#the cellars. At the thought, a feeling of shame tortured her, an anguish
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.863#with which she had never before been afflicted. She wanted to go and see
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.864#him, to explain the matter to him, simply to let him know the truth;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.865#for she was quite ready to go away as soon as he knew this. And her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.866#old fear, the shiver which chilled her when in his presence, suddenly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.867#developed into an ardent desire to see him, not to leave the house
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.868#without telling him she had never belonged to another.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.869#It was nearly five o'clock, and the shop was waking up into life again
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.870#in the cool evening air. She quickly started off for Mouret's office.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.871#But when she arrived at the door, a hopeless melancholy feeling again
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.872#took possession of her. Her tongue refused its office, the intolerable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.873#burden of existence again fell on her shoulders. He would not believe
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.874#her, he would laugh like the others, she thought; and this idea made her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.875#almost faint away. All was over, she would be better alone, out of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.876#way, dead! And, without informing Pauline or Deloche, she went at once
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.877#and took her money.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.878#“You have, mademoiselle,” said the clerk, “twenty-two days; that makes
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.879#eighteen francs and fourteen sous; to which must be added seven francs
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.880#for commission. That's right, isn't it?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.881#“Yes, sir. Thanks.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.882#And Denise was going away with her money, when she at last met Robineau.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.883#He had already heard of her dismissal, and promised to find the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.884#necktie-dealer. In a lower tone he tried to console her, but lost his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.885#temper: what an existence, to be at the continual mercy of a whim! to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.886#thrown out at an hour's notice, without even being able to claim a full
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.887#month's salary. Denise went up to inform Madame Cabin, saying that she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.888#would try and send for her box during the evening. It was just striking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.889#five when she found herself on the pavement of the Place Gaillon,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.890#bewildered, in the midst of the crowd of people and cabs.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.891#The same evening when Robineau got home he received a letter from the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.892#management informing him, in a few lines, that for certain reasons
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.893#relating to the internal arrangements they were obliged to deprive
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.894#themselves of his services. He had been in the house seven years, and it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.895#was only that afternoon that he was talking to the principals; this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.896#was a heavy blow for him. Hutin and Favier were crowing in the silk
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.897#department, as loudly as Clara and Marguerite in the dress one. A jolly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.898#good riddance! Such clean sweeps make room for the others! Deloche and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.899#Pauline were the only ones to regret Denise's departure, exchanging, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.900#the rush of business, bitter words of regret at losing her, so kind, so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.901#well behaved.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.902#“Ah,” said the young man, “if ever she succeeds anywhere else, I should
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.903#like to see her come back here, and trample on the others; a lot of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.904#good-for-nothing creatures!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.905#It was Bourdoncle who in this affair had to bear the brunt of Mouret's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.906#anger. When the latter heard of Denise's dismissal, he was exceedingly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.907#annoyed. As a rule he never interfered with the staff; but this time he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.908#affected to see an encroachment on his power, an attempt to over-ride
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.909#his authority. Was he no longer master in the place, that they dared
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.910#to give orders? Everything must pass through his hands, absolutely
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.911#everything; and he would immediately crush any one who should resist
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.912#Then, after making personal inquiries, all the while in a nervous
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.913#torment which he could not conceal, he lost his temper again. This
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.914#poor girl was not lying; it was really her brother. Campion had fully
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.915#recognised him. Why was she sent away, then? He even spoke of taking her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.916#back.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.917#However, Bourdoncle, strong in his passive resistance, bent before the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.918#storm. He watched Mouret, and one day when he saw him a little calmer,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.919#ventured to say in a meaning voice: “It's better for everybody that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.920#she's gone.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.921#Mouret stood there looking very awkward, the blood rushing to his face.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.922#“Well!” replied he, laughing, “perhaps you're right. Let's go and take
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.923#a turn down stairs. Things are looking better, we took nearly a hundred
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vi.924#thousand francs yesterday.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.1#CHAPTER VII.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.2#For a moment Denise stood bewildered on the pavement, in the sun which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.3#still shone fiercely at five o'clock. The July heat warmed the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.4#gutters, Paris was blazing with the chalky whiteness peculiar to it in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.5#summer-time, and which produced quite a blinding glare. The catastrophe
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.6#had happened so suddenly, they had turned her out so roughly, that she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.7#stood there, turning her money over in her pocket in a mechanical way,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.8#asking herself where she was to go, and what she was to do.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.9#A long line of cabs prevented her quitting the pavement near The Ladies'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.10#Paradise. When she at last risked herself amongst the wheels she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.11#crossed over the Place Gaillon, as if she intended to go into the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.12#Louis-le-Grand; then she altered her mind, and walked towards the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.13#Saint-Roch. But still she had no plan, for she stopped at the corner of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.14#the Rue Neuve-des-Petits-Champs, and finally followed it, after looking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.15#around her with an undecided air. Arrived at the Passage Choiseul, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.16#passed through, and found herself in the Rue Monsigny, without knowing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.17#how, and ultimately came into the Rue Neuve-Saint-Augustin again. Her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.18#head was filled with a fearful buzzing sensation, she thought of her box
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.19#on seeing a commissionaire; but where was she to have it taken to, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.20#why all this trouble, when an hour ago she had a bed to go to?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.21#Then her eyes fixed on the houses, she began to examine the windows.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.22#There were any number of bills, “Apartments to Let.” She saw them
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.23#confusedly, repeatedly seized by the inward emotion which was agitating
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.24#her whole being. Was it possible? Left alone so suddenly, lost in this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.25#immense city in which she was a stranger, without support, without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.26#resources. She must eat and sleep, however. The streets succeeded one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.27#another, the Rue des Moulins, the Rue Sainte-Anne. She wandered about
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.28#the neighbourhood, frequently retracing her steps, always brought back
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.29#to the only spot she knew really well. Suddenly she was astonished,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.30#she was again standing before The Ladies' Paradise; and to escape this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.31#obsession she plunged into the Rue de la Michodière. Fortunately Baudu
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.32#was not at his door. The Old Elbeuf appeared to be dead, behind its
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.33#murky windows. She would never have dared to show herself at her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.34#uncle's, for he affected not to recognise her any more, and she did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.35#wish to become a burden to him, in the misfortune he had predicted for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.36#her. But, on the other side of the street, a yellow bill attracted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.37#her attention. “Furnished room to let.” It was the first that did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.38#frighten her, so poor did the house appear. She soon recognised it,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.39#with its two low storeys, and rusty-coloured front, crushed between The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.40#Ladies' Paradise and the old Hôtel Duvillard. On the threshold of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.41#umbrella shop, old Bourras, hairy and bearded like a prophet, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.42#with his glasses on his nose, stood studying the ivory handle of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.43#walking-stick. Hiring the whole house, he under-let the two upper floors
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.44#furnished, to lighten the rent.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.45#“You have a room, sir?” asked Denise, obeying an instinctive impulse.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.46#He raised his great bushy eyes, surprised to see her, for he knew all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.47#the young persons at The Ladies' Paradise. And, after observing her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.48#clean dress and respectable appearance, he replied: “It won't suit you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.49#“How much is it, then?” replied Denise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.50#“Fifteen francs a month.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.51#She asked to see it. On arriving in the narrow shop, and seeing that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.52#he was still eyeing her with an astonished air, she told him of her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.53#departure from the shop and of her wish not to trouble her uncle. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.54#old man then went and fetched a key hanging on a board in the back-shop,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.55#a small dark room, where he did his cooking and had his bed; beyond
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.56#that, behind a dirty window, could be seen a back-yard about six feet
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.57#square.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.58#“I'll walk in front to prevent you falling,” said Bourras, entering the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.59#damp corridor which ran along the shop.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.60#He stumbled against the lower stair, and commenced the ascent,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.61#reiterating his warnings to be careful. Look out! the rail was close
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.62#against the wall, there was a hole at the corner, sometimes the lodgers
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.63#left their dust-boxes there. Denise, in complete obscurity, could
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.64#distinguish nothing, only feeling the chilliness of the old damp
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.65#plaster. On the first floor, however, a small window looking into the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.66#yard enabled her to see vaguely, as at the bottom of a piece of sleeping
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.67#water, the rotten staircase, the walls black with dirt, the cracked and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.68#discoloured doors.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.69#“If only only these rooms were vacant,” resumed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.70#Bourras. “You would be very comfortable there. But they are always
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.71#occupied by ladies.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.72#On the second floor the light increased, showing up with a raw paleness
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.73#the distress of the house. A journeyman-baker occupied the first room,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.74#and it was the other, the further one, that was vacant. When Bourras
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.75#had opened the door he was obliged to stay on the landing in order that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.76#Denise might enter with ease. The bed placed in the corner nearest the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.77#door, left just room enough for one person to pass. At the other end
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.78#there was a small walnut-wood chest of drawers, a deal table stained
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.79#black, and two chairs. The lodgers who did any cooking were obliged to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.80#kneel before the fire-place, where there was an earthenware stove.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.81#“You know,” said the old man, “it is not luxurious, but the view from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.82#the window is gay. You can see the people passing in the street.” And,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.83#as Denise was looking with surprise at the ceiling just above the bed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.84#where a chance lady-lodger had written her name--Ernestine--by drawing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.85#the flame of the candle over it, he added with a good-natured smile; “If
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.86#I did a lot of repairs, I should never make both ends meet. There you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.87#are; it's all I have to offer.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.88#“I shall be very well here,” declared the young girl.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.89#She paid a month in advance, asked for the linen--a pair of sheets and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.90#two towels, and made her bed without delay, happy, relieved to know
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.91#where she was going to sleep that night. An hour after she had sent a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.92#commissionaire to fetch her box, and was quite at home.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.93#During the first two months she had a terribly hard time of it. Being
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.94#unable to pay for Pépé's board, she had taken him away, and slept him on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.95#an old sofa lent by Bourras. She could not do with less than thirty
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.96#sous a day, including the rent, even by consenting to live on dry bread
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.97#herself, in order to procure a bit of meat for the little one.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.98#During the first fortnight she got on pretty well, having begun her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.99#housekeeping with about ten francs; besides she had been fortunate
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.100#enough to find the cravat-dealer, who paid her her eighteen francs six
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.101#sous. But after that she became completely destitute. It was in vain she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.102#applied to the various shops, at La Place Clichy, the Bon Marché, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.103#Louvre: the dead season had stopped business everywhere, they told
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.104#her to apply again in the autumn, more than five thousand employees,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.105#dismissed like her, were wandering about Paris in want of places. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.106#then tried to obtain a little work elsewhere; but in her ignorance of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.107#Paris she did not know where to apply, often accepting most ungrateful
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.108#tasks, and sometimes even not getting her money. Certain evenings she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.109#gave Pépé his dinner alone, a plate of soup, telling him she had dined
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.110#out; and she would go to bed, her head in a whirl, nourished by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.111#fever which was burning her hands. When Jean dropped suddenly into
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.112#the midst of this poverty, he called himself a scoundrel with such
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.113#a despairing violence that she was obliged to tell some falsehood to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.114#reassure him; and often found means of slipping a two-franc piece into
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.115#his hand, to prove that she still had money. She never wept before the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.116#children. On Sundays, when she would cook a piece of veal in the stove,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.117#on her knees before the fire, the narrow room re-echoed with the gaiety
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.118#of children, careless about existence. Then, when Jean had returned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.119#to his master's and Pépé was sleeping, she spent a frightful night, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.120#anguish about the coming day.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.121#Other fears kept her awake. The two ladies on the first floor received
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.122#visitors up to a late hour; and sometimes a visitor mistook the floor
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.123#and came banging at Denise's door. Bourras having quietly told her not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.124#to answer, she buried her face under her pillow to escape hearing their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.125#oaths. Then, her neighbour, the baker, had shown a disposition to annoy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.126#her: he never came home till the morning, and would lay in wait for her,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.127#as she went to fetch her water; he even made holes in the wall, to watch
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.128#her washing herself, so that she was obliged to hang her clothes against
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.129#the wall. But she suffered still more from the annoyances of the street,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.130#the continual persecution of the passers-by. She could not go downstairs
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.131#to buy a candle, in these streets swarming with the debauchees of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.132#old quarters, without feeling a warm breath behind her, and hearing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.133#crude, insulting remarks; and the men pursued her to the very end of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.134#dark passage, encouraged by the sordid appearance of the house. Why had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.135#she no lover? It astonished people, and seemed ridiculous. She would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.136#certainly have to yield one day. She herself could not have explained
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.137#why she resisted, menaced as she was by hunger, and perturbed by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.138#desires with which the air around her was warm.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.139#One evening Denise had not even any bread for Pépé's soup, when a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.140#gentleman, wearing a decoration, commenced to follow her. On arriving
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.141#opposite the passage he became brutal, and it was with a disgusted,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.142#shocked feeling that she banged the door in his face. Then, upstairs,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.143#she sat down, her hands trembling. The little one was sleeping. What
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.144#should she say if he woke up and asked for bread? And yet she had only
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.145#to consent and her misery would be over, she could have money, dresses,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.146#and a fine room. It was very simple, every one came to that, it was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.147#said; for a woman alone in Paris could not live by her labour. But her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.148#whole being rose up in protestation, without indignation against the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.149#others, simply averse to the disgrace of the thing. She considered life
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.150#a matter of logic, good conduct, and courage.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.151#Denise frequently questioned herself in this way. An old love story
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.152#floated in her memory, the sailor's betrothed whom her love guarded
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.153#from all perils. At Valognes she had often hummed over this sentimental
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.154#ballad, gazing on the deserted street. Had she also a tender affection
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.155#in her heart that she was so brave? She still thought of Hutin, full of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.156#uneasiness. Morning and evening she saw him pass under her window. Now
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.157#that he was second-hand he walked by himself, amid the respect of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.158#simple salesmen. He never raised his head, she thought she suffered from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.159#his vanity, and watched him pass without any fear of being discovered.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.160#And as soon as she saw Mouret, who also passed every day, she began to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.161#tremble, and, quickly concealed herself, her bosom heaving. He had no
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.162#need to know where she was lodging. Then she felt ashamed of the house,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.163#and suffered at the idea of what he thought of her, although perhaps
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.164#they would never meet again.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.165#Denise still lived amidst the agitation caused by The Ladies' Paradise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.166#A simple wall separated her room from her old department; and, from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.167#early morning, she went over her day's work, feeling the arrival of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.168#crowd, the increased bustle of business. The slightest noise shook the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.169#old house hanging on the flank of the colossus; she felt the gigantic
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.170#pulse beating. Besides, she could not avoid certain meetings. Twice
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.171#she had found herself face to face with Pauline, who had offered her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.172#services, grieved to see her so unfortunate; and she had even been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.173#obliged to tell a falsehood to avoid receiving her friend or paying
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.174#her a visit, one Sunday, at Baugé's. But it was more difficult still to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.175#defend herself against Deloche's desperate affection; he watched her,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.176#aware of all her troubles, waited for her in the doorways. One day he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.177#wanted to lend her thirty francs, a brother's savings, he said, with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.178#a blush. And these meetings made her regret the shop, continually
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.179#occupying her with the life they led inside, as if she had not quitted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.180#it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.181#No one ever called upon Denise. One afternoon she was surprised by a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.182#knock. It was Colomban. She received him standing. He, looking very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.183#awkward, stammered at first, asked how she was getting on, and spoke of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.184#The Old Elbeuf.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.185#Perhaps it was Uncle Baudu who had sent him, regretting his rigour;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.186#for he continued to pass his niece without taking any notice of her,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.187#although quite aware of her miserable position. But when she plainly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.188#questioned her visitor, he appeared more embarrassed than ever. No,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.189#no, it was not the governor who had sent him; and he finished by naming
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.190#Clara--he simply wanted to talk about Clara. Little by little he became
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.191#bolder, and asked Denise's advice, supposing that she could be useful
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.192#to him with her old friend. It was in vain that she tried to dishearten
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.193#him, by reproaching him with the pain he was causing Geneviève, all for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.194#this heartless girl. He came up another day, and got into the habit of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.195#coming to see her. This sufficed for his timid passion; he continually
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.196#commenced the same conversation, unable to resist, trembling with joy to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.197#be with a girl who had approached Clara. And this caused Denise to live
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.198#more than ever at The Ladies' Paradise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.199#It was towards the end of September that the young girl experienced the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.200#blackest misery. Pépé had fallen ill, having caught a severe cold. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.201#ought to have been nourished with good broth, and she had not even a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.202#piece of bread. One evening, completely conquered, she was sobbing, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.203#one of those sombre straits which drive women on to the streets, or into
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.204#the Seine, when old Bourras gently knocked at the door. He brought a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.205#loaf, and a milk-can full of broth.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.206#“There! there's something for the youngster,” said he in his abrupt way.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.207#“Don't cry like that; it annoys my lodgers.” And as she thanked him in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.208#fresh outburst of tears, he resumed: “Do keep quiet! To-morrow come and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.209#see me. I've some work for you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.210#Bourras, since the terrible blow dealt him by The Ladies' Paradise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.211#by their opening an umbrella department, had ceased to employ any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.212#workwomen. He did everything himself to save expenses--the cleaning,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.213#mending, and sewing. His trade was also diminishing, so that he was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.214#sometimes without work. And he was obliged to invent something to do the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.215#next day, when he installed Denise in a corner of his shop. He felt that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.216#he could not let any one die of hunger in his house.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.217#“You'll have two francs a day,” said he. “When you find something
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.218#better, you can leave me.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.219#She was afraid of him, and did the work so quickly that he hardly knew
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.220#what else to give her to do. He had given her some silk to stitch, some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.221#lace to repair. During the first few days she did not dare raise her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.222#head, uncomfortable to know he was close to her, with his lion-like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.223#mane, hooked nose, and piercing eyes, under his thick bushy eyebrows.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.224#His voice was harsh, his gestures extravagant, and the mothers of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.225#neighbourhood often frightened their youngsters by threatening to send
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.226#for him, as they would for a policeman. However, the boys never passed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.227#his door without calling out some insulting words, which he did not even
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.228#seem to hear. All his maniacal anger was directed against the scoundrels
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.229#who dishonoured his trade by selling cheap trashy articles, which dogs
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.230#would not consent to use.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.231#Denise trembled whenever he burst out thus: “Art is done for, I tell
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.232#you! There's not a single respectable handle made now. They make sticks,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.233#but as for handles, it's all up! Bring me a proper handle, and I'll give
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.234#you twenty francs!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.235#He had a real artist's pride; not a workman in Paris was capable of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.236#turning out a handle like his, light and strong. He carved the knobs
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.237#especially with charming ingenuity, continually inventing fresh designs,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.238#flowers, fruit, animals, and heads, subjects conceived and executed in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.239#a free and life-like style. A little pocket-knife sufficed, and he spent
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.240#whole days, spectacles on nose, chipping bits of boxwood and ebony.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.241#“A pack of ignorant beggars,” said he, “who are satisfied with sticking a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.242#certain quantity of silk on so much whalebone! They buy their handles by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.243#the gross, handles readymade. And they sell just what they like! I tell
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.244#you, art is done for!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.245#Denise began to take courage. He had insisted on having Pépé down in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.246#shop to play, for he was wonderfully fond of children. When the little
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.247#one was crawling about on all-fours, neither of them had room to move,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.248#she in her corner doing the mending, he near the window, carving with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.249#his little pocket-knife. Every day now brought on the same work and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.250#the same conversation. Whilst working, he continually pitched into The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.251#Ladies' Paradise; never tired of explaining how affairs stood. He had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.252#occupied his house since 1845, and had a thirty years' lease, at a rent
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.253#of eighteen hundred francs a year; and, as he made a thousand francs out
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.254#of his four furnished rooms, he only paid eight hundred for the shop.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.255#It was a mere trifle, he had no expenses, and could thus hold out for a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.256#long time still. To hear him, there was no doubt about his triumph;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.257#he would certainly swallow up the monster. Suddenly he would interrupt
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.258#himself.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.259#“Have they got any dog's heads like that?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.260#And he would blink his eyes behind his glasses, to judge the dog's head
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.261#he was carving, with its lip turned up and fangs out, in a life-like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.262#growl. Pépé, delighted with the dog, would get up, placing his two
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.263#little arms on the old man's knee.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.264#“As long as I make both ends meet I don't care a hang about the rest,”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.265# the latter would resume, delicately shaping the dog's tongue with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.266#point of his knife. “The scoundrels have taken away my profits; but if
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.267#I'm making nothing I'm not losing anything yet, or at least but very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.268#little. And, you see, I'm ready to sacrifice everything rather than
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.269#yield.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.270#He would brandish his knife, and his white hair would blow about in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.271#storm of anger.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.272#“But,” Denise would mildly observe, without raising her eyes from her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.273#needle, “if they made you a reasonable offer, it would be wiser to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.274#accept.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.275#Then his ferocious obstinacy would burst forth. “Never! If my head were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.276#under the knife I would say no, by heavens! I've another ten years'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.277#lease, and they shall not have the house before then, even if I should
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.278#have to die of hunger within the four bare walls. Twice already have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.279#they tried to get over me. They offered me twelve thousand francs for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.280#my good-will, and eighteen thousand francs for the last ten years of my
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.281#lease; in all thirty thousand. Not for fifty thousand even! I have them
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.282#in my power, and intend to see them licking the dust before me!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.283#“Thirty thousand francs! it's a good sum,” Denise would resume. “You
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.284#could go and establish yourself elsewhere. And suppose they were to buy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.285#the house?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.286#Bourras, putting the finishing touches to his dog's tongue, would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.287#appear absorbed for a moment, an infantine laugh pervading his venerable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.288#prophet's face. Then he would, continue: “The house, no fear! They spoke
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.289#of buying it last year, and offered eighty thousand francs, twice as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.290#much as it's worth. But the landlord, a retired fruiterer, as big a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.291#scoundrel as they, wanted to make them shell out more. But not only
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.292#that, they are suspicious about me; they know I'm not so likely to give
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.293#way. No! no! here I am, and here I intend to stay. The emperor with all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.294#his cannon could not turn me out.” Denise never dared say any more, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.295#would go on with her work, whilst the old man continued to break out in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.296#short sentences, between two cuts with his knife, muttering something to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.297#the effect that the game had hardly commenced, later on they would see
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.298#wonderful things, he had certain plans which would sweep away their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.299#umbrella counter; and, in his obstinacy, there appeared a personal
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.300#revolt of the small manufacturer against the threatening invasion of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.301#the great shops. Pépé, however, would at last climb on his knees, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.302#impatiently stretch out his hand towards the dog's head.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.303#“Give it me, sir.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.304#“Presently, my child,” the old man would reply in a voice that suddenly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.305#became tender. “He hasn't any eyes; we must make his eyes now.” And
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.306#whilst carving the eye he would continue talking to Denise. “Do you hear
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.307#them? Isn't there a roar next door? That's what exasperates me more than
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.308#anything, my word of honour! to have them always on my back with their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.309#infernal locomotive-like noise.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.310#It made his little table tremble, he asserted. The whole shop was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.311#shaken, and he would spend the entire afternoon without a customer, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.312#the trepidation of the crowd which overflowed The Ladies' Paradise. It
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.313#was from morning to night a subject for eternal grumbling. Another good
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.314#day's work, they were knocking against the wall, the silk department
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.315#must have cleared ten thousand francs; or else he made merry over a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.316#showery day which had killed the receipts. And the slightest rumours,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.317#the most unimportant noises, furnished him with subjects of endless
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.318#comment.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.319#“Ah! some one has slipped down! Ah, if they could only all fall and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.320#break their backs! That, my dear, is a dispute between some ladies. So
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.321#much the better! So much the better! Do you hear the parcels falling on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.322#to the lower floor? It's disgusting!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.323#It did not do for Denise to discuss his explanations, for he retorted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.324#bitterly by reminding her of the shameful way they had dismissed her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.325#She was obliged to relate for the hundredth time her life in the dress
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.326#department, the hardships she had endured at first, the small unhealthy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.327#bedrooms, the bad food, and the continual struggle between the salesmen;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.328#and they were thus talking about the shop from morning to night,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.329#absorbing it hourly in the very air they breathed.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.330#“Give it me, sir,” Pépé would repeat, with eager outstretched hands.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.331#The dog's head finished, Bourras would hold it at a distance, then
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.332#examine it closely with childish glee. “Take care, it will bite you!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.333#There, go and play, and don't break it, if you can help it.” Then
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.334#resuming his fixed idea, he would shake his fist at the wall. “You may
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.335#do all you can to knock the house down. You sha'n't have it, even if you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.336#invade the whole neighbourhood.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.337#Denise had now her daily bread assured her, and she was extremely
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.338#grateful to the old umbrella-dealer, whose good heart she felt beneath
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.339#his strange violent ways. She had a strong desire, however, to find some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.340#work elsewhere, for she often saw him inventing some trifle for her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.341#to do; she fully understood that he did not require a workwoman in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.342#present slack state of his business, and that he was employing her out
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.343#of pure charity. Six months had passed thus, and the dull winter season
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.344#had again returned. She was despairing of finding a situation before
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.345#March, when, one evening in January, Deloche, who was watching for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.346#her in a doorway, gave her a bit of advice. Why did she not go and see
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.347#Robineau; perhaps he might want some one?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.348#In September, Robineau had decided to buy Vinçard's silk business,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.349#trembling all the time lest he should compromise his wife's sixty
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.350#thousand francs. He had paid forty thousand for the good-will and stock,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.351#and was starting with the remaining twenty thousand. It was not much,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.352#but he had Gaujean behind him to back him up with any amount of credit.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.353#Since his disagreement with The Ladies' Paradise, the latter had been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.354#longing to stir up a system of competition against the colossus; and he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.355#thought victory certain, by creating special shops in the neighbourhood,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.356#where the public could find a large and varied choice of articles. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.357#rich Lyons manufacturers, such as Dumonteil, were the only ones who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.358#could accept the big shops' terms, satisfied to keep their looms going
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.359#with them, looking for their profits by selling to less important
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.360#houses. But Gaujean was far from having the solidity and staying power
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.361#possessed by Dumonteil. For a long time a simple commission agent, it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.362#was only during the last five or six years that he had had looms of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.363#own, and he still had a lot of work done by other makers, furnishing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.364#them with the raw material and paying them by the yard. It was precisely
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.365#this system which, increasing his manufacturing expenses, had prevented
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.366#him competing with Dumonteil for the supply of the Paris Paradise. This
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.367#had filled him with rancour; he saw in Robineau the instrument of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.368#decisive battle to be declared against these drapery bazaars which he
