urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.570#goods around them.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.571#But if honour was saved on both sides, the situation was becoming fatal
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.572#for Robineau. The Ladies' Paradise had money at its disposal and a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.573#patronage which enabled it to balance its profits; whilst he, sustained
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.574#by Gaujean alone, unable to recoup his losses on other articles,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.575#was exhausted, and slipped daily a little further on the verge of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.576#bankruptcy. He was dying from his hardihood, notwithstanding the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.577#numerous customers that the hazards of the struggle had brought him. One
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.578#of his secret torments was to see these customers slowly quitting him,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.579#returning to The Ladies' Paradise, after the money he had lost and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.580#efforts he had made to conquer them.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.581#One day he quite lost patience. A customer, Madame de Boves, had come to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.582#his shop for some mantles, for he had added a ready-made department to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.583#his business. She could not make up her mind, complaining of the quality
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.584#of the goods. At last she said: “Their Paris Paradise is a great deal
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.585#stronger.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.586#Robineau restrained himself, assuring her that she was mistaken, with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.587#tradesman's politeness, all the more respectful, because he was afraid
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.588#to allow his anger to burst forth.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.589#“But just look at the silk of this mantle!” resumed she, “one would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.590#really take it for so much cobweb. You may say what you like, sir, their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.591#silk at five francs is like leather compared with this.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.592#He did not reply, the blood rushing to his face, and his lips tightly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.593#closed. In point of fact he had ingeniously thought of buying some of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.594#his rival's silk for these mantles. So that it was Mouret, not he, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.595#lost on the material. He simply cut off the selvage.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.596#“Really you think the Paris Paradise thicker?” murmured he.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.597#“Oh! a hundred times!” said Madame de Boves. “There's no comparison.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.598#This injustice on her part, her running down the goods in this way,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.599#filled him with indignation. And, as she was still turning the mantle
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.600#over with a disgusted air, a little piece of the blue and silver
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.601#selvage, not cut off, appeared under the lining. He could not contain
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.602#himself any longer; he confessed he would even have given his head.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.603#“Well, madame, this _is_ Paris Paradise. I bought it myself! Look at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.604#border.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.605#Madame de Boves went away greatly annoyed, and a number of ladies
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.606#quitted him when the affair became known. And he, amid this ruin, when
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.607#the fear for the future seized him, only trembled for his wife, who had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.608#been brought up in a happy, peaceful home, and would never be able to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.609#endure a life of poverty. What would become of her if a catastrophe
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.610#threw them into the street, with a load of debts? It was his fault, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.611#ought never to have touched her money. She was obliged to comfort him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.612#Wasn't the money as much his as hers? He loved her dearly, and she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.613#wanted nothing more; she gave him everything, her heart and her life.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.614#They could be heard in the back shop embracing one another. Little by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.615#little, the affairs and ways of the house became more regular; every
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.616#month their losses increased, in a slow proportion which postponed the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.617#fatal issue. A tenacious hope sustained them, they still announced the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.618#near discomfiture of The Ladies' Paradise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.619#“Pooh!” he would say, “we are young yet The future is ours.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.620#“And besides, what matters, if you have done what you wanted to do?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.621# resumed she. “As long as you are satisfied, I am as well, darling.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.622#Denise's affection increased for them on seeing their tenderness. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.623#trembled, feeling their inevitable fall; but she dared not interfere. It
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.624#was then she fully understood the power of the new system of business,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.625#and became impassioned for this force which was transforming Paris. Her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.626#ideas were ripening, a woman's grace was developing out of the savage
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.627#child newly arrived from Valognes. In fact, her life was a pretty
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.628#pleasant one, notwithstanding the fatigue and the little money she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.629#earned. When she had spent all the day on her feet, she had to go
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.630#straight home, and look after Pépé, whom old Bourras insisted on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.631#feeding, fortunately; but there was still a lot to do: a shirt to wash,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.632#stockings to mend; without mentioning the noise made by the youngster,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.633#which made her head ache fit to split. She never went to bed before
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.634#midnight. Sunday was her hardest day: she cleaned her room, and mended
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.635#her own things, so busy that it was often five o'clock before she could
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.636#dress. However, she sometimes went out for health's sake, taking the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.637#little one for a long walk, out towards Neuilly; and their treat was to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.638#drink a cup of milk there at a dairyman's, who allowed them to sit down
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.639#in his yard. Jean disdained these excursions; he put in an appearance
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.640#now and again on week-day evenings, then disappeared, pretending to have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.641#other visits to pay; he asked for no more money, but he arrived with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.642#such a melancholy face, that his sister, anxious, always managed to keep
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.643#a five-franc piece for him. That was her sole luxury.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.644#“Five francs!” he would exclaim each time. “My stars! you're too good!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.645#It just happens, there's the stationer's wife----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.646#“Not another word,” Denise would say; “I don't want to know.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.647#But he thought she was accusing him of boasting. “I tell you she's the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.648#wife of a stationer! Oh! something magnificent!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.649#Three months passed away, spring was returning. Denise refused to return
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.650#to Joinville with Pauline and Bauge. She sometimes met them in the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.651#Saint-Roch, when she left the shop in the evening. Pauline, one evening
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.652#when she was alone, confided to her that she was very likely going to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.653#marry her lover; it was she who was hesitating, for they did not care
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.654#for married saleswomen at The Ladies' Paradise. This idea of marriage
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.655#surprised Denise, she did not dare to advise her friend. One day, just
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.656#as Colomban had stopped her near the fountain to talk about Clara, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.657#latter was crossing the road; and Denise was obliged to run away, for he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.658#implored her to ask her old comrade if she would marry him. What was the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.659#matter with them all? why were they tormenting themselves like this? She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.660#thought herself very fortunate not to be in love with any one.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.661#“You've heard the news?” cried out the umbrella dealer to her one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.662#evening on her return home from business.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.663#“No, Monsieur Bourras.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.664#“Well! the scoundrels have bought the Hôtel Duvillard. I'm hemmed in on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.665#all sides!” He was waving his long arms about, in a burst of fury
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.666#which made his white mane stand up on end. “A regular mixed-up affair,”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.667# resumed the old man. “It appears that the hôtel belonged to the Credit
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.668#Immobilier, the president of which, Baron Hartmann, has just sold it to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.669#our famous Mouret. Now they've got me on the right, on the left, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.670#at the back, just in the way I'm holding the knob of this stick in my
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.671#hand!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.672#It was true, the sale was to have been concluded the previous day.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.673#Bourras's small house, hemmed in between The Ladies' Paradise and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.674#Hôtel Duvillard, hanging on like a swallow's nest in a crack of a wall,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.675#seemed sure to be crushed, as soon as the shop invaded the hôtel, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.676#the time had now arrived. The colossus had turned the feeble obstacle,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.677#and was surrounding it with a pile of goods, threatening to swallow it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.678#up, to absorb it by the sole force of its giant aspiration.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.679#Bourras could feel the embrace which was making his shop creak. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.680#thought he could see the place getting smaller; he was afraid of being
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.681#absorbed himself, of being carried to the other side with his umbrellas
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.682#and sticks, so loudly was the terrible machine roaring just then.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.683#“Do you hear them?” asked he. “One would think they were eating up the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.684#walls even! And in my cellar, in the attic, everywhere, there's the same
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.685#noise as of a saw going through the plaster. Never mind! I don't fancy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.686#they'll flatten me out like a sheet of paper. I'll stick here, even if
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.687#they blow up my roof, and the rain should fall in bucketfuls on my bed!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.688#It was just at this moment that Mouret caused fresh proposals to be made
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.689#to Bourras; they would increase the figure, they would give him fifty
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.690#thousand francs for his good-will and the remainder of the lease. This
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.691#offer redoubled the old man's anger; he refused in an insulting manner.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.692#How these scoundrels must rob people to be able to pay fifty thousand
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.693#francs for a thing not worth ten thousand. And he defended his shop as a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.694#young girl defends her virtue, for honour's sake.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.695#Denise noticed Bourras was pre-occupied during the next fortnight. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.696#wandered about in a feverish manner, measuring the walls of his house,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.697#surveying it from the middle of the street with the air of an architect.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.698#Then one morning some workmen arrived. This was the decisive blow. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.699#had conceived the bold idea of beating The Ladies' Paradise on its own
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.700#ground by making certain concessions to modern luxury. The customers,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.701#who often reproached him about his dark shop, would certainly come back
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.702#again, when they saw it bright and new. In the first place, the workmen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.703#stopped up the crevices and whitewashed the frontage, then they painted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.704#the woodwork a light green, and even carried the splendour so far as to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.705#gild the sign-board. A sum of three thousand francs, held in reserve
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.706#by Bourras as a last resource, was swallowed up in this way. The whole
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.707#neighbourhood was in a state of revolution; people came to look at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.708#him amid all these riches, losing his head, no longer able to find
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.709#the things he was accustomed to. He did not seem to be at home in this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.710#shining frame, in this tender setting; he seemed frightened, with his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.711#long beard and white hair. The people passing on the opposite side
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.712#of the street were astonished on seeing him waving his arms about and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.713#carving his handles. And he was in a state of fever, afraid of dirtying
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.714#his shop, plunging further into this luxurious business, which he did
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.715#not at all understand.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.716#The same as with Robineau, the campaign against The Ladies' Paradise was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.717#opened by Bourras. The latter had just brought out his invention,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.718#the automatic umbrella, which later on was to become popular. But The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.719#Paradise people immediately improved on the invention, and a struggle of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.720#prices commenced. Bourras had an article at one franc and nineteen sous,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.721#in zanella, with steel mounting, everlasting, said the ticket, But
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.722#he was especially anxious to vanquish his competitors with his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.723#handles--bamboo, dogwood, olive, myrtle, rattan, every imaginable sort
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.724#of handle. The Paradise people, less artistic, paid more attention to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.725#the material, extolling their alpacas and mohairs, their twills and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.726#sarcenets.. And they came out victorious. Bourras, in despair, repeated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.727#that art was done for, that he was reduced to carving his handles for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.728#pleasure, without any hope of selling them.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.729#“It's my fault!” cried he to Denise. “I never ought to have kept a lot
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.730#of rotten articles, at one franc nineteen sous! That's where these new
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.731#notions lead one to. I wanted to follow the example of these brigands;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.732#so much the better if I'm ruined by it!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.733#The month of July was very warm, and Denise suffered greatly in her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.734#narrow room, under the roof. So after leaving the shop, she sometimes
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.735#went and fetched Pépé, and instead of going up-stairs at once, went
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.736#for a stroll in the Tuileries Gardens until the gates were closed. One
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.737#evening as she was walking under the chestnut-trees she suddenly stopped
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.738#with surprise; a few yards off, walking straight towards her, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.739#thought she recognised Hutin. But her heart commenced to beat violently.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.740#It was Mouret, who had dined over the water, and was hurrying along on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.741#foot to call on Madame Desforges. At the abrupt movement she made to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.742#escape him, he caught sight of her. The night was coming on, but still
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.743#he recognised her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.744#“Ah, it's you, mademoiselle!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.745#She did not reply, astonished that he should deign to stop. He, smiling,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.746#concealed his constraint beneath an air of amiable protection.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.747#“You are still in Paris?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.748#“Yes, sir,” said she at last.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.749#She was slowly drawing back, desirous of making a bow and continuing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.750#her walk. But he turned and followed her under the black shadows of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.751#chestnut-trees. The air was getting cooler, some children were laughing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.752#in the distance, trundling their hoops.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.753#“This is your brother, is it not?” resumed he, looking at Pépé.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.754#The little boy, frightened by the unusual presence of a gentleman, was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.755#gravely walking by his sister's side, holding her tightly by the hand.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.756#“Yes, sir,” replied she once more.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.757#She blushed, thinking of the abominable inventions circulated by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.758#Marguerite and Clara. No doubt Mouret understood why she was blushing,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.759#for he quickly added: “Listen, mademoiselle, I have to apologise to you.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.760#Yes, I should have been happy to have told you sooner how much I regret
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.761#the error that has been made. You were accused too lightly of a fault.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.762#But the evil is done. I simply wanted to assure you that every one in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.763#our establishment now knows of your affection for your brothers,” he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.764#continued, with a respectful politeness to which the saleswomen in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.765#The Ladies' Paradise were little accustomed. Denise's confusion had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.766#increased; but her heart was filled with joy. He knew, then, that she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.767#had given herself to no one! Both remained silent; he continued beside
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.768#her, regulating his walk to the child's short steps; and the distant
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.769#murmurs of the city were dying away under the black shadows of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.770#spreading chestnut-trees. “I have only one reparation to offer you,”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.771# resumed he. “Naturally, if you would like to come back to us----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.772#She interrupted him, and refused with a feverish haste. “No, sir, I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.773#cannot. Thank you all the same, but I have found another situation.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.774#He knew it, they had informed him she was with Robineau; and leisurely,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.775#on a footing of amiable equality, he spoke of the latter, rendering
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.776#him full justice. A very intelligent fellow, but too nervous. He would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.777#certainly come to grief: Gaujean had burdened him with a very heavy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.778#business, in which they would both suffer. Denise, conquered by this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.779#familiarity, opened her mind further, and allowed it to be seen that she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.780#was for the big shops in the war between them and the small traders:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.781#she became animated, citing examples, showing herself well up in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.782#question, even expressing new and enlightened ideas. He, charmed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.783#listened to her in surprise; and turned round, trying to distinguish
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.784#her features in the growing darkness. She seemed still the same with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.785#her simple dress and sweet face; but from this modest bashfulness, there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.786#seemed to exhale a penetrating perfume, of which he felt the powerful'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.787#influence. Decidedly this little girl had got used to the air of Paris,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.788#she was becoming quite a woman, and was really perturbing, so sensible,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.789#with her beautiful hair, overflowing with tenderness.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.790#“As you are on our side,” said he, laughing, “why do you stay with our
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.791#adversaries? I fancy, too, they told me you lodged with Bourras.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.792#“A very worthy man,” murmured she.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.793#“No, not a bit of it! he's an old idiot, a madman who will force me
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.794#to ruin him, though I should be glad to get rid of him with a fortune!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.795#Besides, your place is not in his house, which has a bad reputation. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.796#lets to certain women----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.797#But feeling that the young girl was confused, he hastened to add: “One
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.798#can be respectable anywhere, and there's even more merit in remaining so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.799#when one is so poor.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.800#They went on a few steps in silence. Pépé seemed to be listening with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.801#the attentive air of a sharp child. Now and again he raised his eyes to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.802#his sister, whose burning hand, quivering with sudden starts, astonished
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.803#him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:vii.804#“Look here!” resumed Mouret, gaily, “will you be my ambassador? I
