urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.245# There was a fresh silence. Then she went on again quietly: “If you only
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.246#knew, I've been accustomed to the idea of this marriage for the last ten
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.247#years. I was still wearing short dresses, when Colomban was courting me.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.248#I hardly remember how things have come about By always living together,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.249#being shut up here together, without any other distractions between us,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.250#I must have ended by believing him to be my husband before he really
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.251#was. I didn't know whether I loved him. I was his wife, and that's all.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.252#And now he wants to go off with another girl! Oh, heavens! my heart is
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.253#breaking! You see, it's a grief that I've never felt before. It hurts
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.254#me in the bosom, and in the head; then it spreads every where, and is
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.255#killing me.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.256#Her eyes filled with tears. Denise, whose eyelids were also wet with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.257#pity, asked her: “Does my aunt suspect anything?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.258#“Yes, mamma has her suspicions, I think. As to papa, he is too worried,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.259#and does not know the pain he is causing me by postponing this marriage.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.260#Mamma has questioned me several times, greatly alarmed to see me pining
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.261#away. She has never been very strong herself, and has often said: 'My
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.262#poor child, I've not made you very strong.' Besides, one doesn't grow
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.263#much in these shops. But she must find me getting really too thin now.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.264#Look at my arms; would you believe it?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.265#And with a trembling hand she again took up the water bottle. Her cousin
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.266#tried to prevent her drinking.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.267#“No, I'm so thirsty, let me drink.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.268#They could hear Baudu talking in a loud voice. Then yielding to an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.269#inspiration of her tender heart, Denise knelt down before Geneviève,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.270#throwing her arms round her neck, kissing her, and assuring her that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.271#everything would turn out all right, that she would marry Colomban, that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.272#she would get well, and live happily. But she got up quickly, her uncle
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.273#was calling her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.274#“Jean is here. Come along.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.275#It was indeed Jean, looking rather scared, who had come to dinner. When
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.276#they told him it was striking eight, he looked amazed. Impossible! He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.277#had only just left his master's. They chaffed him. No doubt he had come
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.278#by way of the Bois de Vincennes. But as soon as he could get near his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.279#sister, he whispered to her: “It's a little laundry-girl who was taking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.280#back some linen. I've got a cab outside by the hour. Give me five
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.281#francs.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.282#He went out a minute, and then returned to dinner, for Madame Baudu
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.283#would not hear of his going away without taking, at least, a plate of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.284#soup. Genevieve had reappeared in her usual silent and retiring manner.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.285#Colomban was half asleep behind the counter. The evening passed away,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.286#slow and melancholy, only animated by Baudu's step, as he walked
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.287#from one end of the empty shop to the other. A single gas-burner was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.288#alight--the shadow of the low ceiling fell in large masses, like black
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.289#earth from a ditch.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.290#Several months passed away. Denise came in nearly every evening to cheer
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.291#up Geneviève a bit, but the house became more melancholy than ever. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.292#works opposite were a continual torment, which intensified their bad
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.293#luck. Even when they had an hour of hope--some unexpected joy--the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.294#falling of a tumbrel-load of bricks, the sound of the saw of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.295#stonecutter, or the simple call of a mason, sufficed at once to mar
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.296#their pleasure. In fact, the whole neighbourhood felt the shock. From
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.297#the boarded enclosure, running along and blocking up the three streets,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.298#there issued a movement of feverish activity. Although the architect
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.299#used the existing buildings, he altered them in various ways to adapt
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.300#them to their new uses; and right in the centre at the opening caused by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.301#the court-yards, he was building a central gallery as big as a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.302#church, which was to terminate with a grand entrance in the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.303#Neuve-Saint-Augustin right in the middle of the frontage. They had, at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.304#first, experienced great difficulty in laying the foundations, for they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.305#had come on to some sewer deposits and loose earth, full of human
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.306#bones. Besides that, the boring of the well had made the neighbours very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.307#anxious--a well three hundred feet deep, destined to give two hundred
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.308#gallons a minute. They had now got the walls up to the first storey;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.309#the entire block was surrounded by scaffolding, regular towers of timber
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.310#work. There was an incessant noise from the grinding of the windlasses
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.311#hoisting up the stone, the abrupt discharge of iron bars, the clamour of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.312#this army of workmen, accompanied by the noise of picks and hammers.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.313#But above all, what deafened the people was the sound of the machinery.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.314#Everything went by steam, screeching whistles rent the air; whilst, at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.315#the slightest gust of wind, clouds of plaster flew about and covered the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.316#neighbouring roofs like a fall of snow. The Baudus in despair looked
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.317#on at this implacable dust penetrating everywhere--getting through the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.318#closest woodwork, soiling the goods in their shop, even gliding into
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.319#their beds; and the idea that they must continue to breathe it--that it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.320#would finish by killing them--empoisoned their existence.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.321#The situation, however, was destined to become worse still, for in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.322#September, the architect, afraid of not being ready, decided to carry
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.323#on the work at night also. Powerful electric lamps were established,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.324#and the uproar became continuous. Gangs of men relieved each other;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.325#the hammers never stopped, the engines whistled night and day; the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.326#everlasting clamour seemed to raise and scatter the white dust The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.327#Baudus now had to give up the idea of sleeping even; they were shaken in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.328#their beds; the noises changed into nightmare as soon as they fell off
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.329#to sleep. Then, if they got up to calm their fever, and went, with bare
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.330#feet, to look out of the window, they were frightened by the vision
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.331#of The Ladies' Paradise flaring in the darkness like a colossal forge,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.332#where their ruin was being forged. Along the half-built walls, dotted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.333#with open bays, the electric lamps threw a large blue flood of light,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.334#of a blinding intensity. Two o'clock struck--then three, then four; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.335#during the painful sleep of the neighbourhood, the works, increased
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.336#by this lunar brightness, became colossal and fantastic, swarming with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.337#black shadows, noisy workmen, whose profiles gesticulated on the crude
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.338#whiteness of the new plastering.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.339#Baudu was quite right. The small traders in the neighbouring streets
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.340#were receiving another mortal blow. Every time The Ladies' Paradise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.341#created new departments there were fresh failures among the shopkeepers
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.342#of the district The disaster spread, one could hear the cracking of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.343#the oldest houses. Mademoiselle Tatin, at the under-linen shop in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.344#Passage Choiseul, had just been declared bankrupt; Quinette, the glover,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.345#could hardly hold out another six months; the furriers, Vanpouille, were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.346#obliged to sub-let a part of their premises; and if the Bédorés, brother
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.347#and sister, the hosiers, still kept on in the Rue Gaillon, they were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.348#evidently living on money saved formerly. And now more smashes were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.349#going to be added to those long since foreseen; the department for fancy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.350#goods threatened a toy-shopkeeper in the Rue Saint-Roch, Deslignières, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.351#big, full-blooded man; whilst the furniture department attacked Messrs.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.352#Piot and Rivoire, whose shops were sleeping in the shadow of the Passage
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.353#Sainte-Anne. It was even feared that an attack of apoplexy would carry
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.354#off the toyman, who had gone into a terrible rage on seeing The Ladies'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.355#Paradise mark up purses at thirty per cent, reduction. The furniture
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.356#dealers, who were much calmer, affected to joke at these counter-jumpers
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.357#who wanted to meddle with such articles as chairs and tables; but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.358#customers were already leaving them, the success of the department had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.359#every appearance of being a formidable one. It was all over, they were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.360#obliged to bow their heads. After these others would be swept off, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.361#there was no reason why every business should not be driven away. One
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.362#day The Ladies' Paradise alone would cover the neighbourhood with its
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.363#roof.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.364#At present, morning and evening, when the thousand employees went in and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.365#came out, they formed such a long procession in the Place Gaillon that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.366#people stopped to look at them as they would at a passing regiment.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.367#For ten minutes they blocked up all the streets; and the shopkeepers at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.368#their doors thought bitterly of their single assistant, whom they hardly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.369#knew how to find food for. The last balance-sheet of the big shop,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.370#the forty millions turned over, had also caused a revolution in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.371#neighbourhood. The figure passed from house to house amid cries of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.372#surprise and anger. Forty millions! Think of that! No doubt the net
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.373#profit did not exceed more than four per cent., with their heavy general
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.374#expenses, and system of low prices; but sixteen hundred thousand francs
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.375#was a jolly sum, one could be satisfied with four per cent., when one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.376#operated on such a scale as that. It was said that Mouret's starting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.377#capital of five hundred thousand francs, augmented each year by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.378#total profits, a capital which must at that moment have amounted to four
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.379#millions, had thus passed ten times over the counters in the form of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.380#goods. Robineau, when he made this calculation before Denise, after
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.381#dinner, was overcome for a moment, his eyes fixed on his empty plate.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.382#She was right, it was this incessant renewal of the capital that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.383#constituted the invincible force of the new system of business. Bourras
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.384#alone denied the facts, refusing to understand, superb and stupid as a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.385#mile-stone. A pack of thieves and nothing more! A lying set! Cheap-jacks
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.386#who would be picked up out of the gutter one fine morning!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.387#The Baudus, however, notwithstanding their wish not to change anything
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.388#in the way of The Old Elbeuf, tried to sustain the competition. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.389#customers no longer coming to them, they forced themselves to go to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.390#customers, through the agency of travellers. There was at that time, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.391#the Paris market, a traveller connected with all the great tailors,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.392#who saved the little cloth and flannel houses when he condescended to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.393#represent them. Naturally they all tried to get hold of him; he assumed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.394#the importance of a personage; and Baudu, having haggled with him, had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.395#the misfortune of seeing him come to terms with the Matignons, in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.396#Rue Croix-des-Petits-Champs. One after the other, two other travellers
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.397#robbed him; a third, an honest man, did no business. It was a slow
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.398#death, without any shock, a continual decrease of business, customers
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.399#lost one by one. A day came when the bills fell very heavily. Up to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.400#that time they had lived on their former savings; but now they began to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.401#contract debts. In December, Baudu, terrified by the amount of the bills
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.402#he had accepted, resigned himself to a most cruel sacrifice: he sold his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.403#country-house at Rambouillet, a house which cost him a lot of money in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.404#continual repairs, and for which the tenants had not even paid the rent
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.405#when he decided to get rid of it. This sale killed the only dream of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.406#his life, his heart bled as for the loss of some dear one. And he had to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.407#sell for seventy thousand francs that which had cost him more than two
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.408#hundred thousand, considering himself fortunate to have met the Lhommes,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.409#his neighbours, who were desirous of adding to their property. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.410#seventy thousand francs would keep the business going a little longer;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.411#for notwithstanding the repulses already encountered, the idea of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.412#struggling sprang up again; perhaps with great care they might conquer
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.413#even now.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.414#The Sunday on which the Lhommes paid the money, they were good enough to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.415#dine at The Old Elbeuf. Madame Aurélie was the first to arrive; they had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.416#to wait for the cashier, who came late, scared by a whole afternoon's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.417#music; as for young Albert, he had accepted the invitation, but did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.418#put in an appearance. It was, moreover, a somewhat painful evening. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.419#Baudus, living without air in their narrow dining-room, suffered from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.420#the gust of wind brought in by the Lhommes, with their scattered family
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.421#and taste for a free existence. Geneviève, wounded by Madame Aurélie's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.422#imperial airs, did not open her mouth; whilst Colomban was admiring
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.423#her with a shiver, on reflecting that she reigned over Clara. Before
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.424#retiring to rest, in the evening, Madame Baudu being already in bed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.425#Baudu walked about the room for a long time. It was a mild night,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.426#thawing and damp. Outside, notwithstanding the closed windows, and drawn
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.427#curtains, one could hear the machinery roaring on the opposite side of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.428#the way.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.429#“Do you know what I'm thinking of, Elisabeth?” said he at last “Well!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.430#these Lhommes may earn as much money as they like, I'd rather be in my
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.431#shoes than theirs. They get on well, it's true. The wife said, didn't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.432#she? that she had made nearly twenty thousand francs this year, and that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.433#has enabled her to take my poor house. Never mind! I've no longer the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.434#house, but I don't go playing music in one direction, whilst you are
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.435#gadding about in the other. No, look you, they can't be happy.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.436#He was still labouring under the grief of his sacrifice, nourishing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.437#a certain rancour against those people who had bought up his darling
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.438#dream. When he came near the bed, he gesticulated, leaning over his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.439#wife; then, returning to the window, he stood silent for a minute,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.440#listening to the noise of the works. And he resumed his old accusations,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.441#his despairing complaints about the new times; nobody had ever seen such
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.442#things, a shop-assistant earning more than a tradesman, cashiers buying
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.443#up the employers' property. Everything was going to the dogs; family
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.444#ties no longer existed, people lived at hôtels instead of eating their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.445#meals at home in a respectable manner. He ended by prophesying that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.446#young Albert would later on swallow up the Rambouillet property with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.447#lot of actresses.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.448#Madame Baudu listened to him, her head flat on the pillow, so pale that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.449#her face was the colour of the sheets. “They've paid you,” at length
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.450#said she, softly.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.451#At this Baudu became dumb. He walked about for an instant with his eyes
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.452#on the ground. Then he resumed: “They've paid me, 'tis true; and,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.453#after all, their money is as good as another's. It would be funny if we
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.454#revived the business with this money. Ah! if I were not so old and worn
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.455#out!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.456#A long silence ensued. The draper was full of vague projects. Suddenly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.457#his wife spoke again, her eyes fixed on the ceiling, without moving her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.458#head: “Have you noticed your daughter lately?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.459#“No,” replied he.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.460#“Well! she makes me rather anxious. She's getting pale, she seems to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.461#pining away.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.462#He stood before the bed, full of surprise. “Really! whatever for? If
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.463#she's ill she should say so. To-morrow we must send for the doctor.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.464#Madame Baudu still remained motionless. After a short time, she declared
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.465#with her meditative air: “This marriage with Colomban, I think it would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.466#be better to get it over.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.467#He looked at her, then began walking about again. Certain things came
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.468#back to his mind. Was it possible that his daughter was falling ill over
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.469#the shopman? Did she love him so much that she could not wait? Here was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.470#another misfortune! It worried him all the more from the fact that he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.471#himself had fixed ideas about this marriage. He could never consent to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.472#it in the present state of affairs. However, his anxiety softened him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.473#“Very good,” said he at last, “I'll speak to Colomban.” And without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.474#saying another word he continued his walk. Soon afterwards his wife
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.475#fell off to sleep, quite white, as if dead; but he still kept on walking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.476#about. Before getting into bed he drew aside the curtains and glanced
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.477#outside; on the other side of the street, the gaping windows of the old
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.478#Hôtel Duvillard showed the workmen moving about in the dazzling glare of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.479#the electric light.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.480#The next morning Baudu took Colomban to the further end of the store,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.481#on the upper floor, having made up his mind over night what he should
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.482#say to him. “My boy,” said he “you know I've sold my property at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.483#Rambouillet. That will enable us to show good fight. But I should like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.484#beforehand to have a talk with you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.485#The young man, who seemed to dread the interview, waited with an awkward
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.486#air. His small eyes twinkled in his large face, and he stood there with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.487#his mouth open--a sign with him of profound agitation.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.488#“Just listen to me,” resumed the draper. “When old Hauchecorne left me
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.489#The Old Elbeuf, the house was prosperous; he himself had received it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.490#from old Finet in a satisfactory state. You know my ideas; I should
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.491#consider it wrong if I passed this family trust to my children in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.492#diminished state; and that's why I've always postponed your marriage
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.493#with Genevieve. Yes, I was obstinate; I hoped to bring back our former
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.494#prosperity; I wanted to hand you the books, saying: 'Look here! the year
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.495#I commenced we sold so much cloth, and this year, the year I retire, we
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.496#have sold ten thousand or twenty thousand francs' worth more.' In short,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.497#you understand, it was a vow I had made to myself, the very natural
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.498#desire I had to prove that the house had not lost anything in my hands.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.499#Otherwise it would seem to me I was robbing you.” His voice was stifled
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.500#with emotion. He blew his nose to recover a bit, and asked, “You don't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.501#say anything?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.502#But Colomban had nothing to say. He shook his head, and waited, more and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.503#more troubled, thinking he could guess what, the governor was aiming at.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.504#It was the marriage without further delay. How could he refuse? He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.505#would never have the strength. And the other girl, of whom he dreamed at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.506#night, devoured by such a flame that he frequently threw himself quite
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.507#naked on the floor, in the fear of dying of it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.508#“Now,” continued Baudu, “there's a sum of money that may save us. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.509#situation becomes worse every day, and perhaps by making a supreme
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.510#effort----In short, I thought it right to warn you. We are going to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.511#venture our last stake. If we are beaten, why that will entirely ruin
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.512#us! But, my poor boy, your marriage must be again postponed, for I don't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.513#wish to throw you two all alone into the struggle. That would be too
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.514#cowardly, wouldn't it?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.515#Colomban, greatly relieved, had seated himself on a pile of swan-skin
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.516#flannel. His legs were still trembling. He was afraid of showing his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.517#joy, he held down his head, rolling his fingers on his knees.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.518#“You don't say anything?” repeated Baudu.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.519#No, he said nothing, he could find nothing to say. The draper then
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.520#slowly continued: “I was sure this would grieve you. You must muster up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.521#courage. Pull yourself together a bit, don't let yourself be crushed in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.522#this way. Above all, understand my position. Can I hang such a weight on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.523#your neck? Instead of leaving you a good business, I should leave you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.524#a bankruptcy perhaps. No, it's only a scoundrel who would play such a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.525#trick! No doubt, I desire nothing but your happiness, but no one shall
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.526#ever make me, go against my conscience.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.527#And he went on for a long time in this way, swaying about in a maze of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.528#contradictions, like a man who would have liked to be understood at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.529#half a word and finds himself obliged to explain everything. As he had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.530#promised his daughter and the shop, strict probity forced him to deliver
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.531#both in good condition, without defects or debts. But he was tired, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.532#burden seemed to be too much for him, his stammering voice was one of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.533#supplication. He got more entangled than ever in his words, he was still
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.534#expecting a sudden rally from Colomban, some heartfelt cry, which came
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.535#not.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.536#“I know,” murmured he, “that old men are wanting in ardour. With young
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.537#ones, things light up. They are full of fire, it's natural. But, no, no,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.538#I can't, my word of honour! If I gave it up to you, you would blame me
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.539#later on.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.540#He stopped, trembling, and as the young man still kept his head down,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.541#he asked him for the third time, after a painful silence: “You don't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.542#say anything?” At last, but without looking at him, Colomban replied:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.543#“There's nothing to say. You are the master, you know better than all of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.544#us. As you wish it we'll wait, we'll try and be reasonable.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.545#It was all over. Baudu still hoped he was going to throw himself into
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.546#his arms, exclaiming: “Father, do you take a rest, we'll fight in our
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.547#turn; give us the shop as it is, so that we may work a miracle and save
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.548#it! Then he looked at him, and was seized with shame, accusing himself
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.549#of having wished to dupe his children. The deep-rooted maniacal honesty
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.550#of the shopkeeper was awakened in him; it was this prudent fellow who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.551#was right, for in business there is no such thing as sentiment, it is
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.552#only a question of figures.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.553#“Give me your hand, my boy,” said he in conclusion. “It's settled we
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.554#won't speak about the marriage for another year. One must think of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.555#business before everything.” That evening in their room when Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.556#Baudu questioned her husband as to the result of the conversation, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.557#result of the conversation, the latter had resumed his obstinate wish to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.558#fight in person to the bitter end. He gave Colomban high praise,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.559#calling him a solid fellow, firm in his ideas, brought up with the best
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.560#principles, incapable, for instance, of joking with the customers like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.561#those puppies at The Paradise. No, he was honest, he belonged to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.562#the family, he didn't speculate on the business as though he were a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.563#stock-jobber.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.564#“Well, then, when's the marriage to take place?” asked Madame Baudu.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.565#“Later on,” replied he, “when I am able to keep to my promises.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.566#She made no gestures, she simply observed: “It will be our daughter's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.567#death.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.568#Baudu restrained himself, stirred up with anger. He was the one whom it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.569#would kill, if they continually upset him like this! Was it his fault?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.570#He loved his daughter--would lay down his life for her; but he could
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.571#not make the business prosper when it obstinately refused to do so.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.572#Geneviève ought to have a little more sense, and wait patiently for a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.573#better balance-sheet The deuce! Colomban was there, no one would run
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.574#away with him!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.575#“It's incredible!” repeated he; “such a well-trained girl!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.576#Madame Baudu said no more. No doubt she had guessed Genevieve's jealous
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.577#agony; but she did not dare to inform her husband. A singular womanly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.578#modesty always prevented her approaching certain tender, delicate
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.579#subjects with him. When he saw her so silent, he turned his anger
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.580#against the people opposite, stretching his fists out in the air,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.581#towards the works, where they were setting up large iron girders, with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.582#great noise of hammers.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.583#Denise had decided to return to The Ladies' Paradise, having understood
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.584#that the Robineaus, though forced to cut down their staff, did not like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.585#to dismiss her. To maintain their position, now, they were obliged to do
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.586#everything themselves. Gaujean, obstinate in his rancour, renewed their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.587#bills, even promised to find them funds; but they were frightened, they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.588#wanted to go in for economy and order. During a whole fortnight Denise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.589#had felt uneasy with them, and she had to speak first, saying she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.590#found a situation elsewhere. This was a great relief. Madame Robineau
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.591#embraced her, deeply affected, saying she should always miss her. Then
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.592#when, in reply to a question, the young girl said she was going back to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.593#Mouret's, Robineau turned pale.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.594#“You are right!” he exclaimed violently.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.595#It was not so easy to tell the news to old Bourras. However, Denise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.596#had to give him notice, and she trembled, for she was full of gratitude
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.597#towards him. Bourras just at this time was in a continual fever of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.598#rage--full of invectives against the works going on next door. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.599#builder's carts blocked up his doorway; the picks tapped on his walls;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.600#everything in his place, the umbrellas and the sticks, danced about
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.601#to the noise of the hammers. It seemed that the hovel, obstinately
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.602#remaining amid all these demolitions, was going to give way. But the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.603#worst of all was that the architect, in order to connect the existing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.604#shops with those about to be opened in the Hôtel Duvillard, had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.605#conceived the idea of boring a passage under the little house that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.606#separated them. This house belonged to the firm of Mouret & Co., and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.607#the lease stipulating that the tenant should submit to all necessary
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.608#repairs, the workmen appeared on the scene one morning. At this Bourras
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.609#nearly went into a fit. Wasn't it enough to strangle him on all sides,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.610#on the right, the left, and behind, without attacking him underfoot as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.611#well, taking the ground from under him! And he drove the masons
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.612#away, and went to law. Repairs, yes! but this was rather a work of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.613#embellishment. The neighbourhood thought he would carry the day,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.614#without, however, being sure of anything The case, however, threatened
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.615#to be a long one, and people became very excited over this interminable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.616#duel. The day Denise resolved to give him notice, Bourras had just
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.617#returned from his lawyer.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.618#“Would you believe it!” exclaimed he, “they now say the house is not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.619#solid; they pretend that the foundations must be strengthened. Confound
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.620#it! they have shaken it up so with their infernal machines, that it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.621#isn't astonishing if it gives way!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.622#Then, when the young girl announced she was going away, and that she was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.623#going back to The Ladies' Paradise at a salary of a thousand francs, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.624#was so amazed that he simply raised his trembling hands in the air. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.625#emotion made him drop into a chair.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.626#“You! you!” he stammered. “Ah, I'm the only one--I'm the only one left!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.627# After a pause, he asked: “And the youngster?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.628#“He'll go back to Madame Gras's,” replied Denise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.629#“She was very fond of him! that can't be refused. You'll all go. Go,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.630#then, leave me here alone. Yes, alone--you understand! There shall be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.631#one who will never bow his head. And tell them I'll win my lawsuit, if I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.632#have to sell my last shirt for it!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.633#Denise was not to leave Robineau's till the end of the month. She had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.634#seen Mouret again; everything was settled. One evening as she was going
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.635#up to her room, Deloche, who was watching for her in a doorway, stopped
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.636#her. He was delighted, having just heard the good news; they were all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.637#talking about it in the shop, he said. And he told her the gossip of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.638#counters.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.639#“You know, the young ladies in the dress department are pulling long
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.640#faces!” Then, interrupting himself, he added: “By the way, you remember
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.641#Clara Primaire? Well, it appears the governor has------ You understand?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.642#He had turned quite red. She, very pale, exclaimed: “Monsieur Mouret!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.643#“Funny taste--eh?” he resumed. “A woman who looks like a horse. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.644#little girl from the under-linen department, whom he had twice last
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.645#year, was, at least, good-looking. However, that's his business.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.646#Denise, once upstairs, almost fainted away. It was surely through coming
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.647#up too quick. Leaning out of the window she had a sudden vision of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.648#Valognes, the deserted street and grassy pavement, which she used to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.649#see from her room as a child; and she was seized with a desire to go
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.650#and live there--to seek refuge in the peace and forgetfulness of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.651#country. Paris irritated her, she hated The Ladies' Paradise, she hardly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.652#knew why she had consented to go back. She would certainly suffer as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.653#much as ever there; she was already suffering from an unknown uneasiness
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.654#since Deloche's stories. Suddenly, without any notice, a flood of tears
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.655#forced her to leave the window. She wept on for some time, and found
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.656#a little courage to live on still. The next day at breakfast-time, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.657#Robineau had sent her on an errand, and she was passing The Old Elbeuf,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.658#she pushed open the door on seeing Colomban alone in the shop. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.659#Baudus were breakfasting; she could hear the clatter of the knives and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.660#forks in the little room.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.661#“You can come in,” said the shopman. “They are at breakfast.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.662#But she motioned him to be silent, and drew him into a corner. Then,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.663#lowering her voice, she said: “It's you I want to speak to. Have you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.664#no heart? Don't you see that Geneviève loves you, and that it's killing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.665#her.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.666#She was trembling, the previous night's fever had taken possession
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.667#of her again. He, frightened, surprised at this sudden attack, stood
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.668#looking at her, without a word.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.669#“Do you hear?” she continued. “Genevieve knows you love another. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.670#told me so. She wept like a child. Ah, poor girl! she isn't very strong
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.671#now, I can tell you! If you had seen her thin arms! It's heart-breaking.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.672#You can't leave her to die like this!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.673#At last he spoke, quite overcome. “But she isn't ill--you exaggerate!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.674#I don't see anything myself. Besides, it's her father who is postponing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.675#the marriage.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.676#Denise sharply corrected this falsehood, certain that the least
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.677#persistence on the part of the young man would decide her uncle. As to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.678#Colomban's surprise, it was not feigned; he had really never noticed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.679#Genevieve's slow agony. For him it was a very disagreeable revelation;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.680#for while he remained ignorant of it, he had no great blame to tax
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.681#himself with.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.682#“And who for?” resumed Denise. “For a worthless girl! You can't know
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.683#who you are loving! Up to the present I have not wanted to hurt your
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.684#feelings, I have often avoided answering your continual questions. Well!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.685#she goes with everybody, she laughs at you, you will never have her, or
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.686#you may have her, like others, just once in a way.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.687#He listened to her, very pale; and at each of the sentences she threw
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.688#into his face, his lips trembled. She, in a cruel fit, yielded to a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.689#transport of anger of which she had no consciousness. “In short,” said
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.690#she in a final cry, “she's with Monsieur Mouret, if you want to know!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.691#Her voice was stifled, she turned paler than Colomban himself. Both
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.692#stood looking at each other. Then he stammered out: “I love her!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.693#Denise felt ashamed of herself. Why was she talking in this way to this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.694#young fellow? Why was she getting so excited? She stood there mute, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.695#simple reply he had just given resounded in her heart like the clang of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.696#a bell, which deafened her. “I love her, I love her!” and it seemed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.697#to spread. He was right, he could not marry another woman. And as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.698#she turned round, she observed Genevieve on the threshold of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.699#dining-room.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.700#“Be quiet!” she said rapidly.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.701#But it was too late, Genevieve must have heard, for her face was white
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.702#bloodless. Just at that moment a customer opened the door--Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.703#Bourdelais, one of the last faithful customers of the Old Elbeuf where
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.704#she found solid goods for her money; for a long time past Madame de
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.705#Boves had followed the fashion, and gone over to The Ladies' Paradise;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.706#Madame Marty herself no longer came, entirely captivated by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.707#seductions of the display opposite. And Genevieve was forced to go
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.708#forward, and say in her weak voice:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.709#“What do you desire, madame?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.710#Madame Bourdelais wished to sec some flannel. Colomban took down a roll
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.711#from a shelf. Genevieve showed the article; and both of them, their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.712#hands cold, found themselves brought together behind the counter.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.713#Meanwhile Baudu came out of the dining-room last, behind his wife, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.714#had gone and seated herself at the pay-desk. At first he did not meddle
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.715#with the sale, but stood up, looking at Madame Bourdelais.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.716#“It is not good enough,” said the latter. “Show me the strongest you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.717#have.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.718#Colomban took down another bundle. There was a silence. Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.719#Bourdelais examined the stuff.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.720#“How much?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.721#“Six francs, madame,” replied Genevieve. The lady made an abrupt
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.722#movement. “Six francs!” said she. “But they have the same opposite at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.723#five francs.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.724#A slight contraction passed over Baudu's face. He could not help
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.725#interfering politely. No doubt madame made a mistake, the stuff ought to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.726#have been sold at six francs and a half; it was impossible to give it at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.727#five francs. It must be another quality she was referring to.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.728#“No, no,” she repeated, with the obstinacy of a lady who could not be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.729#deceived. “The quality is the same. It may even be a little thicker.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.730#And the discussion got very warm. Baudu, his face getting bilious,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.731#made an effort to continue smiling. His bitterness against The Ladies'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.732#Paradise was bursting in his throat.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.733#“Really,” said Madame Bourdelais at last, “you must treat me better,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.734#otherwise I shall go opposite, like the others.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.735#He then lost his head, and cried out, shaking with a passion he could
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.736#not repress: “Well! go opposite!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.737#At this she got up, greatly annoyed, and went away without turning
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.738#round, saying: “That's what I am going to do, sir.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.739#A general stupor ensued. The governor's violence had frightened all of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.740#them. He was himself scared, and trembled at what he had just said. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.741#phrase had escaped against his will in the explosion of a long pent-up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.742#rancour. And the Baudus now stood there motionless, following Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.743#Bourdelais with their looks, watching her cross the street. She seemed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.744#to be carrying off their fortune. When she slowly passed under the high
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.745#door of The Ladies' Paradise, when they saw her disappear in the crowd,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.746#they felt a sort of sudden wrench.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.747#“There's another they've taken from us!” murmured the draper. Then
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.748#turning towards Denise, of whose re-engagement he was aware, he said:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.749#“You as well, they've taken you back. Oh, I don't blame you for it. As
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.750#they have the money, they are naturally the strongest.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.751#Just then, Denise, still hoping that Geneviève had not overheard
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.752#Colomban, was saying to her: “He loves you. Try and cheer up.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.753#But the young girl replied to her in a very low and heartbroken voice:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.754#“Why do you tell me a falsehood? Look! he can't help it, he's always
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.755#glancing up there. I know very well they've stolen him from me, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.756#they've robbed us of everything else.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.757#Geneviève went and sat down on the seat at the desk near her mother. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.758#latter had doubtless guessed the fresh blow received by her daughter,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.759#for her anxious eyes wandered from her to Colomban, and then to The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.760#Ladies' Paradise. It was true, they had stolen everything from them:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.761#from the father, a fortune; from the mother, her dying child; from the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.762#daughter, a husband, waited for for ten years. Before this condemned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.763#family, Denise, whose heart was overflowing with pity, felt for an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.764#instant afraid of being wicked. Was she not going to assist this machine
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.765#which was crushing the poor people? But she felt herself carried away as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.766#it were by an invisible force, and knew that she was doing no wrong.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.767#“Bah!” resumed Baudu, to give himself courage; “we sha'n't die over it,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.768#after all. For one customer lost we shall find two others. You hear,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.769#Denise, I've got over seventy thousand francs there, which will
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.770#certainly trouble your Mouret's rest. Come, come, you others, don't look
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.771#so glum!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.772#But he could not enliven them. He himself relapsed into a pale
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.773#consternation; and they all stood with their eyes on the monster,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.774#attracted, possessed, full of their misfortune. The work was nearly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.775#finished, the scaffolding had been removed from the front, a whole
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.776#side of the colossal edifice appeared, with its walls and large light
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.777#windows.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.778#Along the pavement at last open to circulation, stood eight vans that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.779#the messengers were loading one after the other.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.780#In the sunshine, a ray of which ran along the street, the green panels,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.781#picked out with red and yellow, sparkled like so many mirrors, sending
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.782#blinding reflections right into The Old Elbeuf. The drivers, dressed in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.783#black, of a correct appearance, were holding the horses well in, superb
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.784#pairs, shaking their silvered bits. And each time a van was loaded,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.785#there was a sonorous, rolling noise, which made the neighbouring small
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.786#shops tremble. And before this triumphal procession, which they were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.787#destined to submit to twice a day, the Baudus' hearts broke. The father
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.788#half fainted away, asking himself where this continual flood of goods
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.789#could go to; whilst the mother, tormented to death about her daughter,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:viii.790#continued to gaze into the street, her eyes drowned in a flood of tears.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.1#CHAPTER IX.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.2#It was on a Monday, the 14th of March, that The Ladies' Paradise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.3#inaugurated its new buildings by a great exhibition of summer novelties,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.4#which was to last three days. Outside, a sharp wind was blowing, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.5#passers-by, surprised by this return of winter, spun along, buttoned up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.6#in their overcoats. However, behind the closed doors of the neighbouring
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.7#shops, quite an agitation was fermenting; and one could see, against the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.8#windows, the pale faces of the small tradesmen, occupied in counting the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.9#first carriages which stopped before the new grand entrance in the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.10#Neuve-Saint-Augustin. This door, lofty and deep like a church porch,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.11#surmounted by a group--Industry and Commerce hand-in-hand amidst a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.12#complication of symbols--was sheltered by a vast awning, the fresh
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.13#gilding of which seemed to light up the pavement with a ray of sunshine.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.14#To the right and left stretched the shop fronts, barely dry and of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.15#blinding whiteness, running along the Rue Monsigny and the Rue de
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.16#la Michodière, occupying the whole island, except on the Rue du
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.17#Dix-Décembre side, where the Crédit Immobilier intended to build.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.18#Along this barrack-like development, the small tradesmen, when they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.19#raised their heads, perceived the piles of goods through the large
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.20#plate-glass windows which, from the ground floor up to the second
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.21#storey, opened the house to the light of day. And this enormous cube,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.22#this colossal bazaar, shut out the sky from them, seeming to cause the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.23#cold which was making them shiver behind their frozen counters.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.24#As early as six o'clock, Mouret was on the spot, giving his final
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.25#orders. In the centre, starting from the grand entrance, a large gallery
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.26#ran from end to end, flanked right and left by two narrower galleries,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.27#the Monsigny Gallery and the Michodière Gallery. The court-yards had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.28#been glazed and turned into halls, iron staircases rose from the ground
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.29#floor, iron bridges were thrown from one end to the other on the two
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.30#storeys. The architect, who happened to be a young man of talent with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.31#modern ideas, had only used stone for the under-ground floor and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.32#corner pillars, constructing the whole ground with the corner pillars,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.33#constructing the whole carcase of iron, the assemblage of beams and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.34#rafters being supported by columns. The arches of the flooring and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.35#partitions were of brickwork. Space had been gained everywhere, light
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.36#and air entered freely, and the public circulated with the greatest
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.37#ease under the bold flights of the far-stretching girders. It was the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.38#cathedral of modern commerce, light but solid, made for a nation of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.39#customers. Below, in the central gallery, after the door bargains, came
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.40#the cravat, the glove, and the silk departments; the Monsigny Gallery
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.41#was occupied by the linen and the Rouen goods; the Michodière Gallery
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.42#by the mercery, the hosiery, the drapery, and the woollen departments.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.43#Then, on the first floor were installed the ready-made, the under-linen,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.44#the shawl, the lace, and other new departments, whilst the bedding, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.45#carpets, the furnishing materials, all the cumbersome articles difficult
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.46#to handle, had been relegated to the second floor. The number of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.47#departments was now thirty-nine, with eighteen hundred employees, of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.48#whom two hundred were women. Quite a little world operated there, in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.49#sonorous life of the high metallic naves.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.50#Mouret's unique passion was to conquer woman. He wished her to be queen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.51#in his house, and he had built this temple to get her completely at his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.52#mercy. His sole aim was to intoxicate her with gallant attentions, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.53#traffic on her desires, work on her fever. Night and day he racked his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.54#brain to invent fresh attractions. He had already introduced two lifts
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.55#lined with velvet for the upper storeys, in order to spare delicate
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.56#ladies the trouble of mounting the stairs. Then he had just opened a bar
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.57#where the customers could find, gratis, some light refreshment, syrups
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.58#and biscuits, and a reading-room, a monumental gallery, decorated with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.59#excessive luxury, in which he had even ventured on an exhibition of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.60#pictures. But his most profound idea was to conquer the mother through
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.61#the child, when unable to do so through her coquetry; he neglected no
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.62#means, speculated on every sentiment, created departments for little
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.63#boys and girls, arresting the passing mothers by distributing pictures
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.64#and air-balls to the children. A stroke of genius this idea of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.65#distributing to each buyer a red air-ball made of fine gutta-percha,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.66#bearing in large letters the name of the shop, and which, held by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.67#a string, floated in the air, parading in the streets a living
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.68#advertisement.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.69#But the greatest power of all was the advertising. Mouret spent three
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.70#hundred thousand francs a year in catalogues, advertisements, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.71#bills. For his summer sale he had launched forth two hundred thousand
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.72#catalogues, of which fifty thousand went abroad, translated into every
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.73#language. He now had them illustrated with engravings, even accompanying
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.74#them with samples, gummed between the leaves. It was an overflowing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.75#display; The Ladies' Paradise became a household word all over the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.76#world, invading the walls, the newspapers, and even the curtains at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.77#theatres. He declared that woman was powerless against advertising, that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.78#she was bound to follow the crowd. Not only that, he laid still more
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.79#seductive traps for her, analysing her like a great moralist. Thus he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.80#had discovered that she could not resist a bargain, that she bought
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.81#without necessity when she thought she saw a cheap line, and on this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.82#observation he based his system of reductions in price, progressively
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.83#lowering the price of unsold articles, preferring to sell them at a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.84#loss, faithful to his principle of the continual renewal of the goods.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.85#He had penetrated still further into the heart of woman, and had just
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.86#thought of the “returns,” a masterpiece of Jesuitical seduction. “Take
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.87#whatever you like, madame; you can return the article if you don't like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.88#it.” And the woman who hesitated was provided with the last excuse, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.89#possibility of repairing an extravagant folly, she took the article with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.90#an easy conscience. The returns and the reduction of prices now formed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.91#part of the classical working of the new style of business.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.92#But where Mouret revealed himself as an unrivalled master was in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.93#interior arrangement of the shops. He laid down as a law that not a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.94#corner of The Ladies' Paradise ought to remain deserted, requiring
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.95#everywhere a noise, a crowd, evidence of life; for life, said he,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.96#attracts life, increases and multiplies. From this law he drew all sorts
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.97#of applications. In the first place, there ought always to be a crush at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.98#the entrance, so that the people in the street should mistake it for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.99#a riot; and he obtained this crush by placing a lot of bargains at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.100#doors, shelves and baskets overflowing with very low-priced articles;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.101#so that the common people crowded there, stopping up the doorway, making
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.102#the shop look as if it were crammed with customers, when it was often
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.103#only half full. Then, in the galleries, he had the art of concealing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.104#the departments in which business was slack; for instance, the shawl
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.105#department in summer, and the printed calico department in winter, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.106#surrounded them with busy departments, drowning them with a continual
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.107#uproar. It was he alone who had been inspired with the idea of placing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.108#on the second-floor the carpet and furniture counters, counters where
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.109#the customers were less frequent, and which if placed on the ground
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.110#floor would have caused empty, cold spaces. If he could have managed it,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.111#he would have had the street running through his shop.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.112#Just at that moment, Mouret was a prey to an attack of inspiration. On
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.113#the Saturday evening, as he was giving a last look at the preparations
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.114#for the Monday's great sale, he was suddenly struck with the idea that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.115#the arrangement of the departments adopted by him was wrong and stupid;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.116#and yet It seemed a perfectly logical arrangement: the stuffs on one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.117#side, the made-up articles on the other, an intelligent order of things
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.118#which would enable the customers to find their way themselves. He had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.119#thought of this orderly arrangement formerly, in Madame Hédouin's narrow
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.120#shop; and now he felt his faith shaken, just as he carried out his idea.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.121#Suddenly he cried out that they would “have to alter all that.” They had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.122#forty-eight hours, and half what had been done had to be changed. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.123#staff, frightened, bewildered, had been obliged to work two nights and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.124#the entire Sunday, amidst a frightful disorder. On the Monday morning
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.125#even, an hour before the opening, there was still some goods to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.126#placed. Decidedly the governor was going mad, no one understood, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.127#general consternation prevailed.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.128#[Illustration: 0355]
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.129#“Come, look sharp!” cried Mouret, with the quiet assurance of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.130#genius. “There are some more costumes to be taken upstairs. And the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.131#Japan goods, are they placed on the central landing? A last effort, my
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.132#boys, you'll see the sale by-and-by.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.133#Bourdoncle had also been there since daybreak. He did not understand any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.134#more than the others, and he followed the governor's movements with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.135#an anxious eye. He hardly dared to ask him any questions, knowing how
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.136#Mouret received people in these critical moments. However, he at last
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.137#made up his mind, and gently asked: “Was it really necessary to upset
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.138#everything like that, on the eve of our sale?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.139#At first Mouret shrugged his shoulders without replying. Then as the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.140#other persisted, he burst out: “So that all the customers should heap
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.141#themselves into one corner--eh? A nice idea of mine! I should never have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.142#got over it! Don't you see that it would have localised the crowd. A
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.143#woman would have come in, gone straight to the department she wished,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.144#passed from the petticoat counter to the dress one, from the dress to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.145#the mantle, then retired, without having even lost herself for a moment?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.146#Not one would have thoroughly seen the establishment!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.147#“But,” remarked Bourdoncle, “now that you have disarranged everything,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.148#and thrown the goods all over the place, the employees will wear out
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.149#their legs in guiding the customers from department to department.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.150#Mouret gave a look of superb contempt. “I don't care a hang for that!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.151#They're young, it'll make them grow! So much the better if they do walk
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.152#about! They'll appear more numerous, and increase the crowd. The greater
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.153#the crush the better; all will go well!” He laughed, and deigned to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.154#explain his idea, lowering his voice: “Look here, Bourdoncle, listen to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.155#the result. Firstly, this continual circulation of customers disperses
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.156#them all over the shop, multiplies them, and makes them lose their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.157#heads; secondly, as they must be conducted from one end of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.158#establishment to the other, if they want, for instance, a lining after
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.159#having bought a dress, these journeys in every direction triple the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.160#size of the house in their eyes; thirdly, they are forced to traverse
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.161#departments where they would never have set foot otherwise, temptations
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.162#present themselves on their passage, and they succumb; fourthly----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.163#Bourdoncle was now laughing with him. At this Mouret, delighted, stopped
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.164#to call out to the messengers: “Very good, my boys! now for a sweep, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.165#it'll be splendid!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.166#But on turning round he perceived Denise. He and Bourdoncle were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.167#opposite the ready-made department, which he had just dismembered by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.168#sending the dresses and costumes up on the second-floor at the other
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.169#end of the building. Denise, the first down, was opening her eyes with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.170#astonishment, quite bewildered by the new arrangements.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.171#“What is it?” murmured she; “are we going to move?” This surprise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.172#appeared to amuse Mouret, who adored these sensational effects. Early in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.173#February Denise had returned to The Ladies' Paradise, where she had been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.174#agreeably surprised to find the staff polite, almost respectful. Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.175#Aurélie especially was very kind; Marguerite and Clara seemed resigned;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.176#even down to old Jouve, who also bowed his head, with an awkward
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.177#embarrassed air, as if desirous of effacing the disagreeable memory of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.178#the past. It sufficed that Mouret had said a few words, everybody
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.179#was whispering, following her with their eyes. And in this general
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.180#amiability, the only things that wounded her were Deloche's singularly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.181#melancholy looks, and Paulines inexplicable smiles. However, Mouret was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.182#still looking at her in his delighted way.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.183#“What is it you want, mademoiselle?” asked he at last.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.184#Denise had noticed him. She blushed slightly. Since her return she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.185#received marks of kindness from him which greatly touched her. Pauline,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.186#without her knowing why, had given her a full account of the governor's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.187#and Clara's love affairs: where he saw her, and what he paid her; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.188#she often returned to the subject, even adding that he had another
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.189#mistress, that Madame Desforges, well known by all the shop. Such
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.190#stories stirred up Denise, she felt in his presence all her former
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.191#fears, an uneasiness in which her gratitude was struggling against her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.192#anger.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.193#“It's all this confusion going on in the place,” she murmured.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.194#Mouret then approached her and said in a lower voice:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.195#“Have the goodness to come to my office this evening after business. I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.196#wish to speak to you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.197#Greatly agitated, she bowed her head without saying a word. And she went
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.198#into the department where the other saleswomen were now arriving. But
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.199#Bourdoncle had overheard Mouret, and he looked at him with a smile. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.200#even ventured to say when they were alone:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.201#“That girl again! Be careful; it will end by being serious!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.202#Mouret hastily defended himself, concealing his emotion beneath an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.203#air of superior indifference. “Never fear, it's only a joke! The woman
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.204#who'll catch me isn't born, my dear fellow!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.205#And as the shop was opening at last, he rushed off to give a final look
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.206#at the various counters. Bourdoncle shook his head. This Denise, so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.207#simple and quiet, began to make him uneasy. The first time, he had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.208#conquered by a brutal dismissal. But she had reappeared, and he felt she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.209#had become so strong that he now treated her as a redoubtable adversary,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.210#remaining mute before her, patiently waiting. Mouret, whom he caught up,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.211#was shouting out downstairs, in the Saint-Augustin Hall, opposite the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.212#entrance door:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.213#“Are you playing with me? I ordered the blue parasols to be put as a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.214#border. Just pull all that down, and be quick about it!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.215#He would listen to nothing; a gang of messengers had to come and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.216#re-arrange the exhibition of parasols. Seeing the customers arriving, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.217#even had the doors closed for a moment, declaring that he would not open
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.218#them, rather than have the blue parasols in the centre. It ruined his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.219#composition. The renowned dressers, Hutin, Mignot, and others, came to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.220#look, and opened their eyes; but they affected not to understand, being
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.221#of a different school.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.222#At last the doors were opened again, and the crowd flowed in. From the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.223#first, before the shop was full, there was such a crush at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.224#doorway that they were obliged to call the police to re-establish the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.225#circulation on the pavement. Mouret had calculated correctly; all the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.226#housekeepers, a compact troop of middle-class women and workmen's wives,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.227#swarmed around the bargains and remnants displayed in the open street.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.228#They felt the “hung” goods at the entrance; a calico at seven sous,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.229#a wool and cotton grey stuff at nine sous, and, above all, an Orleans
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.230#cloth at seven sous and half, which was emptying the poorer purses.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.231#There was an elbowing, a feverish crushing around the shelves and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.232#baskets containing the articles at reduced prices, lace at two sous,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.233#ribbon at five, garters at three the pair, gloves, petticoats, cravats,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.234#cotton socks, and stockings, were all tumbled about, and disappearing,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.235#as if swallowed up by the voracious crowd. Notwithstanding the cold, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.236#shopmen who were selling in the open street could not serve fast enough.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.237#A woman in the family way cried out with pain; two little girls were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.238#nearly stifled.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.239#All the morning this crush went on increasing. Towards one o'clock there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.240#was a crowd waiting to enter; the street was blocked as in a time of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.241#riot. Just at that moment, as Madame de Boves and her daughter Blanche
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.242#were standing on the pavement opposite, hesitating, they were accosted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.243#by Madame Marty, also accompanied by her daughter Valentine.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.244#“What a crowd--eh?” said the former. “They're killing themselves inside.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.245#I ought not to have come, I was in bed, but got up to get a little fresh
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.246#air.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.247#“Just like me,” said the other. “I promised my husband to go and see his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.248#sister at Montmartre. Then just as I was passing, I thought of a piece
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.249#of braid I wanted. I may as well buy it here as anywhere else, mayn't I?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.250#Oh, I sha'n't spend a sou! in fact I don't want anything.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.251#However, they did not take their eyes off the door, seized and carried
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.252#away as it were by the force of the crowd.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.253#“No, no, I'm not going in, I'm afraid,” murmured Madame de Boves.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.254#“Blanche, let's go away, we should be crushed.” But her voice failed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.255#she was gradually yielding to the desire to follow the others; and her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.256#fear dissolved in the irresistible attraction of the crush. Madame Marty
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.257#was also giving way, repeating:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.258#“Keep hold of my dress, Valentine. Ah, well! I've never seen such a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.259#thing before. You are lifted off your feet. What will it be like inside?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.260#The ladies, seized by the current, could not now go back. As streams
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.261#attract to themselves the fugitive waters of a valley, so it seemed that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.262#the wave of customers, flowing into the vestibule, was absorbing the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.263#passers-by, drinking in the population from the four corners of Paris.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.264#They advanced but slowly, squeezed almost to death, kept upright by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.265#shoulders and bellies around them, of which they felt the close heat;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.266#and their satisfied desire enjoyed the painful entrance which incited
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.267#still further their curiosity. There was a pell-mell of ladies arrayed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.268#in silk, of poorly dressed middle-class women, and of bare-headed girls,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.269#all excited and carried away by the same passion. A few men buried
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.270#beneath the overflow of bosoms were casting anxious glances around them.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.271#A nurse, in the thickest of the crowd, held her baby above her head, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.272#youngster crowing with delight. The only one to get angry was a skinny
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.273#woman, who broke out into bad words, accusing her neighbour of digging
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.274#right into her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.275#“I really think I shall lose my skirts in this crowd,” remarked Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.276#de Boves.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.277#Mute, her face still fresh from the open air, Madame Marty was standing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.278#on tip-toe to see above the others' heads into the depths of the shop.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.279#The pupils of her grey eyes were as contracted as those of a cat coming
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.280#out of the broad daylight; she had the reposed flesh, and the clear
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.281#expression of a person just waking up.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.282#“Ah, at last!” said she, heaving a sigh.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.283#The ladies had just extricated themselves. They were in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.284#Saint-Augustin Hall, which they were greatly surprised to find almost
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.285#empty. But a feeling of comfort invaded them, they seemed to be entering
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.286#into spring-time after emerging from the winter of the street. Whilst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.287#outside, the frozen wind, laden with rain and hail, was still blowing,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.288#the fine season, in The Paradise galleries, was already budding forth
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.289#with the light stuffs, the flowery brilliancy of the tender shades, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.290#rural gaiety of the summer dresses and the parasols.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.291#“Do look there!” exclaimed Madame de Boves, standing motionless, her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.292#eyes in the air.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.293#It was the exhibition of parasols. Wide-open, rounded off like shields,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.294#they covered the whole hall, from the glazed roof to the varnished oak
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.295#mouldings below. They described festoons round the semi-circular arches
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.296#of the upper storeys; they descended in garlands along the slender
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.297#columns; they ran along in close lines on the balustrades of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.298#galleries and the staircases; and everywhere, ranged symmetrically,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.299#speckling the walls with red, green, and yellow, they looked like great
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.300#Venetian lanterns, lighted up for some colossal entertainment. In the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.301#corners were more complicated patterns, stars composed of parasols at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.302#thirty-nine sous, the light shades of which, pale-blue, cream-white, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.303#blush rose, seemed to burn with the sweetness of a night-light; whilst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.304#up above, immense Japanese parasols, on which golden-coloured cranes
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.305#soared in a purple sky, blazed forth with the reflections of a great
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.306#conflagration.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.307#Madame Marty endeavoured to find a phrase to express her rapture, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.308#could only exclaim, “It's like fairyland!” Then trying to find out
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.309#where she was she continued: “Let's see, the braid is in the mercery
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.310#department. I shall buy my braid and be off.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.311#“I will go with you,” said Madame de Boves. “Eh? Blanche, we'll just go
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.312#through the shop, nothing more.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.313#But they had hardly left the door before they lost themselves. They
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.314#turned to the left, and as the mercery department had been moved, they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.315#dropped right into the middle of the one devoted to collarettes, cuffs,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.316#trimmings, &c. It was very warm under the galleries, a hot-house heat,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.317#moist and close, laden with the insipid odour of the stuffs, and in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.318#which the stamping of the crowd was stifled. They then returned to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.319#door, where an outward current was already established, an interminable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.320#line of women and children, over whom floated a multitude of red
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.321#air-balls. Forty thousand of these were ready; there were men specially
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.322#placed for their distribution. To see the customers who were going out,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.323#one would have thought there was a flight of enormous soap-bubbles above
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.324#them, at the end of the almost invisible strings, reflecting the fiery
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.325#glare of the parasols. The whole place was illuminated by them.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.326#“There's quite a world here!” declared Madame de Boves. “You hardly know
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.327#where you are.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.328#However, the ladies could not remain in the eddy of the door, right in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.329#the crush of the entrance and exit. Fortunately, Jouve, the inspector,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.330#came to their assistance. He stood in the vestibule, grave, attentive,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.331#eyeing each woman as she passed. Specially charged with the inside
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.332#police, he was on the lookout for thieves, and especially followed women
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.333#in the family way, when the fever of their eyes became too alarming.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.334#“The mercery department, ladies?” said he obligingly, “turn to the left;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.335#look! just there behind the hosiery department.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.336#Madame de Boves thanked him. But Madame Marty, turning round, no
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.337#longer saw her daughter Valentine beside her. She was beginning to feel
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.338#frightened, when she caught sight of her, already a long way off, at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.339#end of the Saint-Augustin Hall, deeply absorbed before a table covered
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.340#with a heap of women's cravats at nineteen sous. Mouret practised the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.341#system of offering articles to the customers, hooking and plundering
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.342#them as they passed; for he used every sort of advertisement, laughing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.343#at the discretion of certain fellow-tradesmen who thought the articles
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.344#should be left to speak for themselves. Special salesmen, idle and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.345#smooth-tongued Parisians, thus got rid of considerable quantities of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.346#small trashy things.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.347#“Oh, mamma!” murmured Valentine, “just look at these cravats. They have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.348#a bird embroidered at the corners.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.349#The shopman cracked up the article, swore it was all silk, that the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.350#manufacturer had become bankrupt, and that they would never have such a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.351#bargain again.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.352#“Nineteen sous--is it possible?” said Madame Marty, tempted as well as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.353#her daughter. “Well! I can take a couple, that won't ruin us.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.354#Madame de Boves disdained this style of thing, she detested things
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.355#being offered. A shopman calling her made her run away. Madame Marty,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.356#surprised, could not understand this nervous horror of commercial
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.357#quackery, for she was of another nature; she was one of those fortunate
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.358#women who delight in being thus violated, in bathing in the caress of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.359#this public offering, with the enjoyment of plunging one's hands in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.360#everything, and wasting one's time in useless talk.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.361#“Now,” she said, “I'm going for my braid. I don't wish to see anything
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.362#else.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.363#However, as she crossed the cravat and glove departments, her heart once
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.364#more failed her. There was, under the diffuse light, a display made
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.365#up of bright and gay colours, which produced a ravishing effect The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.366#counters, symmetrically arranged, seemed like so many flower-borders,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.367#changing the hall into a French garden, in which smiled a tender gamut
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.368#of blossoms. Lying on the bare wood, in open boxes, and protruding from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.369#the overflowing drawers, a quantity of silk hand-kerchiefs displayed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.370#the bright scarlet of the geranium, the creamy white of the petunia,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.371#the golden yellow of the chrysanthemum, the sky-blue of the verbena; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.372#higher up, on brass stems, twined another florescence, fichus carelessly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.373#hung, ribbons unrolled, quite a brilliant cordon, which extended along,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.374#climbed up the columns, and were multiplied indefinitely by the mirrors.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.375#But what most attracted the crowd was a Swiss cottage in the glove
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.376#department, made entirely of gloves, a chef d'ouvre of Mignot's, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.377#had taken him two days to arrange. In the first place, the ground-floor
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.378#was composed of black gloves; then came straw-coloured, mignonette,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.379#and red gloves, distributed in the decoration, bordering the windows,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.380#forming the balconies, and taking the place of the tiles.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.381#“What do you desire, madame?” asked Mignot, on seeing Madame Marty
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.382#planted before the cottage. “Here are some Swedish kid gloves at one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.383#franc fifteen sous, first quality.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.384#He offered his wares with furious energy, calling the passing customers
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.385#from the end of his counter, dunning them with his politeness. As she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.386#shook her head in refusal he confined: “Tyrolian gloves, one franc five
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.387#sous. Turin gloves for children, embroidered gloves in all colours.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.388#“No, thanks; I don't want anything,” declared Madame Marty.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.389#But feeling that her voice was softening, he attacked her with greater
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.390#energy than ever, holding the embroidered gloves before her eyes; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.391#she could not resist, she bought a pair. Then, as Madame de Boves looked
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.392#at her with a smile, she blushed.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.393#“Don't you think me childish--eh? If I don't make haste and get my braid
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.394#and be off, I shall be done for.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.395#Unfortunately, there was such a crush in the mercery department that she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.396#could not get served. They had both been waiting for over ten minutes,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.397#and were getting annoyed, when the sudden meeting with Madame Bourdelais
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.398#occupied their attention. The latter explained, with her quiet practical
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.399#air, that she had just brought the little ones to see the show.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.400#Madeleine was ten, Edmond eight, and Lucien four years old; and they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.401#were laughing with joy, it was a cheap treat long promised.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.402#“They are really too comical; I shall buy a red parasol,” said Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.403#Marty all at once, stamping with impatience at being there doing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.404#nothing.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.405#She choose one at fourteen francs and a-half. Madame Bourdelais, after
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.406#having watched the purchase with a look of blame, said to her amicably:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.407#“You are very wrong to be in such a hurry. In a month's time you could
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.408#have had it for ten francs. They won't catch me like that.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.409#And she developed quite a theory of careful housekeeping. As the shops
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.410#lowered their prices, it was simply a question of waiting. She did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.411#wish to be taken in by them, so she preferred to take advantage of their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.412#real bargains. She even showed a feeling of malice in the struggle,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.413#boasting that she had never left them a sou profit.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.414#“Come,” said she at last, “I've promised my little ones to show them the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.415#pictures upstairs in the reading-room. Come up with us, you have plenty
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.416#of time.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.417#And the braid was forgotten. Madame Marty yielded at once, whilst Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.418#de Boves refused, preferring to take a turn on the ground-floor first.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.419#Besides, they were sure to meet again upstairs. Madame Bourdelais was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.420#looking for a staircase when she perceived one of the lifts; and she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.421#pushed her children in to complete their pleasure. Madame Marty and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.422#Valentine also entered the narrow cage, where they were closely packed;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.423#but the mirrors, the velvet seats, and the polished brasswork took up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.424#their attention so much that they arrived at the first storey without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.425#having felt the gentle ascent of the machine. Another pleasure was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.426#in store for them, in the first gallery. As they passed before the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.427#refreshment bar, Madame Bourdelais did not fail to gorge her little
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.428#family with syrup. It was a square room with a large marble counter;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.429#at the two ends there were silvered fountains from which flowed a small
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.430#stream of water; whilst rows of bottles stood on small shelves behind.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.431#Three waiters were continually engaged wiping and filling the glasses.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.432#To restrain the thirsty crowd, they had been obliged to establish a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.433#system of turns, as at theatres and railway-stations, by erecting a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.434#barrier covered with velvet. The crush was terrific. Some people, losing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.435#all shame before these gratuitous treats, made themselves ill.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.436#“Well! where are they?” exclaimed Madame Bourdelais when she extricated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.437#herself from the crowd, after having wiped the children's faces with her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.438#handkerchief.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.439#But she caught sight of Madame Marty and Valentine at the further end
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.440#of another gallery, a long way off. Both buried beneath a heap of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.441#petticoats, were still buying. They were conquered, the mother and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.442#daughter were rapidly disappearing in the fever of spending which was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.443#carrying them away. When she at last arrived in the reading-room Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.444#Bourdelais installed Madeleine, Edmond, and Lucien before the large
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.445#table; then taking from one of the shelves some photographic albums she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.446#brought them to them. The ceiling of the long apartment was covered
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.447#with gold; at the two extremities, monumental chimney-pieces faced each
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.448#other; some rather poor pictures, very richly framed, covered the walls;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:ix.449#and between the columns before each of the arched bays opening into the
