urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.219#Nine o'clock struck. Outside, an ardent blue sky was warming the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.220#streets.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.221#Cabs were rolling toward the railway stations, the whole population
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.222#dressed out in Sunday clothes, was streaming in long rows towards the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.223#suburban woods.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.224#Inside the building, inundated with sun through the large open bays, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.225#cooped-up staff had just commenced the stocktaking. They had closed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.226#the doors; people stopped on the pavement, looking through the windows,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.227#astonished at this shutting-up when an extraordinary activity was going
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.228#on inside. There was, from one end of the galleries to the other, from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.229#the top floor to the bottom, a continual movement of employees, their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.230#arms in the air, and parcels flying about above their heads; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.231#all this amidst a tempest of cries and a calling out of prices, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.232#confusion of which ascended and became a deafening roar. Each of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.233#thirty-nine departments did its work apart, without troubling about its
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.234#neighbour. At this early hour the shelves had hardly been touched, there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.235#were only a few bales of goods on the floors; the machine would have to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.236#get up more steam if they were to finish that evening.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.237#“Why have you come down?” asked Marguerite of Denise, good-naturedly.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.238#“You'll only make yourself worse, and we are quite enough to do the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.239#work.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.240#“That's what I told her,” declared Madame Aurélie, “but she insisted on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.241#coming down to help us.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.242#All the young ladies flocked round Denise. The work was interrupted even
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.243#for a time. They complimented her, listening with various exclamations
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.244#to the story of her sprained ankle. At last Madame Aurélie made her sit
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.245#down at a table; and it was understood that she should merely write
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.246#down the articles as they were called out. On such a day as this they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.247#requisitioned any employee capable of holding a pen: the inspectors, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.248#cashiers, the clerks, even down to the shop messengers; and the various
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.249#departments divided amongst themselves these assistants of a day to get
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.250#the work over quicker. It was thus that Denise found herself installed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.251#near Lhomme the cashier and Joseph the messenger, both bending over
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.252#large sheets of paper.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.253#“Five mantles, cloth, fur trimming, third size, at two hundred and forty
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.254#francs!” cried Marguerite. “Four ditto, first size, at two hundred and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.255#twenty!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.256#The work once more commenced. Behind Marguerite three saleswomen were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.257#emptying the cupboards, classifying the articles, giving them to her in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.258#bundles; and, when she had called them out, she threw them on the table,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.259#where they were gradually heaping up in enormous piles. Lhomme wrote
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.260#down the articles, Joseph kept another list for the clearinghouse.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.261#Whilst this was going on, Madame Aurélie herself, assisted by three
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.262#other saleswomen, was counting the silk garments, which Denise entered
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.263#on the sheets. Clara was employed in looking after the heaps, to arrange
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.264#them in such a manner that they should occupy the least space possible
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.265#on the tables. But she was not paying much attention to her work, for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.266#the heaps were already tumbling down.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.267#“I say,” asked she of a little saleswoman who had joined that winter,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.268#“are they going to give you a rise? You know the second-hand is to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.269#have two thousand francs, which, with her commission, will bring her in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.270#nearly seven thousand.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.271#The little saleswoman, without ceasing to pass some cloaks down, replied
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.272#that if they didn't give her eight hundred francs she would take her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.273#hook. The rises were always given the day after the stock-taking; it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.274#was also the epoch at which, the amount of business done during the year
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.275#being known, the managers of the departments drew their commission on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.276#the increase of this figure, compared with that of the preceding year.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.277#Thus, notwithstanding the bustle and uproar of the work, the impassioned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.278#gossiping went on everywhere. Between two articles called out, they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.279#talked of nothing but money. The rumour ran that Madame Aurélie would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.280#exceed twenty-five thousand francs; and this immense sum greatly excited
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.281#the young ladies. Marguerite, the best saleswoman after Denise, had made
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.282#four thousand five hundred francs, fifteen hundred francs salary, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.283#about three thousand francs commission; whilst Clara had not made two
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.284#thousand five hundred francs altogether.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.285#“I don't care a button for their rises!” resumed the latter, still
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.286#talking to the little saleswoman. “If papa were dead, I would jolly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.287#soon clear out of this! But what exasperates me is to see seven thousand
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.288#francs given to that strip of a girl! What do you say?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.289#Madame Aurélie violently interrupted the conversation, turning round
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.290#with her imperial air. “Be quiet, young ladies! We can't hear ourselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.291#speak, my word of honour!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.292#Then she resumed calling out: “Seven mantles, old style, Sicilian, first
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.293#size, at a hundred and thirty! Three pelisses, surah, second size, at a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.294#hundred and fifty! Have you got that down, Mademoiselle Baudu?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.295#“Yes, madame.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.296#Clara then had to look after the armfuls of garments piled on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.297#tables. She pushed them about, and made more room. But she soon left
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.298#them again to reply to a salesman, who was looking for her. It was the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.299#glover, Mignot, escaped from his department. He whispered a request for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.300#twenty francs; he already owed her thirty, a loan effected the day after
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.301#a race, after having lost his week's salary on a horse; this time he had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.302#squandered his commission, drawn over night, and had not ten sous for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.303#his Sunday. Clara had only ten francs about her, which she lent him with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.304#a fairly good grace. And they went on talking, spoke of a party of six,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.305#indulged in at a restaurant at Bougival, where the women had paid their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.306#share: it was much better, they all felt perfectly at their ease like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.307#that. Then Mignot, who wanted his twenty francs, went and bent over
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.308#Lhomme's shoulder. The latter, stopped in his writing, appeared greatly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.309#troubled. However, he dared not refuse, and was looking for the money
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.310#in his purse, when Madame Aurélie, astonished not to hear Marguerite's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.311#voice, which had been interrupted, perceived Mignot, and understood at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.312#once. She roughly sent him back to his department, saying she didn't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.313#want any one to come and distract her young ladies from their work. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.314#truth is, she dreaded this young man, a bosom friend of Albert's, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.315#accomplice of his doubtful tricks, which she trembled to see turn out
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.316#badly some day. Therefore, when Mignot had got his ten francs, and had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.317#run away, she could not help saying to her husband:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.318#“Is it possible to let a fellow like that get over you!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.319#“But, my dear, I really could not refuse the young man.” She closed his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.320#mouth with a shrug of her substantial shoulders. Then, as the saleswomen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.321#were slyly grinning at this family explanation, she resumed with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.322#severity: “Now, Mademoiselle Vadon, don't let's go to sleep.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.323#“Twenty cloaks, cashmere extra, fourth size, at eighteen francs and a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.324#half,” resumed Marguerite in her sing-song voice.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.325#Lhomme, with his head bowed down, had resumed writing. They had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.326#gradually raised his salary to nine thousand francs a year; and he was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.327#very humble before Madame Aurélie, who still brought nearly triple as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.328#much into the family.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.329#For a while the work pushed forward. Figures flew about, the parcels
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.330#of garments rained thick and fast on the tables, But Clara had invented
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.331#another amusement: she was teasing the messenger, Joseph, about
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.332#a passion that he was said to nourish for a young lady in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.333#pattern-room. This young lady, already twenty-eight years old, thin and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.334#pale, was a protege of Madame Desforges, who had wanted to make Mouret
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.335#engage her as a saleswoman, backing up her recommendation with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.336#touching story: an orphan, the last of the De Fontenailles, an old and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.337#noble family of Poitou, thrown into the streets of Paris with a drunken
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.338#father, but yet virtuous amidst this misfortune, with an education too
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.339#limited, unfortunately, to take a place as governess or music-mistress.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.340#Mouret generally got angry when any one recommended to him these
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.341#broken-down gentlewomen; there was not, said he, a class of creatures
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.342#more incapable, more insupportable, more narrow-minded than these
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.343#gentlewomen; and, besides, a saleswoman could not be improvised,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.344#she must serve an apprenticeship, it was a complicated and delicate
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.345#business. However, he took Madame Desforges's protege, but put her in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.346#the pattern-room, in the same way as he had already found places, to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.347#oblige friends, for two countesses and a baroness in the advertising
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.348#department, where they addressed envelopes, etc. Mademoiselle de
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.349#Fontenailles earned three francs a day, which just enabled her to live
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.350#in her modest room, in the Rue d'Argenteuil. It was on seeing her, with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.351#her sad look and such shabby clothes, that Joseph's heart, very tender
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.352#under his rough soldier's manner, had been touched. He did not confess,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.353#but he blushed, when the young ladies in the ready-made department
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.354#chaffed him; for the pattern-room was not far off, and they had often
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.355#observed him prowling about the doorway.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.356#“Joseph is somewhat absent-minded,” murmured Clara. “His nose is always
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.357#turned towards the under-linen department.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.358#They had requisitioned Mademoiselle de Fontenailles there, and she was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.359#assisting at the outfitting counter. As the messenger was continually
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.360#glancing in that direction, the saleswomen began to laugh. He became
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.361#very confused, and plunged into his accounts; whilst Marguerite, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.362#order to arrest the flood of gaiety which was tickling her throat, cried
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.363#out louder stills “Fourteen jackets, English cloth, second size, at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.364#fifteen francs!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.365#At this, Madame Aurélie, who was engaged in calling out some cloaks,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.366#could not make herself heard. She interfered with a wounded air, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.367#a majestic slowness: “A little softer, mademoiselle. We are not in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.368#market. And you are all very unreasonable, to be amusing yourselves with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.369#these childish matters, when our time is so precious.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.370#Just at that moment, as Clara was not paying any attention to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.371#parcels, a catastrophe took place. Some mantles tumbled down, and all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.372#the heaps on the tables, dragged down with them, fell one after the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.373#other, so that the carpet was strewn with them.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.374#“There! what did I say!” cried the first-hand, beside herself. “Pray be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.375#more careful, Mademoiselle Prunaire; it's intolerable!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.376#But a hum ran along: Mouret and Bourdoncle, making their round of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.377#inspection, had just appeared. The voices started again, the pens
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.378#sputtered along, whilst Clara hastened to pick up the garments. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.379#governor did not interrupt the work. He stood there several minutes,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.380#mute, smiling; and it was on his lips alone that a slight feverish
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.381#shivering was visible in his gay and victorious face of stock-taking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.382#days. When he perceived Denise, he nearly gave way to a gesture of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.383#astonishment. She had come down, then? His eyes met Madame Aurélie's.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.384#Then, after a moment's hesitation, he went away into the under-linen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.385#department.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.386#However, Denise, warned by the slight noise, had raised her head. And,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.387#after having recognised Mouret, she had immediately bent over her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.388#work again, without ostentation. Since she had been writing in this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.389#mechanical way, amidst the regular calling-out of the articles, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.390#peaceful feeling had stolen over her. She had always yielded thus to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.391#the first excesses of her sensitiveness: the tears suffocated her,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.392#her passion doubled her torments; then she regained her self-command,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.393#finding a grand, calm courage, a strength of will, quiet but inexorable.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.394#Now, with her limpid eyes, and pale complexion, she was free from all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.395#agitation, entirely given up to her work, resolved to crush her heart
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.396#and to do nothing but her will.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.397#Ten o'clock struck, the uproar of the stock-taking was increasing in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.398#activity of the departments. And amidst the cries incessantly raised,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.399#crossing each other on all sides, the same news was circulating with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.400#surprising rapidity: every salesman knew that Mouret had written that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.401#morning inviting Denise to dinner. The indiscretion came from Pauline.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.402#On going downstairs, still excited, she had met Deloche in the lace
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.403#department, and, without noticing that Liénard was talking to the young
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.404#man, she immediately relieved her mind of the secret.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.405#“It's done, my dear fellow. She's just received a letter. He invites her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.406#for this evening.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.407#Deloche turned very pale. He had understood, for he often questioned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.408#Pauline; they spoke of their common friend every day, of Mouret's love
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.409#for her, of the famous invitation which would finish by bringing the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.410#adventure to an issue. She frequently scolded him for his secret love
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.411#for Denise, with whom he would never succeed, and she shrugged her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.412#shoulders whenever he expressed his approval of the girl's conduct in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.413#resisting the governor.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.414#“Her foot's better, she's coming down,” continued Pauline.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.415#“Pray don't put on that funeral face. It's a piece of good luck for her,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.416#this invitation.” And she hastened back to her department.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.417#“Ah! good!” murmured Liénard, who had heard all, “you're talking about
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.418#the young girl with the sprain. You were quite right to be so quick in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.419#defending her last night at the café!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.420#He also ran off; but before he had returned to the woollen department,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.421#he had already related the story to four or five fellows. In less than
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.422#ten minutes, it had gone the round of the whole shop.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.423#Liénard's last remark referred to a scene which had taken place the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.424#previous evening, at the Café Saint-Roch. Deloche and he were now
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.425#constantly together. The former had taken Hutin's room at the Hôtel de
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.426#Smyme, when that gentleman, appointed second-hand, had hired a suite of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.427#three rooms; and the two shopmen came to The Ladies' Paradise together
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.428#in the morning, and waited for each other in the evening in order to go
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.429#away together. Their rooms, which were next door to each other, looked
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.430#into the same black yard, a narrow well, the odour from which poisoned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.431#the hôtel. They got on very well together, notwithstanding their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.432#difference of character, the one carelessly squandering the money he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.433#drew from his father, the other penniless, perpetually tortured by ideas
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.434#of saving, both having, however, a point in common, their unskilfulness
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.435#as salesmen, which left them to vegetate at their counters, without any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.436#increase of salary. After leaving the shop, they spent the greater part
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.437#of their time at the Café Saint-Roch. Quite free from customers during
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.438#the day, this café filled up about halfpast eight with an overflowing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.439#crowd of employees, that crowd of shopmen disgorged into the street from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.440#the great door in the Place Gaillon. Then burst forth a deafening uproar
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.441#of clinking dominoes, bursts of laughter and yelping voices, amidst the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.442#thick smoke of the pipes. Beer and coffee were in great demand. Seated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.443#in the left-hand corner, Liénard went in for the dearest drinks, whilst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.444#Deloche contented himself with a glass of beer, which he would take
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.445#four hours to drink. It was there that the latter had heard Favier, at a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.446#neighbouring table, relate some abominable things about Denise, the way
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.447#in which she had “hooked” the governor, by pulling her dress up whenever
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.448#she went upstairs in front of him. He had with difficulty restrained
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.449#himself from striking him. Then, as the other went off, saying that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.450#the young girl went down every night to join her lover, he called him a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.451#liar, feeling mad with rage.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.452#“What a blackguard! It's a lie, it's a lie, I tell you!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.453#And in the emotion which was agitating him, he let out too much, with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.454#stammering voice, entirely opening his heart.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.455#“I know her, and it isn't true. She has never had any affection except
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.456#for one man; yes, for Monsieur Hutin, and even he has never noticed it,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.457#he can't even boast of ever having as much as touched her.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.458#The report of this quarrel, exaggerated, misconstrued, was already
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.459#affording amusement for the whole shop, when the story of Mouret's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.460#letter was circulated. In fact, it was to a salesman in the silk
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.461#department that Liénard first confided the news. With the silk-vendors
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.462#the stock-taking was going on rapidly. Favier and two shopmen, mounted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.463#on stools, were emptying the shelves, passing the pieces of stuff to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.464#Hutin as they went on, the latter, standing on a table, calling out the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.465#figures, after consulting the tickets; and he then dropped the pieces,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.466#which, rising slowly like an autumn tide, were gradually encumbering the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.467#floor. Other men were writing, Albert Lhomme was also helping them,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.468#his face pale and heavy after a night spent in a low public-house at La
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.469#Chapelle. A ray of sun fell from the glazed roof of the hall, through
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.470#which could be seen the ardent blue of the sky.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.471#“Draw those blinds!” cried out Bouthemont, very busy superintending the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.472#work. “The sun is unbearable!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.473#Favier, who was stretching to reach a piece, grumbled under his breath:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.474#“A nice thing to shut people up a lovely day like this! No fear of it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.475#raining on a stock-taking day! And they keep us under lock and key like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.476#a lot of convicts when all Paris is out-doors!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.477#He passed the piece to Hutin. On the ticket was the measurement,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.478#diminished at each sale by the quantity sold, which greatly simplified
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.479#the work. The second-hand cried out: “Fancy silk, small check,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.480#twenty-one yards, at six francs and a half.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.481#And the silk went to increase the heap on the floor. Then he continued
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.482#a conversation commenced, by saying to Favier: “So he wanted to fight
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.483#you?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.484#“Yes, I was quietly drinking my glass of beer. It was hardly worth
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.485#while contradicting me, she has just received a letter from the governor
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.486#inviting her to dinner. The whole shop is talking about it.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.487#“What! it wasn't done!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.488#Favier handed him another piece.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.489#“A caution, isn't it? One would have staked his life on it. It seemed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.490#like an old connection.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.491#“Ditto, twenty-five yards!” cried Hutin.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.492#The dull thud of the piece was heard, whilst he added in a lower tone:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.493#“She carried on fearfully, you know, at that old fool Bourras's.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.494#The whole department was now joking about the affair, without, however,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.495#allowing the work to suffer. The young girl's name passed from mouth to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.496#mouth, the fellows arched their backs and winked. Bouthemont himself,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.497#who took a rare delight in such gay stories, could not help adding his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.498#joke, the bad taste of which filled his heart with joy. Albert,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.499#waking up a bit, swore he had seen Denise with two soldiers at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.500#Gros-Caillou. At that moment Mignot came down, with the twenty francs he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.501#had just borrowed, and he stopped to slip ten francs into Albert's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.502#hand, making an appointment with him for the evening; a projected lark,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.503#restrained for want of money, but still possible, notwithstanding the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.504#smallness of the sum. But handsome Mignot, when he heard about the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.505#famous letter, made such an abominable remark, that Bouthemont was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.506#obliged to interfere.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.507#“That's enough, gentlemen. It isn't our business. Go on, Monsiéur
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.508#Hutin.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.509#“Fancy silk, small check, thirty-two yards, at six francs and a half,”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.510# cried out the latter.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.511#The pens started off again, the parcels fell regularly, the flood of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.512#stuffs still increased, as if the overflow of a river had emptied itself
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.513#there. And the calling out of the fancy silks never ceased. Favier, in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.514#half whisper, remarked that the stock was in a nice state; the governors
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.515#would be enchanted; that big stupid of a Bouthemont might be the best
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.516#buyer in Paris, but as a salesman he was not worth his salt. Hutin
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.517#smiled, delighted, approving by a friendly look; for after having
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.518#himself introduced Bouthemont into The Ladies' Paradise, in order to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.519#drive out Robineau, he was now undermining him also, with the firm
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.520#intention of robbing him of his place. It was the same war as formerly,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.521#treacherous insinuations whispered in the partners' ears, an excessive
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.522#display of zeal in order to push one's-self forward, a regular campaign
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.523#carried on with affable cunning. However, Favier, towards whom Hutin was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.524#displaying some fresh condescension, took a look at the latter, thin and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.525#cold, with his bilious face, as if to count the mouthfuls in this short,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.526#squat little man, and looking as though he were waiting till his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.527#comrade had swallowed up Bouthemont, in order to eat him afterwards.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.528#He, Favier,' hoped to get the second-hand's place, should his friend be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.529#appointed manager. Then, they would see. And both, consumed by the fever
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.530#which was raging from one end of the shop to the other, talked of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.531#probable rises of salary, without ceasing to call out the stock of fancy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.532#silks; they felt sure Bouthemont would reach thirty thousand francs
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.533#that year; Hutin would exceed ten thousand; Favier estimated his pay and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.534#commission at five thousand five hundred. The amount of business in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.535#department was increasing yearly, the salesmen were promoted and their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.536#salaries doubled, like officers in time of war.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.537#“Won't those fancy silks soon be finished?” asked Bouthemont suddenly,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.538#with an annoyed air. “What a miserable spring, always raining! People
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.539#have bought nothing but black silks.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.540#His fat, jovial face became cloudy; he looked at the growing heap on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.541#floor, whilst Hutin called out louder still, in a sonorous voice, not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.542#free from triumph--“Fancy silks, small check, twenty-eight yards, at six
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.543#francs and a half.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.544#There was still another shelf-full. Favier, whose arms were beginning
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.545#to feel tired, was now going very slowly. As he handed Hutin the last
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.546#pieces he resumed in a low tone--“Oh! I say, I forgot. Have you heard
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.547#that the second-hand in the ready-made department once had a regular
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.548#fancy for you?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.549#The young man seemed greatly surprised. “What! How do you mean?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.550#“Yes, that great booby Deloche let it out to us. I remember her casting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.551#sheep's eyes at you some time back.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.552#Since his appointment as second-hand Hutin had thrown up his music-hall
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.553#singers and gone in for governesses. Greatly flattered at heart, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.554#replied with a scornful air, “I like them a little better stuffed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.555#my boy; besides, it won't do to take up with anybody, as the governor
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.556#does.” He stopped to call out--
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.557#“White Poult silk, thirty-five yards, at eight francs fifteen sous.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.558#“Oh! at last!” murmured Bouthemont, greatly relieved.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.559#But a bell rang, it was the second table, to which Favier belonged. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.560#got off the stool, another salesman took his place, and he was obliged
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.561#to step over the mountain of pieces of stuff with which the floor was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.562#encumbered. Similar heaps were scattered about in very department; the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.563#shelves, the boxes, the cupboards were being gradually emptied, whilst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.564#the goods were overflowing on every side, under-foot, between the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.565#counters and the tables, in a continual rising. In the linen department
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.566#was heard the heavy falling of the bales of calico; in the mercery
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.567#department there was a clicking of boxes; and distant rumbling sounds
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.568#came from the furniture department. Every sort of voice was heard
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.569#together, shrill voices, thick voices; figures whizzed through the air,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.570#a rustling clamour reigned in the immense nave--the clamour of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.571#forests in January when the wind is whistling through the branches.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.572#Favier at last got clear and went up the dining-room staircase. Since
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.573#the enlargement of The Ladies' Paradise the refectories had been shifted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.574#to the fourth storey in the new buildings. As he hurried up he came upon
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.575#Deloche and Liénard, so he fell back on Mignot, who was following on his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.576#heels.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.577#“The deuce!” said he, in the corridor leading to the kitchen, opposite
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.578#the blackboard on which the bill of fare was inscribed, “you can see
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.579#it's stock-taking day. A regular feast! Chicken, or leg of mutton, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.580#artichokes! Their mutton won't be much of a success!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.581#Mignot sniggered, murmuring, “Every one's going in for chicken, then!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.582#However, Deloche and Liénard had taken their portions and had gone away.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.583#Favier then leant over at the wicket and called out--“Chicken!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.584#But he had to wait; one of the kitchen helps had cut his finger in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.585#carving, and this caused some confusion. Favier stood there, with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.586#his face to the opening, looking into the kitchen with its giant
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.587#appliances--the central range, over which two rails fixed to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.588#ceiling brought forward, by a system of chains and pullies, the colossal
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.589#coppers, which four men could not have lifted. Several cooks, quite
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.590#white in the sombre red of the furnace, were attending to the evening
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.591#soup coppers, mounted on iron ladders, armed with skimmers fixed on long
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.592#handles. Then against the wall were grills large enough to roast
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.593#martyrs on, saucepans big enough to cook a whole sheep in, a monumental
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.594#plate-warmer, and a marble well kept full by a continual stream of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.595#water. To the left could be seen a washing-up place, stone sinks as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.596#large as ponds; whilst on the other side to the right, was an immense
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.597#meat-safe, in which some large joints of red meat were hanging on steel
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.598#hooks. A machine for peeling potatoes was working with the tic-tac of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.599#a mill. Two small trucks laden with freshly-picked salad were being
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.600#wheeled along by some kitchen helps into the fresh air under a fountain.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.601#“Chicken,” repeated Favier, getting impatient. Then, turning round, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.602#added in a lower tone, “There's one fellow cut himself. It's disgusting,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.603#it's running over the food.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.604#Mignot wanted to see. Quite a string of shopmen had now arrived; there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.605#was a good deal of laughing and pushing. The two young men, their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.606#heads at the wicket, exchanged their remarks before this phalansterian
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.607#kitchen, in which the least utensils, even the spits and larding pins,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.608#assumed gigantic proportions. Two thousand luncheons and two thousand
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.609#dinners had to be served, and the number of employees was increasing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.610#every week. It was quite an abyss, into which was thrown daily something
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.611#like forty-five bushels of potatoes, one hundred and twenty pounds of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.612#butter, and sixteen hundred pounds of meat; and at each meal they had to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.613#broach three casks of wine, over a hundred and fifty gallons were served
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.614#out at the wine counter.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.615#“Ah! at last!” murmured Favier when the cook reappeared with a large
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.616#pan, out of which he handed him the leg of a fowl.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.617#“Chicken,” said Mignot behind him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.618#And with their plates in their hands they both entered the refectory,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.619#after having taken their wine at the counter; whilst behind them the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.620#word “Chicken” was repeated without ceasing, regularly, and one could
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.621#hear the cook picking up the pieces with his fork with a rapid and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.622#measured sound.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.623#The men's dining-room was now an immense apartment, where places for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.624#five hundred at each of the three dinners could easily be laid. There
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.625#were long mahogany tables, placed parallel across the room, and at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.626#either end were similar tables reserved for the managers of departments
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.627#and the inspectors; whilst in the centre was a counter for the extras.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.628#Large windows, right and left, lighted up with a white light this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.629#gallery, of which the ceiling, notwithstanding its being four yards
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.630#high, seemed very low, crushed by the enormous development of the other
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.631#dimensions. The sole ornament on the walls, painted a light yellow,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.632#were the napkin cupboards. After this first refectory came that of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.633#the messengers and carmen, where the meals were served irregularly,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.634#according to the necessities of the work.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.635#“What! you've got a leg as well, Mignot?” said Favier, as he took his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.636#place at one of the tables opposite his companion.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.637#Other young men now sat down around them. There was no tablecloth, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.638#plates gave out a cracked sound on the bare mahogany, and every one was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.639#crying out in this particular corner, for the number of legs was really
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.640#prodigious.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.641#“These chickens are all legs!” remarked Mignot.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.642#Those who had pieces of the carcase were greatly discontented. However,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.643#the food had been much better since the late improvements. Mouret
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.644#no longer treated with a contractor at a fixed sum; he had taken the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.645#kitchen into his own hands, organising it like one of the departments,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.646#with a head-cook, under-cooks, and an inspector; and if he spent more
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.647#he got more work out of the staff--a practical humane calculation which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.648#long terrified Bourdoncle.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.649#“Mine is pretty tender, all the same,” said Mignot. “Pass over the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.650#bread!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.651#The big loaf was sent round, and after cutting a slice for himself he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.652#dug the knife into the crust A few dilatory ones now hurried in, taking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.653#their places; a ferocious appetite, increased by the morning's work,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.654#ran along the immense tables from one end to the other. There was an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.655#increasing clatter of forks, a sound of bottles being emptied, the noise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.656#of glasses laid down too violently, the grinding rumble of five hundred
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.657#pairs of powerful jaws working with wonderful energy. And the talk,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.658#still very rare, was stifled in the mouths full of food.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.659#Deloche, however, seated between Bauge and Liénard, found himself nearly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.660#opposite Favier. They had glanced at each other with a rancorous look.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.661#The neighbours whispered, aware of their quarrel the previous day.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.662#Then they laughed at poor Deloche's ill-luck, always famishing, always
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.663#falling on to the worst piece at table, by a sort of cruel fatality.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.664#This time he had come in for the neck of a chicken and bits of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.665#carcase. Without saying a word he let them joke away, swallowing large
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.666#mouthfuls of bread, and picking the neck with the infinite art of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.667#fellow who entertains a great respect for meat.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.668#“Why don't you complain?” asked Bauge.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.669#But he shrugged his shoulders. What would be the good? It was always the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.670#same. When he ventured to complain things went worse than ever.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.671#“You know the Bobbin fellows have got their club now,” said Mignot, all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.672#at once. “Yes, my boy, the 'Bobbin Club.' It's held at a tavern in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.673#Rue Saint-Honoré, where they hire a room on Saturdays.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.674#He was speaking of the mercery salesmen. The whole table began to joke.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.675#Between two mouthfuls, with his voice still thick, each one made some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.676#remark, added a detail; the obstinate readers alone remained mute,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.677#absorbed, their noses buried in some newspapers. It could not be denied;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.678#shopmen were gradually assuming a better style; nearly half of them now
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.679#spoke English or German. It was no longer good form to go and kick up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.680#a row at Bullier, to prowl about the music-halls for the pleasure of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.681#hissing ugly singers. No; a score of them got together and formed a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.682#club.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.683#“Have they a piano like the linen-drapers?” asked Liénard.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.684#“I should rather think they have a piano!” exclaimed Mignot. “And they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.685#play, my boy, and sing! There's even one of them, little Bavoux, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.686#recites verses.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.687#The gaiety redoubled, they chaffed little Bavoux, but still beneath this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.688#laughter there lay a great respect. They then spoke of a piece at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.689#Vaudeville, in which a counter-jumper played a nasty part, which annoyed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.690#several of them, whilst others were anxiously wondering what time they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.691#would get away, having invitations to pass the evening at friends'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.692#houses; and from all points were heard similar conversations amidst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.693#the increasing noise of the crockery. To drive out the odour of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.694#food--the warm steam which rose from the five hundred plates--the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.695#windows had been opened, while the lowered blinds were scorching in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.696#the heavy August sun. An ardent breath came in from the street, golden
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.697#reflections yellowed the ceiling, bathing in a reddish light the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.698#perspiring eaters.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.699#“A nice thing to shut people up such a fine Sunday as this!” repeated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.700#Favier.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.701#This reflection brought them back to the stock-taking. It was a splendid
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.702#year. And they went on to speak of the salaries--the rises--the eternal
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.703#subject, the stirring question which occupied them all. It was always
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.704#thus on chicken days, a wonderful excitement declared itself, the noise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.705#at last became insupportable. When the waiters brought the artichokes
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.706#one could not hear one's self speak. The inspector on duty had orders to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.707#be indulgent.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.708#“By the way,” cried out Favier, “you've heard the news?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.709#But his voice was drowned. Mignot was asking: “Who doesn't like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.710#artichoke; I'll sell my dessert for an artichoke.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.711#No one replied. Everybody liked artichoke. This lunch would be counted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.712#amongst the good ones, for peaches were to be given for dessert.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.713#“He has invited her to dinner, my dear fellow,” said Favier to his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.714#right-hand neighbour, finishing his story. “What! you didn't know it?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.715#The whole table knew it, they were tired of talking about it since the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.716#first thing in the morning. And the same poor jokes passed from mouth
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.717#to mouth. Deloche had turned pale again. He looked at them, his eyes
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.718#finishing by resting on Favier, who was persisting in repeating:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.719#“If he's not had her, he's going to. And he won't be the first; oh! no,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.720#he won't be the first.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.721#He was also looking at Deloche. He added with a provoking air: “Those
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.722#who like bones can have her for a crown!” Suddenly, he ducked his head.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.723#Deloche, yielding to an irresistible movement, had just thrown his last
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.724#glass of wine into his tormentor's face, stammering: “Take that, you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.725#infernal liar! I ought to have drenched you yesterday!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.726#[Illustration: 0406]
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.727#It caused quite a scandal. A few drops had spurted on Favier's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.728#neighbours, whilst he only had his hair slightly wetted: the wine,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.729#thrown by an awkward hand, had fallen the other side of the table. But
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.730#the others got angry, asking if she was his mistress that he defended
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.731#her in this way? What a brute! he deserved a good sound drubbing to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.732#teach him manners. However, their voices fell, an inspector was observed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.733#coming along, and it was useless to introduce the management into the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.734#quarrel. Favier contented himself with saying:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.735#“If it had caught me, you would have seen some sport!” Then the affair
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.736#wound up in jeers. When Deloche, still trembling, wished to drink to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.737#hide his confusion, and seized his empty glass mechanically, they burst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.738#out laughing. He laid his glass down again awkwardly, and commenced
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.739#sucking the leaves of the artichoke he had already eaten.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.740#“Pass Deloche the water bottle,” said Mignot, quietly; “he's thirsty.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.741#The laughter increased. The young men took their clean plates from the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.742#piles standing on the table, at equal distances, whilst the waiters
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.743#handed round the dessert, which consisted of peaches, in baskets. And
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.744#they all held their sides when Mignot added, with a grin:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.745#“Each man to his taste. Deloche takes wine with his peaches.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.746#The latter sat motionless, with his head hanging down, as if deaf to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.747#joking going on around him: he was full of a despairing regret for what
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.748#he had just done. These fellows were right--what right had he to defend
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.749#her? They would now think all sorts of villanous things: he could have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.750#killed himself for having thus compromised her, in attempting to prove
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.751#her innocence. This was always his luck, he might just as well kill
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.752#himself at once, for he could not even yield to the promptings of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.753#heart without doing some stupid thing. And the fears came into his eyes.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.754#Was it not always his fault if the whole shop was talking of the letter
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.755#written by the governor? He heard them grinning and making abominable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.756#remarks about this invitation, of which Liénard alone had been informed;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.757#and he accused himself, he ought not to have let Pauline speak before
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.758#the latter; he was really responsible for the annoying indiscretion
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.759#committed.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.760#“Why did you go and relate that?” he murmured at last, in a voice full
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.761#of grief. “It's very bad.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.762#“I?” replied Liénard; “but I only told it to one or two persons,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.763#enjoining secrecy. One never knows how these things get about!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.764#When Deloche made up his mind to drink a glass of water the whole table
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.765#burst out laughing again. They had finished and were lolling back on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.766#their chairs waiting for the bell recalling them to work. They had not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.767#asked for many extras at the great central counter, the more so as the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.768#firm treated them to coffee that day. The cups were steaming, perspiring
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.769#faces shone under the light vapours, floating like the blue clouds
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.770#from cigarettes. At the windows the blinds hung motionless, without the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.771#slightest flapping. One of them, drawn up, admitted a ray of sunshine
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.772#which traversed the room and gilded the ceiling. The uproar of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.773#voices beat on the walls with such force that the bell was at first
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.774#only heard by those at the tables near the door. They got up, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.775#the confusion of the departure filled the corridors for a long time.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.776#Deloche, however, remained behind to escape the malicious remarks that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.777#were still being made. Baugé even went out before him, and Baugé was, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.778#a rule, the last to leave, going a circuitous way so as to meet Pauline
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.779#as she went to the ladies' dining-room; a manouvre arranged between
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.780#them--the only chance of seeing each other for a minute during business
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.781#hours. But this time, just as they were indulging in a loving kiss in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.782#corner of the passage they were surprised by Denise, who was also going
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.783#up to lunch. She was walking slowly on account of her foot.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.784#“Oh! my dear,” stammered Pauline, very red, “don't say anything, will
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.785#you?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.786#Baugé, with his big limbs and giant proportions, was trembling like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.787#a little boy. He murmured, “They'd very soon pitch us out. Though our
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.788#marriage may be announced, they don't allow any kissing, the animals!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.789#Denise, greatly agitated, affected not to have seen them; and Baugé
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.790#disappeared just as Deloche, who was going the longest way round,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.791#appeared in his turn. He tried to apologise, stammering out phrases that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.792#Denise did not at first catch. Then, as he blamed Pauline for having
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.793#spoken before Liénard, and she stood there looking very embarrassed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.794#Denise at last understood the whispered phrases she had heard around her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.795#all the morning. It was the story of the letter that was circulating.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.796#She was again seized by the shudder with which this letter had agitated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.797#her; she felt herself disrobed by all these men.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.798#“But I didn't know,” repeated Pauline. “Besides, there's nothing bad in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.799#the letter. Let them gossip; they're jealous, of course!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.800#“My dear,” said Denise at last, with her prudent air, “I don't blame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.801#you in any way! You've spoken nothing but the truth. I _have_ received a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.802#letter, and it is my duty to answer it.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.803#Deloche went away heart-broken, having understood that the young girl
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.804#accepted the situation and would keep the appointment that evening. When
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.805#the two young ladies had lunched in a small room adjoining the large
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.806#dining-room, and in which the women were served much more comfortably,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.807#Pauline had to assist Denise downstairs, for the latter's foot was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.808#worse.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.809#Down below in the afternoon warmth the stock-taking was roaring louder
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.810#than ever. The moment for the supreme effort had arrived, when before
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.811#the work, behindhand since the morning, every force was put forth in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.812#order to finish that evening. The voices got louder still, one saw
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.813#nothing but the waving of arms continually emptying the shelves,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.814#throwing the goods down, and it was impossible to get along, the tide of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.815#the bales and piles of goods on the floor rose as high as the counters.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.816#A sea of heads, of brandished fists, of limbs flying about, seemed to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.817#extend to the very depths of the departments, like the distant confusion
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.818#of a riot. It was the last fever of the clearance, the machine nearly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.819#ready to burst; whilst along the plate-glass windows, round the closed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.820#shop, a few rare pedestrians continued to pass, pale with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.821#stifling boredom of a summer Sunday. On the pavement in the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.822#Neuve-Saint-Augustin were planted three tall girls, bareheaded and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.823#sluttish-looking, impudently sticking their faces against the windows,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.824#trying to see the curious work going on inside.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.825#When Denise returned to the ready-made department Madame Aurélie left
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.826#Marguerite to finish calling out the garments. There was still a lot of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.827#checking to be done, for which, desirous of silence, she retired into
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.828#the pattern-room, taking the young girl with her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.829#“Come with me, we'll do the checking; then you can add up the totals.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.830#But as she wished to leave the door open, in order to look after the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.831#young ladies, the noise came in, and they could not hear much better.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.832#It was a large, square room, furnished simply with some chairs and three
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.833#long tables. In one corner were the great machine knives, for cutting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.834#up the patterns. Entire pieces were consumed; they sent away every year
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.835#more than sixty thousand francs' worth of material, cut up in strips.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.836#From morning to night, the knives were cutting up silk, wool, and linen,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.837#with a scythe-like noise. Then the books had to be got together,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.838#gummed or sewn. And there was also between the two windows, a little
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.839#printing-press for the tickets.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.840#“Not so loud, please!” cried Madame Aurélie, now and again, quite unable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.841#to hear Denise reading out the articles.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.842#When the checking of the first lists was finished, she left the young
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.843#girl at one of the tables, absorbed in the adding-up. But she returned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.844#almost immediately, and placed Mademoiselle de Fontenailles near her;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.845#the under-linen department not wanting her any longer, had sent her to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.846#Madame Aurélie. She could also do some adding-up, it would save time.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.847#But the appearance of the marchioness, as Clara ill-naturedly called
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.848#her, had disturbed the department. They laughed and joked at poor
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.849#Joseph, their ferocious sallies could be heard in the pattern-room.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.850#“Don't draw back, you are not at all in my way,” said Denise, seized
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.851#with pity for the poor girl. “My inkstand will suffice, we'll dip
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.852#together.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.853#Mademoiselle de Fontenailles, dulled and stultified by her unfortunate
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.854#position, could not even find a word of gratitude. She appeared to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.855#a woman who drank, her thinness had a livid appearance, and her hands
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.856#alone, white and delicate, attested the distinction of her birth.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.857#The laughter ceased all at once, and the work resumed its regular roar.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.858#It was Mouret who was once more going through the departments. But he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.859#stopped and looked round for Denise, surprised not to see her there.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.860#He made a sign to Madame Aurélie; and both drew aside, talking in a low
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.861#tone for a moment. He must be questioning her. She indicated with her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.862#eyes the pattern-room, then seemed to be making a report. No doubt she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.863#was relating that the young girl had been weeping that morning.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.864#“Very good!” said Mouret, aloud, coming nearer. “Show me the lists.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.865#“This way, sir,” said the first-hand. “We have run away from the noise.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.866#He followed her into the next room. Clara was not duped by this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.867#manouvre, and said they had better go and fetch a bed at once. But
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.868#Marguerite threw her the garments at a quicker rate, in order to take
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.869#up her attention and close her mouth. Wasn't the second-hand a good
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.870#comrade? Her affairs did not concern any one. The department was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.871#becoming an accomplice, the young ladies got more agitated than ever,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.872#Lhomme and Joseph affected not to see or hear anything. And Jouve,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.873#the inspector, who, passing by, had remarked Madame Aurélie's tactics,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.874#commenced walking up and down before the pattern-room door, with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.875#regular step of a sentry guarding the will and pleasure of a superior.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.876#“Give Monsieur Mouret the lists,” said the first-hand.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.877#Denise gave them, and sat there with her eyes raised. She had slightly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.878#started, but had conquered herself, and retained a fine calm look,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.879#although her cheeks were pale. For a moment, Mouret appeared to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.880#absorbed in the list of articles, without a look for the young girl.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.881#A silence reigned, Madame Aurélie then went up to Mademoiselle de
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.882#Fontenailles, who had not even turned her head, appeared dissatisfied
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.883#with her counting, and said to her in a half whisper:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.884#“Go and help with the parcels. You are not used to figures.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.885#The latter got up, and returned to the department, where she was greeted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.886#by a whispering on all sides. Joseph, exposed to the laughing eyes
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.887#of these young minxes, was writing anyhow. Clara, delighted with this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.888#assistant who arrived, was yet very rough with her, hating her as she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.889#hated all the women in the shop. What an idiotic thing to yield to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.890#love of a workman, when one was a marchioness! And yet she envied her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.891#this love.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.892#“Very good!” repeated Mouret, still affecting to read.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.893#However Madame Aurélie hardly knew how to get away in her turn in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.894#decent fashion. She stamped about, went to look at the knives, furious
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.895#with her husband for not inventing a pretext for calling her; but he was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.896#never any good for serious matters, he would have died of thirst close
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.897#to a pond. It was Marguerite who was intelligent enough to go and ask
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.898#the first-hand a question.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.899#“I'm coming,” replied the latter.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.900#And her dignity being now protected, having a pretext in the eyes of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.901#young ladies who were watching her, she at last left Denise and Mouret
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.902#alone together, going out with her imperial air, her profile so noble,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.903#that the saleswomen did not even dare to smile. Mouret had slowly laid
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.904#the lists on the table, and stood looking at the young girl, who had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.905#remained seated, pen in hand. She did not avert her gaze, but she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.906#turned paler.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.907#“You will come this evening?” asked he.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.908#“No, sir, I cannot. My brothers are to be at uncle's to-night, and I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.909#have promised to dine with them.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.910#“But your foot! You walk with such difficulty.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.911#“Oh, I can get so far very well. I feel much better since the morning.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.912#He had now turned pale in his turn, before this quiet refusal. A nervous
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.913#revolt agitated his lips. However, he restrained himself, and resumed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.914#with the air of a good-natured master simply interesting himself in one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.915#of his young ladies: “Come now, if I begged of you--You know what great
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.916#esteem I have for you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.917#Denise retained her respectful attitude. “I am greatly touched, sir, by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.918#your kindness to me, and I thank you for this invitation. But I repeat,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.919#I cannot; my brothers expect me.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.920#She persisted in not understanding. The door remained open, and she felt
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.921#that the whole shop was pushing her on to yield. Pauline had amicably
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.922#called her a great simpleton, the others would laugh at her if she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.923#refused the invitation. Madame Aurélie, who had gone away, Marguerite,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.924#whose rising voice she could hear, Lhomme, with his motionless, discreet
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.925#attitude, all these people were wishing for her fall, throwing her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.926#into the governor's arms. And the distant roar of the stock-taking,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.927#the millions of goods called out on all sides, thrown about in every
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.928#direction, were like a warm wind, carrying the breath of passion
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.929#straight towards her. There was a silence. Now and again, Mouret's voice
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.930#was drowned by the noise which accompanied him, with the formidable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.931#uproar of a kingly fortune gained in battle.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.932#“When will you come, then?” asked he again. “Tomorrow?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.933#This simple question troubled Denise. She lost her calmness for a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.934#moment, and stammered: “I don't know--I can't----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.935#He smiled, and tried to take her hand, which she withheld. “What are you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.936#afraid of?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.937#But she quickly raised her head, looked him straight in the face, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.938#said, smiling, with her sweet, brave look: “I am afraid of nothing, sir.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.939#I can do as I like, can't I? I don't wish to, that's all!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.940#As she finished speaking, she was surprised by hearing a creaking noise,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.941#and on turning round saw the door slowly closing. It was Jouve, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.942#inspector, who had taken upon himself to pull it to. The doors were a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.943#part of his duty, none should ever remain open. And he gravely resumed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.944#his position as sentinel. No one appeared to have noticed this door
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.945#being closed in such a simple manner. Clara alone risked a strong remark
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.946#in Mademoiselle de Fontenailles's ear, but the latter's face remained
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.947#expressionless.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.948#Denise, however, had got up. Mouret was saying to her in a low and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.949#trembling voice: “Listen, Denise, I love you. You have long known it,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.950#pray don't be so cruel as to play the ignorant. And don't fear anything.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.951#Many a time I've thought of calling you into my office. We should have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.952#been alone, I should only have had to lock the door. But I did not wish
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.953#to; you see I speak to you here, where any one can enter. I love you,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.954#Denise!” She was standing up, very pale, listening to him, still looking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.955#straight into his face. “Tell me. Why do you refuse? Have you no wants?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.956#Your brothers are a heavy burden. Anything you might ask me, anything
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.957#you might require of me----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.958#With a word, she stopped him: “Thanks, I now earn more than I want.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.959#“But it's perfect liberty that I am offering you, an existence of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.960#pleasure and luxury. I will set you up in a home of your own. I will
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.961#assure you a little fortune.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.962#“No, thanks; I should soon get tired of doing nothing. I earned my own
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.963#living before I was ten years old.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.964#He was almost mad. This was the first one who did not yield. He had only
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.965#had to stoop to pick up the others, they all awaited his pleasure
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.966#like submissive slaves; and this one said no, without even giving a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.967#reasonable pretext. His desire, long restrained, goaded by resistance,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.968#became stronger than ever. Perhaps he had not offered enough, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.969#thought, and he doubled his offers; he pressed her more and more.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.970#“No, no, thanks,” replied she each time, without faltering. Then he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.971#allowed this cry from his heart to escape him: “But don't you see that I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.972#am suffering! Yes, it's stupid, but I am suffering like a child!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.973#Tears came into his eyes. A fresh silence reigned. They could still hear
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.974#behind the closed door the softened roar of the stock-taking. It was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.975#like a dying note of triumph, the accompaniment became more discreet, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.976#this defeat of the master. “And yet if I liked--” said he in an ardent
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.977#voice, seizing her hands.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.978#She left them in his, her eyes turned pale, her whole strength was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.979#deserting her. A warmth came from this man's burning hands, filling her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.980#with a delicious cowardice. Good heavens! how she loved him, and with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.981#what delight she could have hung on his neck and remained there!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.982#“I will! I will!” repeated he, in his passionate excitement “I expect
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.983#you to-night, otherwise I will take measures.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.984#He was becoming brutal. She set up a low cry; the pain she felt at her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.985#wrists restored her courage. With an angry shake she disengaged herself.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.986#Then, very stiff, looking taller in her weakness: “No, leave me alone!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.987#I am not a Clara, to be thrown over in a day. Besides, you love another;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.988#yes, that lady who comes here. Stay with her. I do not accept half an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.989#affection.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.990#He was struck with surprise. What was she saying, and what did she want?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.991#The girls he had picked up in the shop had never asked to be loved. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.992#ought to have laughed at such an idea, and this attitude of tender pride
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.993#completely conquered his heart.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.994#“Now, sir, please open the door,” resumed she. “It is not proper to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.995#shut up together in this way.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.996#He obeyed; and with his temples throbbing, hardly knowing how to conceal
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.997#his anguish, he recalled Madame Aurélie, and broke out angrily about the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.998#stock of cloaks, saying that the prices must be lowered, until every one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.999#had been got rid of. Such was the rule of the house--a clean sweep was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1000#made every year, they sold at sixty per cent, loss rather than keep an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1001#old model or any stale material. At that moment, Bourdoncle, seeking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1002#Mouret, was waiting for him outside, stopped before the closed door
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1003#by Jouve, who had said a word in his ear with a grave air. He got very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1004#impatient, without, however, summoning up the courage to interrupt the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1005#governor's tête-à-tête. Was it possible? such a day too, and with that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1006#puny creature! And when Mouret at last came out Bourdoncle spoke to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1007#him about the fancy silks, of which the stock left on hand would be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1008#enormous. This was a relief for Mouret, who could now cry out at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1009#his ease. What the devil was Bouthemont thinking about? He went off,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1010#declaring that he could not allow a buyer to display such a want of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1011#sense as to buy beyond the requirements of the business.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1012#“What is the matter with him?” murmured Madame Aurélie, quite overcome
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1013#by his reproaches.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1014#And the young ladies looked at each other with a surprised air. At six
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1015#o'clock the stock-taking was finished. The sun was still shining--a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1016#blonde summer sun, of which the golden reflection streamed through
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1017#the glazed roofs of the halls. In the heavy air of the streets, tired
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1018#families were already returning from the suburbs, loaded with bouquets,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1019#dragging their children along. One by one, the departments had become
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1020#silent. Nothing was now heard in the depths of the galleries but the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1021#lingering calls of a few men clearing a last shelf. Then even these
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1022#voices ceased, and there remained of the bustle of the day nothing but a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1023#shivering, above the formidable piles of goods. The shelves, cupboards,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1024#boxes, and band-boxes, were now empty: not a yard of stuff, not an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1025#object of any sort had remained in its place. The vast establishment
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1026#presented nothing but the carcase of its usual appearance, the woodwork
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1027#was absolutely bare, as on the day of entering into possession. This
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1028#nakedness was the visible proof of the complete and exact taking of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1029#stock. And on the ground was sixteen million francs' worth of goods, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1030#rising sea, which had finished by submerging the tables and counters.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1031#The shopmen, drowned up to the shoulders, had commenced to put each
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1032#article back into its place. They expected to finish about ten o'clock.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1033#When Madame Aurélie, who went to the first dinner, returned to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1034#dining-room, she announced the amount of business done during the year,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1035#which the totals of the various departments had just given. The figure
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1036#was eighty million francs, ten millions more than the preceding year.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1037#The only real decrease was on the fancy silks.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1038#“If Monsieur Mouret is not satisfied, I should like to know what more he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1039#wants,” added the first-hand. “See! he's over there, at the top of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1040#grand staircase, looking furious.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1041#The young ladies went to look at him. He was standing alone, with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1042#sombre countenance, above the millions scattered at his feet.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1043#“Madame,” said Denise, at this moment, “would you kindly let me go away
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1044#now? I can't do any more good on account of my foot, and as I am to dine
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1045#at my uncle's with my brothers----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1046#They were all astonished. She had not yielded, then! Madame Aurélie
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1047#hesitated, and seemed inclined to prohibit her going out, her voice
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1048#sharp and disagreeable; whilst Clara shrugged her shoulders, full of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1049#incredulity. That wouldn't do! it was very simple--the governor no
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1050#longer wanted her! When Pauline learnt this, she was in the baby-linen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1051#department with Deloche, and the sudden joy exhibited by the young man
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1052#made her very angry. That did him a lot of good, didn't it? Perhaps
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1053#he was pleased to see that his friend had been stupid enough to miss
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1054#a fortune? And Bourdoncle, who did not dare to approach Mouret in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1055#his ferocious isolation, marched up and down amidst these rumours, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1056#despair also, and full of anxiety. However, Denise went downstairs. As
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1057#she arrived at the bottom of the left-hand staircase, slowly, supporting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1058#herself by the banister, she came upon a group of grinning salesmen.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1059#Her name was pronounced, and she felt that they were talking about her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1060#adventure. They had not noticed her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1061#“Oh! all that's put on, you know,” Favier was saying. “She's full of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1062#vice! Yes, I know some one she wanted to take by force.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1063#And he looked at Hutin, who, in order to preserve his dignity as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1064#second-hand, was standing a certain distance apart, without joining
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1065#in their conversation. But he was so flattered by the air of envy with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1066#which the others were contemplating him, that he deigned to murmur: “She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1067#was a regular nuisance to me, that girl!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1068#Denise, wounded to the heart, clung to the banister. They must have seen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1069#her, for they all disappeared, laughing. He was right, she thought,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1070#and she accused herself of her former ignorance, when she used to think
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1071#about him. But what a coward he was, and how she scorned him now! A
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1072#great trouble had seized her: was it not strange that she should have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1073#found the strength just now to repulse a man whom she adored, when she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1074#used to feel herself so feeble in bygone days before this worthless
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1075#fellow, whom she had only dreamed off? Her sense of reason and her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1076#bravery foundered before these contradictions of her being, in which she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1077#could not read clearly. She hastened to cross the hall. Then a sort of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1078#instinct prompted her to raise her head, whilst an inspector opened the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1079#door, closed since the morning. And she perceived Mouret, who was still
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1080#at the top of the stairs, on the great central landing, dominating
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1081#the gallery. But he had forgotten the stock-taking, he did not see his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1082#empire, this building bursting with riches. Everything had disappeared,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1083#his former glorious victories, his future colossal fortune. With a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1084#desponding look he was watching Denise's departure, and when she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:x.1085#passed the door everything disappeared, a darkness came over the house.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.1#CHAPTER XI.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.2#That day Bouthemont was the first to arrive at Madame Desforges's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.3#four o'clock tea. Still alone in her large Louis XVI. drawing-room,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.4#the brasses and brocatelle of which shone out with a clear gaiety, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.5#latter rose with an air of impatience, saying, “Well?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.6#“Well,” replied the young man, “when I told him I should doubtless call
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.7#on you he formally promised me to come.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.8#“You made him thoroughly understand that I counted on the baron to-day?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.9#“Certainly. That's what appeared to decide him.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.10#They were speaking of Mouret, who the year before had suddenly taken
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.11#such a liking to Bouthemont that he had admitted him to share his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.12#pleasures, and had even introduced him to Henriette, glad to have an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.13#agreeable fellow always at hand to enliven an intimacy of which he was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.14#getting tired. It was thus that Bouthemont had ultimately become the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.15#confidant of his governor and of the handsome widow; he did their little
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.16#errands, talked of the one to the other, and sometimes reconciled them.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.17#Henriette, in her jealous fits, abandoned herself to a familiarity which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.18#sometimes surprised and embarrassed him, for she lost all her lady-like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.19#prudence, using all her art to save appearances.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.20#She resumed violently, “You ought to have brought him. I should have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.21#been sure then.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.22#“Well,” said he, with a good-natured laugh, “it isn't my fault if he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.23#escapes so frequently now. Oh! he's very fond of me, all the same. Were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.24#it not for him I should be in a bad way at the shop.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.25#His situation at The Ladies' Paradise was really menaced since the last
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.26#stock-taking. It was in vain that he adduced the rainy season; one could
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.27#not overlook the considerable stock of fancy silks; and as Hutin was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.28#improving the occasion, undermining him with the governors with an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.29#increase of sly rage, he felt the ground cracking under him. Mouret
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.30#had condemned him, weary, no doubt, of this witness who prevented him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.31#breaking with Henriette, tired of a familiarity which was profitless.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.32#But, in accordance with his usual tactics, he was pushing Bourdoncle
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.33#forward; it was Bourdoncle and the other partners who insisted on his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.34#dismissal at each board meeting; whilst he resisted still, according to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.35#his account, defending his friend energetically, at the risk of getting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.36#into serious trouble with the others.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.37#“Well, I shall wait,” resumed Madame Desforges. “You know that girl is
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.38#coming here at five o'clock, I want to see them face to face. I must
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.39#discover their secret.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.40#And she returned to this long-meditated plan. She repeated in her fever
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.41#that she had requested Madame Aurélie to send her Denise to look at a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.42#mantle which fitted badly. When she had once got the young girl in her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.43#room, she would find a means of calling Mouret, and could then act.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.44#Bouthemont, who had sat down opposite her, was gazing at her with his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.45#fine laughing eyes, which he endeavoured to render grave. This jovial,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.46#dissipated fellow, with his coal-black beard, whose warm Gascon blood
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.47#empurpled his cheeks, was thinking that these fine ladies were not much
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.48#good, and that they let out a nice lot of secrets, when they opened
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.49#their hearts. His friend's mistresses, simple shop-girls, certainly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.50#never made more complete confessions.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.51#“Come,” he ventured to say at last, “what does that matter to you? I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.52#swear to you there is nothing whatever between them.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.53#“Just so,” cried she, “because he loves her! I don't care in the least
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.54#for the others, chance acquaintances, friends of a day!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.55#She spoke of Clara with disdain. She was well aware that Mouret, after
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.56#Denise's refusal, had fallen back on this tall, redhaired girl, with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.57#the horse's head, doubtless by calculation; for he maintained her in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.58#department, loading her with presents. Not only that, for the last three
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.59#months he had been leading: a terrible life, squandering his money with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.60#a prodigality which caused a great many remarks; he had bought a mansion
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.61#for a worthless actress, and was being ruined by two or three other
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.62#jades, who seemed to be struggling to outdo each other in costly, stupid
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.63#caprices.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.64#“It's this creature's fault,” repeated Henriette. “I feel sure he's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.65#ruining himself with the others because she repulses him. Besides,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.66#what's his money to me? I should have loved him better poor. You know
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.67#how I love him, you who have become our friend.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.68#She stopped, choked, ready to burst into tears; and with a movement
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.69#of abandon she held out her two hands to him. It was true, she adored
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.70#Mouret for his youth and his triumphs, never had any man thus conquered
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.71#her so entirely in a quiver of her flesh and of her pride; but at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.72#thought of losing him, she also heard the knell of her fortieth year,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.73#and she asked herself with terror how she should replace this great
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.74#love.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.75#“I'll have my revenge,” murmured she. “I'll have my revenge, if he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.76#behaves badly!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.77#Bouthemont continued to hold her hands in his. She was still handsome.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.78#But she would be a very awkward mistress, thought he, and he did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.79#like that style of woman. The thing, however, deserved thinking over;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.80#perhaps it would be worth while risking certain annoyances.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.81#“Why don't you set up for yourself?” she asked all at once, drawing her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.82#hands away.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.83#He was astonished. Then he replied: “But it would require an immense
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.84#sum. Last year I had an idea in my head. I feel convinced that there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.85#are customers enough in Paris for one or two more big shops; but the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.86#district would have to be chosen. The Bon Marche has the left side
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.87#of the river; the Louvre occupies the centre; we monopolise, at The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.88#Paradise, the rich west-end district. There remains the north, where
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.89#a rival to the Place Clichy could be created. And I had discovered a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.90#splendid position, near the Opera House----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.91#“Well?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.92#He set up a noisy laugh. “Just fancy. I was stupid enough to go and talk
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.93#to my father about it Yes, I was simple enough to ask him to find some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.94#shareholders at Toulouse.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.95#And he gaily described the anger of the old man, enraged against the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.96#great Parisian bazaars, in his little country shop. Old Bouthemont,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.97#suffocated by the thirty thousand francs a year earned by his son, had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.98#replied that he would give his money and that of his friends to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.99#hospitals rather than contribute a sou to one of those shops which were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.100#the pests of the drapery business.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.101#“Besides,” continued the young man, “it would require millions.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.102#“Suppose they were found?” observed Madame Desforges, simply.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.103#He looked at her, serious all at once. Was it not merely a jealous
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.104#woman's word? But she did not give him time to question her, adding: “In
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.105#short, you know what a great interest I take in you. We'll talk about it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.106#again.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.107#The outer bell had rung. She got up, and he, himself, with an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.108#instinctive movement, drew back his chair, as if they might have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.109#been surprised. A silence reigned in the drawingroom, with its pretty
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.110#hangings, and decorated with such a profusion of green plants that there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.111#was quite a small wood between the two windows. She stood there waiting,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.112#with her ear towards the door.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.113#“There he is,” she murmured.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.114#The footman announced Monsieur Mouret and Monsieur de Vallagnosc.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.115#Henriette could not restrain a movement of anger. Why had he not come
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.116#alone? He must have gone after his friend, fearful of a tête-à-tête with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.117#her. However, she smiled and shook hands with the two men.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.118#“What a stranger you are getting. I may say the same for you, Monsieur
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.119#de Vallagnosc.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.120#Her great grief was to be becoming stout, and she squeezed herself into
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.121#tight black silk dresses, to conceal her increasing obesity. However,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.122#her pretty face, with her dark hair, preserved its amiable expression.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.123#And Mouret could familiarly tell her, enveloping her with a look:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.124#“It's useless to ask how you are. You are as fresh as a rose.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.125#“Oh! I'm almost too well,” replied she. “Besides, I might have died; you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.126#would have known nothing about it.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.127#She was examining him also, and thought him looking tired and nervous,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.128#his eyes heavy, his complexion livid.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.129#“Well,” she resumed, in a tone which she endeavoured to render
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.130#agreeable, “I cannot return the compliment; you don't look at all well
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.131#to-day.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.132#“Overwork!” remarked De Vallagnosc.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.133#Mouret shrugged his shoulders, without replying. He had just perceived
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.134#Bouthemont, and nodded to him in a friendly way. During the time
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.135#of their close intimacy he used to take him away direct from the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.136#department, bringing him to Henriette's during the busiest moments of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.137#the afternoon. But times had changed; he said to him in a half whisper:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.138#“You went away rather early. They noticed your departure, and are
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.139#furious about it.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.140#He referred to Bourdoncle and the other persons who had an interest in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.141#the business, as if he were not himself the master.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.142#“Ah!” murmured Bouthemont, rather anxious.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.143#“Yes, I want to talk to you. Wait for me, we'll leave together.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.144#Meanwhile, Henriette had sat down again; and while listening to De
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.145#Vallagnosc, who was announcing that Madame de Boves would probably pay
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.146#her a visit, she did not take her eyes off Mouret. The latter, silent
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.147#again, gazed at the furniture, seemed to be looking for something on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.148#ceiling. Then as she laughingly complained that she had only gentlemen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.149#at her four o'clock tea, he so far forgot himself as to blurt out:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.150#“I expected to find Baron Hartmann here.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.151#Henriette turned pale. No doubt she knew he came to her house solely to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.152#meet the baron; but he might have avoided throwing his indifference in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.153#her face like this. At that moment the door had opened and the footman
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.154#was standing behind her. When she had interrogated him by a sign, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.155#leant over her and said in a very low tone:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.156#“It's for that mantle. You wished me to let you know. The young lady is
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.157#there.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.158#Then Henriette raised her voice, so as to be heard. All her jealous
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.159#suffering found relief in the following words, of a scornful harshness:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.160#“She can wait!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.161#“Shall I show her into your dressing-room?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.162#“No, no. Let her stay in the ante-room!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.163#And when the servant had gone out she quietly resumed her conversation
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.164#with De Vallagnosc. Mouret, who had relapsed into his former lassitude,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.165#had listened with a careless, distracted air, without understanding.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.166#Bouthemont, preoccupied by the adventure, was reflecting. But almost
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.167#immediately after the door was opened again, and two ladies were shown
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.168#in.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.169#“Just fancy,” said Madame Marty, “I was alighting at the door, when I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.170#saw Madame de Boves coming under the arcade.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.171#“Yes,” explained the latter, “it's a fine day, and my doctor says I must
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.172#take walking exercise.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.173#Then, after a general hand-shaking, she asked Henriette:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.174#“You're engaging a new maid, then?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.175#“No,” replied the other, astonished. “Why?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.176#“Because I've just seen a young girl in the ante-room.” Henriette
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.177#interrupted her, laughing. “It's true; all these shop-girls look like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.178#ladies' maids, don't they? Yes, it's a young person come to alter a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.179#mantle.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.180#Mouret looked at her intently, a suspicion crossing his mind. She went
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.181#on with a forced gaiety, explaining that she had bought mantle at The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.182#Ladies' Paradise the previous week.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.183#“What!” asked Madame Marty, “have you deserted Sauveur then?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.184#“No my dear, but I wished to make an experiment. Besides, I was pretty
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.185#well satisfied with a first purchase, a travelling cloak. But this time
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.186#it has not succeeded at all. You may say what you like, one is horribly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.187#trussed up in the big shops. I speak out plainly, even before you,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.188#Monsieur Mouret; you will never know how to dress a woman with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.189#slightest claim to distinction.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.190#Mouret did not defend his house, still keeping his eyes on her, thinking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.191#to himself that she would never have dared to do such a thing. And it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.192#was Bouthemont who had to plead the cause of The Ladies' Paradise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.193#“If all the aristocratic ladies who patronise us announced the fact,”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.194# replied he, gaily, “you would be astonished at our customers. Order a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.195#garment to measure at our place, it will equal one from Sauveur's, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.196#will cost but half the money. But there, just because it's cheaper it's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.197#not so good.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.198#“So it doesn't fit, this mantle you speak of?” resumed Madame de
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.199#Boves. “Ah! now I remember the young person. It's rather dark in your
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.200#ante-room.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.201#“Yes,” added Madame Marty, “I was wondering where I had seen that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.202#figure. Well, go, my dear, don't stand on ceremony with us.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.203#Henriette assumed a look of disdainful unconcern. “Oh, presently, there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.204#is no hurry.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.205#The ladies continued to discuss the articles from the big shops. Then
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.206#Madame de Boves spoke of her husband, who, she said, had gone to inspect
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.207#the breeding depot at Saint-Lô; and just then Henriette was relating
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.208#that through the illness of an aunt Madame Guibal had been suddenly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.209#called into Franche-Comté. Moreover, she did not reckon that day on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.210#Madame Bourdelais, who at the end of every month shut herself up with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.211#a needlewoman to look over her young people's under-linen. But Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.212#Marty seemed agitated with some secret trouble. Her husband's position
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.213#at the Lycée Bonaparte was menaced, in consequence of lessons given by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.214#the poor man in certain doubtful institutions where a regular trade was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.215#carried on with the B.A. diplomas; the poor fellow picked up a pound
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.216#where he could, feverishly, in order to meet the ruinous expenses which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.217#pillaged his household; and his wife, on seeing him weeping one evening
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.218#in the fear of a dismissal, had conceived the idea of getting her friend
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.219#Henriette to speak to a director at the Ministry of Public Instruction
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.220#with whom she was acquainted. Henriette finished by quieting her with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.221#few words. It was understood that Monsieur Marty was coming himself to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.222#know his fate and to thank her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.223#“You look ill, Monsieur Mouret,” observed Madame de Boves.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.224#“Overwork!” repeated De Vallagnosc, with his ironical phlegm.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.225#Mouret quickly got up, as if ashamed at forgetting himself thus. He went
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.226#and took his accustomed place in the midst of the ladies, summoning up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.227#all his agreeable talent. He was now occupied with the winter novelties,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.228#and spoke of a considerable arrival of lace; and Madame de Boves
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.229#questioned him as to the price of Bruges lace: she felt inclined to buy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.230#some. She had now got so far as to economise the thirty-sous for a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.231#cab, often going home quite ill from the effects of stopping before the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.232#windows. Draped in a mantle which was already two years old she tried,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.233#in imagination, on her queenly shoulders all the dearest things she saw;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.234#and it was like tearing her flesh away when she awoke and found herself
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.235#dressed in her patched, old dresses, without the slightest hope of ever
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.236#satisfying her passion.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.237#“Baron Hartmann,” announced the man-servant.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.238#Henriette observed with what pleasure Mouret shook hands with the new
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.239#arrival. The latter bowed to the ladies and looked at the young man with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.240#that subtle expression which sometimes illumined his big Alsatian face.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.241#“Always plunged in dress!” murmured he, with a smile. Then, like a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.242#friend of the house, he ventured to add, “There's a charming young girl
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.243#in the ante-room. Who is it?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.244#“Oh, nobody,” replied Madame Desforges, in her ill-natured voice. “Only
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.245#a shop-girl waiting to see me.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.246#But the door remained half open, the servant was bringing in the tea.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.247#He went out, came in again, placed the china service on the table,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.248#then some plates of sandwiches and biscuits. In the vast room, a bright
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.249#light, softened by the green plants, illuminated the brass-work, bathing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.250#the silk hangings in a tender flame; and each time the door was opened
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.251#one could perceive an obscure corner of the ante-room, which was only
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.252#lighted by two ground-glass windows. There, in the darkness, appeared a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.253#sombre form, motionless and patient. It was Denise, still standing up;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.254#there was a leather-covered form there, but a feeling of pride prevented
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.255#her sitting down on it. She felt the insult keenly. She had been there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.256#for the last half-hour, without a gesture, without a word. The ladies
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.257#and the baron had taken stock of her in passing; she could now hear the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.258#voices from the drawingroom. All this amiable luxury wounded her with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.259#its indifference, and still she did not move. Suddenly, through the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.260#half-open door, she perceived Mouret, and he, on his side, had at last
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.261#guessed it to be her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.262#“Is it one of your saleswomen?” asked Baron Hartmann.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.263#Mouret had succeeded in concealing his great agitation; but his voice
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.264#trembled somewhat with emotion: “No doubt; but I don't know which.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.265#“It's the little fair girl from the ready-made department,” replied
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.266#Madame Marty, obligingly, “the second-hand, I believe.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.267#Henriette looked at Mouret in her turn.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.268#“Ah!” said he, simply.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.269#And he tried to change the conversation, speaking of the fêtes given to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.270#the King of Prussia then passing through Paris. But the baron returned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.271#maliciously to the young ladies in the big establishments. He affected
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.272#to be desirous of gaining information, and put several questions: Where
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.273#did they come from in general? Was their conduct as bad as it was said
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.274#to be? Quite a discussion ensued.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.275#“Really,” he repeated, “you think them well behaved.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.276#Mouret defended their virtue with a conviction which made De Vallagnosc
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.277#smile. Bouthemont then interfered, to save his chief. Of course there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.278#were some of all sorts, bad and good. Formerly they had nothing but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.279#the refuse of the trade, a poor, vague class of girls drifted into the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.280#drapery business; whilst now, such respectable families as those living
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.281#in the Rue de Sèvres, for instance, positively brought up their girls
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.282#for the Bon Marche. In short, when they liked to conduct themselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.283#well, they could, for they were not, like the work-girls of Paris,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.284#obliged to board and lodge themselves; they had bed and board, their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.285#existence was provided for, an existence excessively hard, no doubt.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.286#The worst of all was their neutral, badly-defined position, between the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.287#shop-woman and the lady. Thrown into the midst of luxury, often without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.288#any previous instruction, they formed a singular, nameless class. Their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.289#misfortunes and vices sprung from that.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.290#“I,” said Madame de Boves, “I don't know any creatures more
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.291#disagreeable. Really, one could slap them sometimes.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.292#And the ladies vented their spite. They devoured each other before the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.293#shop-counters; it was a question of woman against woman in the sharp
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.294#rivalry of money and beauty. It was an ill-natured jealousy felt by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.295#saleswomen towards the well-dressed customers, the ladies whose manners
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.296#they tried to imitate, and a still stronger feeling on the part of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.297#poorly-dressed customers, the lower-class ones, against the saleswomen,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.298#those girls dressed in silk, from whom they would have liked to exact a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.299#servant's humility when serving a ten sou purchase.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.300#“Don't speak of them,” said Henriette, by way of conclusion, “a wretched
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.301#lot of beings ready to sell themselves the same as their goods.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.302#[Illustration: 0423]
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.303#Mouret had the strength to smile. The baron was looking at him, so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.304#touched by his graceful command over himself that he changed the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.305#conversation, returning to the fêtes to be given to the King of Prussia,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.306#saying they would be superb, the whole trade of Paris would profit by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.307#them. Henriette remained silent and thoughtful, divided between the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.308#desire to forget Denise in the ante-room, and the fear that Mouret, now
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.309#aware of her presence, might go away. At last she quitted her chair.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.310#“You will allow me?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.311#“Certainly, my dear,” replied Madame Marty. “I'll do the honours of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.312#house for you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.313#She got up, took the teapot, and filled the cups. Henriette turned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.314#towards Baron Hartmann, saying: “You'll stay a few minutes, won't you?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.315#“Yes; I want to speak to Monsieur Mouret. We are going to invade your
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.316#little drawing-room.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.317#She went out, and her black silk dress, rustling against the door,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.318#produced a noise like that of a snake wriggling through the brushwood.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.319#The baron at once manoeuvred to carry Mouret off, leaving the ladies to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.320#Bouthemont and De Vallagnosc. Then they stood talking before the window
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.321#of the other room in a low tone. It was quite a fresh affair. For a long
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.322#time Mouret had cherished a desire to realise his former project,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.323#the invasion of the whole block by The Ladies' Paradise, from the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.324#Rue Monsigny to the Rue de la Michodière and from the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.325#Neuve-Saint-Augustin to the Rue du Dix-Décembre. There was still a vast
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.326#piece of ground, in the latter street, remaining to be acquired, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.327#that sufficed to spoil his triumph, he was tortured with the desire to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.328#complete his conquest, to erect there a sort of apotheosis, a monumental
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.329#façade. As long as his principal entrance should remain in the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.330#Neuve-Saint-Augustin, in a dark street of old Paris, his work would be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.331#incomplete, wanting in logic. He wished to set it up before new Paris,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.332#in one of these modern avenues through which passed the busy crowd
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.333#of the latter part of the nineteenth century. He saw it dominating,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.334#imposing itself as the giant palace of commerce, casting a greater
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.335#shadow over the city than the old Louvre itself. But up to the present
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.336#he had been baulked by the obstinacy of die Credit Immobilier, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.337#still held to its first idea of building a rival to the Grand Hôtel on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.338#this land. The plans were ready, they were only waiting for the clearing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.339#of the Rue du Dix-Décembre to commence the work. At last, by a supreme
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.340#effort, Mouret had almost convinced Baron Hartmann.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.341#“Well!” commenced the latter, “we had a board-meeting yesterday, and I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.342#came to-day, thinking I should meet you, and being desirous of keeping
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.343#you informed. They still resist.” The young man gave way to a nervous
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.344#gesture. “But it's ridiculous. What do they say?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.345#“Dear me! they say what I have said to you myself, and what I am still
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.346#inclined to think. Your façade is only an ornament, the new buildings
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.347#would only extend by about a tenth the surface of your establishment,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.348#and it would be throwing away immense sums on a mere advertisement.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.349#At this Mouret burst out “An advertisement! an advertisement! In any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.350#case this will be in stone and outlive all of us. Just consider that it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.351#would increase our business tenfold! We should see our money back in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.352#two years. What matters about what you call the wasted ground, if this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.353#ground returns you an enormous interest! You will see the crowd,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.354#when our customers are no longer obliged to struggle through the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.355#Neuve-Saint-Augustin, but can freely pass down a thoroughfare large
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.356#enough for six carriages abreast.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.357#“No doubt,” replied the baron, laughing. “But you are a poet in your
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.358#way, let me tell you once more. These gentlemen think it would be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.359#dangerous to further extend your business.' They want to be prudent for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.360#you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.361#“What do they mean? Prudent! I don't understand. Don't the figures show
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.362#the constant progression of our business? At first, with a capital
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.363#of five hundred thousand francs, I did business to the extent of two
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.364#millions, turning the capital over four times. It then became four
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.365#million francs, which, turned over ten times, has produced business to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.366#the extent of forty millions. In short, after successive increases,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.367#I have just learnt, from the last stock-taking, that the amount of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.368#business done now amounts to a total of eighty millions; thus
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.369#the capital, only slightly increased--for it does not exceed six
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.370#millions--has passed over our counters in the form of more than twelve
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.371#times.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.372#He raised his voice, tapping the fingers of his right hand on the palm
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.373#of his left hand, knocking down these millions as he would have cracked
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.374#a few nuts. The baron interrupted him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.375#“I know, I know. But you don't hope to keep on increasing in this way,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.376#do you?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.377#“Why not?” asked Mouret, ingenuously. “There's no reason why it should
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.378#stop. The capital can be turned over as often as fifteen times. I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.379#predicted as much long ago. In certain departments it can be turned over
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.380#twenty-five or thirty times. And after? well! after, we'll find a means
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.381#of turning it over more than that.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.382#“So you'll finish by drinking up all the money in Paris, as you'd drink
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.383#a glass of water?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.384#“Most decidedly. Doesn't Paris belong to the women, and don't the women
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.385#belong to us?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.386#The baron laid his hands on Mouret's shoulders, looking at him with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.387#paternal air. “Listen, you're a fine fellow, and I am really fond of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.388#you. There's no resisting you. We'll go into the matter seriously, and I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.389#hope to make them listen to reason. Up to the present, we are perfectly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.390#satisfied with you. Your dividends astonish the Bourse. You must be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.391#right; it will be better to put more money into your business, than to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.392#risk this competition with the Grand Hôtel, which is hazardous.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.393#Mouret's excitement subsided at once; he thanked the baron, but without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.394#any of his usual enthusiasm; and the latter saw him turn his eyes
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.395#towards the door of the next room, again seized with the secret
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.396#anxiety which he was concealing. However, De Vallagnosc had come up,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.397#understanding that they had finished talking business. He stood close to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.398#them, listening to the baron, who was murmuring with the gallant air of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.399#an old man who had seen life:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.400#“I say, I fancy they're taking their revenge.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.401#“Who?” asked Mouret, embarrassed.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.402#“Why, the women. They're getting tired of belonging to you; you now
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.403#belong to them, my dear fellow; it's only just!” He joked him, well
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.404#aware of the young man's notorious love affairs: the mansion bought
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.405#for the actress, the enormous sums squandered with girls picked up in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.406#private supper rooms, amused him as an excuse for the follies he had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.407#formerly committed himself. His old experience rejoiced.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.408#“Really, I don't understand,” repeated Mouret.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.409#“Oh! you understand well enough. They always get the last word. In fact,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.410#I said to myself: It isn't possible, he's boasting he can't be so strong
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.411#as that! And there you are! Bleed the women, work them as you would a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.412#coal mine, and what for? In order that they may work you afterwards, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.413#force you to refund at last! Take care, for they'll draw more blood and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.414#money from you than you have ever sucked from them.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.415#He laughed louder still; and De Vallagnosc was also grinning, without,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.416#however, saying a word.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.417#“Dear me! one must have a taste of everything,” confessed Mouret, at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.418#last, pretending to laugh as well. “Money is so stupid, if it isn't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.419#spent.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.420#“As for that, I agree with you,” resumed the baron. “Enjoy yourself, my
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.421#dear fellow, I'll not be the one to preach to you, nor to tremble for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.422#the great interests we have confided to your care. Every one must sow
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.423#his wild oats, and his head is generally clearer afterwards. Besides,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.424#there's nothing unpleasant in ruining one's self when one feels capable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.425#of building up another fortune. But if money is nothing, there are
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.426#certain sufferings----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.427#He stopped, his smile became sad, former sufferings presented themselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.428#amid the irony of his scepticism. He had watched the duel between
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.429#Henriette and Mouret with the curiosity of one who still felt greatly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.430#interested in other people's love battles; and he felt that the crisis
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.431#had arrived, he guessed the drama, well acquainted with the story of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.432#this Denise, whom he had seen in the ante-room.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.433#“Oh! as for suffering, that's not in my line,” said Mouret, in a tone of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.434#bravado. “It's quite enough to pay.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.435#The baron looked at him for a moment without speaking. Without wishing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.436#to insist on his discreet allusion he added, slowly--“Don't make
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.437#yourself worse than you are! You'll lose something else besides your
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.438#money at that game. Yes, you'll lose a part of yourself, my dear
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.439#fellow.” He stopped, again laughing, to ask, “That often happens,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.440#doesn't it, Monsieur de Vallagnosc?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.441#“So they say, baron,” the young man simply replied.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.442#Just at this moment the door was opened. Mouret, who was going to reply,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.443#slightly started. The three men turned round. It was Madame Desforges,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.444#looking very gay, putting her head through the doorway to call, in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.445#hurried voice--
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.446#“Monsieur Mouret! Monsieur Mouret!” Then, when she perceived the three
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.447#men, she added, “Oh! you'll excuse me, won't you, gentlemen? I'm going
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.448#to take Monsieur Mouret away for a minute. The least he can do, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.449#he has sold me a frightful mantle, is to give me the benefit of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.450#experience. This girl is a stupid, without the least idea. Come, come!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.451#I'm waiting for you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.452#He hesitated, undecided, flinching before the scene he could foresee.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.453#But he had to obey. The baron said to him, with his air at once paternal
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.454#and mocking, “Go, my dear fellow, go, madame wants you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.455#Mouret followed her. The door closed, and he thought he could hear De
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.456#Vallagnosc's grin stifled by the hangings. His courage was entirely
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.457#exhausted. Since Henriette had quitted the drawing-room, and he knew
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.458#Denise was alone in the house in jealous hands, he had experienced a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.459#growing anxiety, a nervous torment, which made him listen from time to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.460#time as if suddenly startled by a distant sound of weeping. What could
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.461#this woman invent to torture her? And his whole love, this love which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.462#surprised him even now, went out to the young girl like a support and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.463#a consolation. Never had he loved her so strongly, with that charm so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.464#powerful in suffering. His former affections, his love for Henriette
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.465#herself--so delicate, so handsome, the possession of whom was so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.466#flattering to his pride--had never been more than agreeable pastimes,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.467#frequently a calculation, in which he sought nothing but a profitable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.468#pleasure. He used quietly to leave his mistresses and go home to bed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.469#happy in his bachelor liberty, without a regret or a care on his mind;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.470#whilst now his heart beat with anguish, his life was taken, he no longer
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.471#enjoyed the forgetfulness of sleep in his great, solitary bed. Denise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.472#was his only thought. Even at this moment she was the sole object of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.473#his anxiety, and he was telling himself that he preferred to be there to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.474#protect her, notwithstanding his fear of some regrettable scene with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.475#other one.
