urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.545#work, she gave her sharp and brief orders, watching for the least sign
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.546#of suffering on Mouret's face.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.547#“Put a pin here! No! not there, here, near the sleeve. You don't seem
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.548#to understand! That isn't it, there's the ruck showing again. Take care,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.549#you're pricking me now!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.550#Twice had Mouret vainly attempted to interfere, to put an end to this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.551#scene. His heart was beating violently from this humiliation of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.552#love; and he loved Denise more than ever, with a deep tenderness, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.553#the presence of her admirably silent and patient attitude. If the young
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.554#girl's hands still trembled somewhat, at being treated in this way
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.555#before his face, she accepted the necessities of her position with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.556#proud resignation of a courageous girl. When Madame Desforges found
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.557#they were not likely to betray themselves, she tried another way, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.558#commenced to smile on Mouret, treating him openly as her lover. The pins
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.559#having run short, she said to him:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.560#“Look, my dear, in the ivory box on the dressing-table. Really! it's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.561#empty? Kindly see on the chimney-piece in the bed-room; you know, at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.562#corner of the looking-glass.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.563#She spoke as if he were quite at home, in the habit of sleeping there,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.564#and knew where to find everything, even the brushes and combs. When he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.565#brought back a few pins, she took them one by one, and forced him to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.566#stay near her, looking at him and speaking low.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.567#“I don't fancy I'm hump-backed. Give me your hand, feel my shoulders,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.568#just to please me. Am I really made like that?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.569#Denise slowly raised her eyes, paler than ever, and set about placing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.570#the pins in silence. Mouret could only see her blonde tresses, twisted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.571#at the back of her delicate neck; but by the slight shudder which was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.572#raising them, he thought he could perceive the uneasiness and shame of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.573#her face. Now, she would certainly repulse him, and send him back to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.574#this woman, who did not conceal her connection even before strangers.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.575#Brutal thoughts came into his head, he could have struck Henriette. How
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.576#was he to stop her talk? How should he tell Denise that he adored her,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.577#that she alone existed for him at this moment, and that he was ready to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.578#sacrifice for her all his former affections? The worst of women would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.579#not have indulged in the equivocal familiarities of this well-born lady.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.580#He took his hand away, and drew back, saying:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.581#“You are wrong to go so far, madame, since I myself consider the garment
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.582#to be a failure.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.583#One of the gas-burners was hissing, and in the stuffy, moist air of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.584#room, nothing else was heard but this ardent breath. The looking-glasses
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.585#threw large sheets of light on the red silk hangings, on which were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.586#dancing the shadows of the two women. A bottle of verbena, of which the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.587#cork had been left out, spread a vague odour, something like that of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.588#fading bouquet.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.589#“There, madame, I can do no more,” said Denise, at last, rising up.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.590#She felt thoroughly worn out. Twice she had run the pins in her fingers,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.591#as if blinded, her eyes in a mist. Was he in the plot? Had he sent for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.592#her, to avenge himself for her refusal, by showing that other women
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.593#loved him? And this thought chilled her; she never remembered to have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.594#stood in need of so much courage, not even during the terrible hours of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.595#her life when she wanted for bread. It was comparatively nothing to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.596#humiliated, but to see him almost in the arms of another woman, as if
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.597#she had not been there! Henriette looked at herself in the glass, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.598#once more broke out into harsh words.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.599#“But it's absurd, mademoiselle. It fits worse than ever. Just look how
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.600#tight it is across the chest I look like a wet nurse.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.601#Denise, losing all patience, made a rather unfortunate remark. “You are
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.602#slightly stout, madame. We cannot make you thinner than you are.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.603#“Stout! stout!” exclaimed Henriette, who now turned pale in her turn.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.604#“You're becoming insolent, mademoiselle. Really, I should advise you to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.605#criticise others!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.606#They both stood looking at each other, face to face, trembling. There
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.607#was now neither lady or shop-girl. They were simply two women, made
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.608#equal by their rivalry. The one had violently taken off the mantle and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.609#cast it on a chair, whilst the other was throwing on the dressing-table
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.610#the few pins she had in her hands.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.611#“What astonishes me,” resumed Henriette, “is that Monsieur Mouret should
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.612#tolerate such insolence. I thought, sir, that you were more particular
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.613#about your employees.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.614#Denise had again assumed her brave, calm manner. She gently replied:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.615#“If Monsieur Mouret keeps me, it's because he has no fault to find. I am
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.616#ready to apologise to you, if he wishes it.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.617#Mouret was listening, excited by this quarrel, unable to find a word to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.618#put a stop to it. He had a great horror of these explanations between
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.619#women, their asperity wounding his sense of elegance and gracefulness.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.620#Henriette wished to force him to say something in condemnation of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.621#young girl; and, as he remained mute, still undecided, she stung him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.622#with a final insult:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.623#“Very good, sir. It seems that I must suffer the insolence of your
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.624#mistresses in my own house even! A girl you've picked up out of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.625#gutter!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.626#Two big tears gushed from Denise's eyes. She had kept them back for some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.627#time, but her whole being succumbed beneath this last insult. When he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.628#saw her weeping like that, without the slightest attempt at retaliation,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.629#with a silent, despairing dignity, Mouret no longer hesitated, his heart
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.630#went out towards her in an immense burst of tenderness. He took her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.631#hands in his and stammered:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.632#“Go away immediately, my child, and forget this house!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.633#Henriette, perfectly amazed, choking with anger, stood looking at them.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.634#“Wait a minute,” continued he, folding up the mantle himself, “take this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.635#garment away. Madame can buy another elsewhere. And pray don't cry any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.636#more. You know how much I esteem you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.637#He went with her to the door, which he closed after her. She had not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.638#said a word; but a pink flame had coloured her cheeks, whilst her eyes
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.639#were wet with fresh tears, tears of a delicious sweetness. Henriette,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.640#who was suffocating, had taken out her handkerchief and was crushing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.641#her lips with it. This was a total overthrowing of her calculations, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.642#herself had been caught in the trap she had laid. She was mortified with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.643#herself for having pushed the matter too far, tortured with jealousy.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.644#To be abandoned for such a creature as that! To see herself disdained
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.645#before her! Her pride suffered more than her love.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.646#“So, it's that girl that you love?” said she, painfully, when they were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.647#alone.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.648#Mouret did not reply at once; he was walking about from the window to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.649#the door, as if absorbed by some violent emotion. At last he stopped,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.650#and very politely, in a voice which he tried to render cold, he replied
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.651#with simplicity: “Yes, madame.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.652#The gas burner was still hissing in the stifling air of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.653#dressing-room. But the reflex of the glasses were no longer traversed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.654#by dancing shadows, the room seemed bare, of a heavy dulness. Henriette
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.655#suddenly dropped on a chair, twisting her handkerchief in her febrile
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.656#fingers, repeating amidst her sobs:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.657#“Good heavens! How miserable I am!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.658#He stood looking at her for several seconds, and then went away quietly.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.659#She, left all alone, wept on in silence, before the pins scattered over
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.660#the dressing-table and the floor.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.661#When Mouret returned to the little drawing-room, he found De Vallagnosc
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.662#alone, the baron having gone back to the ladies. As he felt himself very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.663#agitated still, he sat down at the further end of the room, on a sofa;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.664#and his friend, seeing him turn pale, charitably came and stood before
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.665#him, to conceal him from curious eyes. At first, they looked at each
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.666#other without saying a word. Then De Vallagnosc, who seemed to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.667#inwardly amused at Mouret's confusion, finished by asking in his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.668#bantering voice:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.669#“Are you still enjoying yourself?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.670#Mouret did not appear to understand him at first. But when he remembered
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.671#their former conversations on the empty stupidity and the useless
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.672#torture of life, he replied: “Of course, I've never before lived so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.673#much. Ah! my boy, don't you laugh, the hours that make one die of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.674#grief are by far the shortest.” He lowered his voice, continuing gaily,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.675#beneath his half-wiped tears: “Yes, you know all, don't you? Between
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.676#them they have rent my heart. But yet it's nice, as nice as kisses, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.677#wounds they make. I am thoroughly worn out; but, no matter, you can't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.678#think how I love life! Oh! I shall win her at last, this little girl who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.679#still says no!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.680#De Vallagnosc simply said: “And after?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.681#“After? Why, I shall have her! Isn't that enough? If you think yourself
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.682#strong, because you refuse to be stupid and to suffer, you make a great
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.683#mistake! You are merely a dupe, my boy, nothing more! Try and long for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.684#a woman and win her at last: that pays you in one minute for all your
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.685#misery,” But De Vallagnosc once more trotted out his pessimism. What was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.686#the good of working so much if money could not buy everything? He would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.687#very soon have shut up shop and given up work for ever, the day he found
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.688#out that his millions could not even buy the woman he wanted! Mouret,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.689#listening to him, became grave. Then he set off violently, he believed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.690#in the all-powerfulness of his will.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.691#“I want her, and I'll have her! And if she escapes me, you'll see what
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.692#a place I shall have built to cure myself. It will be splendid, all the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.693#same. You don't understand this language, old man, otherwise you would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.694#know that action contains its own recompense. To act, to create, to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.695#struggle against facts, to overcome them or be overthrown by them, all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.696#human health and joy consists in that!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.697#“Simple method of diverting one's self,” murmured the other.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.698#“Well, I prefer diverting myself. As one must die, I would rather die of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.699#passion than boredom!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.700#They both laughed, this reminded them of their old discussions at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.701#college. De Vallagnosc, in an effeminate voice, then commenced to parade
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.702#his theories of the insipidity of things, investing with a sort of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.703#fanfaronade the immobility and emptiness of his existence. Yes, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.704#dragged on from day to day at the office, in three years he had had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.705#a rise of six hundred francs; he was now receiving three thousand six
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.706#hundred, barely enough to pay for his cigars; it was getting worse than
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.707#ever, and if he did not kill himself, it was simply from a dislike of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.708#all trouble. Mouret having spoken of his marriage with Mademoiselle
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.709#de Boves, he replied that notwithstanding the obstinacy of the aunt
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.710#in refusing to die, the matter was going to be concluded; at least, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.711#thought so, the parents were agreed, and he was ready to do anything
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.712#they might tell him to do. What was the use of wishing or not wishing,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.713#since things never turned out as one desired? He quoted as an example
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.714#his future father-in-law, who expected to find in Madame Guibal an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.715#indolent blonde, the caprice of an hour, but who was now led by her with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.716#a whip, like an old horse on its last legs. Whilst they supposed him to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.717#be busy inspecting the stud at Saint-Lo, she was squandering his last
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.718#resources in a little house hired by him at Versailles.'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.719#“He's happier than you,” said Mouret, getting up.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.720#“Oh! rather!” declared De Vallagnosc. “Perhaps it's only doing wrong
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.721#that's somewhat amusing.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.722#Mouret had now recovered his spirits. He was thinking about getting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.723#away; but not wishing his departure to resemble a flight he resolved to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.724#take a cup of tea, and went into the other drawing-room with his friend,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.725#both in high spirits. The baron asked him if the mantle had been made to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.726#fit, and Mouret replied, carelessly, that he gave it up as far as he was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.727#concerned. They all seemed astonished. Whilst Madame Marty hastened to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.728#serve him, Madame de Boves accused the shops of always keeping their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.729#garments too narrow. At last, he managed to sit down near Bouthemont,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.730#who had not stirred. They were forgotten for a moment, and, in reply to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.731#anxious questions put by Bouthemont, desirous of knowing what he had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.732#to say to him, Mouret did not wait to get into the street, but abruptly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.733#informed him that the board of directors had decided to deprive
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.734#themselves of his services. Between each phrase he drank a drop of tea,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.735#protesting all the while that he was in despair. Oh! a quarrel that he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.736#had not even then got over, for he had left the meeting beside himself
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.737#with rage. But what could he do? he could not break with these gentlemen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.738#about a simple question of staff. Bouthemont, very pale, had to thank
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.739#him once more.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.740#“What a terrible mantle,” observed Madame Marty. “Henriette can't get
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.741#over it.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.742#And really, this prolonged absence began to make every one feel awkward.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.743#But, at that very moment, Madame Desforges appeared.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.744#“So you've given it up as well?” cried Madame de Boves, gaily.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.745#“How do you mean?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.746#“Why, Monsieur Mouret told us you could do nothing with it.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.747#Henriette affected the greatest surprise. “Monsieur Mouret was joking.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.748#The mantle will fit splendidly.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.749#They had again returned to the big shops. Mouret had to give his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.750#opinion; he came up to them and affected to be very just The Bon Marche
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.751#was an excellent house, solid, respectable, but the Louvre certainly had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.752#a more aristocratic class of customers.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.753#“In short, you prefer The Ladies' Paradise,” said the baron, smiling.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.754#“Yes,” replied Mouret, quietly. “There we really love our customers.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.755#All the women present were of his opinion. It was just that, they were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.756#at a sort of private party at The Ladies' Paradise, they felt, there a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.757#continual caress of flattery, an overflowing adoration which detained
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.758#the most dignified and virtuous woman. The enormous success of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.759#establishment sprung from this gallant seduction.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.760#“By the way,” asked Henriette, who wished to appear entirely at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.761#her ease, “what have you done with my protege. Monsieur Mouret? You
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.762#know--Mademoiselle de Fontenailles.” And turning towards Madame Marty
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.763#she explained, “A maricheness, poor girl, fallen into poverty.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.764#“Oh!” said Mouret, “she earns three francs a day stitching.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.765#De Vallagnosc wished to interfere for a joke. “Don't push him too far,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.766#madame, or he'll tell you that all the old families of France ought to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.767#sell calico.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.768#“Well,” declared Mouret, “it would at least be an honourable end for a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.769#great many of them.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.770#They set up a laugh, the paradox seemed rather strong. He continued to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.771#sing the praises of what he called the aristocracy of work. A slight
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.772#flush had coloured Madame de Boves's cheeks, she was wild at the shifts
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.773#she was put to by her poverty; whilst Madame Marty on the contrary
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.774#approved, stricken with remorse on thinking of her poor husband. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.775#footman had just ushered in the professor, who had called to take her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.776#home. He was drier, more emaciated than ever by his hard labour, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.777#still wore his thin shining frock coat. When he had thanked Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.778#Desforges for having spoken for him at the Ministry, he cast at Mouret
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.779#the timid glance of a man meeting the evil that is to kill him. And he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.780#was quite confused when he heard the latter asking him:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.781#“Isn't it true, sir, that work leads to everything?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.782#“Work and economy,” replied he, with a slight shivering of his whole
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.783#body. “Add economy, sir.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.784#Meanwhile, Bouthemont had not moved from his chair, Mouret's words
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.785#were still ringing in his ears. He at last got up, and went and said
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.786#to Henriette in a low tone: “You know, he's given me notice; oh! in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.787#kindest possible manner. But may I be hanged if he sha'n't repent it!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.788#I've just found my sign, The Four Seasons, and shall plant myself close
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.789#to the Opera House!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.790#She looked at him with a gloomy expression. “Reckon on me, I'm with you.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.791#Wait a minute.” And she immediately drew Baron Hartmann into the recess
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.792#of a window, and boldly recommended Bouthemont to him, as a fellow
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.793#who was going to revolutionise Paris, in his turn, by setting up for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.794#himself. When she spoke of an advance of funds for her new protegee, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.795#baron, though now astonished at nothing, could not suppress a gesture of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.796#bewilderment. This was the fourth fellow of genius she had confided to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.797#him, and he began to feel himself ridiculous. But he did not directly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.798#refuse, the idea of starting a competitor to The Ladies' Paradise even
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.799#pleased him somewhat; for he had already invented, in banking matters,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.800#this sort of competition, to keep off others. Besides, the adventure
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.801#amused him, and he promised to look into the matter.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.802#“We must talk it over to-night,” whispered Henriette, returning to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.803#Bouthemont. “Don't fail to call about nine o'clock. The baron is with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.804#us.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.805#At this moment the vast room was foil of voices. Mouret still standing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.806#up, in the midst of the ladies, had recovered his habitual elegant
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.807#gracefulness, and was gaily defending himself from the charge of ruining
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.808#them in dress, offering to prove by the figures that he enabled them
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.809#to save thirty per cent on their purchases. Baron Hartmann watched him,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.810#seized with the fraternal admiration of a former man about town. Come!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.811#the duel was finished, Henriette was decidedly beaten, she certainly was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.812#not the coming woman. And he thought he could see the modest profile of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.813#the young girl whom he had observed on passing through the ante-room.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xi.814#She was there, patient, alone, redoubtable in her sweetness.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1#CHAPTER XII.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.2#It was on the 25th of September that the building of the new façade
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.3#of The Ladies' Paradise was commenced. Baron Hartmann, according to his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.4#promise, had had the matter settled at the last general meeting of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.5#the Credit Immobilier. And Mouret was at length going to enjoy the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.6#realisation of his dreams; this façade, about to arise in the Rue du
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.7#Dix-Décembre, was like the very blossoming of his fortune. He wished,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.8#therefore, to celebrate the laying of the first stone, to make a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.9#ceremony of the work, and he distributed gratuities amongst his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.10#employees, and gave them game and champagne for dinner in the evening.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.11#Every one noticed his wonderfully good humour during the ceremony, his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.12#victorious gesture as he laid the first stone, with a flourish of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.13#trowel. For weeks he had been anxious, agitated by a nervous torment
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.14#that he did not always succeed in concealing; and his triumph served
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.15#as a respite, a distraction in his suffering. During the afternoon he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.16#seemed to have returned to his former healthy gaiety. But, after dinner,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.17#when he went through the refectory to drink a glass of champagne with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.18#his staff, he appeared feverish again, smiling with a painful look, his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.19#features drawn up by the unavowed pain that was devouring him. He was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.20#once more mastered by it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.21#The next day, in the ready-made department, Clara tried to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.22#disagreeable with Denise. She had noticed Colomban's bashful passion,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.23#and took it into her head to joke about the Baudus. As Marguerite was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.24#sharpening her pencil while waiting for customers, she said to her, in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.25#loud voice:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.26#“You know my lover opposite. It really grieves me to see him in that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.27#dark shop, where no one ever enters.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.28#“He's not so badly off,” replied Marguerite, “he's going to marry the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.29#governor's daughter.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.30#“Oh! oh!” replied Clara, “it would be good fun to lead him astray, then!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.31#I'll try the game on, my word of honour!” And she continued in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.32#same strain, happy to feel Denise was shocked. The latter forgave her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.33#everything else; but the idea of her dying cousin Geneviève, finished
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.34#by this cruelty, threw her into an indignant rage. At that moment a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.35#customer came in, and as Madame Aurélie had just gone downstairs, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.36#took the direction of the counter, and called Clara.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.37#“Mademoiselle Prunaire, you had better attend to this lady instead of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.38#gossiping there.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.39#“I wasn't gossiping.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.40#“Have the kindness to hold your tongue, and attend to this lady
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.41#immediately.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.42#Clara gave in, conquered. When Denise showed her authority, quietly,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.43#without raising her voice, not one of them resisted. She had acquired
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.44#absolute authority by her very moderation and sweetness. For a moment
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.45#she walked up and down in silence, amidst the young ladies, who had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.46#become very serious. Marguerite had resumed sharpening her pencil, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.47#point of which was always breaking. She alone continued to approve of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.48#Denise's resistance to Mouret, shaking her head, not acknowledging
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.49#the baby she had had, but declaring that if they had any idea of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.50#consequences of such a thing, they would prefer to remain virtuous.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.51#“What! you're getting angry?” said a voice behind Denise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.52#It was Pauline, who was crossing the department. She had noticed the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.53#scene, and spoke in a low tone, smiling.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.54#“But I'm obliged to,” replied Denise in the same tone, “I can't manage
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.55#them otherwise.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.56#Pauline shrugged her shoulders. “Nonsense, you can be queen over all of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.57#us whenever you like.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.58#She was still unable to understand her friend's refusal. Since the end
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.59#of August, Pauline had been married to Baugé, a most stupid affair,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.60#she would sometimes gaily remark. The terrible Bourdoncle treated her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.61#anyhow, now, considering her as lost for trade. Her only terror was that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.62#they might one fine day send them to love each other elsewhere, for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.63#the managers had decreed love to be execrable and fatal to business.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.64#So great was her fear, that, when she met Baugé in the galleries,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.65#she affected not to know him. She had just had a fright--old Jouve had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.66#nearly caught her talking to her husband behind a pile of dusters.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.67#“See! he's followed me,” added she, after having hastily related the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.68#adventure to Denise. “Just look at him scenting me out with his big
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.69#nose!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.70#Jouve, in fact, was then coming from the lace department, correctly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.71#arrayed in a white tie, his nose on the scent for some delinquent.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.72#But when he saw Denise he assumed a knowing air, and passed by with an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.73#amiable smile.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.74#“Saved!” murmured Pauline. “My dear, you made him swallow that! I say,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.75#if anything should happen to me, you would speak for me, wouldn't you!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.76#Yes, yes, don't put on that astonished air, we know that a word from you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.77#would revolutionise the house.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.78#And she ran off to her counter. Denise had blushed, troubled by these
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.79#amicable allusions. It was true, however. She had a vague sensation of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.80#her power by the flatteries with which she was surrounded. When Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.81#Aurélie returned, and found the department quiet and busy under the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.82#surveillance of the second-hand, she smiled at her amicably. She threw
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.83#over Mouret himself, her amiability increased daily for this young girl
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.84#who might one fine morning desire her situation as first-hand. Denise's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.85#reign was commencing.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.86#Bourdoncle alone still stood out. In the secret war which he continued
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.87#to carry on against the young girl, there was in the first place a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.88#natural antipathy, he detested her for her gentleness and her charm.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.89#Then he fought against her as a fatal influence which would place
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.90#the house in peril the day when Mouret should succumb. The governor's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.91#commercial genius seemed bound to sink amidst this stupid affection:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.92#what they had gained by women would be swallowed up by this woman. None
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.93#of them touched his heart, he treated them with the disdain of a man
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.94#without passion, whose trade is to live on them, and who had had his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.95#last illusions dispelled by seeing them too closely in the miseries of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.96#his traffic. Instead of intoxicating him, the odour of these seventy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.97#thousand customers gave him frightful headaches: and so soon as he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.98#reached home he beat his mistresses. And what made him especially
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.99#anxious in the presence of this little saleswoman, who had gradually
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.100#become so redoubtable, was that he did not in the least believe in her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.101#disinterestedness, in the genuineness of her refusals. For him she was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.102#playing a part, the most skilful of parts; for if she had yielded at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.103#once, Mouret would doubtless have forgotten her the next day; whilst by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.104#refusing, she had goaded his desires, rendering him mad, capable of any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.105#folly. An artful jade, a woman learned in vice, would not have acted any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.106#different to this pattern of innocence.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.107#Thus Bourdoncle could never catch sight of her, with her clear eyes,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.108#sweet face, and simple attitude, without being seized with a real fear,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.109#as if he had before him some disguised female flesh-eater, the sombre
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.110#enigma of woman, Death in the guise of a virgin. In what way could he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.111#confound the tactics of this false novice? He was now only anxious to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.112#penetrate her artful ways, in the hope of exposing them to the light of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.113#day. She would certainly commit some fault, he would surprise her with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.114#one of her lovers, and she should again be dismissed. The house would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.115#then resume its regular working like a well wound-up machine.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.116#“Keep a good look-out, Monsieur Jouve,” repeated Bourdoncle to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.117#inspector. “I'll take care that you shall be rewarded.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.118#But Jouve was somewhat lukewarm, he knew something about women, and was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.119#asking himself whether he had not better take the part of this young
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.120#girl, who might be the future sovereign mistress of the place. Though he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.121#did not now dare to touch her, he still thought her bewitchingly pretty.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.122#His colonel in bygone days had killed himself for a similar little
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.123#thing, with an insignificant face, delicate and modest, one look from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.124#whom ravaged all hearts.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.125#“I do,” replied he. “But, on my word, I cannot discover anything.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.126#And yet stories were circulating, there was quite a stream of abominable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.127#tittle-tattle running beneath the flattery and respect Denise felt
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.128#arising around her. The whole house now declared that she had formerly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.129#had Hutin for a lover; no one could swear that the intimacy still
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.130#continued, but they were suspected of meeting from time to time. Deloche
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.131#also was said to sleep with her, they were continually meeting in dark
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.132#corners, talking for hours together. It was quite a scandal!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.133#“So, nothing about the first-hand in the silk department, nor about the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.134#young man in the lace one?” asked Bourdoncle.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.135#“No, sir, nothing yet,” replied the inspector.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.136#It was with Deloche especially that Bourdoncle expected to surprise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.137#Denise. One morning he himself had caught them laughing together
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.138#downstairs. In the meantime, he treated her on a footing of perfect
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.139#equality, for he no longer disdained her, he felt her to be strong
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.140#enough to overthrow even him, notwithstanding his ten years' service, if
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.141#he lost the game.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.142#“Keep your eye on the young man in the lace department,” concluded he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.143#each time. “They are always together. If you catch them, call me, I'll
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.144#manage the rest.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.145#Mouret, however, was living in anguish. Was it possible that this child
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.146#could torture him in this manner? He could always recall her arriving at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.147#The Ladies' Paradise, with her big shoes, thin black dress, and savage
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.148#airs. She stammered, they all used to laugh at her, he himself had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.149#thought her ugly at first. Ugly! and now she could have brought him on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.150#his knees by a look, he thought her nothing less than an angel! Then she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.151#had remained the last in the house, repulsed, joked at, treated by him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.152#as a curious specimen of humanity. For months he had wanted to see how
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.153#a girl sprung up, and had amused himself at this experiment, without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.154#understanding that he was risking his heart. She, little by little grew
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.155#up, became redoubtable. Perhaps he had loved her from the first moment,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.156#even at the time he thought he felt nothing but pity for her. And yet he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.157#had only really begun to feel this love the evening of their walk under
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.158#the chestnut trees of the Tuileries. His life started from there, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.159#could still hear the laughing of a group of little girls, the distant
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.160#fall of a jet of water, whilst in the warm shade she walked on beside
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.161#him in silence. After that he knew no more, his fever had increased hour
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.162#by hour; all his blood, his whole being, in fact, was sacrificed. And
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.163#for such a child--was it possible? When she passed him now, the slight
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.164#wind from her dress seemed so powerful that he staggered.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.165#For a long time he had struggled, and even now he frequently became
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.166#indignant, endeavouring to extricate himself from this idiotic
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.167#possession. What secret had she to be able to bind him in this way? Had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.168#he not seen her without boots? Had she not been received almost out of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.169#charity? He could have understood it had it been a question of one of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.170#those superb creatures who charm the crowd, but this little girl; this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.171#nobody! She had, in short, one of those insignificant faces which excite
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.172#no remark. She could not even be very intelligent, for he remembered her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.173#bad beginning as a saleswoman. But, after every explosion of anger, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.174#had experienced a relapse of passion, like a sacred terror at having
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.175#insulted his idol. She possessed everything that renders a woman
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.176#good--courage, gaiety, simplicity; and there exhaled from her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.177#gentleness, a charm of a penetrating, perfume-like subtlety. One might
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.178#at first ignore her, or elbow her like any other girl; but the charm
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.179#soon began to act, with a slow invincible force; one belonged to her for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.180#ever, if she deigned to smile. Everything then smiled in her white face,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.181#her pretty eyes, her cheeks and chin full of dimples; whilst her heavy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.182#blonde hair seemed to light up also, with a royal and conquering beauty.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.183#He acknowledged himself vanquished; she was as intelligent as she was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.184#beautiful, her intelligence came from the best part of her being. Whilst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.185#the other saleswomen had only a superficial education, the varnish which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.186#scales off from girls of that class, she, without any false elegance,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.187#retained her native grace, the savour of her origin. The most complete
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.188#commercial ideas sprang up from her experience, under this narrow
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.189#forehead, the pure lines of which clearly announced the presence of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.190#firm will and a love of order. And he could have clasped his hands to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.191#ask her pardon for having blasphemed her during his hours of revolt.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.192#Why did she still refuse with such obstinacy. Twenty times had he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.193#entreated her, increasing his offers, offering money and more money.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.194#Then, thinking she must be ambitious, he had promised to appoint her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.195#first-hand, as soon as there should be a vacant department And she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.196#refused, and still she refused Î For him it was a stupor, a struggle
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.197#in which his desire became enraged. Such an adventure appeared to him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.198#impossible, this child would certainly finish by yielding, for he had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.199#always regarded a woman's virtue as a relative matter. He could see no
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.200#other object, everything disappeared before this necessity: to have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.201#her at last in his room, to take her on his knees, and, kiss her on her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.202#lips; and at this vision, the blood of his veins ran quick and strong,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.203#he trembled, distracted by his own powerlessness.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.204#His days now passed in the same grievous obsession, Denise's image rose
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.205#with him; after having dreamed of her all night, it followed him before
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.206#the desk in his office, where he signed his bills and orders from nine
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.207#to ten o'clock: a work which he accomplished mechanically, never ceasing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.208#to feel her present, still saying no, with her quiet air. Then, at ten
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.209#o'clock, came the board-meeting, a meeting of the twelve directors, at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.210#which he had to preside; they discussed matters affecting the in-door
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.211#arrangements, examined the purchases, settled the window displays; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.212#she was still there, he heard her soft voice amidst the figures, he saw
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.213#her bright smile in the most complicated financial situations. After
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.214#the board-meeting, she still accompanied him, making with him the daily
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.215#inspection of the counters, returned with him to his office in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.216#afternoon, remaining close to his chair from two till four o'clock,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.217#whilst he received a crowd of important business men, the principal
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.218#manufacturers of all France, bankers, inventors; a continual come-and-go
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.219#of the riches and intelligence of the land, an excited dance of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.220#millions, rapid interviews during which were hatched the biggest affairs
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.221#on the Paris market. If he forgot her for a moment whilst deciding
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.222#on the ruin or the prosperity of an industry, he found her again at a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.223#twitch of his heart; his voice died away, he asked himself what was the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.224#use of this princely fortune when she still refused. At last, when five
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.225#o'clock struck, he had to sign the day's correspondence, the mechanical
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.226#working of his hand again commenced, whilst she rose up before him more
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.227#dominating than ever, seizing him entirely, to possess him during the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.228#solitary and ardent hours of the night. And the morrow was the same day
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.229#over again, those days so active, so full of a colossal labour, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.230#the slight shadow of a child sufficed to ravage with anguish.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.231#But it was especially during his daily inspection of the departments
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.232#that he felt his misery. To have built up this giant machine, to reign
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.233#over such a world of people, and to be dying of grief because a little
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.234#girl would not accept him! He scorned himself, dragging the fever and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.235#shame of his pain about with him everywhere. On certain days he became
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.236#disgusted with his power, feeling a nausea at the very sight of the long
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.237#galleries. At other times he would have wished to extend his empire, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.238#make it so vast that she would perhaps yield out of sheer admiration and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.239#fear.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.240#He first of all stopped in the basement opposite the shoot. It was still
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.241#in the Rue Neuve-Saint-Augustin; but it had been necessary to enlarge
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.242#it, and it was now as wide as the bed of a river, down which the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.243#continual flood of goods rolled with the loud noise of rushing water; it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.244#was a constant succession of arrivals from all parts of the world, rows
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.245#of waggons from all railways, a ceaseless discharging of merchandise,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.246#a stream of boxes and bales running underground, absorbed by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.247#insatiable establishment. He gazed at this torrent flowing into his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.248#house, thought of his position as one of the masters of the public
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.249#fortune, that he held in his hands the fate of the French manufacturers,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.250#and that he was unable to buy a kiss from one of his saleswomen.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.251#Then he passed on to the receiving department, which now occupied that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.252#part of the basement running along the Rue Monsigny. Twenty tables were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.253#ranged there, in the pale light of the air-holes; dozens of shopmen were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.254#bustling about, emptying the cases, checking the goods, and marking them
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.255#in plain figures, amidst the roar of the shoot, which almost drowned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.256#their voices. Various managers of departments stopped him, he had to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.257#resolve difficulties and confirm orders. This cellar was filled with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.258#tender glimmer of the satin, the whiteness of the linen, a prodigious
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.259#unpacking in which the furs were mingled with the lace, the fancy goods
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.260#with the Eastern curtains. With a slow step he made his way amongst all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.261#these riches thrown about in disorder, heaped up in their rough state.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.262#Above, they were destined to ornament the window displays, letting loose
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.263#the race after money across the counters, no sooner shown than carried
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.264#off, in the furious current of business which traversed the place. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.265#thought of his having offered the young girl silks, velvets, anything
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.266#she liked to take in any quantities, from these enormous heaps, and that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.267#she had refused by a shake of her fair head.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.268#After that, he passed on to the other end of the basement, to pay his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.269#usual visit to the delivery department. Interminable corridors ran
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.270#along, lighted up with gas; to the right and to the left, the reserves,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.271#closed in with gratings, were like so many subterranean stores, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.272#complete commercial quarter, with its haberdashery, underclothing,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.273#glove, and other shops, sleeping in the shade. Further on was placed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.274#one of the three stoves; further still, a fireman's post guarding
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.275#the gas-meter, enclosed in its iron cage. He found, in the delivery
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.276#department, the sorting tables already blocked with loads of parcels,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.277#bandboxes, and cases, continually arriving in large baskets; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.278#Campion, the superintendent, gave him some particulars about the current
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.279#work, whilst the twenty men placed under his orders distributed the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.280#parcels into large compartments, each bearing the name of a district of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.281#Paris, and from whence the messengers took them up to the vans, ranged
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.282#along the pavement. One heard a series of cries, names of streets, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.283#recommendations shouted out; quite an uproar, an agitation such as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.284#on board a mail boat about to start. And he stood there for a moment,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.285#motionless, looking at this discharge of goods which he had just seen
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.286#absorbed by the house, at the opposite extremity of the basement: the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.287#enormous current there discharged itself into the street, after having
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.288#filled the tills with gold. His eyes became misty, this colossal
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.289#business no longer had any importance; he had but one idea, that of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.290#going away to some distant, land, and abandoning everything, if she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.291#persisted in saying no.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.292#He then went upstairs, continuing his inspection, talking, and agitating
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.293#himself more and more, without finding any respite. On the second floor
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.294#he entered the correspondence department, picking quarrels, secretly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.295#exasperated against the perfect regularity of this machine that he had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.296#himself built up. This department was the one that was daily assuming
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.297#the most considerable importance; it now required two hundred
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.298#employees--some opening, reading, and classifying the letters coming
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.299#from the provinces and abroad, whilst others gathered into compartments
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.300#the goods ordered by the correspondents. And the number of letters was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.301#increasing to such an extent that they no longer counted them; they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.302#weighed them, receiving as much as a hundred pounds per day. He,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.303#feverish, went through the three offices, questioning Levasseur as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.304#to the weight of the correspondence; eighty pounds, ninety pounds,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.305#sometimes, on a Monday, a hundred pounds. The figure increased daily, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.306#ought to have been delighted. But he stood shuddering, in the noise made
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.307#by the neighbouring squad of packers nailing down the cases. Vainly he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.308#roamed about the house; the fixed idea remained fast in his mind, and as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.309#his power unfolded itself before him, as the mechanism of the business
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.310#and the army of employees passed before his gaze, he felt more
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.311#profoundly than ever the insult of his powerlessness. Orders from all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.312#Europe were flowing in, a special post-office van was required for his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.313#correspondence; and yet she said no, always no.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.314#He went downstairs again, visiting the central cashier's office, where
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.315#four clerks guarded the two giants safes, in which there had passed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.316#the previous year forty-eight million francs. He glanced at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.317#clearing-house, which now occupied twenty-five clerks, chosen from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.318#amongst the most trustworthy. He went into the next office, where
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.319#twenty-five young men, junior clerks, were engaged in checking the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.320#debit-notes, and calculating the salesmen's commission. He returned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.321#to the chief cashier's office, exasperated at the sight of the safes,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.322#wandering amidst these millions, the uselessness of which drove him mad.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.323#She said no, always no.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.324#And it was always no, in all the departments, in the galleries, in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.325#saloons, and in every part of the establishment! He went from the silk
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.326#to the drapery department, from the linen to the lace department, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.327#ascended to the upper floors, stopping on the flying bridges, prolonging
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.328#his inspection with a maniacal, grievous minuteness. The house had grown
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.329#out of all bounds, he had created this department, then this other; he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.330#governed this fresh domain, he extended his empire into this industry,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.331#the last one conquered; and it was no, always no, in spite of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.332#everything. His staff would now have sufficed to people a small town:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.333#there were fifteen hundred salesmen, and a thousand other employees
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.334#of every sort, including forty inspectors and seventy cashiers; the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.335#kitchens alone gave occupation to thirty-two men; ten clerks were set
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.336#apart for the advertising; there were three hundred and fifty shop
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.337#messengers, all wearing livery, and twenty-four firemen living on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.338#premises. And, in the stables, royal buildings situated in the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.339#Monsigny, opposite the warehouse, were one hundred and forty-five
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.340#horses, a luxurious establishment which was already celebrated in Paris.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.341#The first four conveyances which used formerly to stir up the whole
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.342#neighbourhood, when the house occupied only the corner of the Place
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.343#Gaillon, had gradually increased to sixty-two trucks, one-horse vans,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.344#and heavy two-horse ones. They were continually scouring Paris, driven
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.345#with knowing skill by drivers dressed in black, promenading the gold
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.346#and purple sign of The Ladies' Paradise. They even went beyond the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.347#fortifications, into the suburbs; they were to be met on the dusty roads
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.348#of Bicêtre, along the banks of the Marne, even in the shady drives of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.349#the Forest of Saint-Germain. Sometimes one would spring up from the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.350#depths of some sunny avenue, where all was silent and deserted, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.351#superb animals trotting along, throwing into the mysterious peacefulness
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.352#of this grand nature the loud advertisement of its varnished panels. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.353#was even dreaming of launching them further still, into the neighbouring
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.354#departments; he would have liked to hear them rolling along every
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.355#road in France, from one frontier to the other. But he no longer even
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.356#troubled to visit his horses, though he was passionately fond of them.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.357#Of what good was this conquest of the world, since it was no, always no?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.358#At present, in the evening, when he arrived at Lhomme's desk, he still
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.359#looked through habit at the amount of the takings written on a card,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.360#which the cashier stuck on an iron file at his side; this figure rarely
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.361#fell below a hundred thousand francs, sometimes it ran up to eight and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.362#nine hundred thousand, on big sale days; but these figures no longer
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.363#sounded in his ears like a trumpet-blast, he regretted having looked at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.364#them, going away full of bitterness and scorn for money.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.365#But Mouret's sufferings were destined to increase, for he became
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.366#jealous. One morning, in the office, before the boardmeeting commenced,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.367#Bourdoncle ventured to hint that the little girl in the ready-made
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.368#department was playing with him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.369#“How?” asked he, very pale.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.370#“Yes! she has lovers in this very building.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.371#Mouret found strength to smile. “I don't think any more about her, my
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.372#dear fellow. You can speak freely. Who are her lovers?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.373#“Hutin, they say, and then a salesman in the lace department--Deloche,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.374#that tall awkward fellow. I can't speak with certainty, never having
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.375#seen them together. But it appears that it's notorious.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.376#There was a silence. Mouret affected to arrange the papers on his desk,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.377#to conceal the trembling of his hands. At last, he observed, without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.378#raising his head: “We must have proofs, try and bring me some proofs. As
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.379#for me, I assure you I don't, care in the least, for I'm quite sick of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.380#her. But we can't allow such things to go on here.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.381#Bourdoncle simply replied: “Never fear, you shall have proofs one of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.382#these days. I'm keeping a good look out.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.383#This news deprived Mouret of all rest. He no longer had the courage to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.384#return to this conversation, but lived in the continual expectation of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.385#a catastrophe, in which his heart would be crushed. And this torment
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.386#rendered him terrible, the whole house trembled before him. He now
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.387#disdained to conceal himself behind Bourdoncle, but performed the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.388#executions in person, feeling a nervous desire for revenge, solacing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.389#himself by an abuse of his power, of that power which could do nothing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.390#for the contentment of his sole desire. Each one of his inspections
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.391#became a massacre, his appearance caused a panic to run along from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.392#counter to counter. The dead winter season was just then approaching,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.393#and he made a clean sweep in the departments, multiplying the victims
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.394#and pushing them into the streets. His first idea had been to dismiss
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.395#Hutin and Deloche; then he had reflected that if he did not keep them,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.396#he would never discover anything; and the others suffered for them: the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.397#whole staff trembled. In the evening, when he found himself alone again,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.398#his eyes swelled up, big with tears.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.399#One day especially terror reigned supreme. An inspector had the idea
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.400#that Mignot was stealing. There were always a lot of strange-looking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.401#girls prowling around his counter; and one of them had just been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.402#arrested, her thighs and bosom padded with sixty pairs of gloves. From
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.403#that moment a watch was kept, and the inspector caught Mignot in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.404#act, facilitating the sleight of hand of a tall fair girl, formerly a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.405#saleswoman at the Louvre, but since gone wrong: the manouvre was very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.406#simple, he affected to try some gloves on her, waited till she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.407#padded herself, and then conducted her to the pay-desk, where she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.408#paid for a single pair only. Mouret happened to be there, just at that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.409#moment. As a rule, he preferred not to mix himself up with these sort of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.410#adventures, which were pretty frequent; for notwithstanding the regular
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.411#working of the well-arranged machine, great disorder reigned in certain
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.412#departments of The Ladies' Paradise, and scarcely a week passed without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.413#some employee being dismissed for theft. The authorities preferred to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.414#hush up such matters as far as possible, considering it useless to set
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.415#the police at work, and thus expose one of the fatal plague-spots of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.416#these great bazaars. But, that day, Mouret felt a real need of getting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.417#angry with some one, and he treated the handsome Mignot with such
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.418#violence, and the latter stood there trembling with fear, his face pale
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.419#and discomposed.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.420#“I ought to call a policeman,” cried Mouret, before all the other
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.421#salesmen. “But why don't you answer? who is this woman? I swear I'll
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.422#send for the police, if you don't tell me the truth.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.423#They had taken the woman away, and two saleswomen were undressing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.424#her. Mignot stammered out: “I don't know her, sir. She's the one who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.425#came----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.426#“Don't tell lies!” interrupted Mouret, in a violent rage. “And there's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.427#nobody here to warn us! You are all in the plot, on my word! We are in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.428#a regular wood, robbed, pillaged, plundered. It's enough to make us have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.429#the pockets of each one searched before going out!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.430#Murmurs were heard. The three or four customers buying gloves stood
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.431#looking on, frightened.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.432#“Silence!” resumed he, furiously, “or I'll clear the place!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.433#But Bourdoncle came running up, anxious at the idea of the scandal.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.434#He whispered a few words in Mouret's ear, the affair was assuming an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.435#exceptional gravity; and he prevailed on him to take Mignot into the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.436#inspectors' office, a room on the ground floor near the entrance in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.437#Rue Gaillon. The woman was there, quietly putting on her stays again.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.438#She had just mentioned Albert Lhomme's name. Mignot, again questioned,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.439#lost his head, and commenced to sob; he wasn't in fault, it was Albert
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.440#who sent him his mistresses; at first he had merely afforded them
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.441#certain advantages, enabling them to profit by the bargains; then, when
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.442#they at last took to stealing, he was already too far compromised
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.443#to report the matter. The principals now discovered a series of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.444#extraordinary robberies; goods taken away by girls, who went into the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.445#neighbouring W.Cs, built near the refreshment bar and surrounded by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.446#evergreen plants, to hide the goods under their petticoats; purchases
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.447#that a salesman neglected to call out at a pay-desk, when he accompanied
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.448#a customer there, the price of which he divided with the cashier; even
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.449#down to false returns, articles which they announced as brought back to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.450#the house, pocketing the money thus repaid; without even mentioning the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.451#classical robbery, parcels taken out under their coats in the evening,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.452#rolled round their bodies, and sometimes even hung down their leg's. For
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.453#the last fourteen months, thanks to Mignot and other salesmen, no doubt,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.454#whom they refused to name, this pilfering had been going on at Albert's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.455#desk, quite an impudent trade, for sums of which no one ever knew the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.456#exact total.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.457#Meanwhile the news had spread into the various departments, causing the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.458#guilty consciences to tremble, and the most honest ones to quake at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.459#the general sweep that seemed imminent. Albert had disappeared into the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.460#inspectors' office. Next his father had passed, choking, his face full
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.461#of blood, showing signs of apoplexy. Madame Aurélie herself was then
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.462#called; and she, her head high beneath the affront, had the fat,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.463#puffed-up appearance of a wax mask. The explanation lasted some time,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.464#no one knew the exact details; but it was said the firsthand had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.465#slapped her son's face, and that the worthy old father wept, whilst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.466#the governor, contrary to all his elegant habits, swore like a trooper,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.467#absolutely wanting to deliver the offenders up to justice. However, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.468#scandal was hushed up. Mignot was the only one dismissed there and then.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.469#Albert did not disappear till two days later; no doubt his mother
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.470#had begged that the family should not be dishonoured by an immediate
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.471#execution. But the panic lasted several days longer, for after this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.472#scene Mouret had wandered from one end of the establishment to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.473#other, with a terrible expression, venting his anger on all those who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.474#dared even to raise their eyes.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.475#“What are you doing there, sir, looking at the flies? Go and be paid!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.476#At last, the storm burst one day on the head of Hutin himself. Favier,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.477#appointed second-hand, was undermining the first-hand, in order to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.478#dislodge him from his position. This was always the way; he addressed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.479#crafty reports to the directors, taking advantage of every occasion to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.480#have the first-hand caught doing something wrong. Thus, one morning, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.481#Mouret was going through the silk department, he stopped, surprised to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.482#see Favier engaged in altering the price tickets of a stock of black
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.483#velvet.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.484#“Why are you lowering the prices?” asked he. “Who gave you the order to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.485#do so?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.486#The second-hand, who was making a great noise over this work, as if
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.487#he wished to attract the governor's attention, foreseeing the result,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.488#replied with an innocent, surprised air:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.489#“Why, Monsieur Hutin told me, sir.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.490#“Monsieur Hutin! Where is Monsieur Hutin?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.491#And when the latter came upstairs, called by a salesman, an animated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.492#explanation ensued. What! he undertook to lower the prices himself now!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.493#But he appeared greatly astonished in his turn, having merely talked
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.494#over the matter with Favier, without giving any positive orders. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.495#latter then assumed the sorrowful air of an employee who finds himself
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.496#obliged to contradict his superior. However, he was quite willing to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.497#accept the blame, if it would get the latter out of a scrape. Things
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.498#began to look very bad.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.499#“Understand, Monsieur Hutin!” cried Mouret, “I have never tolerated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.500#these attempts at independence. We alone decide about the prices.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.501#He continued, with a sharp voice, and wounding intentions, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.502#surprised the salesmen, for as a rule these discussions were carried
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.503#on quietly, and the case might really have resulted from a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.504#misunderstanding. One could feel he had some unavowed spite to satisfy.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.505#He had at last caught that Hutin at fault, that Hutin who was said to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.506#Denise's lover! He could now solace himself, by making him feel that he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.507#was the master! And he exaggerated matters, even insinuating that this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.508#reduction of price appeared to conceal very questionable intentions.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.509#“Sir,” repeated Hutin, “I meant to consult you about it. It is really
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.510#necessary, as you know, for these velvets have not succeeded.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.511#Mouret cut him short with a final insult. “Very good, sir; we will look
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.512#into the matter. But don't do such a thing again, if you value your
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.513#place.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.514#And he walked off. Hutin, bewildered, furious, finding no one but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.515#Favier to confide in, swore he would go and throw his resignation at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.516#brute's head. But he soon left off talking of going away, and began to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.517#stir up all the abominable accusations which were current amongst the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.518#salesmen against their chiefs. And Favier, his eye sparkling, defended
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.519#himself with a great show of sympathy. He was obliged to reply, wasn't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.520#he? Besides, could any one have foreseen such a row for so trifling
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.521#a matter? What had come to the governor lately, that he should be so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.522#unbearable?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.523#“We all know what's the matter with him,” replied Hutin, “Is it my fault
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.524#if that little jade in the dress-department is turning his head? My dear
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.525#fellow, you can see the blow comes from there. He's aware I've slept
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.526#with her, and he doesn't like it; or perhaps it's she herself who wants
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.527#to get me pitched out, because I'm in her way. But I swear she shall
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.528#hear from me, if ever she crosses my path.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.529#Two days after, as Hutin was going up into the work-room, upstairs,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.530#under the roof, to recommend a person, he started on perceiving at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.531#end of a passage Denise and Deloche leaning out of a window, and plunged
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.532#so deeply in private conversation that they did not even turn round. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.533#idea of having them caught occurred to him suddenly, when he perceived
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.534#with astonishment that Deloche was weeping. He at once went away without
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.535#making any noise; and meeting Bourdoncle and Jouve on the stairs, told
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.536#them some story about one of the _extincteurs_ the door of which seemed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.537#to be broken; in this way they would go upstairs and drop on to the two
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.538#others. Bourdoncle discovered them first. He stopped short, and told
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.539#Jouve to go and fetch the governor, whilst he remained there. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.540#inspector had to obey, greatly annoyed at being forced to compromise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.541#himself in such a matter.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.542#This was a lost corner of the vast world in which the people of The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.543#Ladies' Paradise worked. One arrived there by a complication of stairs
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.544#and passages. The work-rooms occupied the top of the house, a succession
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.545#of low sloping rooms, lighted by large windows cut in the zinc roof,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.546#furnished solely with long tables and enormous iron stoves; and right
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.547#along were a crowd of work-girls of all sorts, for the under-clothing,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.548#the lace, the dressmaking, and the house furnishing; living winter and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.549#summer in a stifling heat, amidst the odour special to the business;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.550#and one had to go straight through the wing, and turn to the right
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.551#on passing the dressmakers, before coming to this solitary end of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.552#corridor. The rare customers, that a salesman occasionally brought
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.553#here for an order, gasped for breath, tired out, frightened, with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.554#sensation of having been turning round for hours and hours, and of being
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.555#a hundred leagues above the street.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.556#Denise had often found Deloche waiting for her. As secondhand she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.557#charge of the arrangements between her department and the work-room
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.558#where only the models and alterations were done, and was always going up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.559#and down to give the necessary orders. He watched for her, inventing any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.560#pretext to run after her; then he affected to be surprised when he met
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.561#her at the work-room door. She got to laugh about the matter, it became
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.562#quite an understood thing. The corridor ran alongside the cistern, an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.563#enormous iron tank containing twelve thousand gallons of water; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.564#there was another one of equal size on the roof, reached by an iron
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.565#ladder. For an instant, Deloche would stand talking, leaning with one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.566#shoulder against the cistern in the continual abandonment of his long
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.567#body, bent with fatigue. The noise of the water was heard, a mysterious
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.568#noise of which the iron tank ever retained the musical vibration.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.569#Notwithstanding the deep silence, Denise would turn round anxiously,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.570#thinking she had seen a shadow pass on the bare, yellow-painted walls.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.571#But the window would soon attract them, they would lean out, and forget
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.572#themselves in a pleasant gossip, in endless souvenirs of their native
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.573#place. Below them, extended the immense glass roof of the central
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.574#gallery, a lake of glass bounded by the distant housetops, like a rocky
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.575#coast. Beyond, they saw nothing but the sky, a sheet of sky, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.576#reflected in the sleeping water of the glazed work the flight of its
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.577#clouds and the tender blue of its azure.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.578#It so happened that Deloche was speaking of Valognes that day. “I was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.579#six years old; my mother took me to Valognes market in a cart. You know
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.580#it's ten miles away; we had to leave Bricquebec at five o'clock. It's a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.581#fine country down our way. Do you know it?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.582#“Yes, yes,” replied Denise, slowly, her looks lost in the distance. “I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.583#was there once, but was very little then. Nice roads with grass on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.584#each side, aren't there? and now and again sheep browsing in couples,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.585#dragging their clog along by the rope.” She stopped, then resumed with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.586#a vague smile: “Our roads run as straight as an arrow for miles between
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.587#rows of trees which afford a lot of shade. We have meadows surrounded
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.588#with hedges taller than I am, where there are horses and cows feeding.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.589#We have a little river, and the water is very cold, under the brushwood,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.590#in a spot I know well.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.591#“It is the same with us, exactly!” cried Deloche, delighted. “There's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.592#grass everywhere, each one encloses his plot with thorns and elms, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.593#is at once at home; and it's quite green, a green far different to what
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.594#we see in Paris. Dear me! what fun I've had at the bottom of the road,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.595#to the left, coming down from the mill!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.596#And their voices died away, they stopped with their eyes fixed and lost
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.597#on the sunny lake of the glazed work. A mirage rose up before them from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.598#this blinding water, they saw an endless succession of meadows, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.599#Cotentin bathed in the balmy breath of the ocean, a luminous vapour,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.600#which melted the horizon into a delicate pearly grey. Below, under the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.601#colossal iron framework, in the silk hall, roared the business, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.602#trepidation of the machine at work; the entire house vibrated with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.603#trampling of the crowd, the bustle of the shopmen, and the life of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.604#thirty thousand persons elbowing each other there; and they, carried
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.605#away by their dreams, on feeling this profound and dull clamour with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.606#which the roofs were resounding, thought they heard the wind passing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.607#over the grass, shaking the tall trees.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.608#“Ah! Mademoiselle Denise,” stammered Deloche, “why aren't you kinder to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.609#me? I love you so much!” Tears had come into his eyes, and as she tried
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.610#to interrupt him with a gesture, he continued quickly: “No--let me tell
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.611#you these things once more. We should get on so well together! People
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.612#always find something to talk about when they come from the same place.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.613#He was choking, and she at last managed to say kindly: “You're
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.614#not reasonable; you promised me never to speak of that again. It's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.615#impossible. I have a good friendship for you, because you're a nice
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.616#fellow; but I wish to remain free.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.617#“Yes, yes. I know it,” replied he in a broken voice, “you don't love me.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.618#Oh! you may say so, I quite understand it. There's nothing in me to make
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.619#you love me. Listen, I've only had one sweet moment in my life, and that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.620#was when I met you at Joinville, do you remember? For a moment under the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.621#trees, when it was so dark, I thought your arm trembled, and was stupid
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.622#enough to imagine----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.623#But she again interrupted him. Her quick ear had just caught
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.624#Bourdoncle's and Jouve's steps at the end of the corridor.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.625#“Hark, there's some one coming.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.626#“No,” said he, preventing her leaving the window, “it's in the cistern:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.627#all sorts of extraordinary noises come up from it, as if there were some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.628#one inside.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.629#And he continued his timid, caressing complaints. She was no longer
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.630#listening to him, rocked into dreamland by this declaration of love, her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.631#looks wandering over the roofs of The Ladies' Paradise. To the right
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.632#and the left of the glazed gallery, other galleries, other halls, were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.633#glistening in the sun, between the tops of the houses, pierced with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.634#windows and running along symmetrically, like the wings of a barracks.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.635#Immense metallic works rose up, ladders, bridges, describing a lacework
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.636#of iron in the air; whilst the kitchen chimneys threw out an immense
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.637#volume of smoke like a factory, and the great square cistern, supported
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.638#in the air on wrought-iron pillars, assumed a strange, barbarous
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.639#profile, hoisted up to this height by the pride of one man. In the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.640#distance, Paris was roaring.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.641#When Denise returned from this dreamy state, from this fanciful
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.642#development of The Ladies' Paradise, in which her thoughts floated as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.643#in a vast solitude, she found that Deloche had seized her hand. And he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.644#appeared so woe-begone, so full of grief, that she had not the heart to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.645#draw it away.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.646#“Forgive me,” he murmured. “It's all over now; I should be quite too
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.647#miserable if you punished me by withdrawing your friendship. I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.648#assure you I intended to say something else. Yes, I had determined to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.649#understand the situation and be very good.” His tears again began to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.650#flow, he tried to steady his voice. “For I know my lot in life. It is
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.651#too late for my luck to turn. Beaten at home, beaten in Paris, beaten
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.652#everywhere. I've now been here four years and am still the last in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.653#department So I wanted to tell you not to trouble on my account. I won't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.654#annoy you any longer. Try to be happy, love some one else; yes, that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.655#would really be a pleasure for me. If you are happy, I shall be also.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.656#That will be my happiness.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.657#He could say no more. As if to seal his promise he raised the young
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.658#girl's hand to his lips--kissing it with the humble kiss of a slave. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.659#was deeply affected, and said simply, in a tender, sisterly tone, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.660#attenuated somewhat the pity of the words:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.661#“My poor boy!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.662#But they started, and turned round; Mouret was standing before them.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.663#For the last ten minutes, Jouve had been searching for the governor all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.664#over the place; but the latter was looking at the works going on for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.665#new façade in the Rue du Dix-Décembre. He spent long hours there every
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.666#day, trying to interest himself in this work, of which he had so long
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.667#dreamed. This was his refuge against his torments, amidst the masons
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.668#laying the immense corner-stones, and the engineers setting up the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.669#great iron framework. The façade already appeared above the level of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.670#street, indicating the vast porch, and the windows of the first storey,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.671#a palace-like development in its crude state. He scaled the ladders,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.672#discussing with the architect the ornamentation which was to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.673#something quite new, scrambled over the heaps of brick and iron, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.674#even went down into the cellar; and the roar of the steam-engine, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.675#tic-tac of the trowels, the noise of the hammers, the clamour of this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.676#people of workmen, all over this immense cage surrounded by sonorous
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.677#planks, really distracted him for an instant. He came out white with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.678#plaster, black with iron-filings, his feet splashed by the water from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.679#the pumps, his pain so far from being cured that his anguish returned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.680#and his heart beat stronger than ever, as the noise of the works died
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.681#away behind him. It so happened, on the day in question, a slight
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.682#distraction had restored him his gaiety, and he was deeply interested
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.683#in an album of drawings of the mosaics and enamelled terra-cottas which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.684#were to decorate the friezes, when Jouve came up to fetch him, out of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.685#breath, annoyed at being obliged to dirty his coat amongst all this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.686#building material. At first Mouret had cried out that they must
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.687#wait; then, at a word spoken in a low tone by the inspector, he had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.688#immediately followed him, shivering, a prey again to his passion.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.689#Nothing else existed, the façade crumbled away before being built; what
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.690#was the use of this supreme triumph of his pride, if the simple name of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.691#a woman whispered in his ear tortured him to this extent.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.692#Upstairs, Bourdoncle and Jouve thought it prudent to vanish. Deloche
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.693#had already run away, Denise alone remained to face Mouret, paler than
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.694#usual, but looking straight into his eyes.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.695#“Have the kindness to follow me, mademoiselle,” said he in a harsh
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.696#voice.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.697#She followed him, they descended the two storeys, and crossed the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.698#furniture and carpet departments without saying a word. When he arrived
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.699#at his office, he opened the door wide, saying, “Walk in, mademoiselle.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.700#And, closing the door, he went to his desk. The new director's office
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.701#was fitted up more luxuriously than the old one, the reps hangings had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.702#been replaced by velvet ones, and a book-case, incrusted with ivory,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.703#occupied one whole side; but on the walls there was still no picture but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.704#the portrait of Madame Hédouin, a young woman with a handsome calm face,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.705#smiling in its gold frame.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.706#“Mademoiselle,” said he at last, trying to maintain a cold, severe
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.707#air, “there are certain things that we cannot tolerate. Good conduct is
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.708#absolutely necessary here.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.709#He stopped, choosing his words, in order not to yield to the furious
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.710#anger which was rising up within him. What! she loved this fellow, this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.711#miserable salesman, the laughingstock of his counter! and it was the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.712#humblest, the most awkward of all that she preferred to him, the master!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.713#for he had seen them, she leaving her hand in his, and he covering that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.714#hand with kisses.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.715#“I've been very good to you, mademoiselle,” continued he, making a fresh
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.716#effort “I little expected to be rewarded in this way.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.717#Denise, immediately on entering, had been attracted by Madame Hédouin's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.718#portrait; and, notwithstanding her great trouble, was still pre-occupied
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.719#by it. Every time she came into the director's office her eyes were sure
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.720#to meet those of this lady. She felt almost afraid of her, although
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.721#she knew her to have been very good. This time, she felt her to be a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.722#protection.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.723#“You are right, sir,” he said, softly, “I was wrong to stop and talk,
