urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.919#incessantly renewed around her skirts.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.920#She now had frequent friendly conversations with Mouret. When she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.921#went to the office to take orders and furnish information, he kept her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.922#talking, enjoying the sound of her voice. It was what she laughingly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.923#called “making a good man of him.” In her prudent, cautious Norman head
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.924#there sprang up all sorts of projects, ideas about the new business
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.925#which she had already ventured to hint at when at Robineau's, and some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.926#of which she had expressed on the evening of their walk in the Tuileries
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.927#gardens. She could not be occupied in any matter, see any work going on,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.928#without being moved with a desire to introduce some improvement in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.929#mechanism. Then, since her entry into The Ladies' Paradise, she was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.930#especially pained by the precarious position of the employees; the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.931#sudden dismissals shocked her, she thought them iniquitous and stupid,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.932#hurtful to all, to the house as much as to the staff. Her former
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.933#sufferings were still fresh in her mind, and her heart was seized with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.934#pity every time she saw a new comer, her feet bruised, her eyes dim with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.935#tears, dragging herself along in her misery in her silk dress, amidst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.936#the spiteful persecution of the old hands. This dog's life made the best
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.937#of them bad; and the sad work of destruction commenced: all eaten up by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.938#the trade before the age of forty, disappearing, falling into unknown
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.939#places, a great many dying in harness, some of consumption and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.940#exhaustion, others of fatigue and bad air, a few thrown on the street,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.941#the happiest married, buried in some little provincial shop. Was it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.942#humane, was it just, this frightful consumption of human life that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.943#the big shops carried on every year? And she pleaded the cause of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.944#wheel-work of the colossal machine, not from any sentimental reasons,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.945#but by arguments appealing to the very interests of the employers. To
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.946#make a machine solid and strong, it is necessary to use good iron; if
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.947#the iron breaks or is broken, there is a stoppage of work, repeated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.948#expenses of starting, quite a loss of power.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.949#Sometimes she would become quite animated, she would picture an immense
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.950#ideal bazaar, the phalansterium of modern commerce, in which each one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.951#should have his exact share of the profits, according to his merits,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.952#with the certainty of the future, assured to him by a contract Mouret
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.953#would feel amused at this, notwithstanding his fever. He accused her of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.954#socialism, embarrassed her by pointing out the difficulties of carrying
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.955#out these schemes; for she spoke in the simplicity of her soul, bravely
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.956#trusting in the future, when she perceived a dangerous hole underlying
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.957#her tender-hearted plans. He was, however, shaken, captivated by this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.958#young voice, still trembling from the evils endured, so convinced and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.959#earnest in pointing out the reforms which would tend to consolidate the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.960#house; yet he listened while joking with her; the salesmen's position
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.961#gradually improved, the wholesale dismissals were replaced by a system
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.962#of holidays granted during the dead seasons, and there was also about
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.963#to be created a sort of benefit club which would protect the employees
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.964#against bad times and ensure them a pension. It was the embryo of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.965#vast trades' unions of the twentieth century.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.966#Denise did not confine her attention solely to healing the wounds from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.967#which she had herself bled; she conceived various delicate feminine
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.968#ideas, which, communicated to Mouret, delighted the customers. She also
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.969#caused Lhomme's happiness by supporting a scheme he had long nourished,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.970#that of creating a band of music, in which all the executants should be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.971#chosen from amongst the staff. Three months later Lhomme had a hundred
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.972#and twenty musicians under his direction, the dream of his whole life
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.973#was realised. And a grand fête was given on the premises, a concert and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.974#a ball, to introduce the band of The Ladies' Paradise to the customers
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.975#and the whole world. The newspapers took the matter up, Bourdoncle
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.976#himself, frightened by these innovations, was obliged to bow before this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.977#immense advertisement. Afterwards, a recreation room for the men was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.978#established, with two billiard tables and backgammon and chess boards.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.979#Then classes were held in the house of an evening; there were lessons in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.980#English and German, in grammar, arithmetic, and geography; they even
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.981#had lessons in riding and fencing. A library was formed, ten thousand
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.982#volumes were placed at the disposal of the employees. And a resident
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.983#doctor giving consultations gratis was also added, together with baths,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.984#and hair-dressing and refreshment saloons. Every want in life
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.985#was provided for, everything was to be obtained without going
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.986#outside--board, lodging, and clothing. The Ladies' Paradise sufficed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.987#entirely for all its own wants and pleasures, in the very heart of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.988#Paris, taken up by all this clatter, by this working city which was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.989#springing up so vigorously out of the ruins of the old streets, at last
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.990#opened to the rays of the sun.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.991#Then a fresh movement of opinion took place in Denise's favour. As
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.992#Bourdoncle, vanquished, repeated with despair to his friends that he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.993#would give a great deal to put Denise into Mouret's arms himself, it was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.994#concluded that she had not yielded, that her all-powerfulness resulted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.995#from her refusal. From that moment she became immensely popular. They
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.996#knew for what indulgences they were indebted to her, and they admired
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.997#her for the force of her will. There was one, at least, who could master
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.998#the governor, who avenged all the others, and knew how to get something
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.999#else besides promises out of him! So she had come at last, she who was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1000#to make him treat the poor devils with a little respect! When she went
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1001#through the shop, with her delicate, self-willed head, her tender,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1002#invincible air, the salesmen smiled at her, were proud of her, and would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1003#willingly have exhibited her to the crowd. Denise, in her happiness,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1004#allowed herself to be carried along by this increasing sympathy. Was it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1005#all possible? She saw herself arrive in a poor dress, frightened, lost
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1006#amidst the mechanism of the terrible machine; for a long time she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1007#had the sensation of being nothing, hardly a grain of seed beneath these
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1008#millstones which were crushing a whole world; and now to-day she was the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1009#very soul of this world, she alone was of consequence, able at a word to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1010#increase or slacken the pace of the colossus lying at her feet. And yet
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1011#she had not wished for these things, she had simply presented herself,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1012#without calculation, with the sole charm of her sweetness. Her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1013#sovereignty sometimes caused her an uneasy surprise; why did they all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1014#obey her? she was not pretty, she did nothing wrong. Then she smiled,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1015#her heart at rest, feeling within herself nothing but goodness and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1016#prudence, a love of truth and logic which constituted all her strength.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1017#One of Denise's greatest joys was to be able to assist Pauline. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1018#latter, being about to become a mother, was trembling, aware that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1019#two other saleswomen in the same condition had been sent away. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1020#principals did not tolerate these accidents, maternity being suppressed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1021#as cumbersome and indecent; they occasionally allowed marriage, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1022#would admit of no children. Pauline had, it was true, her husband in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1023#house; but still she felt anxious, it being almost impossible for her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1024#to appear at the counter; and in order to postpone a probable dismissal,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1025#she laced herself very tightly, resolved to conceal her state as long
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1026#as she could. One of the two saleswomen who had been dismissed, had just
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1027#been delivered of a still-born child, through having laced herself up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1028#in this way; and it was not certain that she herself would recover.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1029#Meanwhile, Bourdoncle had observed that Pauline's complexion was getting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1030#very livid, and that she had a painfully stiff way of walking. One
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1031#morning he was standing near her, in the under-linen department, when a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1032#messenger, taking away a bundle, ran up against her with such force that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1033#she cried out with pain. Bourdoncle immediately took her on one side,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1034#made her confess, and submitted the question of her dismissal to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1035#board, under the pretext that she stood in need of country air: the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1036#story of this accident would spread, and would have a disastrous effect
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1037#on the public if she should have a miscarriage, as had already taken
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1038#place in the baby linen department the year before. Mouret, who was not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1039#at the meeting, could only give his opinion in the evening. But Denise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1040#having had time to interfere, he closed Bourdoncle's mouth, in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1041#interest of the house itself. Did they wish to frighten the heads of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1042#families and the young mothers amongst their customers? And it was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1043#decided, with great pomp, that every married saleswoman should, when in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1044#the family way, be sent to a special midwife's as soon as her presence
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1045#at the counter became offensive to the customers.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1046#The next day when Denise went up into the infirmary to see Pauline,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1047#who had been obliged to take to her bed on account of the blow she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1048#received, the latter kissed her violently on both cheeks. “How kind you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1049#are! Had it not been for you I should have been turned away. Pray don't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1050#be anxious about me, the doctor says it's nothing.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1051#Bauge, who had slipped away from his department, was also there, on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1052#other side of the bed. He likewise stammered his thanks, troubled before
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1053#Denise, whom he now treated as an important person, of a superior class.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1054#Ah! if he heard any more nasty remarks about her, he would soon close
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1055#the mouths of the jealous ones! But Pauline sent him away with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1056#good-natured shrug of the shoulders.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1057#“My poor darling, you're always saying something stupid. Leave us to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1058#talk together.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1059#The infirmary was a long, light room, containing twelve beds, with their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1060#white curtains. Those who did not wish to go home to their families were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1061#nursed here. But on the day in question, Pauline was the only occupant,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1062#in a bed near one of the large windows which looked on to the Rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1063#Neuve-Saint-Augustin. And they immediately commenced to exchange
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1064#whispered words, tender confidences, in the calm air, perfumed with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1065#vague odour of lavender.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1066#“So he does just what you wish him to? How cruel you are, to make him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1067#suffer so! Come, just explain it to me, now I've ventured to approach
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1068#the subject. Do you detest him?” Pauline had retained hold of Denise's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1069#hand, as the latter sat near the bed, with her elbow on the bolster; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1070#overcome by a sudden emotion, her cheeks invaded with colour, she had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1071#a moment of weakness at this direct and unexpected question. Her secret
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1072#escaped her, she buried her head in the pillow, murmuring:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1073#“I love him!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1074#Pauline was astonished. “What! you love him? But it's very simple: say
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1075#yes.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1076#Denise, her face still concealed, replied “No!” by an energetic shake of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1077#the head. And she did so, simply because she loved him, without being
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1078#able to explain the matter. No doubt it was ridiculous; but she felt
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1079#like that, she could not change her nature. Her friend's surprise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1080#increased, and she at length asked: “So it's all to make him marry you?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1081#At this the young girl sprung up, quite confused: “Marry me! Oh! no!
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1082#Oh! I assure you that I have never wished for anything of the kind! No,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1083#never has such an idea entered my head; and you know what a horror I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1084#have of all falsehood!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1085#“Well, dear,” resumed Pauline, kindly, “you couldn't have acted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1086#otherwise, if such had been your intention. All this must come to an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1087#end, and it is very certain that it can only finish by a marriage, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1088#you won't let it be otherwise. I must tell you that every one has the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1089#same idea; yes, they feel persuaded that you are riding the high horse,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1090#in order to make him take you to church. Dear me! what a funny girl you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1091#are!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1092#And she had to console Denise, who had again dropped her head on to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1093#bolster, sobbing, declaring that she would certainly go away, since they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1094#attributed all sorts of things to her that had never crossed her mind.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1095#No doubt, when a man loved a woman he ought to marry her. But she asked
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1096#for nothing, she had made no calculations, she simply begged to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1097#allowed to live quietly, with her joys and her sorrows, like other
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1098#people. She would go away.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1099#At the same moment Mouret was going through the premises below. He had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1100#wanted to forget his thoughts by visiting the works once more. Several
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1101#months had elapsed, the façade now reared its monumental lines behind
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1102#the vast hoardings which concealed it from the public. Quite an army of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1103#decorators were at work: marble-cutters, mosaic-workers, and others. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1104#central group above the door was being gilded; whilst on the acroteria
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1105#were being fixed the pedestals destined to receive the statues of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1106#manufacturing cities of France. From morning to night, in the Rue du
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1107#Dix-Décembre, lately opened to the public, a crowd of idlers stood
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1108#gaping about, their noses in the air, seeing nothing, but pre-occupied
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1109#by the marvels that were related of this façade, the inauguration of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1110#which was going to revolutionise Paris. And it was on this feverish
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1111#working-ground, amidst the artists putting the finishing touches to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1112#realisation of his dream commenced by the masons, that Mouret felt more
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1113#bitterly than ever the vanity of his fortune. The thought of Denise had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1114#suddenly arrested him, this thought which incessantly pierced him with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1115#a flame, like the shooting of an incurable pain. He had run away, unable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1116#to find a word of satisfaction, fearful lest he should show his tears,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1117#leaving behind him the disgust of his triumph. This façade, which was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1118#at last erected, seemed little in his eyes, very much like one of those
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1119#walls of sand that children build, and it might have been extended from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1120#one end of the city to the other, elevated to the starry sky, yet it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1121#would not have filled the emptiness of his heart, that the “yes” of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1122#mere child could alone fill.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1123#When Mouret entered his office he was almost choking with sobs. What did
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1124#she want? He dared not offer her money now; and the confused idea of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1125#marriage presented itself amidst his young widower's revolts. And, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1126#the debility of his powerlessness, his tears began to flow. He was very
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xii.1127#miserable.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.1#CHAPTER XIII.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.2#One morning in November, Denise was giving her first orders in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.3#department when the Baudus' servant came to tell her that Mademoiselle
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.4#Geneviève had passed a very bad night, and wished to see her cousin
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.5#immediately. For some time the young girl had been getting weaker and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.6#weaker, and she had been obliged to take to her bed two days before.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.7#“Say I am coming at once,” replied Denise, very anxious.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.8#The blow which was finishing Genevieve was Colomban's sudden
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.9#disappearance. At first, chaffed by Clara, he had stopped out several
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.10#nights; then, yielding to the mad desires of a quiet, chaste fellow, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.11#had become her obedient slave, and had not returned one Monday, but had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.12#simply sent a farewell letter to Baudu, written in the studied terms of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.13#a man about to commit suicide. Perhaps, at the bottom of this passion,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.14#there was also the crafty calculation of a fellow delighted at escaping
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.15#a disastrous marriage. The draper's business was in as bad a way as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.16#his betrothed; the moment was propitious to break with them through any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.17#stupidity. And every one cited him as an unfortunate victim of love.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.18#When Denise arrived at The Old Elbeuf, Madame Baudu was there alone,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.19#sitting motionless behind the pay-desk, with her small white face, eaten
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.20#up by anæmia, silent and quiet in the cold, deserted shop. There were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.21#no assistants now. The servant dusted the shelves, and it was even a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.22#question of replacing her by a charwoman. A dreary cold fell from the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.23#ceiling, hours passed away without a customer coming to disturb this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.24#silence, and the goods, no longer touched, became mustier and mustier
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.25#every day.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.26#“What's the matter?” asked Denise, anxiously. “Is Geneviève in danger?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.27#Madame Baudu did not reply at first. Her eyes filled with tears. Then
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.28#she stammered: “I don't know; they don't tell me anything. Ah, it's all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.29#over, it's all over.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.30#And she cast a sombre glance around the dark old shop, as if she felt
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.31#her daughter and the shop disappearing together. The seventy thousand
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.32#francs, produce of the sale of their Rambouillet property, had melted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.33#away in less than two years in this gulf of competition. In order to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.34#struggle against The Ladies' Paradise, which now kept men's cloths and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.35#materials for hunting and livery suits, the draper had made considerable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.36#sacrifices. At last he had been definitely crushed by the swanskin cloth
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.37#and flannels sold by his rival, an assortment that had not its equal
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.38#in the market. Little by little his debts had increased, and, as a last
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.39#resource, he had resolved to mortgage the old building in the Rue de la
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.40#Michodière, where Finet, their ancestor, had founded the business; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.41#it was now only a question of days, the crumbling away had commenced,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.42#the very ceilings seemed to be falling down and turning into dust, like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.43#an old worm-eaten structure carried away by the wind.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.44#“Your uncle is upstairs,” resumed Madame Baudu in her broken voice. “We
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.45#stay with her two hours each. Some one must look out here; oh! but only
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.46#as a precaution, for to tell the truths----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.47#Her gesture finished the phrase. They would have put the shutters up had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.48#it not been for their old commercial pride, which still propped them up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.49#in the presence of the neighbourhood.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.50#“Well, I'll go up, aunt,” said Denise, whose heart was bleeding, amidst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.51#this resigned despair that even the pieces of cloth themselves exhaled.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.52#“Yes, go upstairs quick, my girl. She's waiting for you. She's been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.53#asking for you all night. She has something to tell you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.54#But just at that moment Baudu came down. The rising bile gave his yellow
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.55#face a greenish tinge, and his eyes were bloodshot. He was still walking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.56#with the muffled step with which he had quitted the Sick room, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.57#murmur-ed, as if he might be heard upstairs, “She's asleep.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.58#And, thoroughly worn out, he sat down on a chair, wiping his forehead
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.59#with a mechanical gesture, puffing like a man who has just finished some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.60#hard work. A silence ensued, but at last he said to Denise: “You'll see
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.61#her presently. When she is sleeping, she seems to me to be all right
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.62#again.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.63#There was again a silence. Face to face, the father and mother stood
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.64#looking at each other. Then, in a half whisper, he went over his grief
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.65#again, naming no one, addressing no one directly: “My head on the block,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.66#I wouldn't have believed it! He was the last one. I had brought him up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.67#as a son. If any one had come and said to me, 'They'll take him away
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.68#from you as well; he'll fall as well,' I would have replied 'Impossible,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.69#it could not be.' And he has fallen all the same! Ah! the scoundrel, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.70#who was so well up in real business, who had all my ideas! And all for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.71#a young monkey, one of those dummies that parade at the windows of bad
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.72#houses! No! really, it's enough to drive one mad!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.73#He shook his head, his eyes fell on the damp floor worn away by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.74#generations of customers. Then he continued in a lower voice, “There are
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.75#moments when I feel myself the most culpable of all in our misfortune.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.76#Yes, it's my fault if our poor girl is upstairs devoured by fever. Ought
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.77#not I to have married them at once, without yielding to my stupid pride,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.78#my obstinacy in refusing to leave them the house less prosperous than
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.79#before? Had I done that she would now have the man she loved, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.80#perhaps their united youthful strength would have accomplished the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.81#miracle that I have failed to work. But I am an old fool, and saw
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.82#through nothing; I didn't know that people fell ill over such things.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.83#Really he was an extraordinary fellow: with such a gift for business,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.84#and such probity, such simplicity of conduct, so orderly in every
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.85#way--in short, my pupil.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.86#He raised his head, still defending his ideas, in the person of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.87#shopman who had betrayed him. Denise could not bear to hear him accuse
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.88#himself, and she told him so, carried away by her emotion, on seeing him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.89#so humble, with his eyes full of tears, he who used formerly to reign as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.90#absolute master.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.91#“Uncle, pray don't apologise for him. He never loved Geneviève, he would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.92#have run away sooner if you had tried to hasten the marriage. I have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.93#spoken to him myself about it; he was perfectly well aware that my
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.94#cousin was suffering on his account, and you see that did not prevent
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.95#him leaving. Ask aunt.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.96#Without opening her lips, Madame Baudu confirmed these words by a nod.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.97#The draper turned paler still, blinded by his tears. He stammered out:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.98#“It must be in the blood, his father died last year through having led a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.99#dissolute life.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.100#And he once more looked round the obscure shop, his eyes wandering from
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.101#the empty counters to the full shelves, then resting on Madame Baudu,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.102#who was still at the pay-desk, waiting in vain for the customers who did
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.103#not come.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.104#“Come,” said he, “it's all over. They've ruined our business, and now
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.105#one of their hussies is killing our daughter.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.106#No one spoke. The rolling of the vehicles, which occasionally shook the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.107#floor, passed like a funereal beating of drums in the still air, stifled
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.108#under the low ceiling. Suddenly, amidst this gloomy sadness of the old
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.109#dying shop, could be heard several heavy knocks, struck somewhere in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.110#the house. It was Geneviève, who had just awoke, and was knocking with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.111#stick they had left near her bed.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.112#“Let's go up at once,” said Baudu, rising with a start. “Try and be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.113#cheerful, she mustn't know.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.114#He himself rubbed his eyes to efface the trace of his tears. As soon as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.115#he had opened the door, on the first storey, they heard a frightened,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.116#feeble voice crying: “Oh, I don't like to be left alone. Don't leave me;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.117#I'm afraid to be left alone.” Then, when she perceived Denise, Geneviève
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.118#became calmer, and smiled joyfully. “You've come, then! How I've been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.119#longing to see you since yesterday. I thought you also had abandoned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.120#me!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.121#It was a piteous sight. The young girl's room looked out on to the yard,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.122#a little room lighted by a livid light At first her parents had put her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.123#in their own room, in the front; but the sight of The Ladies' Paradise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.124#opposite affected her so much, that they had been obliged to bring
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.125#her back to her own again. And there she lay, so very thin, under the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.126#bed-clothes, that one hardly suspected the form and existence of a human
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.127#body. Her skinny arms, consumed by a burning fever, were in a perpetual
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.128#movement of anxious, unconscious searching; whilst her black hair seemed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.129#thicker still, and to be eating up her poor face with its voracious
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.130#vitality, that face in which was agonising the final degenerateness of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.131#a family sprung up in the shade, in this cellar of old commercial Paris.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.132#Denise, her heart bursting with pity, stood looking at her. She did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.133#at first speak, for fear of giving way to tears. At last she murmured:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.134#“I came at once. Can I be of any use to you? You asked for me. Would you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.135#like me to stay?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.136#“No, thanks. I don't want anything. I only wanted to embrace you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.137#Tears filled her eyes. Denise quickly leant over, and kissed her on both
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.138#cheeks, trembling to feel on her lips the flame of those hollow cheeks.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.139#But Geneviève, stretching out her arms, seized and kept her in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.140#desperate embrace. Then she looked towards her father.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.141#“Would you like me to stay?” repeated Denise. “Perhaps there is
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.142#something I can do for you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.143#Geneviève's glance was still obstinately fixed on her father, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.144#remained standing, with a stolid air, almost choking. He at last
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.145#understood, and went away, without saying a word; and they heard his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.146#heavy footstep on the stairs.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.147#“Tell me, is he with that woman?” asked the sick girl immediately,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.148#seizing her cousin's hand, and making her sit on the side of the bed.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.149#“I want to know, and you are the only one can tell me. They're living
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.150#together, aren't they?” Denise, surprised by these questions, stammered,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.151#and was obliged to confess the truth, the rumours that were current in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.152#the shop. Clara, tired of this fellow, who was getting a nuisance to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.153#her, had already broken with him, and Colomban, desolated, was pursuing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.154#her everywhere, trying to obtain a meeting from time to time, with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.155#sort of canine humility. They said that he was going to take a situation
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.156#at the Grands Magasins du Louvre.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.157#“If you still love him, he may return,” said Denise, to cheer the dying
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.158#girl with this last hope. “Get well quick, he will acknowledge his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.159#errors, and marry you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.160#Geneviève interrupted her. She had listened with all her soul, with an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.161#intense passion that raised her in the bed. But she fell back almost
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.162#immediately. “No, I know it's all over! I don't say anything, because I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.163#see papa crying, and I don't wish to make mamma worse than she is. But I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.164#am going, Denise, and if I called for you last night it was for fear of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.165#going off before the morning. And to think that he is not happy after
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.166#all!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.167#And Denise having remonstrated, assuring her that she was not so bad as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.168#all that, she cut her short again, suddenly throwing off the bed-clothes
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.169#with the chaste gesture of a virgin who has nothing to conceal in death.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.170#Naked to the waist, she murmured: “Look at me! Is it possible?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.171#Trembling, Denise quitted the side of the bed, as if she feared to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.172#destroy this fearful nudity with a breath. It was the last of the flesh,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.173#a bride's body used up by waiting, returned to the first infantile
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.174#slimness of her young days. Geneviève slowly covered herself up again,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.175#saying: “You see I am no longer a woman. It would be wrong to wish for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.176#him still!” There was a silence. Both continued to look at each other,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.177#unable to find a word to say. It was Geneviève who resumed: “Come, don't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.178#stay any longer, you have your own affairs to look after. And thanks, I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.179#was tormented by the wish to know, and am now satisfied. If you see him,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.180#tell him I forgive him. Adieu, dear Denise. Kiss me once more, for it's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.181#the last time.” The young girl kissed her, protesting: “No, no, don't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.182#despair, all you want is loving care, nothing more.” But the sick girl,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.183#shaking her head in an obstinate way, smiled, quite sure of what she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.184#said. And as her cousin was making for the door, she exclaimed: “Wait a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.185#minute, knock with this stick, so that papa may come up. I'm afraid to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.186#stay alone.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.187#Then, when Baudu arrived in that small, gloomy room, where he spent
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.188#hours seated on a chair, she assumed an air of gaiety, saying to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.189#Denise--“Don't come to-morrow, I would rather not. But on Sunday I shall
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.190#expect you; you can spend the afternoon with me.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.191#The next morning, at six o'clock, Geneviève expired after four hours'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.192#fearful agony. The funeral took place on a Saturday, a fearfully black,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.193#gloomy day, under a sooty sky which hung over the shivering city. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.194#Old Elbeuf, hung with white linen, lighted up the street with a bright
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.195#spot, and the candles burning in the fading day seemed so many stars
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.196#drowned in the twilight The coffin was covered with wreaths and bouquets
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.197#of white roses; it was a narrow child's coffin, placed in the obscure
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.198#passage of the house on a level with the pavement, so near the gutter
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.199#that the passing carriages had already splashed the coverings. The whole
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.200#neighbourhood exhaled a dampness, a cellar-like mouldy odour, with its
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.201#continual rush of pedestrians on the muddy pavement.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.202#At nine o'clock Denise came over to stay with her aunt. But as the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.203#funeral was starting, the latter--who had ceased weeping, her eyes burnt
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.204#with tears--begged her to follow the body and look after her uncle,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.205#whose mute affliction and almost idiotic grief filled the family with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.206#anxiety. Below, the young girl found the street full of people, for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.207#small traders in the neighbourhood were anxious to show the Baudus
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.208#a mark of sympathy, and in this eagerness there was also a sort of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.209#manifestation against The Ladies' Paradise, whom they accused of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.210#causing Geneviève's slow agony. All the victims of the monster were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.211#there--Bédoré and sister from the hosier's shop in the Rue Gaillon, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.212#furriers, Vanpouille Brothers, and Deslignières the toyman, and Piot
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.213#and Rivoire the furniture dealers; even Mademoiselle Tatin from the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.214#underclothing shop, and the glover Quinette, long since cleared off by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.215#bankruptcy, had made it a duty to come, the one from Batignolle, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.216#other from the Bastille, where they had been obliged to take situations.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.217#Whilst waiting for the hearse, which was late, these people, tramping
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.218#about in the mud, cast glances of hatred towards The Ladies' Paradise,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.219#the bright windows and gay displays of which seemed an insult in face
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.220#of The Old Elbeuf, which, with its funeral trappings and glimmering
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.221#candles, cast a gloom over the other side of the street A few curious
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.222#faces appeared at the plate-glass windows; but the colossus maintained
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.223#the indifference of a machine going at full speed, unconscious of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.224#deaths it may cause on the road.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.225#Denise looked round for her brother Jean, whom she at last perceived
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.226#standing before Bourras's shop, and she went and asked him to walk with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.227#his uncle, to assist him if he could not get along. For the last few
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.228#weeks Jean had been very grave, as if tormented by some worry. To-day,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.229#buttoned up in his black frock-coat, a full grown man, earning his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.230#twenty francs a day, he seemed so dignified and so sad that his sister
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.231#was surprised, for she had no idea he loved his cousin so much as that.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.232#Desirous of sparing Pépé this needless grief, she had left him with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.233#Madame Gras, intending to go and fetch him in the afternoon to see his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.234#uncle and aunt.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.235#The hearse had still not arrived, and Denise, greatly affected, was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.236#watching the candles burn, when she was startled by a well-known voice
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.237#behind her. It was Bourras. He had called the chestnut-seller opposite,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.238#in his little box, against the public-house, and said to him:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.239#“I say, Vigouroux, just keep a look-out for me a bit, will you? You see
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.240#I've closed the door. If any one comes tell them to call again. But don't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.241#let that disturb you, no one will come.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.242#Then he took his stand on the pavement, waiting like the others. Denise,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.243#feeling rather awkward, glanced at his shop. He entirely abandoned it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.244#now; there was nothing left but a disorderly array of umbrellas eaten up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.245#by the damp air, and canes blackened by the gas. The embellishments
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.246#that he had made, the delicate green paint work, the glasses, the gilded
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.247#sign, were all cracking, already getting dirty, presenting that rapid
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.248#and lamentable decrepitude of false luxury laid over ruins. But though
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.249#the old crevices were re-appearing, though the spots of damp had sprung
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.250#up over the gildings, the house still held its ground obstinately,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.251#hanging on to the flanks of The Ladies' Paradise like a dishonouring
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.252#wart, which, although cracked and rotten, refused to fall off.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.253#“Ah! the scoundrels,” growled Bourras, “they won't even let her be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.254#carried away.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.255#The hearse, which had at last arrived, had just got into collision with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.256#one of The Ladies' Paradise vans, which was spinning along, shedding in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.257#the mist its starry radiance, with the rapid trot of two superb horses.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.258#And the old man cast on Denise an oblique glance, lighted up under his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.259#bushy eyebrows. Slowly, the funeral started off, splashing through the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.260#muddy pools, amid the silence of the omnibuses and carriages suddenly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.261#pulled up. When the coffin, draped with white, crossed the Place
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.262#Gaillon, the sombre looks of the cortege were once more plunged into the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.263#windows of the big shop, where two saleswomen alone had run up to look
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.264#on, pleased at this distraction. Baudu followed the hearse with a heavy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.265#mechanical step, refusing by a sign the arm offered by Jean, who was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.266#walking with him. Then, after a long-string of people, came three
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.267#mourning coaches. As they passed the Rue Neuve-des-Petits-Champs,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.268#Robineau ran up to join the cortege, very pale, and looking much older.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.269#At Saint-Roch, a great many women were waiting, the small traders of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.270#the neighbourhood, who had been afraid of the crowd at the house. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.271#manifestation was developing into quite a riot; and when, after the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.272#service, the procession started off back, all the men followed, although
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.273#it was a long walk from the Rue Saint-Honoré to the Montmartre Cemetery.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.274#They had to go up the Rue Saint-Roch, and once more pass The Ladies'
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.275#Paradise. It was a sort of obsession; this poor young girl's body was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.276#paraded round the big shop like the first victim fallen in time of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.277#revolution. At the door some red flannels were flapping like so many
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.278#flags, and a display of carpets blazed forth in a florescence of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.279#enormous roses and full-blown pæonies. Denise had got into one of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.280#coaches, being agitated by some smarting doubts, her heart oppressed by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.281#such a feeling of grief that she had not the strength to walk At
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.282#that moment there was a stop, in the Rue du Dix-Décembre, before the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.283#scaffolding of the new façade which still obstructed the thoroughfare.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.284#'And the young girl observed old Bourras, left behind, dragging along
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.285#with difficulty, close to the wheels of the coach in which she was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.286#riding alone. He would never get as far as the cemetery, she thought. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.287#raised his head, looked at her, and all at once got into the coach.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.288#“It's my confounded knees,” exclaimed he. “Don't draw back! Is it you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.289#that we detest?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.290#She felt him to be friendly and furious as in former days. He grumbled,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.291#declared that Baudu must be fearfully strong to be able to keep up after
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.292#such blows as he had received. The procession had resumed its slow pace;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.293#and on leaning out, Denise saw her uncle walking with his heavy step,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.294#which seemed to regulate the rumbling and painful march of the cortege.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.295#She then threw herself back into the corner, listening to the endless
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.296#complaints of the old umbrella maker, rocked by the melancholy movement
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.297#of the coach.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.298#“The police ought to clear the public thoroughfare, my word! They've
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.299#been blocking up our street for the last eighteen months with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.300#scaffolding of their façade, where a man was killed the other day. Never
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.301#mind! When they want to enlarge further they'll have to throw bridges
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.302#over the street. They say there are now two thousand seven hundred
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.303#employees, and that the business will amount to a hundred millions this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.304#year. A hundred millions! Just fancy, a hundred millions!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.305#Denise had nothing to say in reply. The procession had just turned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.306#into the Rue de la Chaussée d'Antin, where it was stopped by a block of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.307#vehicles. Bourras went on, with a vague expression in his eyes, as if he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.308#were dreaming aloud. He still failed to understand the triumph
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.309#achieved by The Ladies' Paradise, but he acknowledged the defeat of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.310#old-fashioned traders.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.311#“Poor Robineau's done for, he's got the face of a drowning man. And the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.312#Bédorés and the Vanpouilles, they can't keep going; they're like me,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.313#played out Deslignières will die of apoplexy. Piot and Rivoire have the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.314#yellow jaundice. Ah! we're a fine lot; a pretty cortege of skeletons to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.315#follow the poor child. It must be comical for those looking on to see
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.316#this string of bankrupts pass. Besides, it appears that the clean sweep
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.317#is to continue. The scoundrels are creating departments for flowers,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.318#bonnets, perfumery, shoemaking, all sorts of things. Grognet, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.319#perfumer in the Rue de Grammont, can clear out, and I wouldn't give ten
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.320#francs for Naud's shoe-shop in the Rue d'Antin. The cholera has spread
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.321#as far as the Rue Sainte-Anne, where Lacassagne, at the feather and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.322#flower shop, and Madame Chadeuil, whose bonnets are so well-known, will
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.323#be swept away before long. And after those, others; it will still go
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.324#on! All the businesses in the neighbourhood will suffer. When
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.325#counter-jumpers commence to sell soap and goloshes, they are quite
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.326#capable of dealing in fried potatoes. My word, the world is turning
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.327#upside down!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.328#The hearse was just then crossing the Place de la Trinité to ascend the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.329#steep Rue Blanche, and from the corner of the gloomy coach Denise, who,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.330#broken-hearted, was listening to the endless complaints of the old man,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.331#could see the coffin as they issued from the Rue de la Chaussée d'Antin.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.332#Behind her uncle, marching along with the blind, mute face of an ox
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.333#about to be poleaxed, she seemed to hear the tramping of a flock of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.334#sheep led to the slaughter-house, the discomfiture of the shops of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.335#whole district, the small traders dragging along their ruin, with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.336#thud of damp shoes, through the muddy streets of Paris. Bourras still
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.337#went on, in a deeper voice, as if slackened by the difficult ascent of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.338#the Rue Blanche.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.339#“As for me, I am settled. But I still hold on all the same, and won't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.340#let go. He's just lost his appeal case. Ah! that's cost me something,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.341#what with nearly two years' pleading, and the solicitors and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.342#barristers! Never mind, he won't pass under my shop, the judges have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.343#decided that such a work could not be considered as a legitimate case
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.344#of repairing. Fancy, he talked of creating underneath a light saloon to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.345#judge the colours of the stuffs by gas-light, a subterranean room which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.346#would have united the hosiery to the drapery department! And he can't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.347#get over it; he can't swallow the fact that an old humbug like me should
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.348#stop his progress when everybody are on their knees before his money.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.349#Never! I won't! that's understood. Very likely I may be worsted. Since I
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.350#have had to go to the money-lenders, I know the villain is looking after
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.351#my paper, in the hope to play me some villanous trick, no doubt. But
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.352#that doesn't matter. He says 'yes,' and I say 'no,' and shall still say
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.353#'no,' even when I get between two boards like this poor little girl who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.354#has just been nailed up.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.355#When they reached the Boulevard de Clichy, the coach went at a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.356#quicker pace; one could hear the heavy breathing of the mourners, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.357#unconscious haste of the cortege, anxious to get the sad ceremony over.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.358#What Bourras did not openly mention, was the frightful misery into which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.359#he had fallen, bewildered amidst the confusion of the small trader who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.360#is on the road to ruin and yet remains obstinate, under a shower of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.361#protested bills. Denise, well acquainted with his situation, at last
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.362#interrupted the silence by saying, in a voice of entreaty:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.363#“Monsieur Bourras, pray don't stand out any longer. Let me arrange
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.364#matters for you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.365#But he interrupted her with a violent gesture. “You be quiet. That's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.366#nobody's business. You're a good little girl, and I know you lead him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.367#a hard life, this man who thought you were for sale like my house. But
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.368#what would you answer if I advised you to say 'yes?' You'd send me about
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.369#my business. Therefore, when I say 'no,' don't you interfere in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.370#matter.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.371#And the coach having stopped at the cemetery gate, he got out with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.372#young girl. The Baudus' vault was situated in the first alley on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.373#left. In a few minutes the ceremony was terminated. Jean had drawn
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.374#away his uncle, who was looking into the grave with a gaping air. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.375#mourners wandered about amongst the neighbouring tombs, and the faces
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.376#of all these shopkeepers, their blood impoverished by living in their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.377#unhealthy shops assumed an ugly suffering look under the leaden sky.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.378#When the coffin slipped gently down, their blotched and pimpled cheeks
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.379#paled, and their bleared eyes, blinded with figures, turned away.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.380#“We ought all to jump into this hole,” said Bourras to Denise, who had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.381#kept close to him. “In burying this poor girl they are burying the whole
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.382#district. Oh! I know what I am saying, the old-fashioned business may go
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.383#and join the white roses they are throwing on to her coffin.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.384#Denise brought back her uncle and brother in a mourning coach. The day
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.385#was for her exceedingly dull and melancholy. In the first place, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.386#began to get anxious at Jean's paleness, and when she understood that it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.387#was on account of another woman, she tried to quiet him by opening her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.388#purse, but he shook his head and refused, saying it was serious this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.389#time, the niece of a very rich pastry-cook, who would not accept even
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.390#a bunch of violets. Afterwards, in the afternoon, when Denise went to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.391#fetch Pépé from Madame Gras's, the latter declared that he was getting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.392#too big for her to keep any longer; another annoyance, for she would be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.393#obliged to find him a school, perhaps send him away. And to crown all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.394#she was thoroughly heart-broken, on bringing Pépé back to kiss his aunt
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.395#and uncle, to see the gloomy sadness of The Old Elbeuf. The shop was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.396#closed, and the old couple were at the further end of the little room,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.397#where they had forgotten to light the gas, notwithstanding the complete
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.398#obscurity of this winter's day. They were now quite alone, face to face,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.399#in the house, slowly emptied by ruin; and the death of their daughter
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.400#deepened the shady corners, and was like the supreme cracking which was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.401#soon to break up the old rafters, eaten away by the damp. Beneath this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.402#destruction, her uncle, unable to stop himself, still kept walking round
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.403#the table, with his funeral-like step, blind and silent; whilst her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.404#aunt said nothing, she had fallen into a chair, with the white face of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.405#wounded person, whose blood was running away drop by drop. They did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.406#even weep when Pépé covered their cold cheeks with kisses. Denise was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.407#choked with tears.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.408#That same evening Mouret sent for the young girl to speak of a child's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.409#garment he wished to launch forth, a mixture of the Scotch and Zouave
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.410#costumes. And still trembling with pity, shocked at so much suffering,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.411#she could not contain herself; she first ventured to speak of Bourras,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.412#of that poor old man whom they were about to ruin. But, on hearing the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.413#umbrella maker's name, Mouret flew into a rage at once. The old madman,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.414#as he called him, was the plague of his life, and spoilt his triumph
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.415#by his idiotic obstinacy in not giving up his house, that ignoble hovel
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.416#which was a disgrace to The Ladies' Paradise, the only little corner
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.417#of the vast block that escaped his conquest. The matter was becoming a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.418#regular nightmare; any one else but Denise speaking in favour of Bourras
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.419#would have run the risk of being dismissed immediately, so violently was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.420#Mouret tortured by the sickly desire to kick the house down. In short,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.421#what did they wish him to do? Could he leave this heap of ruins sticking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.422#to The Ladies' Paradise? It would be got rid of, the shop was to pass
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.423#through it. So touch the worse for the old fool! And he spoke of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.424#repeated proposals; he had offered him as much as a hundred thousand
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.425#francs. Wasn't that fair? He never higgled, he gave the money required;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.426#but in return he expected people to be reasonable, and allow him to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.427#finish his work! Did any one ever try to stop the locomotives on a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.428#railway? She listened to him, with drooping eyes, unable to find any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.429#but purely sentimental reasons. The old man was so old, they might have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.430#waited till his death; a failure would kill him. Then he added that he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.431#was no longer able to prevent things going their course. Bourdoncle had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.432#taken the matter up, for the board had resolved to put an end ta it. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.433#had nothing more to add, notwithstanding the grievous pity she felt for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.434#her old friend.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.435#After a painful silence, Mouret himself commenced to speak of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.436#Baudus, by expressing his sorrow at the death of their daughter. They
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.437#were very worthy people, very honest, but had been pursued by the worst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.438#of luck. Then he resumed his arguments; at bottom, they had really
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.439#caused their own misfortune by obstinately sticking to the old ways in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.440#their worm-eaten place; it was not astonishing that the place should be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.441#falling about their heads. He had predicted it scores of times; she must
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.442#remember that he had charged her to warn her uncle of a fatal disaster,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.443#if the latter still clung to his old-fashioned stupid ways. And the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.444#catastrophe had arrived; no one in the world could now prevent it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.445#They could not reasonably expect him to ruin himself to save the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.446#neighbourhood. Besides, if he had been foolish enough to close The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.447#Ladies' Paradise, another big shop would have sprung up of itself next
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.448#door, for the idea was now starting from the four corners of the globe;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.449#the triumph of these manufacturing and industrial cities was sown by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.450#the spirit of the times, which was sweeping away the tumbling edifice
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.451#of former ages. Little by little Mouret warmed up, and found an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.452#eloquent emotion with which to defend himself against the hatred of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.453#involuntary victims, the clamour of the small dying shops that was heard
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.454#around him. They could not keep their dead, he continued, they must bury
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.455#them; and with a gesture he sent down into the grave, swept away and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.456#threw into the common hole the corpse of old-fashioned business, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.457#greenish, poisonous remains of which were becoming a disgrace to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.458#bright, sun-lighted streets of new Paris. No, no, he felt no remorse,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.459#he was simply doing the work of his age, and she knew it; she, who loved
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.460#life, who had a passion for big affairs, concluded in the full glare of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.461#publicity. Reduced to silence, she listened to him for some time, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.462#then went away, her soul full of trouble.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.463#That night Denise slept but little. A sleeplessness, traversed by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.464#nightmare, kept her turning over and over in her bed. It seemed to her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.465#that she was quite little, and she burst into tears, in their garden at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.466#Valognes, on seeing the blackcaps eat up the spiders, which themselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.467#devoured the flies. Was it then really true, this necessity for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.468#world to fatten on death, this struggle for existence which drove
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.469#people into the charnel-house of eternal destruction? Afterwards she saw
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.470#herself before the vault into which they had lowered Geneviève, then
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.471#she perceived her uncle and aunt in their obscure dining-room. In
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.472#the profound silence, a heavy voice, as of something tumbling down,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.473#traversed the dead air; it was Bourras's house giving way, as if
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.474#undermined by a high tide. The silence recommenced, more sinister than
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.475#ever, and a fresh rumbling was heard, then another, then another; the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.476#Robineaus, the Bédorés, the Vanpouilles, cracked and fell down in their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.477#turn, the small shops of the neighbourhood were disappearing beneath an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.478#invisible pick, with a brusque, thundering noise, as of a tumbril being
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.479#emptied. Then an immense pity awoke her with a start. Heavens! what
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.480#tortures! There were families weeping, old men thrown out into the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.481#street, all the poignant dramas that ruin conjures up. And she could
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.482#save nobody; and she felt that it was right, that all this misery was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.483#necessary for the health of the Paris of the future. When day broke she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.484#became calmer, a feeling of resigned melancholy kept her awake, turned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.485#towards the windows through which the light was making its way. Yes, it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.486#was the meed of blood that every revolution exacted from its martyrs,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.487#every step forward was made over the bodies of the dead. Her fear
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.488#of being a wicked girl, of having assisted in the ruin of her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.489#fellow-creatures, now melted into a heartfelt pity, in face of these
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.490#evils without remedy, which are the painful accompaniment of each
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.491#generation's birth. She finished by seeking some possible comfort in her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.492#goodness, she dreamed of the means to be employed in order to save her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.493#relations at least from the final crash.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.494#Mouret now appeared before her with his passionate face and caressing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.495#eyes. He would certainly refuse her nothing; she felt sure he would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.496#accord her all reasonable compensation. And her thoughts went astray
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.497#in trying to judge him. She knew his life, was aware of the calculating
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.498#nature of his former affections, his continual exploitation of woman,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.499#mistresses taken up to further his own ends, and his intimacy with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.500#Madame Desforges solely to get hold of Baron Hartmann, and all the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.501#others, such as Clara and the rest, pleasure bought, paid for, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.502#thrown out on the pavement. But these beginnings of a love adventurer,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.503#which were the talk of the shop, were gradually effaced by the strokes
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.504#of genius of this man, his victorious grace. He was seduction itself.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.505#What she could never have forgiven was his former deception, his lover's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.506#coldness under the gallant comedy of his attentions. But she felt
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.507#herself to be entirely without rancour, now that he was suffering
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.508#through her. This suffering had elevated him. When she saw him tortured
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.509#by her refusal, atoning so fully for his former disdain for woman, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.510#seemed to have made amends for all his faults.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.511#That morning Denise obtained from Mouret the compensation she might
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.512#judge legitimate the day the Baudus and old Bourras should succumb.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.513#Weeks passed away, during which she went to see her uncle nearly every
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.514#afternoon, escaping from her counter for a few minutes, bringing her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.515#smiling face and brave courage to enliven the sombre shop. She was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.516#especially anxious about her aunt, who had fallen into a dull stupor
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.517#since Geneviève's death; it seemed that her life was quitting her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.518#hourly; and when people spoke to her she would reply with an astonished
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.519#air that she was not suffering, but that she simply felt as if overcome
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.520#by sleep. The neighbours shook their heads, saying she would not live
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.521#long to regret her daughter.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.522#One day Denise was coming out of the Baudus', when, on turning the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.523#corner of the Place Oaillon, she heard a loud cry. The crowd rushed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.524#forward, a panic arose, that breath of fear and pity which so
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.525#suddenly seizes a crowd. It was a brown omnibus, belonging to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.526#Bastille-Batignolles line, which had run over a man, coming out of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.527#Rue Neuve-Saint-Augustin, opposite the fountain. Upright on his seat,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.528#with furious gestures, the driver was pulling in his two kicking horses,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.529#and crying out, in a great passion:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.530#“Confound you! Why don't you look out, you idiot!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.531#The omnibus had now stopped, and the crowd had surrounded the wounded
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.532#man, and, strange to say, a policeman was soon on the spot. Still
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.533#standing up, invoking the testimony of the people on the knife-board,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.534#who had also got up, to look over and see the wounded man, the coachman
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.535#was explaining the matter, with exasperated gestures, choked by his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.536#increasing anger.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.537#“It's something fearful. This fellow was walking in the middle of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.538#road, quite at home. I called out, and he at once threw himself under
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.539#the wheels!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.540#A house-painter, who had run up, brush in hand, from a neighbouring
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.541#house, then said, in a sharp voice, amidst the clamour: “Don't excite
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.542#yourself. I saw him, he threw himself under. He jumped in, head first.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.543#Another unfortunate tired of life, no doubt.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.544#Others spoke up, and all agreed upon it being a case of suicide, whilst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.545#the policeman pulled out his book and made his entry. Several ladies,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.546#very pale, got out quickly, and ran away without looking back, filled
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.547#with horror by the soft shaking which had stirred them up when the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.548#omnibus passed over the body. Denise approached, attracted by a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.549#practical pity, which prompted her to interest herself in all sorts
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.550#of street accidents, wounded dogs, horses down, and tilers falling off
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.551#roofs. And she immediately recognised the unfortunate fellow who had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.552#fainted away, his clothes covered with mud.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.553#“It's Monsieur Robineau,” cried she, in her grievous astonishment.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.554#The policeman at once questioned the young girl, and she gave his name,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.555#profession, and address. Thanks to the driver's energy, the omnibus had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.556#twisted round, and thus only Robineau's legs had gone under the wheels,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.557#but it was to be feared that they were both broken. Four men carried
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.558#the wounded draper to a chemist's shop in the Rue Gaillon, whilst the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.559#omnibus slowly resumed its journey.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.560#“My stars!” said the driver, whipping up his horses, “I've done a famous
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.561#day's work.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.562#Denise followed Robineau into the chemist's. The latter, waiting for a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.563#doctor who could not be found, declared there was no immediate danger,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.564#and that the wounded man had better be taken home, as he lived in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.565#the neighbourhood. A lad started off to the police-station to order a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.566#stretcher, and Denise had the happy thought of going on in front and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.567#preparing Madame Robineau for this frightful blow. But she had the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.568#greatest trouble in the world to get into the street through the crowd,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.569#which was struggling before the door. This crowd, attracted by death,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.570#was increasing every minute; men, women, and children stood on tip-toe,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.571#and held their own amidst a brutal pushing, and each new comer had his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.572#version of the accident, so that at last it was said to be a husband
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.573#pitched out of the window by his wife's lover.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.574#In the Rue Neuve-des-Petits-Champs, Denise perceived Madame Robineau
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.575#on the threshold of the silk warehouse. This gave her a pretext for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.576#stopping, and she talked on for a moment, trying to find a way of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.577#breaking the terrible news. The shop presented the disorderly, abandoned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.578#appearance of the last struggles of a dying business. It was the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.579#inevitable end of the great battle of the silks; the Paris Paradise had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.580#crushed its rival by a fresh reduction of a sou; it was now sold at four
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.581#francs nineteen sous, Gaujean's silk had found its Waterloo. For the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.582#last two months Robineau, reduced to all sorts of shifts, had been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.583#leading a fearful life, trying to prevent a declaration of bankruptcy.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.584#“I've just seen your husband pass through the Place Gaillon,” murmured
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.585#Denise, who had now entered the shop.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.586#Madame Robineau, whom a secret anxiety seemed to be continually
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.587#attracting towards the street, said quickly: “Ah, just now, wasn't it?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.588#I'm waiting for him, he ought to be back; Monsieur Gaujean came up this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.589#morning, and they have gone out together.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.590#She was still charming, delicate, and gay; but her advanced state of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.591#pregnancy gave her a fatigued look, and she was more frightened, more
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.592#bewildered than ever, by these business matters, which she did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.593#understand, and which were all going wrong. As she often said, what was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.594#the use of it all? Would it not be better to live quietly in some small
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.595#house, and be contented with modest fare?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.596#“My dear child,” resumed she with her smile, which was becoming sadder,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.597#“we have nothing to conceal from you. Things are not going on well,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.598#and my poor darling is worried to death. To-day this Gaujean has been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.599#tormenting him about some bills overdue. I was dying with anxiety at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.600#being left here all alone.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.601#And she was returning to the door when Denise stopped her, having heard
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.602#the noise of the crowd and guessing that it was the wounded man being
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.603#brought along, surrounded by a mob of idlers anxious to see the end of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.604#the affair. Then, with a parched throat, unable to find the consoling
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.605#words she would have wished, she had to explain the matter.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.606#“Don't be anxious, there's no immediate danger. I've seen Monsieur
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.607#Robineau, he has met with an accident. They are just bringing him home,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.608#pray don't be frightened.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.609#The poor woman listened to her, white as a sheet, without clearly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.610#understanding. The street was full of people, the drivers of the impeded
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.611#cabs were swearing, the men had laid down the stretcher before the shop
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.612#in order to open both glass doors.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.613#“It was an accident,” continued Denise, resolved to conceal the attempt
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.614#at suicide. “He was on the pavement and slipped under the wheels of an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.615#omnibus. Only his feet were hurt. They've sent for a doctor. There's no
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.616#need to be anxious.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.617#A shudder passed over Madame Robineau. She set up an inarticulate cry,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.618#then ceased talking and ran to the stretcher, drawing the covering away
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.619#with her trembling hands. The men who had brought Robineau were waiting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.620#to take him away as soon as the doctor arrived. They dared not touch
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.621#him, who had come round again, and whose sufferings were frightful at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.622#the slightest movement. When he saw his wife his eyes filled with tears.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.623#She embraced him, and stood looking fixedly at him, and weeping. In the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.624#street the tumult was increasing; the people pressed forward as at a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.625#theatre, with glistening eyes; some work-girls, escaped from a shop,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.626#were almost pushing through the windows eager to see what was going on.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.627#In order to avoid this feverish curiosity, and thinking, besides, that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.628#it was not right to leave the shop open, Denise decided on letting the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.629#metallic shutters down. She went and turned the winch, the wheels of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.630#which gave out a plaintive cry, the sheets of iron slowly descended, like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.631#the heavy draperies of a curtain falling on the catastrophe of a fifth
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.632#act. When she went in again, after closing the little round door in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.633#shutters, she found Madame Robineau still clasping her husband in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.634#her arms, in the half-light which came from the two stars cut in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.635#shutters. The ruined shop seemed to be gliding into nothingness, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.636#two stars alone glittered on this sudden and brutal catastrophe of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.637#streets of Paris.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.638#At last Madame Robineau recovered her speech. “Oh, my darling!--oh, my
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.639#darling! my darling!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.640#This was all she could say, and he, suffocated, confessed himself with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.641#cry of remorse when he saw her kneeling thus before him. When he did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.642#move he only felt the burning lead of his legs.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.643#“Forgive me, I must have been mad. When the lawyer told me before
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.644#Gaujean that the posters would be put up tomorrow, I saw flames dancing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.645#before me as if the walls were burning. After that I remember nothing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.646#else. I came down the Rue de la Michodière--it seemed that The Paradise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.647#people were laughing at me, that immense house seemed to crush me.. So,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.648#when the omnibus came up, I thought of Lhomme and his arm, and threw
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.649#myself underneath the omnibus.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.650#Madame Robineau had slowly fallen on to the floor, horrified by this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.651#confession. Heavens! he had tried to kill himself. She seized the hand
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.652#of her young friend, who leant over towards her quite overcome. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.653#wounded man, exhausted by emotion, had just fainted away again; and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.654#doctor not having arrived, two men went all over the neighbourhood for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.655#him. The doorkeeper belonging to the house had gone off in his turn to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.656#look for him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.657#“Pray, don't be anxious,” repeated Denise, mechanically, herself also
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.658#sobbing.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.659#Then Madame Robineau, seated on the floor, with her head against the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.660#stretcher, her cheek placed on the mattress where her husband was lying,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.661#relieved her heart “Oh! I must tell you. It's all for me he wanted to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.662#die. He's always saying, 'I've robbed you; it was not my money.' And at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.663#night he dreams of this money, waking up covered with perspiration,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.664#calling himself an incapable fellow, saying that those who have no head
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.665#for business ought not to risk other people's money. You know he has
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.666#always been nervous, his brain tormented. He finished by conjuring up
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.667#things that frightened me. He saw me in the street in tatters, begging,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.668#his darling wife, whom he loved so tenderly, whom he longed to see rich
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.669#and happy.” But on turning round, she noticed he had opened his eyes;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.670#and she continued in a trembling voice: “My darling, why have you done
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.671#this? You must think me very wicked! I assure you, I don't care if we
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.672#are ruined. So long as we are together, we shall never be unhappy. Let
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.673#them take everything, and we will go away somewhere, where you won't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.674#hear any more about them. You can still work; you'll see how happy we
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.675#shall be!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.676#She placed her forehead near her husband's pale face, and both were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.677#silent, in the emotion of their anguish. There was a pause. The shop
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.678#seemed to be sleeping, benumbed by the pale night which enveloped it;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.679#whilst behind the thin shutters could be heard the noises of the street,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.680#the life of the busy city, the rumble of the vehicles, and the hustling
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.681#and pushing of the passing crowd. At last Denise, who went every minute
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.682#to glance through the hall door, came back, exclaiming: “Here's the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.683#doctor!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.684#He was a young fellow, with bright eyes, whom the doorkeeper had found
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.685#and brought in. He preferred to examine the poor man before they put him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.686#to bed. Only one of his legs, the left one, was broken above the ankle;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.687#it was a simple fracture, no serious complication appeared likely to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.688#result from it. And they were about to carry the stretcher into the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.689#back-room when Gaujean arrived. He came to give them an account of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.690#a last attempt to settle matters, an attempt which had failed; the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.691#declaration of bankruptcy was definite.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.692#“Dear me,” murmured he, “what's the matter?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.693#In a few words, Denise informed him. Then he stopped, feeling rather
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.694#awkward, while Robineau said, in a feeble voice: “I don't bear you any
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.695#ill-will, but all this is partly your fault.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.696#“Well, my dear fellow,” replied Gaujean, “it wanted stronger men than
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.697#us. You know I'm not in a much better state than you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.698#They raised the stretcher; Robineau still found strength to say: “No,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.699#no, stronger fellows than us would have given way as we have. I can
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.700#understand such obstinate old men as Bourras and Baudu standing out, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.701#you and I, who are young, who had accepted the new style of tilings! No,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.702#Gaujean, it's the last of a world.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.703#They carried him off. Madame Robineau embraced Denise with an eagerness
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.704#in which there was almost a feeling of joy, to have at last got rid of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.705#all those worrying business matters. And, as Gaujean went away with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.706#young girl, he confessed to her that this poor devil of a Robineau was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.707#right. It was idiotic to try and struggle against The Ladies' Paradise.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.708#He personally felt himself lost, if he did not give in. Last night, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.709#fact, he had secretly made a proposal to Hutin, who was just leaving for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.710#Lyons. But he felt very doubtful, and tried to interest Denise in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.711#matter, aware, no doubt, of her powerfulness.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.712#“My word,” said he, “so much the worse for the manufacturers! Every
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.713#one would laugh at me if I ruined myself in fighting for other people's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.714#benefit, when these fellows are struggling who shall make at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.715#cheapest price! As you said some time ago, the manufacturers have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.716#only to follow the march of progress by a better organisation and new
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.717#methods. Everything will come all right; it suffices that the public are
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.718#satisfied.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.719#Denise smiled and replied: “Go and say that to Monsieur Mouret himself.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.720#Your visit will please him, and he's not the man to display any rancour,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.721#if you offer him even a centime profit per yard.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.722#Madame Baudu died in January, on a bright sunny afternoon. For some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.723#weeks she had been unable to go down into the shop that a charwoman now
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.724#looked after. She was in bed, propped up by the pillows. Nothing but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.725#her eyes seemed to be living in her white face, and, her head erect, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.726#kept them obstinately fixed on The Ladies' Paradise opposite, through
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.727#the small curtains of the windows. Baudu, himself suffering from this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.728#obsession, from the despairing fixity of her gaze, sometimes wanted
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.729#to draw the large curtains to. But she stopped him with an imploring
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.730#gesture, obstinately desirous of seeing the monster shop till the last
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.731#moment. It had now robbed her of everything, her business, her daughter;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.732#she herself had gradually died away with The Old Elbeuf, losing a part
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.733#of her life as the shop lost its customers; the day it succumbed, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.734#had no more breath left When she felt she was dying, she still found the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.735#strength to insist on her husband opening the two windows. It was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.736#very mild, a bright day of sun gilded The Ladies' Paradise, whilst the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.737#bed-room of their old house shivered in the shade. Madame Baudu lay with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.738#her fixed gaze, absorbed by the vision of the triumphal monument, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.739#clear, limpid windows, behind which a gallop of millions was passing.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.740#Slowly her eyes grew dim, invaded by darkness; and when they at last
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.741#sunk in death, they remained wide open, still looking, drowned in tears.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.742#Once more the ruined traders of the district followed the funeral
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.743#procession. There were the brothers Vanpouille, pale at the thought of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.744#their December bills, paid by a supreme effort which they would never be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.745#able to repeat. Bédoré, with his sister, leant on his cane, so full of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.746#worry and anxiety that his liver complaint was getting worse every day.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.747#Deslignières had had a fit, Piot and Rivoire walked on in silence, with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.748#downcast looks, like men entirely played out. They dared not question
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.749#each other about those who had disappeared, Quinette, Mademoiselle
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.750#Tatin, and others, who were sinking, ruined, swept away by this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.751#disastrous flood; without counting Robineau, still in bed, with his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.752#broken leg. But they pointed with an especial air of interest to the new
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.753#tradesmen attacked by the plague; the perfumer Grognet, the milliner
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.754#Madame Chadeuil, Lacassagne, the flower maker, and Naud, the bootmaker,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.755#still standing firm, but seized by the anxiety of the evil, which would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.756#doubtless sweep them away in their turn. Baudu walked along behind the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.757#hearse with the same heavy, stolid step as when he had followed his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.758#daughter; whilst at the back of a mourning coach could be seen Bourras's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.759#sparkling eyes under his bushy eyebrows, and his hair of a snowy white.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.760#Denise was in great trouble. For the last fifteen days she had been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.761#worn out with fatigue and anxiety; she had been obliged to put Pépé to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.762#school, and had been running about for Jean, who was so stricken with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.763#the pastrycook's niece, that he had implored his sister to go and ask
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.764#her hand in marriage. Then her aunt's death, these repeated catastrophes
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.765#had quite overwhelmed the young girl. Mouret again offered his services,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.766#giving her leave to do what she liked for her uncle and the others.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.767#One morning she had an interview with him, at the news that Bourras was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.768#turned into the street, and that Baudu was going to shut up shop. Then
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.769#she went out after breakfast in the hope of comforting these two, at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.770#least.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.771#In the Rue de la Michodière, Bourras was standing on the pavement
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.772#opposite his house, from which he had been expelled the previous day by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.773#a fine trick, a discovery of the lawyers; as Mouret held some bills, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.774#had easily obtained an order in bankruptcy against the umbrella-maker;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.775#then he had given five hundred francs for the expiring lease at the sale
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.776#ordered by the court; so that the obstinate old man had allowed himself
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.777#to be deprived of, for five hundred francs, what he had refused to give
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.778#up for a hundred thousand. The architect, who came with his gang of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.779#workmen, had been obliged to employ the police to get him out. The goods
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.780#had been taken and sold; but he still kept himself obstinately in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.781#corner where he slept, and from which they did not like to drive him,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.782#out of pity. The workmen even attacked the roofing over his head.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.783#They had taken off the rotten slates, the ceilings fell in, the walls
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.784#cracked, and yet he stuck there, under the naked old beams, amidst the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.785#ruins of the shop. At last the police came, and he went away. But the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.786#following morning he again appeared on the opposite side of the street,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.787#after having spent the night in a lodging-house in the neighbourhood.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.788#“Monsieur Bourras!” said Denise, kindly.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.789#He did not hear her, his flaming eyes were devouring the workmen who
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.790#were attacking the front of the hovel with their picks. Through the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.791#empty window-frames could be seen the inside of the house, the miserable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.792#rooms, and the black staircase, where the sun had not penetrated for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.793#last two hundred years. .
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.794#“Ah! it's you,” replied he, at last, when he recognised her. “A nice bit
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.795#of work they're doing, eh? the robbers!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.796#She did not now dare to speak, stirred up by the lamentable sadness of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.797#the old place, herself unable to take her eyes off the mouldy stones
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.798#that were falling. Above, in a corner of the ceiling of her old room, she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.799#still perceived the name in black and shaky letters--Ernestine--written
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.800#with the flame of a candle, and the remembrance of those days of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.801#misery came back to her, inspiring her with a tender sympathy for all
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.802#suffering. But the workmen, in order to knock one of the walls down at a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.803#blow, had attacked it at its base. It was tottering.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.804#“Should like to see it crush all of them,” growled Bourras, in a savage
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.805#voice.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.806#There was a terrible cracking noise. The frightened workmen ran out into
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.807#the street. In falling down, the wall tottered and carried all the house
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.808#with it. No doubt the hovel was ripe for the fall--it could no longer
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.809#stand, with its flaws and cracks; a push had sufficed to cleave it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.810#from top to bottom. It was a pitiful crumbling away, the razing of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.811#mud-house soddened by the rains. Not a board remained standing; there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.812#was nothing on the ground but a heap of rubbish, the dung of the past
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.813#thrown at the street corner.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.814#“Oh, heavens!” exclaimed the old man, as if the blow had resounded in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.815#his very entrails.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.816#He stood there gaping, never supposing it would have been over so quick.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.817#And he looked at the gap, the hollow space at last left free on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.818#flanks of The Ladies' Paradise. It was like the crushing of a gnat, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.819#final triumph over the annoying obstinacy of the infinitely small, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.820#whole isle invaded and conquered. The passers-by lingered to talk to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.821#workmen, who were crying out against these old buildings, only good for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.822#killing people.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.823#“Monsieur Bourras,” repeated Denise, trying to get him on one side, “you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.824#know that you will not be abandoned. All your wants will be provided
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.825#for.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.826#He held up his head. “I have no wants. You've been sent by them, haven't
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.827#you? Well, tell them that old Bourras still knows how to work, and that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.828#he can find work wherever he likes. Really, it would be a fine thing to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.829#offer charity to those they are assassinating!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.830#Then she implored him: “Pray accept, Monsieur Bourras; don't give me
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.831#this grief.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.832#But he shook his bushy head. “No, no, it's all over. Good-bye. Go and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.833#live happily, you who are young, and don't prevent old people sticking
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.834#to their ideas.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.835#He cast a last glance at the heap of rubbish, and then went away. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.836#watched him disappear, elbowed by the crowd on the pavement. He turned
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.837#the corner of the Place Gaillon, and all was over. For a moment, Denise
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.838#remained motionless, lost in thought. At last she went over to her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.839#uncle's. The draper was alone in the dark shop of The Old Elbeuf. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.840#charwoman only came morning and evening to do a little cooking, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.841#to take down and put up the shutters. He spent hours in this solitude,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.842#often without being disturbed once during the whole day, bewildered, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.843#unable to find the goods when a stray customer happened to venture in.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.844#And there in the half-light he marched about unceasingly, with that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.845#heavy step he had at the two funerals, yielding to a sickly desire,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.846#regular fits of forced marching, as if he were trying to rock his grief
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.847#to sleep.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.848#“Are you feeling better, uncle?” asked Denise. He only stopped for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.849#a second to glance at her. Then he started off again, going from the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.850#pay-desk to an obscure corner.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.851#“Yes, yes. Very well, thanks.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.852#She tried to find some consoling subject, some cheerful remark, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.853#could think of nothing. “Did you hear the noise? The house is down.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.854#“Ah! it's true,” murmured he, with an astonished look, “that must have
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.855#been the house. I felt the ground tremble. Seeing them on the roof this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.856#morning, I closed my door.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.857#And he made a vague movement, to imitate that such things no longer
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.858#interested him. Every time he arrived before the pay-desk, he looked at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.859#the empty seat, that well-known velvet-covered seat, where his wife and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.860#daughter had grown up. Then when his perpetual walking brought him to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.861#the other end, he gazed at the shelves drowned in shadow, in which a few
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.862#pieces of cloth were gradually growing mouldy. It was a widowed house,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.863#those he loved had disappeared, his business had come to a shameful
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.864#end, and he was left alone to commune with his dead heart, and his pride
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.865#brought low amidst all these catastrophes. He raised his eyes towards
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.866#the black ceiling, overcome by the sepulchral silence which reigned in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.867#the little dining-room, the family nook, of which he had formerly loved
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.868#every part, even down to the stuffy odour. Not a breath was now heard in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.869#the old house, his regular heavy step made the ancient walls resound, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.870#if he were walking over the tombs of his affections.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.871#At last Denise approached the subject which had brought her. “Uncle, you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.872#can't stay like this. You must come to a decision.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.873#He replied, without stopping his walk--“No doubt; but what would you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.874#have me do? I've tried to sell, but no one has come. One of these
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.875#mornings I shall shut up shop and go off.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.876#She was aware that a failure was no longer to be feared. The creditors
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.877#had preferred to come to an understanding before such a long series
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.878#of misfortunes. Everything paid, the old man would find himself in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.879#street, penniless.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.880#“But what will you do, then?” murmured she, seeking some transition in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.881#order to arrive at the offer she dared not make.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.882#“I don't know,” replied he. “They'll pick me up all right.” He had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.883#changed his route, going from the dining-room to the windows with their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.884#lamentable displays, looking at the latter, every time he came to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.885#them, with a gloomy expression. His gaze did not even turn towards the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.886#triumphal façade of The Ladies' Paradise, whose architectural lines ran
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.887#as far as the eye could see, to the right and to the left, at both
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.888#ends of the street. He was thoroughly annihilated, and had not even the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.889#strength to get angry.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.890#“Listen, uncle,” said Denise, greatly embarrassed; “perhaps there might
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.891#be a situation for you.” She stopped, and stammered. “Yes, I am charged
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.892#to offer you a situation as inspector.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.893#“Where?” asked Baudu.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.894#“Opposite,” replied she; “in our shop. Six thousand francs a year; a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.895#very easy place.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.896#Suddenly he stopped in front of her. But instead of getting angry as she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.897#feared he would, he turned very pale, succumbing to a grievous emotion,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.898#a feeling of bitter resignation.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.899#“Opposite, opposite,” stammered he several times. “You want me to go
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.900#opposite?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.901#Denise herself was affected by this emotion. She recalled the long
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.902#struggle of the two shops, assisted at the funerals of Geneviève and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.903#Madame Baudu, saw before her The Old Elbeuf overthrown, utterly ruined
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.904#by The Ladies' Paradise. And the idea of her uncle taking a situation
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.905#opposite, and walking about in a white neck-tie, made her heart leap
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.906#with pity and revolt.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.907#“Come, Denise, is it possible?” said he, simply, wringing his poor
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.908#trembling hands.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.909#“No, no, uncle,” exclaimed she, in a sudden burst of her just and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.910#excellent being. “It would be wrong. Forgive me, I beg of you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.911#He resumed his walk, his step once more broke the funereal silence
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.912#of the house. And when she left him, he was still going on in that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.913#obstinate locomotion of great griefs, which turn round themselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.914#without ever being able to get beyond.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.915#Denise passed another sleepless night. She had just touched the bottom
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.916#of her powerlessness. Even in favour of her own people she was unable to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.917#find any consolation. She had been obliged to assist to the bitter end
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.918#at this invincible work of life which requires death as its continual
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.919#seed. She no longer struggled, she accepted this law of combat; but her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.920#womanly soul was filled with a weeping pity, with a fraternal tenderness
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.921#at the idea of suffering humanity. For years, she herself had been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.922#caught in the wheel-work of the machine. Had she not bled there? Had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.923#they not bruised her, dismissed her, overwhelmed her with insults? Even
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.924#now she was frightened, when she felt herself chosen by the logic of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.925#facts. Why her, a girl so puny? Why should her small hand suddenly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.926#become so powerful amidst the monster's work? And the force which was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.927#sweeping everything away, carried her away in her turn, she, whose
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.928#coming was to be a revenge. Mouret had invented this mechanism for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.929#crushing the world, and its brutal working shocked her; he had sown ruin
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.930#all over the neighbourhood, despoiled some, killed others; and yet she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.931#loved him for the grandeur of his work, she loved him still more at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.932#every excess of his power, notwithstanding the flood of tears which
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiii.933#overcame her, before the sacred misery of the vanquished.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1#CHAPTER XIV.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.2#The Rue du Dix-Décembre, looking quite new with its chalk-white houses
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.3#and the final scaffoldings of some nearly finished buildings, stretched
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.4#out beneath a clear February sun; a stream of carriages was passing at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.5#a rattling pace through this gleam of light, which traversed the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.6#damp shadow of the old Saint-Roch quarter; and, between the Rue de
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.7#la Michodière and the Rue de Choiseul, there was a great tumult, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.8#crushing of a crowd excited by a month's advertising, their eyes in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.9#the air, gaping at the monumental façade of The Ladies' Paradise,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.10#inaugurated that Monday, on the occasion of a grand show of white goods.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.11#The bright new masonry displayed a vast development of polychromatic
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.12#architecture, relieved by gildings, announcing the tumult and sparkle
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.13#of the business inside, and attracting attention like a gigantic
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.14#window-display all aglow with the liveliest colours. In order not to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.15#neutralise the show of goods, the decoration of the ground floor was of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.16#a sober description; the base of sea-green marble; the corner pillars
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.17#and the supporting columns were covered with black marble, the severity
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.18#of which was relieved by gilded medallions; and the rest of plate-glass,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.19#in iron sashes, nothing but glass, which seemed to open up the depths
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.20#of the halls and galleries to the full light of day. But as the floors
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.21#ascended, the tones became brighter. The frieze on the ground floor was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.22#decorated with a series of mosaics, a garland of red and blue flowers,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.23#alternating with marble slabs, on which were cut the names of goods,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.24#running all round, encircling the colossus. Then the base of the first
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.25#floor, made of enamelled bricks, supported the large windows, as high as
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.26#the frieze, formed of gilded escutcheons, with the arms of the towns of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.27#France, and designs in terra-cotta, the enamel of which reproduced
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.28#the bright coloured flowers of the base. Then, right at the top, the
