urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.632#was snowing down from every shelf, they were almost stifled, and found
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.633#it very difficult to get past.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.634#In the first place, at the stay counter a little scene was causing a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.635#crowd to collect. Madame Boutarel, who had arrived in Paris this time
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.636#with her husband and daughter, had been wandering all about the shop
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.637#since the morning collecting an outfit for the young lady, who was about
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.638#to be married. The father was consulted every moment, and they never
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.639#appeared likely to finish. At last the family had just stranded here;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.640#and whilst the young lady was absorbed in a profound study of some
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.641#drawers, the mother had disappeared, having cast her coquettish eyes on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.642#a delicious pair of stays. When Monsieur Boutarel, a big, full-blooded
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.643#man, left his daughter, bewildered, to go and look for his wife, he at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.644#last found her in a fitting-room, at the door of which he was politely
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.645#invited to take a seat. These rooms were like narrow cells, glazed with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.646#ground glass, where the men, and even the husbands, were not allowed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.647#to enter, by an exaggerated sentiment of propriety on the part of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.648#directors. Saleswomen came out and went in again quickly, allowing those
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.649#outside to divine, by the rapid closing of the door, visions of ladies
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.650#in their petticoats, with bare arms and shoulders--stout women with
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.651#white flesh, and thin ones with flesh the colour of old ivory. A row of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.652#men were waiting outside, seated on arm-chairs, and looking very weary.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.653#Monsieur Boutarel, when he understood, got really angry, crying out
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.654#that he wanted his wife, that he insisted on knowing what was going on
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.655#inside, that he certainly would not allow her to undress without him. It
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.656#was in vain that they tried to calm him; he seemed to think there were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.657#some very queer things going on inside. Madame Boutarel was obliged to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.658#come out, to the delight of the crowd, who were discussing and laughing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.659#over the affair.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.660#Denise and her brothers were at last able to get past. Every article of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.661#female linen, all those white under-things that are usually concealed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.662#were here displayed, in a suite of rooms, classed in various
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.663#departments. The corsets and dress-improvers occupied one counter, there
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.664#were the stitched corsets, the Duchesse, the cuirass, and, above all,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.665#the white silk corsets, dove-tailed with colours, forming for this day
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.666#a special display; an army of dummies without heads or legs, nothing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.667#but the bust, dolls' breasts flattened under the silk, and close by,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.668#on other dummies, were horse-hair and other dress improvers, prolonging
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.669#these broomsticks into enormous, distended croups, of which the profile
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.670#assumed a ludicrous unbecomingness. But afterwards commenced the gallant
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.671#dishabille, a dishabille which strewed the vast rooms, as if an army
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.672#of lovely girls had undressed themselves from department to department,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.673#down to the very satin of their skin. Here were articles of fine linen,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.674#white cuffs and cravats, white fichus and collars, an infinite variety
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.675#of light gewgaws, a white froth which escaped from the drawers and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.676#ascended like so much snow. There were jackets, little bodices, morning
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.677#dresses and peignoirs, linen, nansouck, long white garments, roomy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.678#and thin, which spoke of the lounging in a lazy morning after a night
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.679#of tenderness. Then appeared the under-garments, falling one by one; the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.680#white petticoats of all lengths, the petticoat that clings to the knees,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.681#and the long petticoat with which the gay ladies sweep the pavement, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.682#rising sea of petticoats, in which the legs were drowned; cotton, linen,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.683#and cambric drawers, large white drawers in which a man could dance;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.684#lastly, the chemises, buttoned at the neck for the night, or displaying
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.685#the bosom in the day, simply supported by narrow shoulder-straps;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.686#chemises in all materials, common calico, Irish linen, cambric, the last
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.687#white veil slipping from the panting bosom and hips.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.688#And, at the outfitting counter, there was an indiscreet unpacking, women
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.689#turned round and viewed on all sides, from the small housewife with her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.690#common calicoes, to the rich lady drowned in laces, an alcove publicly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.691#open, of which the concealed luxury, the plaitings, the embroideries,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.692#the Valenciennes lace, became a sort of sexual depravation, as it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.693#developed into costly fantasies. Woman was dressing herself again, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.694#white wave of this fall of linen was returning again to the shivering
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.695#mystery of the petticoats, the chemise stiffened by the fingers of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.696#workwomen, the frigid drawers retaining the creases of the box, all this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.697#cambric and muslin, dead, scattered over the counters, thrown about,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.698#heaped up, was going to become living, with the life of the flesh,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.699#odorous and warm with the odour of love, a white cloud become sacred,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.700#bathed in night, and of which the least flutter, the pink of a knee
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.701#disclosed through the whiteness, ravaged the world. Then there was
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.702#another room devoted to the baby linen, where the voluptuous snowy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.703#whiteness of woman's clothing developed into the chaste whiteness of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.704#the infant: an innocence, a joy, the young wife become a mother, flannel
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.705#garments, chemises and caps large as doll's things, baptismal dresses,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.706#cashmere pelisses, the white down of birth, like a fine shower of white
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.707#feathers.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.708#“They are embroidered chemises,” said Jean, who was delighted with this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.709#display, this rising tide of feminine attire into which he was plunging.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.710#Pauline ran up at once, when she perceived Denise; and before even
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.711#asking what she wanted, began to talk in a low tone, stirred up by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.712#rumours circulating in the shop. In her department, two saleswomen had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.713#even got quarrelling, one affirming and the other denying her departure.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.714#“You'll stay with us, I'll stake my life. What would become of me?” And
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.715#as Denise replied that she intended to leave the next day. “No, no, you
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.716#think so, but I know better. You must appoint me second-hand, now that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.717#I've got a baby. Baugé is reckoning on it, my dear.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.718#Pauline smiled with an air of conviction. She then gave the six
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.719#chemises; and, Jean having said that he was now going to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.720#handkerchief counter, she called an auxiliary to carry the chemises and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.721#the jacket left by the auxiliary from the readymade department The
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.722#girl who happened to answer was Mademoiselle de Fontenailles, recently
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.723#married to Joseph. She had just obtained this menial situation as a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.724#great favour, and she wore a long black blouse, marked on the shoulder
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.725#with a number in yellow wool.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.726#“Follow this young lady,” said Pauline. Then returning, and again
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.727#lowering her voice: “It's understood that I am to be appointed
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.728#second-hand, eh?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.729#Denise, troubled, defended herself; but at last promised, with a laugh,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.730#joking in her turn. And she went away, going down with Jean and Pépé,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.731#and followed by the auxiliary. On the ground-floor, they fell into
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.732#the woollen department, a corner of a gallery entirely hung with white
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.733#swanskin cloth and white flannel. Liénard, whom his father had vainly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.734#recalled to Angers, was talking to the handsome Mignot, now a traveller,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.735#and who had boldly reappeared at The Ladies' Paradise. No doubt they
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.736#were speaking of Denise, for they both stopped talking to bow to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.737#her with a ceremonious air. In fact, as she went along through the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.738#departments the salesmen appeared full of emotion and bent their heads
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.739#before her, uncertain of what she might be the next day. They whispered,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.740#thought she looked triumphant, and the betting was again altered;
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.741#they began to risk bottles of wine, etc., over the event. She had gone
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.742#through the linen-gallery, in order to get to the handkerchief counter,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.743#which was at the further end. They saw nothing but white goods: cottons,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.744#madapolams, muslins, etc.; then came the linen, in enormous piles,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.745#ranged in alternate pieces like blocks of stone, stout linen, fine
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.746#linen, of all sizes, white and unbleached, pure flax, whitened in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.747#sun; then the same thing commenced once more, there were departments for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.748#each sort of linen: house linen, table linen, kitchen linen, a continual
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.749#fall of white goods, sheets, pillow-cases, innumerable styles of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.750#napkins, aprons, and dusters. And the bowing continued, they made way
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.751#for Denise to pass, Baugé had rushed out to smile on her, as the good
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.752#fairy of the house. At last, after crossing the counterpane department,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.753#a room hung with white banners, she arrived at the handkerchief counter,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.754#the ingenious decoration of which delighted the crowd; there were
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.755#nothing but white columns, white pyramids, white castles, a complicated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.756#architecture, solely composed of handkerchiefs, cambric, Irish linen,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.757#China silk, marked, embroidered by hand, trimmed with lace, hemstitched,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.758#and woven with vignettes, an entire city, built of white bricks, of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.759#infinite variety, standing out in a mirage against an Eastern sky,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.760#warmed to a white heat.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.761#“You say another dozen?” asked Denise of her brother.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.762#“Yes, like this one,” replied he, showing a handkerchief in his parcel.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.763#Jean and Pépé had not quitted her side, clinging to her, as they had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.764#done formerly, on arriving in Paris, knocked up by the journey. This
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.765#vast shop, in which she was quite at home, seemed to trouble them, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.766#they sheltered themselves in her shadow, placing themselves under the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.767#protection of their second mother by an instinctive awakening of their
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.768#infancy. People watched them as they passed, smiling at the two big
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.769#fellows following in the footsteps of this grave thin girl; Jean
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.770#frightened with his beard, Pépé bewildered in his tunic, all three of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.771#the same fair complexion, a fairness which caused the whisper from one
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.772#end of the counters to the other: “They are her brothers! They are her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.773#brothers!”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.774#But whilst Denise was looking for a saleswoman there was a meeting.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.775#Mouret and Bourdoncle entered the gallery; and as the former again
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.776#stopped in front of the young girl, without, however, speaking to her,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.777#Madame Desforges and Madame Guibal passed by. Henriette suppressed the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.778#shiver which had invaded her whole being; she looked at Mouret and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.779#then at Denise. They had also looked at her, and it was a sort of mute
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.780#catastrophe, the common end of these great dramas of the heart, a glance
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.781#exchanged in the crush of a crowd. Mouret had already gone off, whilst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.782#Denise lost herself in the depths of the department, accompanied by her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.783#brothers, still in search of a disengaged salesman. But Henriette having
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.784#recognised Mademoiselle de Fontenailles, in the auxiliary following
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.785#Denise, with a yellow number on her shoulder, and her coarse,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.786#cadaverous, servant's-looking face, relieved herself by saying to Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.787#Guibal, in a trembling voice:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.788#“Just see what he's doing with that unfortunate girl. Isn't it shameful?
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.789#A marchioness! And he makes her follow like a dog the creatures picked
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.790#up by him in the street!” She tried to calm herself, adding, with an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.791#affected air of indifference: “Let's go and see their display of silks.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.792#The silk department was like a great chamber of love, hung with white
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.793#by the caprice of some snowy maiden wishing to show off her spotless
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.794#whiteness. All the milky tones of an adored person were there, from the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.795#velvet of the hips, to the fine silk of the thighs and the shining satin
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.796#of the bosom. Pieces of velvet hung from the columns, silk and satins
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.797#stood out, on this white creamy ground, in draperies of a metallic and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.798#porcelain-like whiteness: and falling in arches were also poult and gros
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.799#grain silks, light foulards, and surahs, which varied from the heavy
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.800#white of a Norwegian blonde to the transparent white, warmed by the sun,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.801#of an Italian or a Spanish beauty.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.802#Favier was just then engaged in measuring some white silk for “the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.803#pretty lady,” that elegant blonde, a frequent customer at the counter,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.804#and whom the salesmen never referred to except by this name. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.805#had dealt at the shop for years, and yet they knew nothing about
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.806#her--neither her life, her address, and not even her name. None of them
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.807#tried to find out, although they all indulged in supposition every time
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.808#she made her appearance, but simply for something to talk about. She
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.809#was getting thinner, she was getting stouter, she had slept well, or she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.810#must have been out late the previous night--such were the remarks made
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.811#about her: thus every little fact of her unknown life, outside events,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.812#domestic dramas, were in this way reproduced and commented on. That day
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.813#she seemed very gay. So, on returning from the pay-desk where he had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.814#conducted her, Favier remarked to Hutin:
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.815#“Perhaps she's going to marry again.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.816#“What! is she a widow?” asked the other.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.817#“I don't know; but you must remember that she was in mourning the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.818#last time she came. Unless she's made some money by speculating on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.819#Bourse.” A silence ensued. At last he ended by saying: “But that's her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.820#business. It wouldn't do to take notice of all the women we see here.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.821#But Hutin was looking very thoughtful, having had, two days ago, a warm
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.822#discussion with the direction, and feeling himself condemned. After the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.823#great sale his dismissal was certain. For a long time he had felt his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.824#position giving way; at the last stock-taking they had complained of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.825#being below the amount of business fixed on in advance; and it was also,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.826#in fact chiefly, the slow working of the appetites that were swallowing
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.827#him up in his turn--the whole silent war of the department, amidst
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.828#the very motion of the machine. Favier's obscure mining could be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.829#perceived--a deadened sound as of jaw-bones working under the earth.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.830#The latter had already received the promise of the first-hand's place.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.831#Hutin, who was aware of all this, instead of attacking his old comrade,
