urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1032#Her face was full of anguish, she threw a rapid glance around her. Then
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1033#she resigned herself all at once, resumed her haughty look, and walked
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1034#by his side like a queen who deigns to accept the services of an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1035#aide-de-camp. Not one of the customers had observed the scene, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1036#Deloche, on returning to the counter, looked at her being walked off,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1037#his mouth wide open with astonishment What! this one as well! this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1038#noble-looking lady! Really it was time to have them all searched! And
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1039#Blanche, who was left free, followed her mother at a distance, lingering
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1040#amidst the sea of faces, livid, divided between the duty of not
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1041#deserting her mother and the terror of being detained with her. She saw
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1042#her enter Bourdoncle's office, but she contented herself with waiting
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1043#near the door. Bourdoncle, whom Mouret had just got rid of, happened to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1044#be there. As a rule, he dealt with these sorts of robberies committed by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1045#persons of distinction. Jouve had long been watching this lady, and had
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1046#informed him of it, so that he was not astonished when the inspector
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1047#briefly explained the matter to him; in fact, such extraordinary cases
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1048#passed through his hands that he declared the women capable of anything
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1049#once the rage for dress had seized them. As he was aware of Mouret's
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1050#acquaintance with the thief, he treated her with the utmost politeness.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1051#“We excuse these moments of weakness, madame. But pray consider the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1052#consequences of such a thing. Suppose some one else had seen you slip
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1053#this lace----”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1054#But she interrupted him in great indignation. She a thief! Who did
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1055#he take her for? She was the Countess de Boves, her husband,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1056#Inspector-General of the Stud, was received at Court.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1057#“I know, I know, madame,” repeated Bourdoncle, quietly. “I have the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1058#honour of knowing you. In the first place, will you kindly give up the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1059#lace you have on you?”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1060#She again protested, not allowing him to say another word, handsome in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1061#her violence, going as far as tears. Any one else but he would have been
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1062#shaken and feared some deplorable mistake, for she threatened to go to
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1063#law to avenge herself for such an insult.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1064#“Take care, sir, my husband will certainly appeal to the Minister.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1065#“Come, you are not more reasonable than the others,” declared
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1066#Bourdoncle, losing patience. “We must search you.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1067#Still she did not yield, but said with her superb assurance, “Very good,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1068#search me. But I warn you, you are risking your house.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1069#Jouve went to fetch two saleswomen from the corset department. When
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1070#he returned, he informed Bourdoncle that the lady's daughter, left at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1071#liberty, had not quitted the doorway, and asked if she should also
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1072#be detained, although he had not seen her take anything. The manager,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1073#always correct, decided that she should not be brought in, for the sake
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1074#of morality, and in order not to force a mother to blush before her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1075#daughter. The two men retired into a neighbouring room, whilst the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1076#saleswomen searched the countess, even taking off her dress to search
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1077#her bosom and hips. Besides the twelve yards of Alençon point at a
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1078#thousand francs the yard concealed in her sleeve, they found in her
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1079#bosom a handkerchief, a fan, and a cravat, making a total of about
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1080#fourteen thousand francs' worth of lace. She had been stealing like this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1081#for the last year, ravaged by a furious, irresistible passion for dress.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1082#These fits got worse, growing daily, sweeping away all the reasonings of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1083#prudence, and the enjoyment she felt in the indulgence of this passion
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1084#was all the more violent from the fact that she was risking before the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1085#eyes of a crowd her name, her pride, and her husband's high position.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1086#Now that the latter allowed her to empty his drawers, she stole although
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1087#she had her pockets full of money, she stole for the pleasure of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1088#stealing, as one loves for the pleasure of loving, goaded on by desire,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1089#urged on by the species of kleptomania that her unsatisfied luxurious
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1090#tastes had developed in her formerly at sight of the enormous and brutal
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1091#temptation of the big shops.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1092#“It's a trap,” cried she, when Bourdoncle and Jouve came in. “This lace
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1093#has been placed on me, I swear before Heaven.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1094#She was now weeping tears of rage, and fell on a chair, suffocated in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1095#her dress. The partner sent away the saleswomen, and resumed, with his
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1096#quiet air: “We are quite willing, madame, to hush up this painful
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1097#affair for the sake of your family. But you must first sign a paper thus
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1098#worded: 'I have stolen some lace from The Ladies' Paradise,' followed by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1099#the details of the lace, and the day of the month. Besides, I shall be
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1100#happy to return you this document whenever you like to bring me a sum of
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1101#two thousand francs for the poor.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1102#She got up again, and declared in a fresh outburst: “I'll never sign
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1103#that, I'd rather die.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1104#“You won't die, madame; but I warn you that I shall shortly send for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1105#police.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1106#Then followed a frightful scene. She insulted him, she stammered that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1107#it was cowardly for a man to torture a woman in that way. Her Juno-like
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1108#beauty, her tall majestic body was distorted by vulgar rage. Then she
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1109#tried to melt them, entreating them in the name of their mothers, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1110#spoke of dragging herself at their feet. And as they remained quite
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1111#unmoved, hardened by custom, she sat down all at once and began to write
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1112#with a trembling hand. The pen sputtered, the words: “I have stolen,”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1113# written madly, went almost through the thin paper, whilst she repeated
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1114#in a strangled voice: “There, sir, there. I yield to force.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1115#Bourdoncle took the paper, carefully folded it, and put it in a drawer,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1116#saying: “You see it's in company, for ladies, after talking of dying
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1117#rather than signing, generally forget to come and redeem their _billets
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1118#doux_. However, I hold it at your disposal. You'll be able to judge
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1119#whether it's worth two thousand francs.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1120#She was buttoning up her dress, and became as arrogant as ever, now that
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1121#she had paid. “I can go now?” asked she, in a sharp tone.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1122#Bourdoncle was already occupied with other business. On Jouve's report,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1123#he decided on Deloche's dismissal, as a stupid fellow, who was always
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1124#being robbed, never having any authority over the customers. Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1125#de Boves repeated her question, and as they dismissed her with an
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1126#affirmative nod, she enveloped both of them in a murderous look. In the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1127#flood of insulting words that she kept back, a melodramatic cry escaped
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1128#from her lips.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1129#“Wretches!” said she, banging the door after her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1130#Meanwhile Blanche had not gone far away from the office. Her ignorance
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1131#of what was going on inside, the passing backwards and forwards of Jouve
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1132#and the two saleswomen frightened her, she had visions of the police,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1133#the assize court, and the prison. But all at once she stopped short: De
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1134#Vallagnosc was before her, this husband of a month, with whom she still
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1135#felt rather awkward; and he questioned her, astonished at her bewildered
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1136#appearance.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1137#“Where's your mother? Have you lost each other? Come, tell me, you make
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1138#me feel anxious.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1139#Nothing in the way of a colourable fiction presented itself to her,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1140#and in great distress she told him everything in a low voice: “Mamma,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1141#mamma--she has been stealing.”
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1142#“What! stealing?” At last he understood. His wife's bloated face, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1143#pale mask, ravaged by fear, terrified him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1144#“Some lace, like that, up her sleeve,” she continued stammering.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1145#“You saw her, then? You were looking on?” murmured he, chilled to feel
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1146#her a sort of accomplice.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1147#They had to stop talking, several persons were already turning round. An
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1148#hesitation full of anguish kept De Vallagnosc motionless for a moment.
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1149#What was to be done? He was about to go into Bourdoncle's office, when
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1150#he perceived Mouret crossing the gallery. He told his wife to wait for
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1151#him, and seized his old friend's arm, informing him of the affair, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1152#broken sentences. The latter hastily took him into his office, where
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1153#he soon put him at rest as to the possible consequences. He assured him
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1154#that he need not interfere, and explained in what way the affair would
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1155#be arranged, without appearing at all excited about this robbery, as if
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1156#he had foreseen it long ago. But De Vallagnosc, when he no longer feared
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1157#an immediate arrest, did not accept the adventure with this admirable
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1158#coolness. He had thrown himself into an arm-chair, and now that he could
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1159#discuss the matter, began to lament his own unfortunate position. Was it
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1160#possible that he had married into a family of thieves? A stupid marriage
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1161#that he had drifted into, just to please his father! Surprised at this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1162#childish violence, Mouret watched him weeping, thinking of his former
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1163#pessimist boasting. Had he not heard him announce scores of times the
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1164#nothingness of life, in which evil alone had any attraction? And by
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1165#way of a joke he amused himself for a minute or so, by preaching
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1166#indifference to his friend, in a friendly, bantering tone. But at this
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1167#De Vallognosc got angry: he was quite unable to recover his compromised
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1168#philosophy, his middle-class education broke out in virtuously indignant
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1169#cries against his mother-in-law. As soon as trouble fell on him, at
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1170#the least appearance of human suffering, at which he had always coldly
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1171#laughed, the boasted sceptic was beaten and bleeding. It was abominable,
urn:cts:fuTexts:zola.paradise.novoa:xiv.1172#they were dragging the honour of his race into the mud, and the world
